a 15-year search for meteorites in antarctica has turned up thousands of meteorites, including six from the moon and one possible rock from mars, scientists say
those seven meteorites _ solid bodies that travel through space and survive passage through the earth's atmosphere _ have been the focus of years of scrutiny by scientists looking for insight on the composition of the two heavenly bodies
it has always been assumed that a lot of material should be falling off the moon from meteoritic impact,'' said ursula b. marvin, a geologist at the smithsonian institution's center for astrophysics here. ``we suspected that some of our meteorites came from the moon before the apollo missions.''
marvin was part of the u.s. expedition that discovered the plum-sized rock weighing about four grams in january 1982
japanese scientists have located five lunar meteorites in antarctica. scientists also are ``building a case'' for martian origin of the meteorite found in 1979
comparing the 1982 find with lunar samples collected by american astronauts, scientists found the meteorite closely matched highland materials returned by the apollo 15, 16 and 17 crews
analysis indicated that the fragment was blasted away from the moon by an asteroid impact about 100,000 years ago and hurled to earth
the 66-year-old marvin, who also teaches part-time at harvard university, said the lunar meteorite probably was traveling in space for between 1,900 and 2,500 years before crashing through the atmosphere and landing on the antarctic ice
the antarctic rock believed to be from mars spent about 10 million years in space
some of the 1,000 moon rocks retrieved in the apollo missions have been dated at more than 4 billion years old _ a short time, by geologic standards
x-rays and gamma-rays of the moon's surface taken by apollo orbiters have led scientists to believe the lunar meteorite may come from a crater on the far-eastern rim of the moon or on the unexplored dark side, marvin said
we went to six places on the moon and the russians sent unmanned landers to three places,'' she said. ``we have no exact location for this composition anywhere.''
annual u.s. meteorite expeditions to antarctica occur in the six weeks of the year when the continent is bathed in sunlight 24 hours a day
the national science foundation, the national aeronautics and space administration and the smithsonian provide equipment and financing for research for the meteoritic expeditions, said marvin, who has has made three trips to the 5-million-square-mile continent to search for meteorites
she said that since manned moon exploration stopped after the apollo 17 mission in 1972, meteorite searches are crucial
it's one of the most vital and productive aspects of the space program,'' marvin said. ``as a matter of fact, in planetary exploration it's the only show in town. this all gives us more information _ without actually going up there _ about the evolution of the moon as a body.''
a foul-smelling mist came rolling into atwater, calif., on the night air, silently blanketing a row of homes on the outskirts. within an hour, townsfolk were staggering into the emergency room
environmentalists point to the june 1 incident, which they contend was caused by pesticides sprayed on nearby peach orchards, to fuel their arguments that the nation must do more to control the poisons
the senate agriculture committee is set to try once again to overhaul the federal insecticide, fungicide and rodenticide act (fifra), the primary law providing for regulation of the compounds
pesticides are now a $5 billion-a-year industry. tomatoes, beef, potatoes, apples, pork and many other foods arrive at the dinner table laden with chemicals. in a number of states, pesticides have been found in groundwater, often used for drinking
chemical makers contend that the benefits of pesticides outweigh the risks. they say drinking a glass of well water where contamination has been measured poses less hazard than downing a shot of vodka
however, there are some 113,000 cases of pesticide-related illness and injury logged each year. a may 1987 national academy of sciences report said cancer is caused in laboratory animals by 30 percent of the insecticides most likely to show up in food, 50 percent of the herbicides and 90 percent of the fungicides
congress has moved fitfully at best to tighten regulation of the 1 billion pounds of pesticides sprayed on u.s. fields annually in the war on bacteria, fungi, bugs, worms, mice and other forms of crop blight
critics ridicule fifra as hopelessly toothless. ``we call it a no-law law because it doesn't do anything,'' consumer advocate ralph nader says
a 1972 rewrite of fifra gave the environmental protection agency until 1975 to complete a ``reregistration'' process, including a full-scale safety review, of some 700 pesticides. in 1975, lawmakers approved a one-year extension. in 1978, the deadline was junked altogether
the general accounting office, an investigative arm of congress, now estimates that at the present crawl, the job won't be completed until the year 2024
senate agriculture committee chairman patrick j. leahy, d-vt., and sen. richard g. lugar, r-ind., have proposed a nine-year deadline for the reregistration process, plus a possible two-year extension
i think most americans are willing to put up with a spot on their lettuce or a blemish on their apple rather than risk cancer,'' says leahy
the national agricultural chemicals association, champion of the nation's pesticide makers, has no objection to a speedup in itself
more complex issues, however, are lying in the legislative weeds and could rise up to scuttle the bill. something similar happened in 1986 when a seeming compromise came unglued just before congress adjourned
chemical companies are willing to contribute to the costs of reregistration by paying $150,000 per ingredient. but the leahy-lugar bill calls for $750,000, which the naca calls ``a money grab, pure and simple.''
under current law, companies are entitled to indemnities from epa to compensate for the banning of their products. already the agency has paid $2.4 million to chemical makers for taking the pesticide edb off the market and $18 million for a chemical known as 2,4,5-t, or silex
and the agency estimates it will pay out between $60 million and $155 million in indemnities and disposal costs to get rid of a pesticide called dinoseb, the annual budget of the entire epa pesticide program is $70 million
the leahy-lugar bill would bar such indemnities unless congress passed an individual money bill for each one. such a measure is guaranteed a rough time on capitol hill. the industry is firmly opposed
manufacturers have other objections as well, especially to an amendment leahy co-sponsored with sen. david durenberger, r-minn. naca president jack d. early told the agriculture committee that the leahy-durenberger amendment contains ``an unrealistic ground water definition, unenforceable goals for water quality standards and (an) unworkable state ground and surface water protection program.''
of the main legislation, he said the plan to require separate money bills for indemnities would ``ultimately be bad for agriculture'' because ``there is no guarantee that agricultural users will recoup their losses.''
however, one incentive to action is a provision that would extend patent rights for chemical manufacturers
the 1986 bill passed by the house also included provisions that would preempt states from setting more stringent safety standards than those of the federal government and exempt agricultural producers from cleanup liability under the environmental laws. they were rejected by the senate when it fashioned its own version
in the house, the agriculture and the energy and commerce committees are fighting over jurisdiction of the bill
some fifra critics, such as rick hind of the u.s. public interest research group, declare in disgust that it ``will take a disaster'' to get the house moving on pesticide legislation. but house agriculture committee chairman e. ``kika'' de la garza, d-texas, scoffs at that notion
we don't need a disaster,'' he says. ``we know what we have to do.''
eleven cars of a 133-car union pacific railroad freight train derailed and spilled an acid solution into a creek, threatening the water supply for thousands of people, authorities said
no one was injured in sunday's derailment in which one car spilled about 13,000 gallons of phosphatic fertilizer solution containing phosphoric acid into the creek leading to the lamine river, said walter fussner, a union pacific spokesman
the lamine river, which feeds into the missouri river, is the water source for nearby boonville, a town of nearly 7,000 residents. officials shut off the water intake valve to the community as a precaution, and residents were asked to conserve water, said lt. becky loesing of the cooper county emergency operations office
the jefferson city water department was monitoring its water supply from the missouri river
phosphoric acid can irritate the skin and respiratory system, said larry alderson, environmental emergency specialist with the missouri department of natural resources
a 50-man cleanup crew worked into the night with backhoes and bulldozers to clean up and neutralize the acid. trace elements of the acid were found in the lamine river, but no fish were killed, fussner said
fussner said the cause of the accident, which occurred shortly before noon two miles from the missouri river, was under investigation
union pacific officials called a cleanup contractor, who built a dam to try to prevent the fertilizer from further contaminating the lamine river. lime was hauled in to neutralize the acid, alderson said
fussner said the railroad encountered problems because the spill was in a remote area. no roads lead to the area, and all supplies were being brought in by train
the train was traveling from east st. louis, ill., to north platte, neb., when the accident occurred near this central missouri town
premier jacques chirac, long mired in third place in opinion polls, has seen his presidential campaign take off, giving him an edge over rival conservative raymond barre with two months left before the vote
the first round of the election, april 24, has become in effect a primary election between chirac and barre. unless there is a stunning turnaround, one of the two will oppose a socialist, probably incumbent president francois mitterrand, in the decisive may 8 runoff for a seven-year term
policy differences between chirac and barre are few and minor, so the campaign has focused on the contrasting personalities of the two men, and what their political advisers increasingly call ``le look.''
there is certainly no need for the voters to discover the candidates _ mitterrand has been a major national figure for 40 years, barre and chirac for 15 years each
it's a question of sentiment, who looks better and talks better,'' said bertrand louapre, a barre supporter interviewed on the edges of a cocktail reception during a chirac campaign swing wednesday through reims, capital of the champagne country northeast of paris
personally, i've chosen raymond barre,'' said louapre, a construction engineer. ``mr. chirac has certainly taken off faster. he has much stronger support from his party.''
chirac, a rangy, almost hyperactive figure, then displayed his formidable skills as a campaigner, moving swiftly through the crowd, but often stopping to grasp the hands of his supporters briefly in his own oversized hands
i think the premier is closer to people, and that's what will make him win,'' political science professor alain redslob, author of a book on chirac, said in an interview. ``i think there's a strong movement beginning to lift off.''
the barre style is that of a fairly cold man, who has wanted to give himself an image of rigor,'' bernard pons, chirac's minister of overseas territories, recently said in a radio interview. ``he is a man who is fairly secret and who ... frequently makes decisions alone.''
barre, a rotund economics professor who had never run for public office when he began his five-year term as premier in 1976, is widely respected but inspires little enthusiasm. he prides himself on telling people what they need to know, whether or not they want to hear it
they tell me to offer the french people a dream,'' barre told a campaign rally in the southwestern city of poitiers on wednesday. ``but to dream, one must first go to sleep. i love my country too much, i respect my fellow citizens too much to lend myself to that.''
barre says chirac's government, which took over from the socialists in march 1986, has made some good moves. he says he would take stronger action to boost french industry
mitterrand has long had a solid lead in all published opinion surveys, while chirac trailed barre thoughout last year. a poll published jan. 16, the day chirac declared his candidacy, gave mitterrand 41 percent to 25 percent for barre and 18.5 percent for chirac
but surveys published in the past two weeks have shown chirac pushing ahead. friday's edition of the magazine paris-match, for exampale, reported 23 percent of those questioned planning to vote for chirac, to 19 percent for barre. mitterrand, who says he will wait until mid-march to disclose his plans, remained far ahead with 36 percent
the questions were posed for paris-match and a radio network by the polling firm b.v.a., which between feb. 1-4 interviewed 1,316 people who said they intended to vote. no margin of error was disclosed
barre, who insists on his independence from all political parties, is supported by the union for french democracy, a loose grouping of five center-right parties that is part of chirac's governing coalition
the main event of chirac's five-hour visit to reims was a campaign rally that drew 7,000 supporters to a new exposition hall in the suburbs. many arrived in buses chartered by chirac's party, the rally for the republic, france's most efficient political machine
rather than give a speech, chirac answered questions from three men and two women chosen to raise issues of concern in the region
he defended france's agricultural policies and promised to improve schools and universities so that students learn skills they need to find jobs. he also said he hoped to increase family allowances to mothers of three or more children to the minimum wage, about $825 a month, ``because they deserve it.''
the first question asked of chirac, who is juggling duties as mayor of paris, premier of france and member of a regional council in south-central france, was how he can do all the work
i'm an optimist by nature,'' he replied, ``which probably gives me more energy to face problems.''
young cancer victims and their parents gained emotional support and more than $300,000 in financial help from college students who swayed and staggered through a 48-hour dance marathon
i just like the fact that people are dancing not just to dance for fun but to help kids,'' said 10-year-old diane brannon of etters, a leukemia patient who took a few turns around the dance floor with penn state university students sunday
billed as the largest student-run fund-raising event in the country, the 16th annual interfraternity dance marathon raised $324,200 in pledges for the four diamonds fund at penn state's milton s. hershey medical center, organizers said sunday
diane's mother, teresa, said she and her husband, jim, would have been forced to sell their house without financial help from the fund, which helps pay for treatment of children suffering from cancer
bob sherfy, a social worker at hershey medical center who works with the young cancer victims, said the dance marathon offered the parents and children more than money
they know there's someone out in the world who cares about them,'' sherfy said
near then end of the marathon, participants complained of sore feet, fatigue and boredom
it's torture,'' said marc baskin, a junior management major from glen cove, n.y
but baskin and many other dancers said they gained resolve from the children at the dance
when they brought the kids in saturday, you said to yourself, `you can do it,''' said tammie rutherford, a sophomore business management major from white plains, n.y
hundreds of volunteers, clad in yellow t-shirts, attended the hobbled and weary dancers as they endured the final leg of the marathon
tom west, a sophomore sports medicine major from west long branch, n.j., taped feet, iced ankles and treated blisters from a trainer's table off the dance floor
some people come in and their feet are just flat,'' said west, explaining that fallen arches were the most frequent physical malady
carol stelmach, a junior marketing major from baltimore, said she and other dancers had a tactic for keeping their minds off their feet
you have to do something that makes you think of your hands,'' ms. stelmach said. she said she had played catch using a frisbee and balls and even participated in a card game
a total of 272 couples _ 544 dancers _ entered the marathon this year, said pat dugan, a senior accounting major from pittsburgh and head of the organizing committee. a total of 506 finished
they were allowed only three-minute breaks every eight hours and three other three-minute breaks at some time during the marathon
spectators filled the white building gymnasium to capacity for the final hours of the marathon, clapping and cheering
dugan said this year's marathon was the most financially successful in the event's history
james h. brucker, director of development for the medical center, said the marathon is the single biggest source of income for the four diamonds fund
last year, the dance marathon raised $297,000, dugan said. win</head>
democrat richard gephardt, who has made ``it's your fight too'' his populist rally cry, has chosen this state as a staging ground for a bid to block michael dukakis from sweeping the handful of states holding presidential primaries or caucuses before super tuesday
south dakota, and to a lesser extent wyoming, are the states chosen by the gephardt campaign for an intensive effort even as the three-week campaign for the south and its rich pool of delegates has already begun
according to the calendar and the democratic party's nomination rules, south dakota might not appear a major battleground. its primary was set for tuesday, earlier than national democratic officials wanted it, only after agreement was reached that means the state's nominating delegates won't be selected until later and won't be bound by the primary outcome
but gephardt has attached far more significance to south dakota, boarding a jet to fly here just as the sun was starting to rise wednesday morning on his badly needed second-place finish in new hampshire
you have a powerful voice in the election in 1988,'' gephardt told a group of senior citizens in sioux falls, on the opposite end of the state
sen. paul simon of illinois, his campaign on the ropes after finishing behind the missouri congressman in iowa and new hampshire, has chosen minnesota and south dakota to make what could be his last stand
he said at one point that if he didn't win in south dakota, or in minnesota's caucuses which also are held tuesday, he will drop out of the race, but then backed off on that assertion, citing a surge of donations
gephardt strategists, however, say it is not simon but dukakis that they regard as their bigger concern in those two states, coming as he does off a big victory in new hampshire's primary last tuesday
that is in part because gephardt would like to have a primary victory before heading into the 20-state contests on march 8. perhaps more importantly, however, his campaign would like to block dukakis from gaining the state and going into the south with one or even more victories under his belt from outside his native new england
they do not want dukakis to have the suggestion of inevitibility riding on his side should gephardt _ or one of the other candidates _ fail to stop him
there are five states holding primaries or caucuses between now and the contests across the south on super tuesday. they are sometimes referred to in the jargon of the campaign trail as the ``lesser antilles'' or the ``gateway states'' to super tuesday
a boost from any of these five gateway states would give us a boost to super tuesday,'' said ali webb, gephardt's press secretary
the contests include maine's caucuses feb. 26 and vermont's beauty-contest primary march 1. the gephardt campaign is conceding the new england states to dukakis, governor of nearby massachusetts
gephardt attended a debate in minnesota last week but isn't otherwise competing in the state, arguing that its caucus system and internal party divisions make it too confusing to spend time competing
gephardt brought close to 20 paid staffers from south dakota to iowa as soon as iowa's caucuses were finished. they have purchased $40,000 in television commercials in the states's two major cities, rapid city and sioux falls _ an amount of money small by other states' standards but regarded as large in the state of fewer than three-quarters of a million people
internal polling conducted by the gephardt campaign wednesday night showed dukakis was leading in the state by a nine-point margin, with no other candidates close. but it also showed the race was largely uniformed in the state, less than a week before the voting
another candidate, albert gore jr. of tennessee, has been quietly at work in south dakota and wyoming too, even as he concentrates on the states of his native south. he has ads on the air in south dakota and has visited wyoming several times
another reason for concentrating here is that gephardt forces believe the states should respond nicely to his populist message _ an assertion the nation is in economic decline in part because of unfair trade practices by asian countries
gephardt's support for an oil import fee is considered a plus, particularly in wyoming, where a large oil industry remains hard-hit by depressed prices
he stressed that at a small rally in casper, wyo., last week, and seemed to strike a chord among the audience
barb reese, a member of the county democratic executive committee, said she saw gore speak in wyoming a week or so earlier but found gephardt more appealing. she said she was wavering, and might back gephart rather than go along with an effort by state party leaders to back an uncommitted slate
i was really set on being uncommitted in the caucuses because i thought it was best for wyoming,'' she said. but, she said: ``i'm impressed.''
house negotiators are making plans to scuttle a trade retaliation plan authored by democratic presidential hopeful richard gephardt, but the missouri congressman is vowing to fight for his amendment
conferees plan to strip the provision from a house-passed trade measure in an effort to save the overall bill, according to congressional leaders
but lawmakers suggest that as a courtesy to gephardt, the conferees will wait until after the march 8 super tuesday primary elections before formally abandoning the proposal
the gephardt provision will be dropped. we're going to dump it because it's bad policy,'' said rep. sam gibbons, d-fla., chairman of the trade subcommittee of the house ways and means committee and a member of the house-senate conference committee hammering out a compromise trade bill
the gephardt plan calls for trade retaliation against japan and other trading partners that maintain large trade surpluses with the united states. the omnibus trade legislation it is attached to has languished in congress since last fall
gephardt's a nice fellow and he's got a lot of friends here,'' gibbons said. ``we're kind of proud of him. but we're not going to make his amendment law.''
gibbons and other house leaders said that once super tuesday is past, the house conferees will move quickly to get rid of the gephardt provision _ regardless of how he does in those primary states
gephardt said he has no intention of dropping his push for the amendment that bears his name
i'm going to fight for my amendment,'' he said as he campaigned in south dakota on sunday. ``i think it will make it through the conference'' committee
the missouri congressman, who has made trade issues a key part of his presidential pitch, was asked if rejection of the amendment would hurt his campaign. ``let's see what the result is before we jump to conclusions,'' he said
conference leaders have held off on moving ahead on the measure to await the results of the early presidential contests _ in part because gephardt's amendment is such a major part of the house bill
president reagan opposes the imposition of retaliatory trade measures by congress, and the white house has said he will veto the trade bill if it contains gephardt's amendment
twenty states hold democratic primary elections on march 8, with 13 in the south where trade is a major issue because of import-battered textile and other local industries
however, with recent signs that the nation's stubborn trade deficit is finally easing under the pressure of a weaker dollar, which makes u.s. goods more competitive overseas, political sentiment has been shifting in congress away from tough retaliatory sanctions
last october's stock market plunge, which underscored the fragility of world financial markets, has also subdued some of the most vocal calls for protectionist measures on capitol hill
the gephardt measure, passed last spring by the house, is aimed particularly at japan. it would require mandatory retaliation after a six-month period if those negotiations prove fruitless. then, a 10 percent a year reduction in the offending nation's trade surplus _ through tariffs or quotas _ would be required
trade analysts suggest that as long as the gephardt amendment is a central part of the house bill, action on trade this year is likely to remain paralyzed; and the better gephardt does in the primary campaigns, the harder it will be to win agreement on any compromise trade bill
actually, democratic leaders have said privately for some time that, at some point, the gephardt amendment would have to be dropped
however, deciding just how to go about it with the presidential election year in full swing has all but frozen action on the trade measure until now
addressing the afl-cio executive council in bal harbour, fla., last week, house speaker jim wright, d-texas, predicted that the conference panel would agree on ``something in between'' gephardt's proposal and the milder senate version
the senate bill calls for formal investigations that could lead to sanctions against nations running large trade surpluses but would not require blanket retaliation
a man awakened by three intruders searching his apartment for a stolen jacket fatally shot one of them with a crossbow, authorities said
james r. hucek, 21, was killed after he and his two companions burst into tom hedgecock's apartment early saturday, according to jim solomons, a spokesman for the orange county sheriff's office
gregory m. farmer and joseph roehrick were being held without bail after being charged with burglary and second-degree murder under a state law that permits such prosecution for those involved in a felony resulting in death
it was pretty traumatic,'' said the 27-year-old hedgecock, who was shot in the leg
solomons said hucek, roehrick, 22, and farmer, 25, spotted hedgecock's roommate when they were out driving late friday
the three thought that the roommate, kurt chaillet, had something to do with the theft of an expensive leather jacket that belonged to one of them, solomons said
chaillet, 25, joined the three for driving and beer drinking and later took them back to the apartment, where they confronted him with their suspicions and demanded to search the apartment, solomons said
the search, which turned up no leather jacket, quickly turned into a ransacking, and the noise woke hedgecock, solomons said
he told them to get out,'' solomons said. when they refused, hedgecock armed himself with a screwdriver and forced them out
he locked and bolted the door, but the three kicked in the door and pushed their way inside, where hedgecock had armed himself with a crossbow
he fired once, striking hucek in the chest and killing him
the violence continued as chaillet ran to call authorities. the fight between farmer, roehrick and hedgecock moved into the parking lot, where roehrick pulled a gun from his truck and shot twice, hitting hedgecock in the leg, solomons said
when deputies arrived, they found farmer and roehrick in the parking lot and hedgecock sitting on his couch
george vassiliou, a communist-backed millionaire businessman, was formally proclaimed president today and vowed to be flexible in seeking reunification of this war-divided island
in his first foray into politics, the 56-year-old vassiliou narrowly defeated veteran conservative leader glafcos clerides in sunday's runoff
it was cyprus' closest election since independence from britain in 1960
vassiliou is committed to peace talks with the turkish cypriots in the northern, turkish-occupied part of cyprus
he told thousands of jubilant and cheering supporters on sunday night that he would ``launch an unprecedented effort to promote a settlement.''
vassiliou has promised to abandon the inflexible approach of president spyros kyprianou, who insisted on the withdrawal of 30,000 turkish troops and 65,000 mainland settlers from the north as a precondition to resumed peace talks. kyprianou had sought a third five-year term, but was knocked out in the election's first round on feb. 14. he endorsed neither vassiliou nor clerides
in an acceptance speech broadcast by the state radio, vassiliou said he also will work for the withdrawal of the turkish troops and settlers and for the right of the 180,000 greek cypriot refugees to return to their homes in the north. turkey invaded the island in 1974 following a short-lived coup by greek cypriot extremists favoring union with greece
rauf denktash, president of the turkish cypriot breakaway state established in 1983, has offered to meet the new president in preliminary talks to break a 3-year-old deadlock in united nations-sponsored peace talks
vassiliou, who ran as an independent with the support of the powerful communist party, defeated clerides on sunday with 51.63 percent of the vote. he won 167,834 votes to 157,228 or 48.37 percent for the 68-year-old clerides, said kyriacos christofi, chief election official
christofi formally proclaimed vassiliou president early today in a speech from the first-story balcony of the eight-story building that houses vassiliou's market research company, the largest in the middle east
the new president ordered cameramen of the state-run television not to film leftists waving red flags in the crowd of 5,000 supporters gathered to cheer the proclamation
a pre-dawn victory rally in the capital's main square was called off after minor scuffles between vassiliou supporters and backers of clerides
vassiliou repeatedly appealed for calm during his broadcast speech and in earlier statements, declaring that he saw his election as a victory for cyprus
there is no victor or vanquished. we should all work for the good of cyprus,'' he said, stressing the need for national unity
voting was compulsory for all greek cypriots over 21. more than 90 percent of the 363,000 registered voters cast valid ballots
reunification was the main issue of the campaign, with both vassiliou and clerides stressing the urgency of breaking a peace talks deadlock to avoid the risk of international recognition for the breakaway turkish cypriot state
the proclamation of a statelet by the 150,000 turkish cypriots was branded invalid by the u.n. security council and has only been recognized by turkey
the turkish cypriots took no part in the election
the new president will be sworn in next sunday
the union representing 4,500 pan am ground employees in 14 cities vowed ``guerrilla warfare'' against the airline after talks in which management is seeking $35 million in concessions broke down
the pan american world airways reservation clerks and other ground staff represented by the teamsters continued working sunday after the union's 12:01 a.m. strike deadline passed
we can strike any time we want,'' said william genoese, director of the teamsters airline division
we're going to pick our strategic time,'' genoese said. meantime, he said, teamsters would attempt to disrupt operations through ``guerrilla warfare,'' starting immediately
there's going to be trouble on the job,'' he said. ``they're not going to correct anybody's errors, they're not going to help anybody, they're not going to do anything for anybody.''
but a pan am spokesman, jeff kriendler, called genoese ``the jerk'' and said his words were ``completely ridiculous.''
whereas the leadership may be at warfare with pan am, the rank and file are completely loyal to the company. it is not in their hearts to turn their backs on their customers,'' kriendler said
and, kriendler added, any workers taking part in that warfare would face ``discipline in the severest form.''
a federal mediator said both sides told him they would act on his request to reevaluate their positions
the board will stay in touch with the parties and there will be a resumption of negotiations at an early and appropriate time,'' said walter c. wallace of the federal mediation board
negotiations began late saturday at wallace's request, and continued for six hours past the strike deadline. when talks broke off sunday morning, teamsters leaders promised that union members _ reservation clerks, customer service agents and other clerical staff _ would continue to work
the talks resumed in the afternoon at pan am headquarters here, but recessed after about a half-hour when the company rejected the mediator's call for arbitration, genoese said
the dispute involves pan am's attempts to cut costs by $35 million through concessions by the teamsters. the airline has said it needs about $540 million in concessions from its unionized employees during the next three years to ensure its survival
asked about the major points of contention, kriendler said, ``let's say that the company long ago established a $35 million objective of achieving cost reductions. what is negotiable is how we reach the $35 million figure.''
the company does not view the amount as negotiable, kriendler said, but the union maintains that it is
the company said it would maintain operations with replacement workers in the event of a strike. the transport workers union voted friday not to support a teamsters' strike, and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers were not expected to honor picket lines
the teamsters represent workers at airports in boston, detroit, chicago, seattle, san francisco, san diego, los angeles, honolulu, houston, washington, new york and the florida cities of tampa, orlando and miami. the vast majority of the workers are employed in new york and miami
israeli foreign minister shimon peres says he is concerned about the soviet role in setting up arab-israeli peace talks even as the soviets pledged to be more of a factor in negotiations
peres, who favors an international conference to quell the violence in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, voiced doubts about soviet involvement in arranging such a conference
the deaths of two arabs sunday brought the number of palestinians killed by israelis since the protests began dec. 8 to 61, according to u.n. figures
what role the russians will play depends on what role the international conference will play,'' peres said sunday in an interview from jerusalem on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley.''
i would never agree that any foreign country, russia or other country, will make decisions instead of us or will try to force us to make a decision,'' peres said. ``i don't accept the russian concept that an international conference should be an authoritative conference. i think it should be an authorizing conference, namely enabling the parties to negotiate among themselves freely.''
peres said he understood that jordan, egypt, israel and the united states share this view
the foreign minister said the conference ``should be like somebody that opens the door to a new era, but not somebody who replaces the residents in the house itself.''
peres also acknowledged sunday that he sent a handwritten note to attorney general edwin meese iii in 1985 about a proposed iraqi pipeline
peres, who was israel's prime minister at the time, previously has denied writing to meese that he supported the $1 billion, 540-mile pipeline project, which was never built
meanwhile in moscow, soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze, prior to meeting with secretary of state george p. shultz, said that his government wants ``to play a more active role _ also in the negotiations.''
shultz, who travels to israel later this week, met with soviet officials to discuss the next superpower summit meeting between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, the iran-iraq war and the conflict in the middle east
prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel has resisted soviet participation in the search for a middle east settlement. in addition to not having relations with israel, the soviets generally support arab positions
the soviets broke relations with israel after it defeated egypt, then a soviet ally, in the 1967 mideast war. however, a small group of soviet diplomats was sent to israel last year to take care of some consular matters
peres emphasized the urgent need for negotiations
i'm convinced that the time has really come _ which shouldn't be postponed _ to start to negotiate and find a solution which will answer the expressions of the palestinians on one hand, and the security call of israel on the other,'' he said
israeli defense minister yitzhak rabin, interviewed on cbs-tv's ``face the nation,'' welcomed u.s. efforts to set up talks on resolving the mideast crisis and never was asked about a soviet role
i believe it's a very good idea to bring about a beginning of a talking,'' rabin said. ``after all, the problem that we face can be solved only by political means. by military means, by force, we can bring about tranquility but not a solution. ..
we have a very great respect and trust to secretary shultz. we believe that he is honest, decent human being and is trying his best to bring about a beginning of a talk.''
former secretary of state henry kissinger, who appeared on the abc program, said negotiations should be conducted under u.s. auspices and not soviet authority
i have the gravest doubts about an international conference,'' kissinger said. ``i have grave doubts about a soviet role, unless the soviets are willing to ask of their arab friends what we are going to propose to our israeli friends. so, i think that american mediation is the best course.''
president daniel ortega charged that u.s. lawmakers who are seeking to secure additional aid for the contra rebels are egotistically toying with nicaraguan lives
ortega said in a two-hour speech to the national assembly on sunday that, despite a feb. 4 vote in the house of representatives against a reagan administration request for more contra aid, ``this chapter has not closed.''
president reagan, he said, will look for a way to get more money to the rebels by calling the assistance humanitarian aid
if the (u.s.) congress approves that type of financing, it would be erasing the word peace that it wrote when it voted against the funds, and would be putting (in) the word `war,''' ortega said in the speech, broadcast over a government national radio network
that is the little game of congress, a congress where many interests, particularly egotistical, are involved and which is playing with life, hunger, security and the self-determination of the nicaraguan people,'' he said
the house voted against reagan's plan to give the contras a $36.2 million aid package that included about $3.6 million for weapons and ammunition to help them in their 6{-year-old fight against the leftist sandinista government
democrats prevailed in the vote, 219-211, after the party's leadership promised members there would be a later chance to vote on a package of contra aid for food, clothing, medicine and shelter only
a group of democrats, together with one or two republicans who voted against the president's plan, have been trying to draw up such an alternative
one proposal for the alternative aid request would give the contras humanitarian aid at a rate of about $1.8 million a month
ortega said 26,500 people have been killed since the war began and 23,882 wounded. other, unofficial sources, have put the death toll at more than 40,000. the war, he said, has cost the country $3.6 billion
damage to the economy was estimated at $376 million last year, exceeding the $270 million in export earnings, he said
even so, he said, the economy advanced at an inflation-adjusted rate of 1.7 percent in 1987. it contracted 0.4 percent in 1986
the inflation rate skyrocketed to 1,347 percent last year, well ahead of the 657 percent of the previous year
the government last week unveiled a new program to try to control runaway inflationm. it introduced a new cordoba currency, boosted prices of basic goods, increased salaries and cracked down on speculators
the dollar fell slightly against the japanese yen today, closing at 129.95 yen, while stock prices in tokyo rose moderately
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which posted a 98.05-point gain last friday, added another 73.30 points or 0.29 percent to close the day's trading at 24,846.71 points. volume in the first section was 870 million shares
the dollar opened trading monday at 129.95 yen, down 0.58 yen from last friday's close of 130.53, and ranged between 129.87 and 130.05 yen. trading totaled $2.526 billion
there's absolutely nothing going on'' in the foreign exchange market, said a trader at goldman sachs who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``the dollar's been moving in a 10-point range in inactive trading. it's extremely, extremely quiet.''
traders said the dollar's relative stability against the yen was behind the recent upswing of stock prices in tokyo
prospects of favorable trade and economic figures for fiscal 1987, which ends march 31, helped lift stock prices, said kunihiro ono of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage
other traders said share prices also were boosted by a report published over the weekend that the economic planning agency foresees a 4 percent growth in japan's gross national product in 1988
dealers said buying interest faded and volume sagged after a sharp rally in the morning session, as investors began to worry about a correction following the market`s rally last week
foods and retails, such as seven-eleven, had a fast speculative run, along with securities companies and steels, which were stronger earlier in the day but eased off in later trading, according to stephen codrington of jardine fleming ltd
light electricals, constructions and pharmaceuticals also firmed, while department stores and textiles fell back, other traders said
the reagan administration is likely to find out during a visit by portuguese prime minister anibal cavaco silva this week if a proposed $46 million increase in military aid satisfies portugal's request for more compensation for u.s. use of a major air base
cavaco silva's first trip to washington since he took office last august is expected to be dominated by discussion of the base situation, which has injected a dose of sourness into an otherwise sweet relationship between the two nato nations
portugal is getting $117 million in u.s. assistance this fiscal year _ in nato only turkey and greece got more _ but that was $30 million less than the fiscal 1987 payment
in the budget sent to congress last week, portugal would get $163 million
portugal wants $207 million a year, which u.s. negotiators pledged in 1983 they would make their ``best efforts'' to provide in return for a base-rights agreement that gives the united states access to lajes air base in the mid-atlantic azores islands
besides being part of the nato chain of bases, lajes is viewed by the pentagon as an indispensable refueling point for mammoth transports heading for the middle east and africa
the grumbling in lisbon is similar to noises being heard in the philippines, greece, turkey and spain _ allies seeking more benefits from the united states in return for use of military installations
security cooperation is an important part of the relationship between the united states and portugal and obviously will be discussed during the prime minister's visit,'' the portuguese embassy said in its announcement of cavaco silva's meetings, which include talks with reagan on wednesday
there will be further discussions about promised economic assistance,'' the embassy said
under the terms of the base rights agreement, portugal has the right to demand a review of the pact at its mid-term, which occurs this month. the form of the review is not spelled out, but u.s. officials have said it could result in a demand by portugal for specific amounts of additional aid
after defense secretary frank c. carlucci visited lisbon feb. 3-4, the two countries announced an agreement under which portugal would hold off calls for a formal review of the pact and the united states would supply surplus military equipment to compensate for the aid cutback
since then, however, the agreement has come under attack
portuguese president mario soares said the surplus equipment agreement is unsatisfactory
in a speech last thursday, portuguese foreign minister joao de deus pinheiro said he favored ``an update'' of the defense accord
officials of both countries _ notably pentagon and state department officers sympathetic to portugal's requests and frustrated by budget strictures _ have said the dispute is purely financial
unlike in spain and greece, where the voters support a reduced u.s. military presence, there is widespread support for the american bases in portugal
the upcoming portuguese-american negotiations shouldn't be dramatized,'' pinhero said. ``our common interests and views far exceed any possible bilateral difficulties.'' ^plane hijack attempt foiled</head>
hijackers on monday tried to commandeer a china airlines plane carrying 105 passengers on a domestic flight but were foiled by crew members, officials of the airline reported
officials of china airlines, taiwan's official flag carrier, said the boeing 737 was en route from taipei to the southern port of kaohsiung, 240 miles away, when the hijack attempt occurred
china airlines officials declined to identify the hijackers, say how many persons were involved, or provide any additional information. the said further details would be released at a news conference later today
in 1985, an attempted hijacking occurred aboard a china airlines' boeing 737 flying the same route with 107 passengers. a homesick army sergeant who wanted to see his parents was overpowered by crew members after he seized a stewardess. agreeing to congressional request to keep midgetman program alive.</note>
the new pentagon budget has reopened the bitter fight between congress and the reagan administration over the mx nuclear missile and how to build america's future arsenal of land-based atomic weapons
and in the latest round _ on a possible successor to the mx missile _ past administration critics have gained grudging support from an unusual quarter _ defense secretary frank carlucci
although he personally doesn't think much of the midgetman missile, the congressionally designated heir apparent to the mx, carlucci has agreed to request enough funding to keep the project alive until a new administration can make the final decision
the budget sent to the democratic-controlled congress last week proposed $807 million to buy a dozen more of the 10-warhead mx weapons, along with $793 million for a new method of basing the giant missiles aboard trains
the current plan is to put 50 of the weapons into silos on warren air force base in southeastern wyoming. the air force also wants to build 50 more and deploy two each aboard 25 specially-built trains
but carlucci told the senate armed services committee last week that if it were up to him, he would put all 100 mx weapons on the trains
we badly need a survivable missile system,'' he explained
that statement echoed criticisms by mx opponents, who claimed during a series of long fights in reagan's first term that putting the mx into land-based silos would make the missiles vulnerable to a first strike by accurate soviet missiles
former defense secretary caspar weinberger strongly disagreed and pushed hard for approval for 100 of the weapons. they were to replace some of the aging minuteman missiles which now make up the heart of america's land-based nuclear missile force
after a series of long fights, congress finally agreed to put 50 of the weapons in land-based silos and then approved the single-warhead midgetman weapon as a successor to the mx. the air force agreed with that plan, but later reagan decided to try to win approval for the second 50 mx weapons
even as the budget was unveiled thursday, mx critics were lining up to oppose the railroad-basing plan
the debate concerning survivability has been raging for years and apparently will continue,'' said rep. nicholas mavroules, d-mass., one of the chief opponents of the weapon in reagan's first term
based on the available data, serious questions remain regarding the safety and survivability of that type of deployment system,'' said mavroules. ``because of these lingering questions, congress must be concerned about the rashness of this proposal.''
another critic, rep. les aucoin, d-ore., said ``rail garrison would be vulnerable to more than soviet missiles. because commercial rail lines would be used, the threat of terrorism and sabotage must be considered serious.''
additionally, in light of the recent problems surrounding the safety of our nation's rail system, it is not pleasant to contemplate the thought of nuclear warheads being trundled around through populated areas.''
both mavroules and aucoin promised to try to eliminate all money for the rail-basing plan
carlucci also said he wanted to kill the midgetman program because budgetary restraints made it necessary to choose between midgetman and the mx. but to meet a congressional request, he included $200 million to keep the program alive until a new president takes office next year
that met with the approval of sen. sam nunn, d-ga., chairman of the senate armed services committee and a midgetman supporter
i felt it would be a mistake to zero the program and i wanted it kept alive for the next administration. this money seems to me to meet that request,'' said nunn, who helped defeat an attempt to kill the midgetman program two months ago
of the 50 mx weapons to be deployed, 33 are now in their silos, but only 20 of those are operational because of problems in delivering the guidance systems. but carlucci said that all 50 will be in the silos by the end of 1988
cars and trucks capable of switching from one fuel to another could discourage future oil price increases by foreign producers, the energy department says
the department says dual-fuel motor vehicles, in sufficient numbers on american highways, would offer that benefit even if the foreign oil producers also supplied the second, non-petroleum fuel
in the first of a series of reports planned for this year on alternate fuels, the department says enough twin-fuel vehicles would have to be in use to switch away from about 1 million barrels of oil a day
the united states uses almost 17 million barrels of oil per day, a bit more than a third of it imported, and five-eighths of it devoted to transportation
it would take a decade of spending several billion dollars a year to build the plants and distribution system necessary for significant switching ability to methanol or natural gas, the report said
the department and many in the oil industry are worried that imports will account for 60 percent of supplies by the middle of the next decade. that would give the organization of petroleum exporting countries leverage it has been unable to exercise in the surplus-sloshed soft markets of recent years, because opec will then have the only spare production capacity available in the world
the department promised more detailed reports on the experience of other countries, supply prospects, environmental effects and a cost-benefit analysis later this year. the most recent report was described as ``context and analytical framework.''
whatever strategy the country goes with has got to withstand cyclical swings in oil prices,'' said scott campbell, director of the office of policy, planning and analysis, whose staff did the work
though other approaches should be pursued, only methanol ``appears at this stage of the assessment to be a fuel with clear potential for meeting a significant percentage of this country's transportation fuel demand in the short run,'' the study said
the study director, vito stagliano, estimated that a dual-fuel car would cost $50 to $350 more in volume production. ford motor co. already has produced several hundred
to cut oil demand by 1 million barrels a day, the report estimated these needs:
_ten new methanol plants each year for a decade, costing a total of $20 billion to $25 billion
_development of 10,000 to 30,000 alternative-capable retail outlets a year, with an eventual total of 150,000 stations costing more than $5 billion in all. no cost estimate was given for changing pipelines, barges and other distribution facilities to methanol
_methanol-compatible vehicles entering the motor vehicle fleet at a rate of 1.5 million to 8 million a year. there are more than 170 million cars, trucks and buses on u.s. highways now
except in emergencies, motorists would not use methanol unless it were ``perceptibly less expensive'' _ more than two gallons of methanol are needed to provide the mileage obtainable with a gallon of gasoline
nevertheless, it is conceivable that the very prospect of seeing large volumes of the demand for oil translate into demand for alternative fuels will in itself discourage future increases in oil prices,'' the report said
methanol is made most cheaply from natural gas. the report observed that although the united states is the world's biggest methanol producer, it has been a net importer since 1982, and middle eastern countries can produce at half the u.s. cost
a future methanol market ``could be dominated by opec oil suppliers, or it might be one in which those countries play a less significant role,'' the report said
middle eastern countries could supply u.s. methanol needs economically, but ``any increase in the total potential supply of liquid fuels in the world should tend to enhance u.s. energy security, because it would cause the world energy market to loosen up,'' the report said
a methanol cartel that raised prices would call forth increased supplies from elsewhere, just as oil output expanded elsewhere in the 1970s after opec began steep price hikes, the report said
because feedstocks of natural gas are more widely distributed, even greater price competition would result in this case,'' it said
california continued to pace the nation last year in the receipt of pentagon contracts despite suffering a significant drop in awards compared to the previous year, new reports show
california also maintained its position as the state with the largest defense department payroll, as well as the no. 1 destination for military retirees. payroll and pension checks combined pumped $12.7 billion into the california economy in fiscal 1987, the reports show
nationally, the pentagon awarded $147.12 billion in contracts for work performed inside the united states during fiscal 1987 _ a drop of $2.1 billion compared to fiscal 1986
it also paid out $84.5 billion in payroll and pensions during the year to individuals retired or working inside the united states, up $2.7 billion compared to the previous year
of that $84.5 billion grand total, $26.3 billion went to pay civilian employees in the 50 states; $34 billion went to pay active-duty personnel in the 50 states; $5.5 billion went to pay reservists and national guard members, and $18.7 billion went to retirees
the new figures are contained in two annual statistical reports _ one known as the defense department ``atlas'' and the other entitled ``prime contract awards by state'' _ that attempt to show how pentagon spending is affecting the 50 states
those figures will be augmented in the coming months with additional reports on such things as the nation's top defense contractors; total contract actions, including work outside the united states, and civilian and military employee comparisons
the state statistics for fiscal 1987 show that the 12 months ending last sept. 30 produced some unusually wide swings in pentagon spending patterns
for example, california easily paced the nation with military contractors in that state winning $24.5 billion in awards. but that total represented an 11.6 percent drop, or $3.2 billion less than the $27.7 billion in contracts awarded in fiscal 1986
similarly, texas tumbled from second place to fourth in the contract rankings because of 20.9 percent decline in awards, while virginia climbed from eighth to fifth thanks to a whopping 44.5 percent increase in awards
texas finished the fiscal year with awards totaling $8.65 billion, while virginia finished with $7.8 billion. second place went to new york with $9.6 billion, while third place went to massachusetts with $8.69 billion
the remainder of the top 10 included missouri at sixth place with $6 billion; florida with $5.8 billion; connecticut with $5 billion; maryland with $4.75 billion, and ohio with $4.5 billion
even setting aside contracting, california benefited the most from the defense department's presence, with $12.7 billion flowing into the state in pension checks and salaries for civilian, active-duty and reserve employees
virginia, texas, florida and georgia rounded out the top five, retaining the same positions in fiscal 1987 they had the year before. virginia saw $8.8 billion flow into its borders in total compensation, compared to $6.6 billion for texas, $5.6 billion in florida and $3.2 billion in georgia
the remainder of the top 10 included north carolina with $3 billion in total compensation; maryland with $2.74 billion; washington with $2.66 billion; pennsylvania with $2.4 billion, and south carolina with $2.3 billion
breaking down those figures to focus on retiree compensation, the most money again flowed into california _ totaling $2.7 billion. next was texas with $1.9 billion, followed by florida with $1.88 billion; virginia with $1.4 billion and georgia with $682.5 million. investigators say</head>
a federal watchdog says it is time to use a few of the millions of dollars spent annually on anti-drug education to answer a simple question: what works and what doesn't?
that was the conclusion reached by inspector general richard kusserow after he was asked by the white house to evaluate a variety of programs
in weeks of studying nancy reagan's ``just say no'' campaign and two other antidrug efforts targeted at the very young, investigators found more questions than answers
the main recommendation in a preliminary version of kusserow's report is that federal agencies ``should develop an evaluation strategy to include long- and short-term evaluations of the implementation and effectiveness of youth drug education programs.''
specifically, he said those strategies should be devised by the education department and the alcohol, drug abuse and mental health administration
kusserow, charged with monitoring programs of the department of health and human services, agreed to discuss the study after the associated press obtained a draft copy
he acknowledged that the document lacks the precision typically associated with ig reports, but said that should not be read as an indictment of any of the programs surveyed. in fact, he said, ``it looks like they're on the right track.''
but the former fbi agent said his investigators' attempts to determine whether the programs are ``just fluff and puffery or real'' were hampered by lack of measurable data
there is no evidence that seems to be available to tell us how successful these programs are,'' he said. ``i think we've put the first layer in, but if you want to have an ongoing, effective program we're going to get more sophisticated. you cannot get sophisticated until you start developing some objective criteria and some instruments to measure progress
our concern is that if these programs satisfy themselves that they can relax on their laurels and sort of coast on to ever increasing success, i think they're deluding themselves. if we want to increase the effectiveness of the programs we are going to have some sort of measurement that would allow them to know what are successful techniques versus the less successful techniques.''
kusserow added: ``you're not talking about hoards of money to do that. you're just saying that somewhere along the line they're going to have to set aside some resource to look at how they can go about developing a model they can measure.''
and developing such measurements, he said, are beyond the scope of the ig's office
in addition to ``just say no,'' a loosely knit association of local efforts operating under a private foundation, the ig study looked at the boys clubs of america's ``smart moves'' and the national federation of parents' ``drug free youth.''
these programs sort of spontaneously came into being,'' kusserow said, noting that each is financed almost totally at the community level
he said each of the three should consider developing its own criteria for measuring success and that someone _ perhaps the federal alcohol, drug abuse and mental health administration _ ``might want to ask which one is best.''
kidnappers of a u.s. marine officer serving with the united nations released on monday a videotaped message from the captive in which he pleaded with the u.s. government to meet his captors' demands
lt. col. william r. higgins appeared reading from a statement in the 70-second tape that was released by the organization of the oppressed on earth to a western news agency office in beirut
he wore a dark green sweater and a newly grown beard
i, william higgins, in order to get me released, these demands have to be met,'' said the 43-year-old decorated vietnam veteran and one-time military assistant to former defense secretary caspar weinberger
higgins was abducted near south lebanon's ancient port city of tyre on wednesday. in the videotape, he looked gloomy, but physically fit
higgins said president reagan ``has to take responsibility for the crimes he has committed against the oppressed people in the region.''
he listed the same demands made by his captors when they first claimed his abduction in a statement friday that branded the marine colonel a spy for the ``satanic cia.''
the demands, as listed by higgins, are:
_withdrawal of israeli forces from all occupied territories in lebanon
_the release of all detained lebanese and palestinian mujahedeen, or holy warriors, from the khiam detention camp, in south lebanon, and all jails of ``the zionist regime in occupied palestine.''
_an end to u.s. intervention in lebanon and to u.s. diplomatic missions to the middle east
american universities have awarded more doctorates in education than in any other field over the past two decades, and women outnumber men among the newest ph.d.s, a government study says
education has been the most popular field of choice for doctoral study since 1966,'' said the report by the department of education's center for statistics
the report, based on federal surveys, said that in 1966, education held a narrow lead over the physical sciences as the most popular field of doctoral-level study. of the 18,239 doctorates awarded by u.s. universities that year, 3,063, or 17 percent, were in education, compared to 3,045 in the physical sciences
in 1986, education was still in the no. 1 spot, but by a much wider margin. it accounted for 7,110, or 21 percent, of the 33,653 ph.d.s awarded. the physical sciences again were second with 3,551
but education's share of doctorates peaked in 1977 at 7,960 and has declined steadily since then as fewer men pursued the advanced degree. men outnumbered women four-to-one among the education ph.d.s in 1966. women took the lead in 1983 and outnumbered the men in 1986, 3,795 to 3,315
the 7,110 education ph.d.s in 1986 was the lowest since 1972
the report, ``profile of education doctorates: 1976 to 1986,'' was written by the center's susan t. hill, p. elaine kroe and summer d. whitener
education administration and supervision was the most popular specialty, accounting for 1,622 of the ph.d.'s in 1986. some 787 were in curriculum and instruction, 609 in higher education, 323 in educational psychology and 315 in counseling and personnel services
a total of 1,141 of the ph.d.s were in various subjects or teaching fields, with physical education, health and recreation the most popular (291), followed by reading education (134), music education (94), trade and industrial education (86) and english education (79)
the report said 194 of the 438 doctoral-granting institutions in the united states awarded education ph.d.s in 1986. the top 10 were: temple university, 171; university of pittsburgh, 165; columbia university-teachers college and nova university, both 163; vanderbilt university, 149; michigan state university 139; university of georgia, 129; university of texas-austin, 125; university of maryland-college park, 124; university of massachusetts-amherst, 112
foreign students received 700, or nearly 10 percent of the education doctorates in 1986
gov. richard celeste says he believes the ohio primary election this may will determine the presidential nominees for both the democrats and the republicans
celeste said sunday he thinks the state will play the pivotal role because the may 3 primary will fall at a key time in the nominating process and because of the nature of the state
i think that the ohio primary will determine who the nominee is for each of the parties,'' celeste said in answer to a question at a news conference. ``they (the winners) may not have all the delegates, but i think ... it will be clear that they are going to be the first-ballot choice.''
any nominee understands that to win the general election, they must carry ohio,'' said celeste. ``our state is kind of a fulcrum in the political process, it seems to me.''
celeste said it is too early for him to try to influence the nominating process by endorsing a candidate, but that he may do so prior to the ohio primary
the california republican party has voted to prohibit any endorsement by either the statewide party or any official republican county central committee prior to the gop primary
in a three-day convention, noteworthy principally for the absence of all of the party's presidential candidates who are campaigning in states with ``super tuesday'' primaries on march 8, the only other significant business was adoption of new rules for naming members to the party's governing board
the ban on endorsements sunday was in response to a 1986 court ruling that a state law prohibiting such endorsements violated constitutional free speech guarantees. however, that ruling left the political parties free to adopt any rules they want restricting themselves
contrary to the gop action sunday, the california democratic party is expected to adopt rules permitting pre-primary endorsements at its statewide convention next month
the presidential primary scorecard, in the view of former house speaker thomas p. ``tip'' o'neill, allows for more than one ballot at the democratic convention and division among republicans
in his first public appearance since surgery late last year for rectal cancer and an enlarged prostate, o'neill told a convention crowd of 2,000 on saturday that missouri congressman dick gephardt doesn't have the financing to run a successful race and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. may have waited too late to join the fray
jesse jackson will control a sizable block of votes and make the convention, which o'neill believes ``is going to go more than one ballot, and there are going to be a lot of smoke-filled rooms.''
o'neill backs a fellow massachusetts politician, gov. michael dukakis
on the gop side, o'neill said vice president george bush got his timing back with his win in new hampshire, but senate minority leader bob dole ``has a democratic style and can distance himself from the administration.''
but internal strife may hurt republicans, he told members of the national electrical manufacturers representatives association
here are some comments from political observers about pat robertson in the super tuesday states:
north carolina: merle black, political scientist at the university of north carolina at chapel hill: ``i think bush's biggest competition in the south will come from robertson. he's a big unknown. we don't know how strong he is, but he's likely much stronger here than in new hampshire.''
missouri: gop chairman hillard selck: ``it does not appear to be in the cards for pat robertson to make a strong showing in missouri. he's probably going to pick up a few delegates. but you can't go around the nation and pick up a few delegates here and a few there and expect to win the nomination.''
arkansas: state democratic executive director kip blakely, assessing robertson's support: ``remember the right to life march a couple of weekends ago? it was raining and it was a saturday morning and it was freezing. there were over 3,000 people who turned out. that's pat robertson.''
texas: gop chairman george strake: ``i think he's going to be present and accounted for. he's going to pick up some delegates.''
tennessee: republican chairman jim henry: ``he's going to get 40,000 or 50,000 votes in tennessee. that will probably give him a solid third (behind bush-dole or dole-bush).''
massachusetts: paul cellucci, coordinator for george bush: ``we're not expecting any invisible army. we haven't seen any signs of that, although there is (robertson) support out there. i'm not nervous at this point. new hampshire makes me feel a lot better.''
oklahoma: republican chairman tom cole: ``i think pat robertson causes us a lot fewer problems than jesse jackson causes democrats.''
maryland: former gop chairman allan levey, a bush supporter: ``i think 10 percent would be the top that he (robertson) would get.''
washington: bruce hawkins, robertson's state director: ``new hampshire was actually a positive for our people. they look (at roberton's last place finish) and said, `we will not let that happen here.'''
rhode island: gop chairman j. michael levesque, forecasting a weak robertson showing: ``i have not seen any kind of signal or signs that there is a significantly large evangelical movement in rhode island.''
georgia: former state gop chairman bob bell: ``if those people who are voting for pat robertson stay in the republican column, there's a whole lot of democrats who are going to be out of office.''
louisiana: robertson state director billy e. mccormack, citing a 6 percent jump in republican registration since october: ``we feel like we were responsible for 90 to 95 percent of them.''
florida: rep. david troxler, r-fla., one of the few elected officials supporting robertson: ``i do believe that if he takes a substantial number of super tuesday delegates _ 55 or 60 percent _ he will be the nominee.''
alabama: al lapierre, executive director of the state democratic party, on robertson's claim that the russians have missiles in cuba: ``i don't think it hurts him with his voters. they think it's true.''
kentucky: harold rogers, state chairman for bush, on robertson's support: ``essentially it's still limited to the religious conservatives. i don't see him breaking out beyond that very narrow base, except in spotty cases, here and there.''
