aids and lasers top the list of issues as thousands of dentists gathered for the 123rd midwinter meeting of the chicago dental society
only a few dentists now use lasers as surgical tools to remove lesions and damaged soft tissue from around gums. but experts predict dentists will soon use lasers to do everything from fitting crowns to drilling cavities, said harvey wigdor, chief of dental service at ravenswood hospital medical center
the four-day conference, which started sunday, is expected to attract 27,000 dentists and technicians from 26 countries
aids poses challenges because of the small chance of dentists' contracting it from patients and the difficulty of treating symptoms of the disease, said dr. sol silverman, chairman of oral medicine at the university of california, san francisco
silverman said he will urge dentists to wear gloves to protect themselves from contracting aids from patients. he said he would impress upon them they are legally and morally obligated to treat people with aids
only one dentist is believed to have contracted aids by treating patients with the deadly virus without taking the proper percautions. another dentist has tested positive for antibodies to the virus, but has not yet shown symptoms of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, silverman said
the risk of contracting the virus is very, very low _ but why take the chance?'' he said
aids patients develop many symptoms that must be treated by a dentist, such as mouth lesions, ulcers, fungus and other lumps and bumps, he said
silverman said he will instruct dentists how to treat these problems and give them information on how to refer the aids patients if the dentist can not handle treatment
he said he would instruct dentists how to spot early symptoms of aids and how to refer them for additional medical assistance
a french dentist, francois duret of marseilles university, was scheduled to present his new computerized laser systems, which may revolutionize current procedures for crowns and bridges, dental society spokesman allen rafalson said
doctors discussed the future uses of lasers at preconference workshops at ravenswood hospital saturday
lasers offer the advantages of being bloodless, very clean and causing less post-treatment pain, he said
david harris of the wenske laser center said his laboratory is trying to develop a laser drill ``to get rid of the noise and vibration ... that patients find so adverse'' when they are having cavities drilled
the high cost of laser equipment _ $20,000 to $25,000 _ prevents most individual dentists from purchasing it, widgor said
but widgor and harris, who helped organize the workshops, said prices are expected to drop dramatically in the next few years to an affordable level
a moderate earthquake shook central california, jarring residents awake as it sent dishes rattling and house beams creaking but caused no injuries or major damage, officials said
the quake, measuring 3.9 on the richter scale, hit at 11:43 p.m. sunday, and was centered about 40 miles west-northwest of bakersfield, said robert finn, spokesman for the california institute of technology's seismology laboratory in pasadena
shaking was felt over a broad area in kern and san luis obispo counties, and as far north as paso robles, about 75 miles away
it rattled some dishes and caused some attic beams to creak, but after the initial fright, most of our callers settled right down,'' said san luis obispo county sheriff's sgt. gary hogan
we've had about a dozen calls, spread out over about 40 miles,'' hogan said. ``it woke people up, but there weren't any reports of injury or damage.''
residents in bakersfield and nearby taft felt the ground shake, but taft police officers said they barely noticed the temblor
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. an earthquake of 3.5 on the open-ended scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage
passengers and crew members on a china airlines flight today prevented a taiwanese man from hijacking the plane to beijing by hitting him over the head and wrestling him to the floor, the airline said
the boeing 737 jetliner was carrying 114 people, including one american, on a flight from taipei to the southern port city of kaohsiung, 240 miles away, when the hijack attempt by the 29-year-old man occurred
the man, an employee at a knife grinding shop, was carrying two fake grenades made of wood and a slip of paper from a fortuneteller predicting a year of bad luck, the airline said at a news conference
according to the airline, the would-be hijacker was subdued after a crew member hit him on the head with a ``hard object.''
no injuries were reported among the other 106 passengers and seven crew members aboard the jetliner. the plane landed at kaohsiung and later returned to taipei where members of the cabin crew appeared at a press conference
stewardess lee lin said she was passing out drinks to the passengers about 20 minutes after takeoff when the would-be hijacker, chien chu-yuan, handed her a slip of paper demanding the plane be diverted to beijing
he threatened on the slip of paper that he would kill all of us with his two grenades if we didn't fly to beijing,'' she said. the man later said he wanted to go to taipei, but crew members said he was nervous and probably meant beijing. the would-be hijacker claimed to have two partners, but the airline has ruled out that possibility
the stewardess asked four stewards for help as most passengers remained unaware of the unfolding drama. the stewards and a few passengers then pounced on the hijacker when he tried to show the phony grenades to the passengers and subdued him after a 10-minute scuffle
we asked the captain to fly in circles and told the hijacker we would divert to beijing,'' said steward chi hsi-an
police said the would-be hijacker, a native taiwanese who worked in his brother's knife grinding shop, was in custody in kaohsuing. attempted hijacking can carry the death sentence in taiwan
officials were unsure how many foreigners were aboard the plane besides the one american. among the passengers was yu chen yueh-ying, the kaohsiung county magistrate who is an opposition member
in 1985, an attempted hijacking occurred aboard a china airlines' boeing 737 flying the same route with 107 passengers. in that incident, a homesick army sergeant who wanted to see his parents was overpowered by crew members after he seized a stewardess
soviet president andrei gromyko says he rebuffed mao tse-tung's proposal that the soviet union help lure u.s. troops into china where they would be attacked by nuclear weapons, a newspaper reported today
gromyko's two-volume memoir covers nearly 50 years of soviet diplomacy, including dealings with nine american presidents, according to the new york times, which said an advance copy was made available to its moscow bureau
in ``memoir,'' expected to be distributed to bookstores in the next few weeks by its soviet publisher, gromyko says mao's proposal came during a secret visit to beijing in august 1958
gromyko, soviet foreign minister from 1957 to 1985, said he was surprised by the audacity of the plan, according to the times
the scenario of war described by you cannot meet a positive response by us,'' gromyko said he told mao. ``i can say this with certainty.''
gromyko, 78, wrote that mao was anticipating an american attack on china because of tensions over the islands of quemoy and matsu, off mainland china
mao said chinese forces would retreat to the heartland of china, luring american soldiers after them. then, mao proposed, ``the soviet union should catch them with all its means,'' gromyko wrote
at the time, china was expecting to receive nuclear weapons from the soviet union, but moscow withdrew their offer in 1959. soviet officials later accused mao of recklessness. china exploded its own nuclear bomb in 1964
gromyko denies reports that he misled president kennedy about the presence of soviet missiles in cuba during the 1962 missile crisis
in spite of several allegations circulating in the west, not once in the whole course of the conversation did kennedy raise the question of the presence of soviet missiles in cuba,'' he wrote
consequently, i did not have to answer whether or not there were such weapons in cuba.''
gromyko, who dealt with every u.s. president from franklin d. roosevelt to ronald reagan reserved special praise for roosevelt
he describes roosevelt as someone ``who knew how to conduct conversation freely, without any tension,'' and a leader who knew how to make and carry out policy
he also described meetings with american stars such as marilyn monroe, whom he met during a hollywood reception for soviet officials in 1959. he said they exchanged a few words, and he recalled her ``special and indescribable attractiveness.''
every year the chamber of commerce manages to find volunteers to taste more than 100 bottles of homemade wine for the newport wine and seafood festival
it's hard work, some of the 27 volunteer judges tapped this year said over the weekend
we taste a lot of different wines and try to decide, try to be objective,'' opal white said. ``we don't want to say anything bad about them, but some of them ....'' she trailed off, perhaps not wishing to leave a bitter aftertaste
since wine can be made from nearly anything organic, some of the entries are, well, unusual. garlic, dried kiwi fruit, rose petals, zucchini and even sauerkraut have found their way into bottles during past competitions
a little sauerkraut wine is good on a cold night,'' judge joseph swafford said dryly
stomach aches are unlikely, since the rules say the judges are supposed to sniff, swirl, taste and spit. still, the volunteer judges must sign a waiver releasing the chamber from any blame should they be struck with a sudden illness, and nobody else is allowed the taste the amateur wines that are displayed at the festival
the festival, which opened friday and runs through feb. 28, allows the public to taste commercial wines, and compare their choices with results from a panel of professional judges
whales are coming to lake michigan
the shedd aquarium says its oceanarium, a $43 million expansion project that should be completed by 1990, will exhibit six whales, four dolphins, several sea otters and a rookery of penguins
the oceanarium design calls for huge rocks, cliffs and 35-foot trees on 1.8 acres of what was lake michigan before 30 million gallons of water was siphoned so construction could begin below lake level in august
to give the illusion the whales are in the ocean, a 600-foot-long 35-foot-high picture window will overlook the lake from behind their tanks
i've got a gut feeling that we might even have to turn people away,'' aquarium director william p. braker said recently as cranes pounded 75-foot-long steel pilings for the foundation. ``we had 1.1 million visitors in 1987, and with the oceanarium, i think we may hit 2 million.''
three milk-white, 15-foot beluga whales will be airlifted from churchill, manitoba on the hudson bay, aquarium officials said. as whales go, manitobas are small, but the largest animal now at shedd is a 7-foot nurse shark
three more pacific black whales, about the size of manitobas, will be brought from japan, the aquarium staff said
braker said shedd, which opened in 1929 and is the world's largest indoor aquarium at 230,000 square feet, ``needed a good shot in the arm to bring it out of many years of being static.''
money for the oceanarium includes $5 million each from the state and the chicago park district. the aquarium has spent $8 million and hopes to raise the remainder of the $25 million price tag through donations
