mildred seydell, a globe-trotting journalist who interviewed benito mussolini and covered the scopes ``monkey trial,'' died saturday. she was 98
ms. seydell, a resident of suburban roswell, once said she ``much preferred to set the stage for adventure rather than the table for dinner.''
her work as a writer and columnist for hearst publications, including the now-defunct atlanta georgian newspaper, took her around the world
she wrote ``talks with celebrities,'' including an interview with the italian dictator mussolini, for universal news service and 27 hearst papers
she also covered for hearst the 1925 tennessee trial of john scopes, a teacher indicted for illegally teaching the theory of evolution
ms. seydell was a columnist for the atlanta georgian from 1926 to 1939, the year the paper closed
she was born mildred woolley and in 1910 married paul seydel, a chemist she met while studying at the sorbonne in paris. she added an ``l'' to seydel and used the name professionally
william claiborne ``red'' hayes jr., the nasa official who greeted astronaut john glenn after his history-making flight in 1962, died saturday. he was 63
hayes, who spent 27 years with the national aeronautics and space administration, directed the at-sea recovery efforts that plucked astronauts from the ocean after their space capsules had returned to earth
when glenn was brought aboard an aircraft carrier after america's first manned orbital flight, hayes was the first to shake his hand
hayes joined the national advisory committee on aeronautics in 1952 and was there when nasa was organized a few years later
hayes directed the recovery of astronauts glenn, scott carpenter, walter schirra and gus grissom. he retired in 1979
makoto miike, the eldest member of japan's house of councilors, died saturday. he was 87
miike had been a member of the upper house of the governing liberal democratic party since 1986
he was first elected to the house of representatives, the lower house, in 1949 and was postal and telecommunciations minister in 1972 in the government of prime minister kakuei tanaka
jim woods, a major-league baseball announcer for six clubs during a 26-year career, died saturday. he was 71
he began his big-league career with the new york yankees in 1953 as mel allen's partner. he also worked with the old new york giants, pittsburgh pirates, st. louis cardinals, oakland a's and boston red sox
woods left the red sox after the 1978 season and worked for the usa network on cable television before retiring
