palestinians today held memorial services for the 61 arabs killed by israelis in anti-occupation violence, and israel's attorney general ruled soldiers could not use force to punish or humiliate protesters
also today, hospital officials said a 14-year-old arab boy was wounded in the thigh in the gaza strip
the army reported an arab was arrested after trying to attack an israeli soldier with a knife in the west bank town of ramallah. it was the third such attack on soldiers in four days
leaflets distributed by underground palestinian groups in the occupied territories called for demonstrations this week _ beginning with memorial services on ``martyrs day'' today _ to protest the visit to israel by secretary of state george p. shultz
army officials said the five-day visit, scheduled to start thursday, might prompt an escalation in violence in the west bank and gaza strip. ``it's not organized or systematic, but outside events like the shultz visit do affect the situation,'' an army spokeswoman said. she spoke on condition of anonymity
attorney general yosef harish sent a letter to defense minister yitzhak rabin saying soldiers may not use force as a means of punishment or humiliation, israel radio reported
orders that call for such use of force are illegal, ruled harish, who demanded rabin issue appropriate instructions to the troops. harish said many palestinians have complained to him about abuse by soldiers
in an army survey, 65 percent of soldiers questioned said they had witnessed rough treatment of palestinians by troops, said the army's chief psychologist, col. shlomo dover. the radio did not say how many soldiers were questioned
dover said 70 percent felt angry and frustrated by the situation in the occupied lands and said they thought using the army to break up civilian protests damages its effectiveness to fight a war
dover told israel radio that 92 percent of the soldiers questioned expressed full trust in their commanders
we don't have problems with the motivation of soliders ... not that they rejoice to do it, but it's an assignment that has been given to the army and that's how it is seen by the soldiers,'' he said
since the wave of protests began dec. 8 in the territories israel seized in the 1967 middle east war, israelis have killed 61 palestinians. the latest fatalities were two men shot and killed by soldiers sunday
the government has spent $330 million, or 1 percent of the government's 1988 budget, in an attempt to quell the violence
in one memorial services today, women marched to a cemetery in the west bank village of anabta to honor three residents who died in clashes with the army earlier this month
a molotov cocktail was thrown at an israeli car in the west bank town of ramallah, but no one was injured, the army said
in the gaza strip refugee camp of jabaliya, soldiers clashed with protesters, and a 14-year-old boy was shot in the thigh, doctors at gaza city's shifa hospital said
in gaza city, anti-american slogans painted in red on closed store shutters read: ``no to the shultz visit. yes to the palestinian government. yes to the plo.''
the palestine liberation organization has ordered palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip not to meet with shultz, saying he is pro-israeli and has rejected minimal palestinian demands
but local palestinian leaders said today that they were trying to persuade plo chief yasser arafat to lift the ban. u.s. officials met with several palestinian representatives over the weekend to discuss the shultz visit
during his visit, shultz will present to israeli leaders a u.s. peace initiative calling for an international forum for direct talks on palestinian self-rule and negotiations on a final settlement by december
but prime minister yitzhak shamir told european jewish leaders sunday night he objected to the hurried pace: ``any attempt to force the pace and shorten the period (of self-rule) would be a detriment to the very essence of the agreement.''
he also indicated he would not give in to pressure to accept the american plan: ``when the time comes for decisions, we shall decide on the basis of what is in our national interests.'' him'</head>
relatives of a man whose decomposed body was found about three weeks after his death apparently were convinced that he was still alive, officials said
i understand they were seeing a voodoo man,'' pickens county coroner herbert latham said of the deceased man and his relatives
pickens county sheriff david abston identified the dead man as jessie james latham, 42, not related to the coroner
the body was discovered in a bedroom in a mobile home wednesday by county health workers, authorities said. the coroner said the man had been dead about three weeks
he was pretty well decomposed at the time and the odor all around the trailer was pretty strong,'' abston said. ``some of the kids playing in the yard were wearing face masks, like in an operating room.''
the coroner said the dead man's relatives ``tried to convince me that he was still alive, that god was dealing with him, that he was fine.''
this was a weird case,'' he said sunday, a day after the body was buried
the coroner said that although no foul play was suspected, he was awaiting hospital records from new york, where latham had received some treatment, before announcing the cause of death
the coroner said latham apparently was aware he was suffering from a fatal disease. the autopsy did not reveal the exact disease, he said
abston said latham returned to alabama recently from new york, and was picked up at the tuscaloosa airport by his sister, catherine latham, who took him to a motel in reform. the two stayed there for two weeks
dilip bhakta, the motel manager, said he never saw latham, but asked latham's sister to leave the motel feb. 2 ``because of the smell.''
she never would let anyone come in the room and would meet our maids at the door to get materials,'' bhakta said
bhakta said the odor ``was very strong, very offensive'' and that there were several complaints from other guests
ms. latham said she took her brother to a man in hale county who told him to drink goat's milk with some pills he gave him. she said she took her brother to the mobile home on feb. 2
the nine occupants of the trailer included two infants and several teen-agers, the coroner said
ms. latham dismissed the claim that her brother was treated by a ``voodoo doctor.''
abston said she told him that her brother was alive when he was moved and did not die until the day authorities found his body
l.c. keasler, director of the pickens county department of human resources, said agency workers went to the trailer feb. 14 after an anonymous tip, but were refused entrance. the agency workers returned wednesday with police
asked if any supernatural elements or voodoo were involved in latham's treatment, his sister told the tuscaloosa news on saturday: ``i don't like to use that word. i'm not working for the devil _ i work for god
all i could do was minister to him. he's in god's hands now.''
now that the new york post has been saved, readers and employees wonder what the nation's oldest continuously published newspaper will look like under the new owner, and whether he'll stop its money-losing ways
peter kalikow, who is buying the tabloid from rupert murdoch for $37.6 million, spent sunday talking with advisers about what direction to take the post
the paper's 10 unions agreed saturday to $22 million in concessions that murdoch and kalikow said were necessary to keep the paper alive. that includes eliminating 130 of the post's 1,200 jobs
kalikow is widely thought to want to back away from the paper's emphasis on stories of sex, crime and scandal
it will remain a tabloid, but ``there will be a change in format,'' said his spokesman, howard rubenstein. ``there'll be changes in headlines, in the front page, in the emphasis of the paper.''
but, rubenstein added, kalikow ``still wants it to be feisty and provocative.''
murdoch bought the paper in 1976 and fashioned it after the british tabloids. soon readers were seeing such headlines as ``headless body in topless bar,'' which ran above a story about a homicide in a tavern
they saw a photo of prince rainier of monaco looking into, and making an obscene hand gesture at, a post photographer's lens. the caption read: ``the prince gives us the finger.''
and then there was the story about libyan leader moammar gadhafi's reported psychological problems, featuring a photograph doctored to show readers what he would look like dressed as a woman, complete with lipstick and earrings
kalikow, a real estate developer and businessman worth an estimated $500 million, has approved a $2 million promotional campaign for the newspaper, said rubenstein
according to his agreement with murdoch, kalikow promised to keep the post in operation for at least one year after he takes over march 7
the post lost about $17 million before taxes last year, and about a quarter of its advertising in the last few months. its circulation has dropped from 700,000 to 500,000, partly because of a retrenchment in areas outside metropolitan new york
a $1 million marketing study commissioned by kalikow ``shows the paper already appeals to a fairly well-to-do audience,'' rubenstein said. clarify that hezbollah is also shiite. picks up 8th graf, `the demands, ... '' subs 26th graf, `unifil units ...,' with 3 grafs to update with plo saying it also looking for higgins. picks up 27th graf, `higgins was ...' edits to tighten thruout.</note>
a pro-iranian extremist group today released a videotaped message from a kidnapped u.s. marine colonel calling on president reagan to meet his captors' demands
the 70-second tape from the organization of the oppressed on earth was accompanied by a typewritten arabic statement reiterating the group's claim that the hostage, lt. col. william r. higgins, is a cia agent
the arabic statement also warned lebanon's mainstream shiite moslem militia, amal, to stop searching for higgins, 43, of danville, ky., who was abducted wednesday near the southern port city of tyre
amal, which continued its search today, has taken into custody dozens of members of hezbollah, lebanon's most radical shiite group. hezbollah, which is believed to be the umbrella organization for pro-iranian groups holding most of the 24 foreign hostages in lebanon, on sunday declared support for higgins' captors
hezbollah and amal militimen clashed in a brief firefight sunday. no casualties were reported in the half-hour shootout in the southeastern village of ein el-tineh
in the videotape delivered today to a western news agency in beirut, an unshaven higgins appears to be reading from a statement. the statement by higgins says reagan ``has to take responsibility for the crimes he has committed against the oppressed people in the region.''
in the statement, higgins then lists the same demands his captors made when they first claimed his abduction friday in a statement that called the colonel a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the spying charge
the demands, as given by higgins, are:
_israel's withdrawal from the self-proclaimed security zone it carved out in southern lebanon when the bulk of its army withdrew from lebanon in 1985, ending a three-year invasion
_the release of all detained lebanese and palestinian ``mujahedeen,'' or holy warriors, from the khiam detention camp in the security zone and in israeli jails. an estimated 300 detainees are believed held at khiam
_an end to what they call u.s. intervention in lebanon and to u.s. diplomatic missions to the middle east
secretary of state george p. shultz is to travel to the region this week to present a peace plan aimed at ending 10 weeks of rioting by palestinians in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
the statement accompanying the videotape calls on justice minister nabih berri's amal militia to call off its search for higgins in southern lebanon
we call on our brethren in amal to understand the dangerous espionage role higgins was carrying out, profiting from the u.n. observer role,'' the statement says. in an earlier statement given to a beirut newspaper, the group said it was ``lying in wait for any other suspicious american.''
a decorated vietnam veteran and one-time assistant to former defense secretary caspar weinberger, higgins heads a 76-man observer group attached to a u.n. peacekeeping force in south lebanon
his abduction has stirred tension between amal and hezbollah, which has been challenging amal's dominance in southern lebanon
amal has rejected the kidnappers' charge that higgins is a spy, saying in a statement that most abductions by extremist shiite factions in lebanon were motivated by a desire to extract ransoms
in washington, reagan on sunday night said, ``we're doing everything we can and exploring every avenue'' to free higgins
higgins' abduction prompted the u.n.'s interim forces in lebanon, or unifil, to withdraw 20 observers to its headquarters in naqoura, near the israel-lebanon border, said timor goksel, spokesman for unifil
the rest of the observer group, which is required to be unarmed, remained sunday in positions overlooking beirut's green line, which divides the city into moslem and christian sectors, he said
the palestine liberation organization meanwhile declared it was working for higgins' release
in an interview today in tunisia, plo leader yasser arafat said he had given instructions to his colleagues in lebanon to contact the kidnappers
in general i can say it was one of the fanatic lebanese groups'' that was responsible for the abduction, he said on cbs-tv's ``this morning.''
higgins was the third u.n. official abducted in south lebanon in three weeks. jan stening, 44, of sweden and willian jorgensen, 58, of norway, both employees of the u.n. relief and works agency that cares for palestinian refugees, were kidnapped feb. 5 about 25 miles north of tyre
there are 22 other foreigners missing in lebanon, including eight americans, four frenchmen, three britons, two west germans, an irishman, an italian, an indian and two unidentified men
the longest held is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
at least a fifth of the nation's parents would refuse to send their children to school if a classmate contracted aids, according to a survey by louis harris and associates
the poll, conducted for children magazine, also found more than half of the parents would want to know the identity of young aids victims in their community, and all but 6 percent believe schools should educate youngsters about the deadly disease
the pollsters surveyed 411 parents with children 3 to 18 years old between oct. 23 and oct. 25. the survey has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points
according to the poll, 21 percent of parents would keep their children home if a classmate contracted acquired immune defeciency syndrome; 66 percent would allow their youngsters to continue attending classes; and 12 percent were uncertain or would need to weigh the circumstances to decide
experts with the federal centers for disease control insist aids is not transmitted through casual contact but through sex, contaminated blood products and tainted hypodermic needles, and infected pregnant women can give it to their fetus
but a few cases, including a child in pennsylvania's rural monroe county, have no easily explained source for the virus, which destroys the body's ability to fight infection
scientifically, you could not make the statement that it would be impossible to contact aids from casual contact with a classmate,'' said lester lave, a professor of economics at carnegie-mellon university in pittsburgh and past president of the society of risk analysis
but it seems extremely unlikely. we lose kids every year in school bus accidents. we haven't lost any kids from a casual contact with aids,'' he said
the survey also found that 56 percent would want to know the identity of aids victims enrolled in school, while 39 percent believe the information should remain confidential, as required by federal law
parents believe the special nature of the disease requires extraordinary steps on the part of school districts
according to the survey, 94 percent of the parents say schools need to educate teachers and students about the disease, even if no one in the district has contracted aids
i think that's a virtual mandate for schools to get information out for teachers and students to understand,'' said michael r. kagay, vice president of the harris organization
currently, 17 states require aids education in public schools
the figures from various parts of the country differ
in the west, 74 percent of the parents would allow their children to attend school with an aids victim; in the midwest, the figure is 70 percent; and in the east the percentage drops to 60 percent
kagay believes the concentration of the disease in large cities, particularly on the east coast, accounts for the difference
what you are seeing here is the nearness of the threat,'' kagay said. ``so the stronger the threat or the closer to home, the more reluctant parents may be to send their kids to school.''
official estimates of the number of children with aids vary from 300 to 500, according to the magazine. but dr. james oleske of children's hospital in new jersey in newark believes up to 3,000 children now carry the virus and half suffer from the disease. to imports, sted exports. picks up 4th graf, `in that .. .'</note>
official corruption linked to the drug trade is spreading around latin america, giving an anxious edge to longstanding predictions the illegal traffic could damage the region's political stability
because the people who produce and deal in cocaine, marijuana and heroin are so wealthy, the law enforcement agencies entrusted with the fight against them are often outmatched
indeed, bolivian president victor paz estenssoro estimates cocaine brings in $600 million each year to his nation, compared to $500 million for all legal exports combined
in that impoverished south american country alone, about 400,000 farmers, merchants and others depend directly or indirectly on coca leaf farming and cocaine for their livelihood
allegations that the drug trade is providing funds for candidates has become an issue in this year's election in venezuela. an outburst of drug-related violence in colombia has led to calls for the government to be given special powers to combat it
bolivia, colombia and mexico have for some time been known as notorious centers of drug production and trafficking
but in recent months, cases and allegations of officials playing an integral role in the drug trade have emerged in once overlooked countries _ honduras, haiti and panama
and after a period of relative calm, drug cases proceeding in the u.s. judicial system are once again having a major impact on relations between washington and many latin american nations
unfortunately, much the united states does these days becomes buried in ideological rhetoric which has nothing whatever to do with the issue at hand,'' said a recent editorial in the daily nation, the largest newspaper in the caribbean island nation of barbados
traditionally, the response from governments and observers in the region is to call for the united states to look more closely at how to control american drug consumers, whose dollars provide the basic incentive for the trade
in a recent editorial, the mexican government news agency notimex said the money floated in the drug trade approximates the total amount of debt service payments made by latin american countries each year _ something in the neighborhood of $47 billion
that figure shows the economic magnitude that the networks of narcotics trafficking have, and the use of planes, ships, weapons and a great deal of money to bribe officials and judicial authorities,'' the editorial said. ``however, the principal problem is the enormous consumption of drugs that exists in the united states, and that reaches $110 billion.''
gen. manuel antonio noriega, chief of the defense forces of panama and the power behind his country's nominally civilian government, was named in two florida indictments feb. 5 for racketeering and other drug-related charges
allegations of his involvement in a wide range of illicit activities, including drug trafficking and money laundering, have played a role in protests against his rule that began in june
in retaliation for the steady attacks from washington, noriega's supporters have called for the ouster of the southern command, headquarters for all u.s. military activities in latin america
the pentagon, meanwhile, has described as ``isolated cases'' the recent discovery of two cocaine shipments aboard u.s. military aircraft based in panama, saying they did not appear linked to official corruption in that country
in honduras, a key u.s. ally in central america, the government and armed forces have responded with indignation to newspaper accounts alleging links between the military and drug traffickers
i am free of any guilt,'' gen. humberto regalado hernandez, chief of the honduran armed forces, said in a telephone interview. ``i will not deceive my own people.''
haitian col. jean-claude paul, who runs an army unit known as his country's most brutal, was named by a miami businessman as haiti's main cocaine trafficker. the businessman, osvaldo quintana, told reporters he also knew of involvement by higher haitian officials
testimony at the trial of reputed colombian drug kingpin carlos lehder rivas in jacksonville, fla., has implicated prime minister lynden o. pindling of the bahamas
nine mexicans were indicted in january in los angeles in the 1985 kidnap-murder of american drug agent enrique camarena salazar, while a san diego case a week later named seven mexicans among 12 foreign nationals said to be behind a major cocaine ring
we insist that it will not be possible to defeat international drug trafficking unless production, distribution and consumption are attacked with similar strength and effectiveness,'' president miguel de la madrid said at his feb. 13 meeting with president reagan. ``this final link (consumption in the united states) continues to have a determining influence in the criminal chain.''
it looks like (u.s. officials) are taking the problem seriously but they're not,'' bayardo ramirez monagas, president of venezuela's national commission on drug abuse, said in an interview. ``the problem is not production or consumption, but the financing.'' 1,500 meter speed skating, sted 5,000 meter. a longer version moved on the sports wire.</note>
he didn't win the 6.0 scores that signal an absolutely flawless program. but to figure skater brian boitano, his gold medal-winning performance at the olympics was the ultimate ``10.''
this time, it was perfect,'' the 24-year-old californian said one day after he defeated friend and rival brian orser of canada to become the only u.s. olympic gold medalist. the united states' only other medals have been a bronze in the figure skating pairs and a silver in 1,500 meter speed skating
for the first time in my life it looked better than it felt,'' boitano told a news conference sunday, after watching a video of his triumphant performance. ``i'm usually so critical of myself that i thought i'd see things i'd done wrong
instead ... it was the first time i could say the jumps were the best i've done and i could say, `hey, what a good program.' it's something you build for for years and when it happens ... it's the ultimate.''
saturday night's dramatic ``battle of the brians'' capped 10 years of skating rivalry that saw boitano lose the last two meetings, at skate canada last fall and at the 1987 world championships. each man selected his own military music and battle colors _ blue for boitano, red for orser
boitano, from the solemn opening notes from carmine coppola's ``napoleon'' to the final seconds when he thrust his fist in the air and wiped away a tear of elation, shone throughout
the four-time american titlist was first with five of the nine judges, to orser's four. although they tied in points, the judges gave boitano the victory on better technical marks
writing about his future for usa today newspaper, boitano said: ``it's kind of scary because you know your life is going to change, and you don't know if you're ready for it or if you want it to change.''
money, from commercial endorsements or other appearances, was not the reason behind his drive to win the gold, he wrote for today's edition. ``i'm sure i'll do some things with it, but it's not why i treasure it.''
it's going to be different when i go home. it's kind of scary thinking about what it's going to be like when i get back to san francisco, wondering if i'll be able to slip in and out everywhere without being recognized. i worry about privacy, about always being on show. `brain boitano seen drinking a wine,''' he said
a british soldier was arrested today after he fatally shot a civilian in the back as the man walked to a football match, the army said
the army said the soldier was in an observation tower sunday at a permanent military checkpoint a half-mile from the irish border
from the tower he took a shot at the man, aidan mcanespie, who was walking to a weekly gaelic football game in the village of aughnacloy, county tyrone
the 23-year-old died on the road before medical aid or a priest could reach him, police said
police said the soldier was arrested and was being interrogated. villagers said mcanespie belonged to the roman catholic minority in the british-ruled, protestant-majority province
the army said it ``deeply regrets'' the incident. it gave no other information and did not identify the soldier
it was cold-blooded murder _ i saw mcanespie shot in the back,'' said anthony mcgonnell, a councilman
francis molloy, another councilman, said mcanespie was an election worker for sinn fein, political arm of the outlawed irish republican army fighting british rule
molloy said mcanespie claimed to have been repeatedly harassed and threatened by the security forces
he said he was afraid the security forces would carry out their threats,'' molloy said
the shooting further strained relations between britain and the irish republic government in dublin. dublin called immediately for details of the killing
the irish government, which regards itself as responsible for the catholic minority in the north, has been angered by two recent developments
the british court of appeal recently upheld the convictions of six irishmen jailed for life for two bombings that killed 21 people on the british mainland in 1974. the irish republican army claimed responsibility for the blasts
britain also decided not to prosecute any northern ireland police officers connected with the police shootings of six unarmed catholics in an alleged ``shoot-to-kill'' policy against guerrilla suspects
the ira is fighting to end british rule in northern ireland and unite the province with the irish republic, which is predominantly roman catholic
fidel castro, in an interview published today, flatly denied presidential aspirant pat robertson's charge that the soviet union has nuclear missiles in cuba
in the interview, published in usa today, castro told the newspaper's chairman, allen h. neuharth, that there ``is not even a semblance of a soviet missile in cuba. not one. i repeat, not one.''
he also said in the weekend interview, conducted in havana, that talk of such missiles is ``insane.''
castro was asked about robertson's recent assertions that 25 intermediate-range soviet ss-4 and ss-5 missiles, armed with nuclear warheads, have been stationed in cuba. the white house subsequently said it had ``no indication'' of any nuclear weapons being in cuba
indeed, castro said in the interview, ``with your sophisticated satellite spying, you know when a cat is walking on the roof of a house in cuba.''
