rescuers struggled in the rain early today to find survivors in the rubble of a collapsed apartment building in rio, where three days of mudslides and flash floods have killed at least 80 people
mayor roberto saturnino braga said the mud, water and debris made the city look like ``a giant stepped through'' the area
officials said the flooding, the worst in the city's history, had rendered homeless at least 11,000 of rio's 5.6 million residents, washing ramshackle homes down steep slopes and turning streets into raging torrents
throughout the city, army trucks and volunteers helped transport evacuated dwellers of precarious hillside shantytowns to temporary shelters in schools, churches and public buildings
citizens throughout the nation, prompted by all-night appeals on three commercial tv networks, donated truckloads of medicine, food, clothing and building supplies to the victims
using sledgehammers and chain saws, drenched firefighters worked frantically early today to pull people out of the concrete remains of a three-story, six-apartment building in the abolicao district
the dwelling was hit by a mudslide sunday night that killed at least 11 inhabitants in an avalanche of concrete and plaster
by sunday night, 9.6 inches of rain had fallen on the city since friday, when the flooding began
braga postponed the post-carnival reopening of schools and asked private employers to give their workers today off, saying the city could not handle a normal flux of traffic
health secretary jose noronha warned there might be an outbreak of leptospirosis, a group of sometimes fatal diseases that can cause fever, vomiting, anemia and bleeding of the skin and mucous membranes. leptospirosis is best known as weill's or swineherd's disease and is spread from animals to man. noronha told residents to boil drinking water and said the government would vaccinate for typhoid and tetanus
the building that collapsed in abolicao was in a lower-middle-class area. but most victims of the storms were poor people who had lived in shacks built on the city's steep mountainsides
water, mud and boulders washed many such shacks down the steep slopes and turned streets below into raging torrents and even lagoons
i can't even imagine what will happen to this city if the rains continue,'' said vice mayor jo rezende. ``the situation is desperate. we estimate 50,000 people will have to be given new housing in safer areas.''
at the collapsed building in abolicao, rescue workers trudged through knee-deep mud and rubble searching for victims. at least 13 people were rescued
in another district, rescue workers were forced to temporarily abandon their search for elderly patients and hospital staff killed when a mudslide wiped out a three-floor wing of the santa genoveva hillside clinic
although 350 mostly older patients were in the hospital when the slide occurred saturday, civil defense officials said only about 30 were missing
in the same district santa teresa, an eight-floor apartment building threatened to topple and was evacuated, engineers said
although the hillside slums that are home to about 2 million people were hardest hit, wealthy areas also suffered serious damage. evacuations were ordered after flooding hit the wealthy gavea, lagoa and jardim botanico districts
torrents raged down streets, prompting some people to tie their cars to posts to prevent them from being swept away. civil defense workers used amphibious vehicles and surfboards to reach people in partially submerged cars
meteorologists said the downpour, caused by an antarctic cold front, was likely to continue through today
earlier this month, 207 people died in flooding and mudslides around the state and 13,000 were left homeless. the worst-hit area was petropolis, a mountain resort town 40 miles north of rio. support</head>
a baby born with nearly no brain was on life-support equipment today as a potential organ donor, after a similar infant was taken off life support machinery, officials said
both newborns, born with the birth defect known as anencephaly, or severely underdeveloped brains, were part of a controversial program at loma linda university medical center preserving brain-dead anencephalic infants for use as organ donors
the practice has drawn fire from right-to-life groups charging cruelty, and from medical ethicists, who say it is questionable to keep the babies on life support when they have no chance at long-term survival
evelyn keys, born saturday in san antonio, texas, was flown to loma linda that night to be used in the donor program
she arrived just hours after a child identified only as baby john was taken off life support when a worldwide search failed to turn up any needy organ recipients matching his tissue type, said hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell
but one of the infant's heart valves was removed and stored for later use, ms. rockwell said
anencephalic babies usually die shortly after birth, and loma linda, where infant heart transplants have become routine, wants to establish a practice of sustaining such babies so their organs can be transplanted after brain death is certified by two independent physicians
hospital officials said removal of baby john's heart valve was the first use of body parts from a u.s. anencephalic infant. loma linda previously transplanted the heart from an anencephalic baby declared brain-dead in canada
baby evelyn was born to judy keys, 22, and airman todd keys, 21, of the 6993rd electronic security squad at lackland air force base
doctors report baby evelyn is resting comfortably, and although there are some signs of brain stem deterioration, she has not yet met all the criteria of brain death,'' ms. rockwell said today
loma linda is the first hospital in the united states to develop a medical program allowing the practice of sustaining anencephalic infants for transplants
if brain death does not occur within a week of birth, an anencephalic baby will be removed from its respirator and allowed to die naturally
several thousand anencephalic babies are born in the united states each year. their brain stems can sustain basic functions such as breathing for a short time, but death usually occurs within hours or days of birth
loma linda has specialized in infant heart transplants, with 13 babies under the age of four months given new hearts at the hospital. nine have survived
the center, 65 miles east of los angeles, became well known in 1984 when dr. leonard bailey unsuccessfully transplanted the heart of a baboon into an infant known as baby fae. ethiopia</head>
six european relief workers who were abducted by rebels in ethiopia have been released, a medical aid official said today
three irishwomen, two belgians and a dutchman were set free after being kidnapped by the popular front for the liberation of the tigre last thursday, said an official of the medical relief group medicins sans frontieres-belgium
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no details were available and did not specify when the relief workers were freed
earlier today, seyoum musse, head of foreign relations for the london office of the rebel group said the six were in good condition
the whole aim of taking them with us was to show there are millions of people who are beyond the reach of ... isolated symbolic (government) food distribution centers like the one they were stationed at,'' musse said in a telephone interview
the aim is to dispel the government's misinformation that millions are being reached with aid,'' he said, denying that the group's action was an abduction
the government will not allow these workers to go outside the place they work. for this reason we have taken them a few hours away,'' he said. ``they are the guests of millions of starved people.''
the rebels abducted two belgian doctors and a dutch nurse of the international aid group along with two irish nuns and an irish doctor from their base in idaga hamous in tigre, about 340 miles north of the capital addis ababa, the medical group reported sunday
medicins san frontieres is an international non-governmental organization that has medical aid projects in 15 countries in central america, africa, the middle east and asia
a spokesman for the doctors group initially said the relief workers may have been abducted to treat rebel wounded. fighting in the northern province has been intense between the secessionist rebels and the government of lt. col. mengistu haile mariam
musse denied that the workers had been taken to treat wounded
we have our own doctors,'' he said. warning shots; picks up 7th graf pvs: u.s. officials...</note>
a u.s. warship making its maiden voyage on the persian gulf fired warning shots today at a pair of fishing boats that crew members initially believed were attack vessels
a u.s. military official, asking not to be identified, said the landing-dock ship trenton took the action ``after it observed two apparent boghammar-type boats coming toward it,'' about 30 miles off the coast of dubai
he said the trenton issued two verbal warnings, which were ignored, and as the boats approached to within 3,300 yards ``it fired a flare and bursts of .50-caliber machine-gun fire, at which time the craft stopped, then veered off toward the northeast
a helicopter sent up from the frigate john a. moore later confirmed through observation that both were fishing boats and neither was hit or damaged,'' the official added
he said the boats at first appeared to resemble the fast, swedish-built boghammar marin boats frequently used by iran's revolutionary guards to attack commercial ships in the gulf
u.s. warships in the past have fired warning shots to keep unidentified small boats and iraqi aircraft from approaching too close to convoys escorted by the navy
the 17,000-ton trenton had just arrived in the gulf hours earlier carrying about 400 u.s. marines and a contingent of marine attack helicopters
it was accompanied by the missile frigate john a. moore and the gus w. darnell, a 39,000-ton oiler chartered by the u.s. military sealift command. the darnell makes periodic trips into the gulf to pick up fuel oil for u.s. warships
u.s. officials said that because the group included no kuwaiti tankers or other commercial vessels under the u.s. flag, it would not be counted as a gulf ``transit.'' the navy has conducted 35 escorted convoys since last july and the next one is expected to leave kuwait in the next few days
meanwhile, the u.s. gulf operation will get a new commander this week, a 50-year-old career aviator who once headed the blue angels, the navy's elite acrobatic jet team
rear adm. anthony a. less, will become commanding officer of the navy's middle east force in ceremonies saturday aboard a new flagship, uss coronado. the salem, ohio, native replaces rear adm. harold j. bernsen
as commander of the force since july 1986, bernsen oversaw last year's buildup that followed president reagan's decision to re-register 11 kuwaiti oil tankers under the american flag to protect them from attacks by iran
under bernsen, the force nearly tripled in size, from about six to 17 warships. it was recently cut back to 16
the united states has been escorting kuwaiti vessels since last summer. the only mishap occurred during the first convoy when the supertanker bridgeton struck a mine, believed laid by iran, on july 24. since then, the navy has escorted 34 other convoys without a hitch
iranian ships frequently stop and search vessels they suspect of carrying cargo for iraq. iran also attacks neutral ships in retaliation for iraqi air raids on iran's oil shipping in the gulf. the two nations have been at war for 7{ years
the last such raid claimed by iraq was last tuesday, and no ship attacks by iran have been reported since feb. 11
less takes over a command being drastically reshaped for the second time in the past several months
on feb. 3 he relieved rear adm. dennis brooks as commander of the joint task force middle east, a shipboard headquarters created last year to improve coordination between the gulf-based ships and two supporting battle groups in the arabian sea
well-informed navy officers, speaking on condition of anonymity, say the system failed because of operational conflicts between the gulf and task force commanders
although the middle east force is a surface unit, u.s. law requires any ship with extensive air capability, such as the 16,912-ton coronado and the 15,000-ton la salle, which it replaces, to be commanded by an aviator
less flew a-7 corsair attack bombers from the carrier kitty hawk during the vietnam war and in 1973 became the first commanding officer of the blue angels when the flight demonstration team was formally made a squadron. he served as its commander and flight leader for three years
less later commanded the oil tanker wichita and the attack carrier ranger, operating in the western pacific and the indian ocean with the u.s. seventh fleet. since last august, he had commanded a carrier group and battle group
bernsen, a boston native, and specialist in aerial electronic surveillance, served five tours aboard the carrier forrestal in the mediterranean. he was commanding officer of the la salle _ later his own flagship _ during the 1979 u.s. hostage crisis in iran and the start of the iraq-iran war in 1980. and with trial beginning.</note>
explosions apparently caused by firebombs rocked a nursery school and a morgue early today in paris, causing extensive damage but no injuries, firefighters reported
a previously unknown group called committee of international revolutionary solidarity claimed responsibility for the morgue explosion, radio station rtl reported. the explosions came on the day that a trial of seven alleged french terrorists began
police said the explosion at the morgue, called medical-legal institute, occurred at about 5:30 a.m. a guardian and his family who live at the institute were awakened by the blast but not hurt
about half an hour later and a mile to the northeast, a second blast hit the ground floor of the wake-up school, a private nursery school in the lower middle-class charonne district east of the bastille
no one was at the school
fires at both locations were rapidly brought under control by firefighters
there was no immediate report of a claim of responsibility for the second explosion, and no indication why the nursery school or the morgue might have been chosen as targets
police refused to confirm that leaflets, claiming responsibility for the blast, had been found at the morgue
the radio station quoted the leaflets as saying ``although we are not sympathizers of direct action, we are against the state as arms dealer and a society that profits from death.''
direct action, the best-known extreme left terrorist group in france, was effectively dismantled by a series of arrests last year
the fourth trial this month of direct action members opened this afternoon, with seven people charged in the 1983 robberies of a jewelry store and a bank
jean-marc rouillan, one of four leaders of the group who have been on a hunger strike for 84 days but kept alive with transfusions, is among the seven defendants. confirming protester punishment edict, details of second memorial troops looking for agitators prior to shultz visit, additional injury in ramallah; picks up 15th graf pvs: ``a molotov...'' pls note keyword line was incorrectly given as israel-violence in 1st ld-writethru, a0529.</note>
palestinians held memorial services today for the 61 arabs killed by israelis troops, and israel's attorney general ruled soldiers could not use force to punish or humiliate protesters
two palestinians were wounded in clashes with soldiers in the west bank city of ramallah and the gaza strip refugee camp jabaliya, hospital officials said
in the gaza strip city khan yunis, an israeli civilian fired in the air after his car was stoned by protesters, an arab reporter said
the army said it was checking both reports. it also said an arab was arrested after trying to stab an israeli soldier in ramallah, the third such attack in four days
leaflets distributed in the occupied territories declared a ``martyrs' day'' today and called for demonstrations and a strike this week to protest the visit to israel by u.s. secretary of state george shultz
army officials said the five-day shultz visit, scheduled to begin thursday, might prompt an escalation of violence
it's not organized or systematic, but outside events like the shultz visit do affect the situation,'' an army spokeswoman said on condition of anonymity
jerusalem police spokesman rafi levy said 1,500 additional officers brought in from other areas had been deployed in the holy city to curb arab violence
israeli troops entered the arab neighborhood of silwan at the foot of the mount of olives and cleared away makeshit barricades, while national police went door-to-door checking identifications and looking for agitators
attorney general yosef harish sent a letter to defense minister yitzhak rabin saying soldiers may not use force as a means of punishment or humiliation, said justice ministry spokeswoman etty eshed
orders that call for such use of force are illegal, ruled harish, who demanded rabin issue appropriate instructions to the troops
ms. eshed said harish decided to take action after many palestinians complained to him about abuse by soldiers
in an army survey, 65 percent of soldiers questioned said they had witnessed rough treatment of palestinians by troops, said the army's chief psychologist, col. shlomo dover, on israel radio
we don't have problems with the motivation of soliders ... not that they rejoice to do it, but it's an assignment that has been given to the army and that's how it is seen by the soldiers,'' he said
since the wave of protests began dec. 8 in the territories israel seized in the 1967 middle east war, israelis have killed 61 palestinians. the latest fatalities were two men shot and killed by soldiers sunday
the government has spent $330 million, or 1 percent of the government's 1988 budget, in an attempt to quell the violence
palestinians held memorial services monday to mark arabs killed by israeli soldiers
about 1,500 arabs marched through kfar naama in the west bank to mourn the loss of the second village to die in the violence that began dec. 8. marchers listened to a series of defiant speeches condemning israel's occupation and renamed one of the roads, the street of the martyrs of the uprising
no soldiers appeared, and no violence was reported
in another memorial service today, women marched to a cemetery in the west bank village of anabta to honor three residents who died in clashes with the army earlier this month
a molotov cocktail was thrown at an israeli car in the west bank town of ramallah, but no one was injured, the army said
in the gaza strip refugee camp of jabaliya, soldiers clashed with protesters, and a 14-year-old boy was shot in the thigh, doctors at gaza city's shifa hospital said
in gaza city, anti-american slogans painted in red on closed store shutters read: ``no to the shultz visit. yes to the palestinian government. yes to the plo.''
the palestine liberation organization has ordered palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip not to meet with shultz, saying he is pro-israeli and has rejected minimal palestinian demands
but local palestinian leaders said today that they were trying to persuade plo chief yasser arafat to lift the ban. u.s. officials met with several palestinian representatives over the weekend to discuss the shultz visit
during his visit, shultz will present to israeli leaders a u.s. peace initiative calling for an international forum for direct talks on palestinian self-rule and negotiations on a final settlement by december
but prime minister yitzhak shamir told european jewish leaders sunday night he objected to the hurried pace: ``any attempt to force the pace and shorten the period (of self-rule) would be a detriment to the very essence of the agreement.''
he also indicated he would not give in to pressure to accept the american plan: ``when the time comes for decisions, we shall decide on the basis of what is in our national interests.''
the supreme court today agreed to study a key affirmative action issue _ the power of local governments to require minority participation in public works projects
the justices said they will hear an appeal by richmond, va., officials seeking to revive a so-called set-aside program for construction industry businesses owned by minorities
the court previously expressed interest in examining the issue when on jan. 19 it asked the justice department to comment on a construction company's challenge to a set-aside program in the miami area
but the justices stopped short of announcing whether they will hear arguments in the miami dispute
in the richmond case, the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last september that the city's preferential treatment for minority businesses approved in 1983 is an unconstitutional form of reverse discrimination
the richmond plan would require the prime contractor on any city building contract to subcontract at least 30 percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least one-half minority owned
the minorities covered by the plan were blacks, hispanics, orientals, indians, eskimos and aleuts
the appeals court, in its 2-1 decision, relied heavily on a 1986 supreme court ruling that struck down an affirmative action plan in michigan designed to protect from lay-offs minority teachers with less seniority than whites
the supreme court in that case said preferential treatment of minorities must be narrowly tailored to avoid hurting whites. the court restricted the power of employers to adopt affirmative action programs when there has not been proof those employers practiced past discrimination
supporters of local set-aside programs, on the other hand, point to a 1980 supreme court ruling that congress may require 10 percent of federal public works contracts be earmarked for minority-controlled businesses
an eventual supreme court ruling on local set-aside programs would have far-reaching impact
most states and some 160 local governments have such programs, according to a study by the minority business enterprise legal defense education fund
the 4th circuit court, in striking down the richmond plan, said the city's program was adopted on scant evidence of past discrimination
the appeals court noted that minorities comprise about half of richmond's population and that minority-owned businesses had received less than 1 percent of the value of the city's public building contracts
but the appeals court said there are few minority-owned businesses in the city area, and there was no evidence they had been victims of past discrimination
general population statistics suggest, if anything, more of a political than a remedial basis for the racial preference'' quota in the set-aside program, the 4th circuit court said. ``there has been no showing that qualified minority contractors who submitted low bids were passed over.''
the appeals court also said the 30 percent quota ``was chosen arbitrarily. the figure simply emerged from the mists.''
the richmond ordinance reflects the most casual deployment of race in the dispensation of public benefits. it prefers some, and in so doing diminishes the rights of all,'' the appeals court said
a coalition of groups representing local and state governments urged the supreme court to reinstate the richmond plan
the coalition said it would reopen old wounds and discourage affirmative action if governments must first show past discrimination before adopting remedial programs
the coalition groups are the national league of cities, the u.s. conference of mayors, the national association of counties and the international city management association
richmond's plan was challenged by the j.a. croson co. after its bid _ the only one submitted _ to install stainless steel urinals and water closets at the city jail was rejected
city officials refused to award the contract after croson said there was only one unqualified minority contractor that could help on the project. the company said the cost of the project would rise by $7,663 if the minority contractor were used. the city then called for new bids
the case is richmond vs. croson, 87-998
sara and amy kienast glare at each other over feet propped on the dining room table and argue the finer points of rock 'n' roll music. they both like it, but amy wouldn't be caught listening to rem
and so it goes with the kienast quintuplets: they are so much alike yet so different
sara, amy, abby, ted and gordon turn 18 on wednesday and hope the day marks the end of media-mobbed birthdays and the beginning of separate lives
we've been five all our lives. now is our chance to be one,'' said sara as her brothers and sisters nod in agreement. ``we want to make a name for ourselves, by ourselves.''
after years of press scrutiny, well-publicized financial problems and the suicide of their father, the quints are a steely bunch and proud of it
they also are distinctly individual. each plans to attend a different college and four have picked schools far from the spacious farmhouse in this new york city suburb where they grew up
it's about time,'' abby said with a grin. ``i've been with them for 18 years. i could make do without seeing their faces every day.''
none plans to tell new friends he or she is a quintuplet
why should we have someone look at us and think of four different people,'' said sara
the quints say their separation in the fall will be painless because they all live separate lives now
we basically have the same friends, but we don't hang out with the same people,'' said amy. ``on the weekends, we don't do things together.''
the siblings say that all that sets them apart from other teen-agers is that there are five of them
we have the same fights, you know, that other brothers and sisters have. the girls are always taking my sweaters and stuff,'' ted said to the protests of his sisters
the quints gained worldwide attention when they were born feb. 24, 1970, after their mother, peggy jo kienast, took fertility drugs
at first, many offers of help and endorsement opportunities clothed and fed the children. but financial pressures began a few years later and an anonymous source saved them from eviction by providing more than $115,000 to pay off mortgages and property taxes the kienasts owed
in 1984, the quints' father, william, committed suicide after his plastics business began to falter
at that most difficult time, reporters and photographers camped outside the family's home, making the family angry
i really started to resent the media when dad died,'' said sara. ``there's a limit you can take
i understand now,'' said ted. ``they have a job to do and someone sends them out to get a picture and they have paychecks and families, too. but at the time it was too much.''
despite the unwanted attention, the quintuplets say they appreciated the cards and letters they received from around the world when their father died
they also say they have put his death behind them
we couldn't dwell on it,'' amy said. ``mom wanted us to get on with our lives.''
mrs. kienast says she's looking forward to her children leaving home
i'm all for parenting and children, but i don't live through my children. i'm looking forward to this next step,'' she said. ``you're worn out by their senior year.''
the quints' birthdays _ what ted calls ``press day'' _ have always been met by clicking cameras and a string of interviews. but this year will be different: the quints plan to go their separate ways and celebrate with friends on wednesday, then hold a private family party on sunday
the supreme court today refused to let a texas hospital withhold the names of its blood donors from a woman who says her baby daughter contracted aids after receiving transfusions
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the donors' privacy rights do not override belinda jackson's need to find out their identities in her wrongful-death lawsuit against the hospital
ms. jackson sued the tarrant county hospital district in 1986, alleging that her daughter, tristainne, died of acquired immune deficiency syndrome after receiving blood transfusions in 1983 at john peter smith hospital in fort worth
in pretrial discovery proceedings, ms. jackson sought to find out the identities and addresses of all blood donors whose blood had been used in the treatment of her prematurely born daughter
hospital district officials asked for permisssion to withhold the information, contending that releasing it would violate the donors' privacy rights and threaten the future availability of a volunteer blood supply program
judge william l. hughes jr., who is presiding over the state court case, ruled for ms. jackson in late 1986, but later blocked any disclosure of the blood donors' identities so the hospital district could appeal
a state appeals court also ruled for ms. jackson, and the texas supreme court refused to hear the hospital district's appeal last oct. 7
in the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the hospital district said it is unclear whether restrictions imposed by the state judge would block ms. jackson from asking friends, co-workers and others about intimate and discreet details about the donors' personal lives
the parameters of the constitutional right of privacy of blood donors should be considered and defined by this court,'' the hospital district lawyers said. ``a viable national supply of blood and blood products is at stake.''
the case is tarrant county hospital district vs. hughes, 87-1082
an army colonel accused in the 1986 slaying of a leftist leader surrendered to the military today, military sources said
lt. col. eduardo ``red'' kapunan was placed under house arrest at his residence in suburban quezon city's camp aquinaldo, home of the philippine armed forces, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity
last week, chief of staff gen. renato de villa ordered the arrest of kapunan and three other members of a military group known as reform the armed forces movement in connection with the nov. 13, 1986, slaying of leftist leader rolando olalia and his chauffeur
two of the four remained at large and the other member, navy capt. rex robles, also is under house arrest at camp aguinaldo
a letter purportedly written by kapunan and given to filipino reporters denied he was involved in the slaying of olalia
i am innocent of these charges being leveled against me and i believe this is all part of a grand scheme to discredit all of us who were involved in the february revolution which installed mrs. (corazon) aquino as president,'' it said
kapunan said because he has been implicated in the olalia case he has become an enemy of the kilusang mayo uno, or may first movement, a leftist labor movement that blames the military for olalia's death
meanwhile, robles left his house monday and started to walk with his wife to a post chapel for a mass for members of his movement but military police made him return home, his wife said
the mass marked the second anniversary of the day when then defense minister juan ponce enrile and then-lt. gen. fidel ramos broke with president ferdinand e. marcos as part of the ``people power'' revolution in february 1986 that led to the downfall of marcos and the rise of aquino
last week, members of the military reform movement claimed ramos, now defense secretary, had failed to check corruption during his tenure as military chief of staff and had used his position to increase his personal wealth
ramos has dismissed the allegations made in a letter by the reform the armed forces movement
the supreme court today agreed to decide when police need court warrants before searching from helicopters for marijuana growing in fenced-in yards
the justices said they will study a florida supreme court ruling that a helicopter search by sheriff's deputies in pasco county four years ago violated the right of privacy
the nation's highest court in 1986 ruled that a warrantless search by santa clara, calif., police in an airplane had not violated privacy rights
in that case, police spotted marijana plants growing in a fenced-in yard while flying at a lawful altitude of 1,000 feet
voting 5-4 then, the justices said the constitution's fourth amendment, which bans unreasonable government searches, ``simply does not require the police traveling in public airways at this altitude (1,000 feet) to obtain a warrant in order to observe what is visible to the naked eye.''
in the florida case, pasco county deputies received an anonymous tip that michael a. riley was growing marijuana in his yard
unable to tell what plants were growing in a greenhouse in the yard, the deputies flew over the yard in a helicopter, at an altitude of about 400 feet. from there, they could look into missing panels in the greenhouse roof
based on what they saw, the deputies obtained a search warrant and entered riley's yard, seizing 44 marijuana plants
riley challenged the helicopter search, seeking to block prosecutors from using the marijuana plants as evidence against him
the florida supreme court last july 9 ruled for riley, stating that the helicopter search violated riley's reasonable expectation of privacy under the fourth amendment
the state court said the 1986 decision did not authorize ``an unlimited right to any type of examination of residential property from the air.''
the state court added, ``surveillance by helicopter is particularly likely to unreasonably intrude upon private activities ... because of a helicopter's virtually unlimited maneuverability and observational capabilities.''
it noted that fixed-wing airplanes are not authorized to fly lower than 500 feet in the area where the search occurred
florida prosecutors filed the appeal acted on today
the case is florida vs. riley, 87-764
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether states may tax any income from oil and natural gas extracted from the outer continental shelf
the court said it will hear an appeal by shell oil co. challenging an iowa tax
the state tax is designed to be imposed on that portion of a company's income derived from doing business in iowa
shell oil said it was improper for state officials to include any revenue from offshore gas and oil in determining the company's taxable income
shell said the state tax violates a 1953 federal law authorizing exploration and production of outer continental shelf oil and gas
the shelf is underwater land more than three miles off the shore of any state. the land is owned by the federal government and leased to private companies
the iowa supreme court upheld the state tax last october. it said the levy ``is in no way dependent upon the exercise of legislative jursidiction on outer continental shelf lands'' that the 1953 federal law was intended to prohibit
including revenue from ocs oil and gas ``apparently aids in obtaining an accurate measure of the tax to be imposed as a result of shell's iowa activities,'' the state court said
the reagan administration agreed with the ruling of the iowa court but urged the u.s. supreme court to use shell's appeal to settle the dispute
justice department lawyers noted that the iowa case would be a good one for the high court to use in examining state tax authority because the iowa tax takes into account sales both on and off the outer continental shelf
the case is shell oil vs. iowa, 87-984
the supreme court today refused to reconsider its 4-4 decision last december striking down an illinois law that could have made abortions more difficult to obtain for some teen-agers
the justices, without comment, rejected a request by illinois attorney general neil f. hartigan that they restudy the law ``after the appointment of a ninth justice.''
justice anthony m. kennedy joined the court last thursday, filling an eight-month vacancy. he did not participate in today's order denying reconsideration
despite his 12-year tenure as a federal appeals court judge, kennedy's legal views on abortion are unknown
the high court's decision in december was not accompanied by a written opinion, but merely upheld a ruling that the challenged illinois law impermissibly interfered with abortion rights
such even splits among the justices automatically uphold lower court decisions in the particular cases but set no national precedent
in seeking reconsideration, hartigan emphasized the importance of ``a decision by a full court'' in the case
the illinois law required that girls under 18 and still financially dependent on their parents notify both parents 24 hours before having an abortion
the law allowed a girl to avoid notifying her parents if she could prove to a state judge that she was mature enough and well-informed enough to make the decision on her own and that notifying her parents would not be in her best interest
doctors who failed to comply with the law's requirement faced criminal prosecution
a federal appeals court ruled that the 24-hour waiting period is an impermissible infringement on the right to have an abortion, established by a landmark 1973 supreme court decision
the appeals court also said the illinois law provision for parental notification or judicial permission could not be enforced because it did not ensure confidentiality and anonymity for girls who appeal when a judge denies permission for an abortion
the chauffeur of defense minister jose horacio jaunarena was shot to death when he tried to prevent a robbery aboard a bus, police said
the chauffeur, roquelmo ismael zapata, 57, was heading home in the early morning hours when two armed men boarded his bus in suburban sarandi and demanded the passengers' money and valuables
police said zapata produced his .38-caliber handgun, carried as part of his duties as the defense minister's driver, and a shootout occurred in which zapata was wounded several times. no other casualties were reported, and the gunmen fled, police said
zapata was pronounced dead at finocchieto hospital, officials said
a 24-hour transport strike called by leftist guerrillas virtually halted bus and truck traffic today and drastically curtailed use of automobiles
the strike was called by members of the farabundo marti national liberation front to protest legislative and municipal elections scheduled for march 20. the rebels say the elections are a farce
no buses circulated in this capital of 1 million people. thousands of people walked to work, although some pickup trucks jammed with passengers were on the roads
the army said it doubled motorized patrols to provide security for people who defied the strike
the private radio station ysu said truck and bus traffic nationwide was about 5 percent of normal. from the western provincial capital of santa ana, the radio reported that the stoppage of buses was total
it said two buses of 50 that normally would have been dispatched left the eastern provincial capital of san miguel for other cities
the leftist guerrillas have been fighting the u.s.-backed government since 1979 with a campaign that includes economic sabotage
there were seven guerrilla-imposed transport strikes last year. three strike violators were killed, about 30 were wounded and some 160 vehicles were destroyed or damaged
the supreme court today said it will consider reversing a victory basketball coach jerry tarkanian won in his legal battle with the ncaa
the justices agreed to review a decision barring the ncaa from suspending tarkanian as coach at the university of nevada-las vegas for alleged recruiting and other violations
lower courts also awarded tarkanian substantial reimbursement for legal expenses
tarkanian, who has coached at unlv since 1973 during a highly successful 30-year career, was accused by the national collegiate athletic association in 1976 of numerous rule violations
ncaa officials said tarkanian arranged for a student to get a ``b'' grade without attending class, provided free air fare to a student-athlete, encouraged individuals to give the ncaa false information to impede its probe, falsely certified unlv's program as being in compliance with ncaa rules and failed to comport with high ethical standards
the ncaa placed the unlv basketball program on two years' probation in 1977 for recruiting violations and ordered the university to suspend tarkanian from coaching for two years
but tarkanian obtained a court order blocking the suspension and continued coaching
the nevada supreme court ruled last august that the ncaa violated tarkanian's constitutional rights by failing to afford him due process in its 2{-year investigation
the state court said the probe was based largely on recollections by investigators of interviews with their sources. notes of the interviews sometimes were dictated after the fact, the state court said
it also said tarkanian and unlv officials presented signed affidavits by those the ncaa interviewed in which the witnesses contradicted the ncaa's evidence
in the circumstances of this case, this procedure does not comport with due process requirements,'' the state court said
the state court also ruled that the ncaa, a private organization representing nearly 1,000 colleges and universities, acted in the capacity of the state in depriving tarkanian of his rights
purely private organizations cannot violate anyone's constitutional rights
the nevada supreme court said the ncaa is vested with state power in this case because tarkanian works for a state school
the right to discipline public employees is traditionally the exclusive prerogative of the state,'' the nevada court said. ``unlv cannot escape responsibility for disciplinary action against employees by delegating that duty to a private entity (the ncaa).''
a state court judge awarded tarkanian $200,000 in legal fees. the state supreme court said the the sum should be reduced, and ordered further hearings to determine the amount
in the appeal acted on today, ncaa officials said tarkanian was treated fairly
they also argued that tarkanian got a ``home court'' advantage by taking his case to a nevada state judge who overruled the findings of the ncaa investigators
the judge ruled ``in favor of a popular, local personality'' substituting his views ``for that of 21 independent teachers and administrators who heard all of the evidence,'' the ncaa's appeal said
the case is ncaa vs. tarkanian, 87-1061
flash floods roared through central south africa today, killing at least 12 people and leaving hundreds of others without homes
up to 12 inches of rain soaked parts of orange free state province during the weekend, washing out roads, bursting dams and flooding huge stretches of farmland, authorities said
military helicopters plucked 200 people from houses, trees, cars and areas inaccessible by road, the air force reported
telephone lines were down in many areas, and the city of bloemfontein, the capital of the orange free state, only could be reached by air, officials said
rivers in the region have overflowed their banks and many small towns have been evacuated, officials added. heavy rains were predicted to continue through tuesday, forecasters said
officials said the storm killed 12 people and forced several hundred others to flee their homes
lulu de jager, spokesman for the orange free state agricultural union, said farm damage from the flooding would run into millions of dollars
we will start a survey when the weather clears up, but we may take if for granted that crop and livestock losses have been astronomical,'' de jager said
heavy flooding last september in the southeastern part of the country left more than 300 people dead and 500,000 homeless
the supreme court today agreed to judge the validity of a 5 percent tax illinois imposes on all telephone calls charged to in-state numbers
the court said it will study arguments that the tax interferes impermissibly with interstate commerce
the tax is assessed at a flat rate on all calls, intrastate and interstate, charged to illinois service addresses
two state residents, jerome f. goldberg and robert mctigue, challenged the law in a class-action lawsuit three years ago in chicago. gte sprint communications corp. joined the case later, seeking to recover taxes already paid
from sept. 15, 1985, to july 1986, gte sprint paid $2.6 million in taxes under the challenged illinois telecommunications excise tax
the illinois supreme court upheld the tax last june 24, reversing a state appeals court ruling that had invalidated it
the appeals court had said illinois ``is attempting to tax the entire cost of an interstate act which takes place only partially in illinois.''
the appeals court had added, ``this tax ... discriminates against interstate commerce and it is not related to services provided in illinois.''
the state supreme court acknowledged that illinois is taxing the ``gross charge'' of an entire interstate call ``even though the benefits it affords are limited to that portion of the communication occurring within the state.''
but it said the tax does not unduly burden interstate commerce
the two state residents and gte sprint filed separate supreme court appeals, and the national taxpayers union urged the justices as a ``friend of the court'' to strike down the tax
its brief argued:
if illinois attempted to tax united parcel service on the entire value of its service for all packages picked up in the state, regardless of where they were delivered, that tax would fall before the (constitution's) commerce clause ... telecommunications companies, whether they are in the telephone, telegraph or electronic data transmission business, provide a service which, for many purposes, is functionally identical.''
the cases are goldberg vs. sweet, 87-826, and gte sprint vs. sweet, 87-1101. `passenger sary ....' ^by joe ruff</note>
an amtrak official defended the actions of crew members aboard a train that caught fire over the weekend, saying that despite passenger complaints, several lives may have been saved
passengers aboard amtrak's california zephyr said they received no warnings or instructions from crew members after the fire broke out early saturday, killing a chef and injuring 19 other people
i think our on-board crew's initial instinct was to make sure passengers weren't in any danger from the fire. then they had to get employees out of the car,'' said amtrak spokesman john jacobsen in a telephone interview from washington
we could have easily had four or five employees killed in that dormitory car yesterday,'' jacobsen said
however, the actions of a conductor and his assistant may have saved several lives, jacobsen said
conductor j.p. jones, of arvada, colo., and assistant conductor todd m. witaker of denver separated the crew car from the train's baggage car and engine to reach people endangered by the smoke, jacobsen said
the fire aboard the 14-car westbound train carrying 294 passengers and a crew of 18 was reported about 3 a.m. as the train was pulling into hastings for a scheduled stop. hastings fire chief jim mitera said the blaze was under control about 90 minutes later
passenger sara bentley of fremont said later it was a miracle no one panicked
i think the worse thing was that they didn't let anyone in our car know whether we were in danger,'' ms. bentley said. ``we couldn't find out if our car was safe.''
jacobsen said an amtrak investigation was continuing, and that no disciplinary action had been taken against any crew members. the national transportation safety board also was investigating
jacobsen said the fire may have been caused by luggage or some other flammable material placed near a heater in a crew car, contrary to earlier findings by the nebraska state fire marshal's office that pointed to an electrical short in the heater
amtrak investigators didn't find evidence of a short, jacobsen said. state fire marshal wally barnett said he would stand by the state report
we're fire investigators, and we think we're right,'' barnett said sunday
the victim, identified as chef cesar arguelles, 70, of chicago, was one of seven crew members on the car, jacobsen said. county attorney gary anderberg said an autopsy showed the chef died of smoke inhalation
nine crew members and three passengers were treated for smoke inhalation at mary lanning hospital. all but two had been released by this morning, nursing supervisor mona mueller said. those two were in satisfactory condition and were expected to be released today
jacobsen said the fire probably would prompt amtrak officials to renew their search for an effective smoke alarm for their trains. but no models work now because they are often set off by the constant vibrations of trains, he said
edward s. ``ted'' o'meara, who has a spent a decade as an aide to members of maine's congressional delegation, today launched his own bid for southern maine's 1st congressional district seat
i have done my apprenticeship with the best and i am ready to enter the arena as a candidate in my own right,'' he said
he will oppose l.l. bean heiress linda bean-jones for the republican nomination. the seat is held by democratic rep. joseph e. brennan, a former governor completing his first two-year term
o'meara, 35, worked for rep. olympia j. snowe during her first term in congress and joined sen. william cohen's staff in 1981. he is cohen's executive assistant for maine, with responsibility for six offices in the state and a staff of 16 people. court</head>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that forces ann arbor, mich., city officials to justify in federal court a zoning ordinance limiting where adult bookstores may be opened for business
the court, without comment, refused to hear arguments aimed at squelching a lawsuit challenging the ordinance
the ordinance limits the area where adult bookstores may locate to a portion of downtown ann arbor representing less than 1 percent of the land within the city's 25.3 square miles
adult bookstores are defined by the ordinance as those where sexually explicit materials comprise more than 20 percent of the stock in trade. so any business establishment, anywhere in the city, may have up to 20 percent of its trade in adult materials
karen christy, who sought to operate an adult bookstore in an area not zoned for adult entertainment, sued the city. she sought to block enforcement of the zoning ordinance
u.s. district judge charles joiner refused to block enforcement, ruling that the ordinance is not impermissibly restrictive
the 20 percent requirement provides a beneficial way for decentralization of the adult book business,'' he said. ``by sanctioning the selling of adult books and other books together, the city has eliminated most of the well-known problems of urban blight that result from concentrations of these bookstores without sacrificing its citizens' first amendment freedoms,'' joiner said
but the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last july 23 that joiner was wrong
a city cannot arbitrarily limit the exercise of first amendment rights,'' the appeals court said. ``a limitation of adult materials to 20 percent of a bookseller's wares conditions the constitutional right to speak in one way on the bookseller's willingness to speak in a different way 80 percent of the time.''
the appeals court sent the case back to joiner for further study after saying it found no evidence ``of a legitimate government objective for the passage of this zoning ordinance.''
in the appeal acted on today, city officials argued, among other things, that the constitution's first amendment does not guarantee the existence of adult bookstores if ``the right of access to such materials may be accommodated in other ways.''
the case is ann arbor vs. christy, 87-649. with report that two planes shot down. picks up 3rd graf pvs, `south africa ...' inserts 3 grafs after 6th graf, `during the . ..,' with details of report. picks up 7th graf, `south africa .. .'</note>
the military today said a south african pilot was missing after his plane was shot down in southeast angola during a weekend air raid
the plane was struck by ground fire while attacking cuban and angolan government troops during a battle saturday, the military said. it was the second time during south africa's five-month intervention in angola that it acknowledged losing one of its warplanes inside the country
the angolan news agency angop reported today that angolan government troops shot down two south african jetfighters over the weekend and have scored significant gains in recent battles against south african units and the angolan rebel movement unita
south africa launched two other air attacks saturday in southern angola against bases of the south-west african people's organization, known as swapo, in retaliation for the bombing friday of a bank in south-west africa. the death toll in the bombing reached 20, south-west african police said today
south africa also announced that it followed up the air attacks with long-range mortar bombardments saturday and sunday on swapo positions. the military said the mortar attacks were ``successful,'' but did not disclose any details
south africa occupies south-west africa, also known as namibia, in violation of a united nations resolution. its forces regularly enter angola to raid swapo bases
during the saturday afternoon attack, a plane piloted by maj. edward every was downed by ground fire, the military said, adding that the air raid was staged because the angolan-cuban forces ``posed a potential threat'' to south african troops
the angop report, monitored in lisbon, portugal, identified one of the downed south african pilots as maj. every, and said angolan officials had recovered his personal effects
the report did not specify whether every was in angolan custody, and did not identify the pilot of the other plane, both of which were french-made mirage fighter bombers
in a separate dispatch, angop reported that south african bombing raids caused ``countless deaths'' over the weekend
south africa announced in november that its troops were fighting in angola to support the national union for the total independence of angola, or unita, rebel movement. however, it is widely believed that south african troops began fighting in angola one month earlier, in october
unita has been fighting a 12-year bush war for a power-sharing agreement with angola's marxist government, which is backed by cuban and soviet forces
president eduardo dos santos of angola said sunday that 9,000 south african soldiers are deployed in southern angola. he also said south africa has staged 16 air raids so far this year, and that six south african planes have been shot down and 140 of that nation's soldiers have been killed
south africa has repeatedly refused in recent months to disclose the extent of its military involvement in angola. however, it has announced the deaths of more than 30 soldiers since november
the military said in november that one of its warplanes had crashed in angola while participating in an attack on swapo forces and that another plane had been hit but managed to return to a base in namibia before crash-landing
republican presidential contenders jack kemp and bob dole each collected $1 million or more in contributions during january, leading all the candidates, financial reports showed today
but rival george bush still sits the most comfortably, ending the month with more than $9 million in cash on hand. that compared to $4 million for dole, the senator from kansas, and $446,067 for kemp, the new york congressman who had $1.3 million in debts after paying off $2.5 million with the federal matching funds he got in january
the financial disclosure statement for former television evangelist pat robertson was not on file this morning at the federal election commission, although the reports were due saturday
bush raised $767,892 in contributions for the month, but he also got $6.4 million in federal matching funds based on his total fund-raising from last year. dole got $1.2 million in contributions and $5.6 million in matching funds during january, and kemp raised $1 million in donations, $3.9 million in matching funds and $750,000 in loans
on the democratic side, sen. paul simon of illinois and rep. richard gephardt of missouri both went into february's iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary in debt and had to take out loans
both have said their fund-raising has improved since then
democrats michael dukakis, the massachusetts governor, and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, on the other hand, apparently were in good shape _ dukakis with $4 million in the bank, and gore with $2 million
gore however, while abandoning the iowa race to devote attention to the southern states, raised just $180,746 for the month of january, in addition to the $1.8 million in matching funds he got
dukakis raised $804,839 in contributions and got $3.5 million matching funds
matching funds were released in january based on the candidates' fund-raising for all preceding months
simon's finance director bob edgar said the senator has raised more than $1 million in donations so far this year, and in the two weeks following the feb. 8 iowa contest set a record for his campaign
his report shows that in january he raised $534,259 in contributions, got $1.9 million in matching funds, and $523,674 in loans
gephardt collected $212,702 in contributions and $1.9 million in matching funds
the reports of democrats gary hart and jesse jackson were not on file this morning, nor was that of bruce babbitt, the former arizona governor who dropped out of the race last week
republican pete du pont, the former delaware governor who also dropped out of the running last week, closed his campaign with $564,223 in cash on hand and $59,089 in debts, his report showed
the supreme court today agreed to hear appeals by the reagan administration and coal mining companies seeking to block the possible award of billions of dollars in black lung disease benefits to thousands of miners
the court said it will review a ruling that the government must reopen some previously rejected claims for benefits
the administration said the ruling by a federal appeals court, if extended nationwide, could force officials to re-examine 94,000 claims at potentially tremendous cost to the overburdened fund that pays benefits to miners afflicted with the disease
the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals last march ruled that thousands of miners seeking the benefits had been unfairly denied a hearing
the ruling applied to miners with less than 10 years of work in the mines whose claims were denied in the late 1970s and early 1980s
the appeals court said the u.s. department of labor must take a fresh look at the claims under liberalized standards adopted by congress in 1977. the appeals court applied the ruling to miners who failed to exhaust their administrative remedies or who missed deadlines for filing court appeals
the appeals court said miners seeking benefits ``have encountered enormous frustration in the processing of their claims due to administrative delays and determinations under improper standards. congress has repeatedly attempted to ease the burden of proof of disability and to expedite black lung claims.''
the justice department said the ruling would force the labor department ``to embark on a potentially enormous reopening of closed cases that will impose a massive administrative burden. the records for approximately 94,000 claims would have to be retrieved and analyzed'' if the appeals court ruling were to apply nationwide
the 8th circuit court has jurisdiction in north and south dakota, minnesota, nebraska, iowa, arkansas and missouri
congress has created a special fund to pay off claims for miners with black lung disease, also known as pneumonconiosis
coal mine operators owe the government some $3 billion that has been loaned to the fund from the federal treasury
the operators said the 8th circuit court ruling, if applied nationwide, could burden the industry with $13.6 billion in additional payments
the u.s. treasury ``will be required to borrow the money to pay these claims until the coal industry is able to do so, if that day ever comes.''
in another dispute over black lung benefits, the supreme court in december made it easier for mining companies to block the award of some disability benefits. that decision upheld a labor department rule that miners are not entitled to an interim presumption they were disabled by the disease based on a single piece of medical evidence
the cases acted on today are pittston coal group vs. sebben, 87-821, and whitfield vs. sebben, 87-827. from mother.</note>
police are getting numerous calls from people who say they have seen a 4-week-old girl kidnapped from her mother's home, but so far officers have turned up no suspects
rachael ann white was taken friday when her grandmother left the room while interviewing a woman for a babysitting job
the phone has been ringing steadily at the colorado springs police department with reports from area residents who say they have been the infant with the woman who kidnapped her, but so far police have been unable to trace the infant or her abducter, officer mike stewart said today
cora abbott, mother of the missing baby, said authorities won't tell her specifically ``what they're working on for fear i'll get my hopes up and then it'll turn out to be nothing.''
the most important thing we have is the composite (drawing) of the female suspect. that person has to stop somewhere for gas, groceries. there's got to be someone out there who has information on that person,'' police lt. joe vernier said sunday
no ransom has been sought, police said late sunday
abbott, 27, was working when the abduction occurred. her mother, evelyn reed of canon city, told police she was interviewing a woman for a babysitting job at her daughter's home when the telephone rang
reed said she handed the baby to the woman and went into another room to answer the phone. when she returned the woman was gone
the woman was described as hispanic with reddish-tinted black hair, 5-feet-6 tall, 150 pounds, and 40 to 45 years old. atorney, with other cases, comment.</note>
the supreme court today threw out an appeal by seven tennessee families who say their religious freedom was violated when their children were exposed to ``godless'' public school textbooks
it also agreed to study a key affirmative action issue _ the power of local governments to require minority participation in public works projects
and it agreed to judge the validity of a federal law creating independent counsels to investigate alleged wrongdoing by high-ranking executive branch officials
it was justice anthony m. kennedy's first day on the court, which was at full strength for the first time since last june 26 when justice lewis f. powell retired
the justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that requiring the fundamentalist christian children to read the books was constitutional
today's action essentially ends a widely publicized case some have called scopes ii, a comparison to the furor surrounding the 1925 prosecution of john scopes in tennessee for teaching evolution
the controversy began in 1983, when the hawkins county board of education adopted a new reading list for students in grades 1-8. pupils initially were allowed to read from other textbooks if they desired, but the school board later eliminated that alternative
all county schoolchildren were required to read the chosen textbooks or leave public school
the seven families who filed the appeal acted on today sued the county school board in late 1983, listing more than 300 objections to the assigned readings
the lawsuit objected on religious grounds to themes or passages in such works as ``the wizard of oz'' and ``cinderella,'' science fiction by isaac asminov, fairy tales by hans christian andersen and stories by anthropologist margaret mead, among others
the lawsuit said the books in dispute violated the families' beliefs by teaching evolution, secular humanism, the occult, feminism and other beliefs, theories or philosophies they consider godless
a federal trial judge ruled for the families, finding that their religious freedom had been violated and awarding them $50,000 in damages
he ruled that the children should have been allowed to ``opt out'' of the reading program while enjoying the rest of the public school curriculum
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals reversed that ruling and threw out the families' lawsuit
the only conduct compelled ... was reading and discussing the material ... and hearing other students' interpretation of those materials,'' the appeals court said. ``what is absent from this case is the critical element of compulsion to affirm or deny a religious belief or to engage or refrain from engaging in a practice forbidden or required in the exercise of (any child's) religion.''
in seeking supreme court review, lawyers for the families said the case ``presents a classic confrontation between parents and public school officials over the education of children.''
they said children should not be required to read religiously offensive books as a condition of remaining in school
the appeal likened the families' objections to those made by jehovah's witnesses families that sparked the supreme court's 1943 decision striking down a west virginia law that required all public school students to participate in the daily recitings of the pledge of allegiance
the appeal added, ``the rule emerging from (the 6th circuit ruling) is that children can be forced to read books which violate their sincere religious beliefs so long as they are not forced to believe the contents of what they have read.''
tennessee attorney general w.j. michael cody said expressed pleasure at the decision and said ``any alternative disposition would have been the cause of chaos in the school system.''
but mike farris, attorney for concerned women of america who represented the east tennessee families, called for the removal of all born-again christian children from the public school system as a result of the decision
in the affirmative action case, the justices said they will hear an appeal by richmond, va., officials seeking to revive a so-called set-aside program for construction industry businesses owned by minorities
the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last september that the city's preferential treatment for minority businesses approved in 1983 is an unconstitutional form of reverse discrimination
setting the stage for a major constitutional decision over independent counsels, the justices said they will review an appeals court ruling that the watergate-era law impermissibly gives presidential powers to the federal courts
the decision, expected by july, will affect the criminal conviction of former white house aide michael k. deaver and the stalled investigation of ex-justice department official theodore b. olson
in a separate order, the court rejected marine lt. col. oliver north's latest attempt to block an investigation of his role in the iran-contra affair. it let stand a ruling that north may not halt the criminal investigation by independent counsel lawrence e. walsh by challenging its legality in a civil lawsuit
in other action, the court:
_ refused to let a texas hospital withhold the names of its blood donors from a woman who says her baby daughter contracted aids after receiving transfusions
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the donors' privacy rights do not override belinda jackson's need to find out their identities in her wrongful-death lawsuit against the hospital
_ agreed to hear appeals by the reagan administration and coal mining companies seeking to block the possible award of billions of dollars in black lung disease benefits to thousands of miners
the court said it will review a ruling that the government must reopen some previously rejected claims for benefits
_ let stand a ruling that drastically limits the power of communities to regulate cable television and raises doubts about the constitutionality of a key federal law governing cable operations
the court, citing a lack of jurisdiction, turned away an appeal by two california cities barred from enforcing public access and other rules challenged by a cable operator
_ agreed to decide when police need court warrants before searching from helicopters for marijuana growing in fenced-in yards
the justices said they will study a florida supreme court ruling that a helicopter search by sheriff's deputies in pasco county four years ago violated the right of privacy
the textbook case is mozert vs. hawkins county public schools, 87-1100
president reagan will hold a news conference wednesday night, his first formal meeting with reporters in four months, it was announced today
the press conference will be in the east room at 8 p.m. est. white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan would open the session with a prepared statement and then answer questions for 30 minutes
reagan's last news conference was on oct. 22
a videotape by lt. col. william r. higgins on behalf of demands by his captors was ``obviously ... made under duress,'' the white house said today
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said the tape had been viewed by members of the national security council and white house staff but he did not believe president reagan had seen it
obviously it was made under duress,'' fitzwater said. ``we continue to call for the immediate and safe release of colonel higgins as well as other hostages in lebanon. we are not going to give in to the demands of terrorists. we will continue to pursue all avenues for his release.''
when asked if reagan had any reaction, the spokesman said, ``you know the president's deep convictions about colonel higgins and all the hostages, but we want to avoid saying anything that could exacerbate the situation.'' comment in top 9 grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, the 4,067; subs 9th graf pvs, massachusetts gov.</note>
democratic presidential contender michael dukakis said today at the white house that the reagan administration's anti-terrorist policy is worthless because of arms dealing with iran. in the midwest republican bob dole taunted george bush for refusing to compete in minnesota and south dakota
dukakis, speaking to reporters after a national governors' association meeting with the president, said, ``i'd have a much tougher, and much more consistent anti-terrorist policy.''
the massachusetts governor, referring to the sale of arms to iran during secret negotiations to free american hostages, said, ``we'll be living with the consequences of what happened in 1985 for a long time.''
you never, ever make concessions to terrorism. if you ever do it, then your policy is worthless. and that's what we did,'' said dukakis
asked about dukakis' statement, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``i think it's very dangerous to make terrorism a political issue, especially when you're talking about specific episodes
vice president bush, who has said repeatedly he supported reagan's iran initiative but was involved with few details, was campaigning in south carolina today. but dole, in duluth, minn., was suggesting bush wasn't where he should have been
minnesota and south dakota, the next two events on the long road to the 1988 presidential nominations, vote on tuesday
we're ready to do well here tomorrow. we're here to play,'' dole told supporters in duluth today
i don't know where george bush is,'' dole said. ``i didn't find him yesterday in wyoming. couldn't find him in south dakota. couldn't find him in minnesota. must be somewhere. and these are very important states. later today we're going to send him a map of minnesota so at least he gets a little idea where it is.''
among the democrats, richard gephardt, who also finished first in iowa, is bidding for a strong showing in south dakota's democratic straw poll to give him a boost as the campaign moves toward the super tuesday showdown on march 8
the 4,067 minnesota caucuses are the first step toward choosing 78 delegates to the democratic national convention, while on the republican side caucus attendees will mark a non-binding straw ballot to express their presidential preference
in south dakota's primary, republican voters will determine allocation of 18 convention delegates, while the democrats will hold a beauty contest ballot that will not have a binding effect on who gets the state's national convention delegates
bush, faced with the potential of a repeat of the iowa results in which midwesterner dole was a big winner, is concentrating on the south where he hopes to cripple the kansas senator's effort
dole is a strong favorite in south dakota, while minnesota is shaping up as a three-way fight between dole, rep. jack kemp of new york and former television evangelist pat robertson
dukakis, winner of the new hampshire democratic presidential primary, is campaigning hard in both these upper midwest states in an effort to prove he can win support outside his native new england
after an appearance at the national governors association meeting in washington, including a session with president reagan, dukakis was flying to minnesota to campaign
on his way into the white house for a black-tie dinner sunday night, dukakis quipped, ``i'm just looking the place over, that's all.'' asked where he hoped to be next year, dukakis replied, ``i hope right here
gephardt, who has made tough action to correct trade imbalances a cornerstone of his campaign, got a blow from his house colleagues when words came out they planned to scuttle his legislation that would impose sanctions on countries that maintain large trade surpluses with the united states through unfair practices
we're going to dump it because it's bad policy,'' said rep. sam gibbons, d-fla., chairman of the trade subcommittee of the house ways and means committee
i'm going to fight for my amendment,'' said gephardt, when told of the plan
much of the sniping between presidential rivals was being done by long distance
sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, who made little effort in iowa and not much more in new hampshire while pursuing a southern strategy for the democratic nomination, was interviewed on the nbc show ``meet the press'' on sunday and got in jabs at both dukakis and gephardt
the senator attacked gephardt for shifting positions. ``it's not a case of just having one or two or three issues where he has changed 180 degrees,'' said gore. ``there is a long, long list of issues.''
turning to dukakis, gore said the governor has not had ``a single day's experience in foreign policy.''
dukakis' spokesman leslie dach quickly retorted that ``al gore's never had a day of experience balancing a budget or building an economy.''
gephardt was attacking dukakis in ads running in south dakota that criticize the massachusetts governor for not supporting farm legislation sponsored by gephardt and iowa sen. tom harkin. the ads also take a shot at dukakis for once suggesting in iowa that farmers ought to consider diversifying into such crops as belgian endive
the ads drew retorts from dukakis supporters in both minnesota and south dakota
a new low in south dakota presidential politics,'' said state sen. roger mckellips, a co-chairman of dukakis' south dakota campaign
after his surprising second-place finish in the iowa caucuses, robertson was considered a strong contender in minnesota where caucus organization is once again important
