pentecostal leaders and worshipers expressed sympathy, jim bakker offered advice, tammy bakker cried and jessica hahn said she was shocked after tv evangelist jimmy swaggart quit his pulpit because of a reported sex scandal
swaggart tearfully told his congregation in baton rouge, la., on sunday that he would leave his ministry ``for an undetermined, indeterminate period of time'' because he had sinned
many members of the congregation gathered around swaggart after the service to cry, pray and hold hands
i think he's truly repentant. and i think he's set a tremendous example for all of us of what true repentance is about,'' said congregant evelyn murray
swaggart said the future of his ministry was up to the lord and officials of his denomination, the assemblies of god, who reportedly were reviewing photographs purporting to show swaggart and a prostitute entering and leaving a motel room
church officials and congregants praised the candor of the evangelist, whose broadcasts reach into more than 100 countries and whose ministry had an income estimated at $142 million in 1986
forest h. hall, secretary-treasurer of the assemblies' he and his wife, tammy, were ``kind of sick to our stomachs'' over the news of swaggart's problems and added, ``our heart goes out to them and their family
my advice to jimmy would be don't do anything for about a month and just pray, and then make decisions. i made a very bad mistake by making decisions too quick,'' bakker said
bakker resigned from his ptl ministry in march and later was defrocked by the assemblies of god after admitting to a sexual encounter with miss hahn, a church secretary
mrs. bakker said she cried when she heard about swaggart's troubles. ``i just felt like i didn't want anyone to suffer the way our family has had to suffer this last year,'' she said sunday. ``we love him and we're praying for him.''
the rev. jerry falwell, who took over the ptl ministry for eight months after bakker left, said: ``i am deeply saddened over this tragedy. with the credibility crisis in recent days involving wall street, the world of politics and the arena of religion, many sincere people have had their faith shattered.''
david clark, the trustee of ptl appointed by u.s. bankruptcy court, said, ``it's hard to assess the impact on the so-called electronic church. i'm sure our telephones will tell us tomorrow what they're thinking.''
miss hahn, who accepted secret payments from ptl to cover up her encounter with bakker, said she expected swaggart's troubles to affect contributors
when they turn on the tv, they're going to see a preacher and wonder if this offering is paying hush money or for a prostitute ... i just feel bad,'' she said
miss hahn said she had heard months ago swaggart was going to be involved in the current controversy, but when she learned of his public confession, ``i almost fell on the floor.''
what shocked me was that he resigned. i feel really bad about this. it hit me. i think that there's too many preachers hanging vendettas over each other,'' she said in a telephone interview from the playboy mansion where she lives in los angeles. highway,'' to update with highways reopened.</note>
a forest fire sparked by a hiker's campfire and fanned by 90 mph gusts slowed today after threatening up to 100 houses near boulder, colo., and a wind-whipped 2,400-acre blaze in montana destroyed at least four houses
no injuries were reported
roads in colorado's sunshine canyon area were closed late sunday and occupants of one apartment building near the blaze voluntarily left the building, as did residents of five homes. but no evacuations were ordered and the roads were reopened today
the fire grew to more than 200 acres of grass and light timber by early today, the boulder county sheriff's department said
the area was under a high wind warning with 90 mph gusts reported. wind had been expected to reach 100 mph today, but at 3 a.m. it subsided to gusts of no more than 30 mph and there was an early morning calm of 6 mph, the national weather service said
the fire has laid down considerably since last night,'' said firefighter john gregg. ``it's not contained in the sense that there is no fire line around the fire completely, but it's not spreading out of control as it was last night when the winds were high.''
strong wind blew through much of the rockies on sunday. afternoon and evening wind gusted to 65 mph in cody, wyo., and near calgary, alberta, chinook wind forced postponement of the final heats of the men's two-man bobsled competition at the winter olympics
the colorado fire started on boulder's mountain park land in sunshine canyon and threatened 80 to 100 homes, said sheriff's spokesman brian leach
i don't know of one that has threatened as many structures as this one,'' he said
warm, dry and windy conditions existed just before the fire was reported about 5 p.m. sunday. no buildings had burned by early today, as the fire burned about one-half mile southwest of boulder memorial hospital
about 100 firefighters battled the blaze
residents of suburban sunshine canyon were asked to be ready to leave their homes in case the fire crossed a ridge into their area, the sheriff's department said
one family evacuated that subdivision sunday night, and four families in boulder did so by today, according to reports from the scene
as flames topped a ridge above one neighborhood, homeowners hooked up garden hoses to spray their roofs and started packing
i'm scared to death,'' said ne resident patricia grant
colorado highway 119 through the fire area was closed overnight between boulder and nederland, as were two other roads, but they were reopened today
sheriff's sgt. ernst l. little said a 30-year-old hiker told police he had started a campfire that apparently caused the blaze
in southwestern montana, a grass fire whipped by gusts up to 50 and 70 mph raced across 2,400 acres south of whitehall and destroyed four houses before being brought under control early today, said dan fisher, assistant chief of the whitehall volunteer fire department
firefighters from at least 10 volunteer fire departments in the rural area northwest of yellowstone national park battled the blaze, assisted by volunteers from the forest service, the department of state lands and two mining companies
about two dozen families endangered by the fire were evacuated, but might be able to return to their homes later today, fisher said. emergency kitchens were set up in two whitehall churches to feed homeless and firefighters, and emergency sleeping space was provided at the high school gymnasium and in private homes
the houses that burned were scattered rural residences
the wind ``is as bad as i've ever seen it,'' said glen hanson, a trapper who lives on the south edge of town. ``the ... stuff was going faster than you could run.''
whitehall fire chief dale davis said the blaze started sunday when a cottonwood tree was blown over and severed a montana power co. line two miles south of whitehall
flames estimated at 20 to 30 feet high licked the tops of trees along the jefferson river, and jefferson county fire warden doug schmitz said the fire jumped the river
the fire charred an area three miles wide and two miles long, and firefighters said some ranchers cut barbed wire fences to set their cattle, horses and sheep free ahead of the racing flames
sandi patti was chosen today as a finalist for her seventh straight award as the gospel music association's female vocalist of the year, the association announced
miss patti also was one of five finalists for the top award, artist of the year, which she won in 1982, 1984, 1985 and 1987
in addition, she is a finalist for song of the year for the record ``in the name of the lord,'' which she co-wrote with phil mchugh and gloria gaither
joining miss patti as finalists for top female vocalist were cece winans, cynthia clawson, margaret becker and twila paris
other finalists for artist of the year are first call, larnelle harris, steve green and wayne watson
finalists for no. 1 male vocalist are bebe winans, michael w. smith, mike english, green, harris and watson
winners will be announced april 14. no pickup.</note>
fire raced through a ski resort hotel in bulgaria before dawn today, killing six people and injuring 36 others, bulgaria's official news agency reported
the news agency bta said the fire in borovets, a ski resort 22 miles southeast of sofia, began at 3 a.m
measures were taken to put out the blaze but the building was quickly engulfed in flames,'' said the bta report received in vienna. ``in the panic that followed, six people died.''
the agency said two of the dead were dutch, one was bulgarian and three had not been identified
of the 36 injured, bta said 17 were british, four soviet, five west german, seven greek, two danish and one dutch, according to bta. their names were not released
the causes of the fire are still not known,'' the news agency said, adding a commission was appointed to investigate ``the tragic accident.''
bta identified the dead dutch visitors as ``ms. ever vanderberg'' and ``mr. peter zekelenburg.'' their home towns were not made public. the name of the dead bulgarian was not reported
an unidentified man who answered the telephone at the bulgarian state tourist office in borovets said the 170-bed hotel was destroyed in the blaze. he refused to give further details about the fire
initial reports from western diplomats in sofia said britons, west germans and dutch tourists were injured when they jumped out hotel windows to escape the blaze at the moussala hotel. the diplomats, contacted by telephone from vienna, spoke on condition of anonymity
several western embassies said they had sent diplomats to borovets to try and learn more about the fire
bulgaria has recently made great efforts to encourage western tourists to visit its mountain resorts on comparatively cheap ski vacations
carol thatcher, daughter of british prime minister margaret thatcher, was a recent visitor to borovets, a picturesque village in the rila mountains. it is close to mount moussala, the highest peak in bulgaria at 9,652 feet
legislation to replace the five-member nuclear regulatory commission with a nuclear safety agency headed by a single administrator was approved monday by a senate subcommittee
sponsors of the package said the change is needed to end internal battling at the nrc, help restore public confidence in nuclear power and provide better inspection and regulation of commercial generators
the bill, worked out by sens. john breaux, d-la., and alan simpson, r-wy., also would create a nuclear reactor safety investigations board to conduct independent reviews of major accidents and safety problems at nuclear facilities
the package also sets up an inspector general to monitor internal operations of the nuclear licensing agency and create an office of investigations to look for wrongdoing by nuclear licensees
breaux said ``it is only through a program of more effective regulation that the confidence of the american people in the benefits of this technology will be restored. ..
the record amply demonstrates that the nuclear regulatory commission is a collegial body that rarely makes its most important decisions collegially,'' breaux said
discussing the commissioners, simpson said ``they don't communicate with each other.'' he said the nrc suffers from a ``pernicious diffusion of accountability and responsibility'' that produces ``indecisive, ineffective, inefficient regulation of the commercial nuclear industry.''
frank ingram, a spokesman for the nrc, said the agency had no immediate comment on the details of the legislation but added that ``a majority of the commission supports a single administrator concept.''
the bill was approved by voice vote of the environment and public works subcommittee on nuclear regulation
the spanish communist party elected julio anguita as its new secretary-general monday, ending at least temporarily the leadership crisis that has threatened the survival of the once influential party
anguita, leader of the communists of the southern andalusia region and former mayor of cordoba, was elected by the 100-member central committee at the end of the party's three-day 12th congress
in accepting the post, the 46-year-old son of an army officer called on the workers and intellectuals who have left the party to return
the congress took place amidst struggles with problems of direction and membership, which has fallen to 62,300 from a high of more than 150,000 during the 1979 general elections
under outgoing secretary-general gerardo iglesias, the party tried to broaden its appeal to include ecological and pacifist groups and to reach out to the middle class
the united left coalition, which includes the communists, now holds seven of the 350 seats in the spanish lower house of parliament, down from a peak of 20 seats held by the communists alone after the 1979 elections. correct to dmitri, sted dimitri, and to correct to ss-12, sted ss-22. picks up 6th graf, `shultz also .. .'</note>
the united states and soviet union today gave their arms control negotiators one month to complete the key provisions of a new treaty to sharply reduce their strategic nuclear weapons
the decision was taken as u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz wound up two days of talks in moscow. he said negotiators in geneva who have so far failed to make significant progress toward a 50 percent cut in long-range nuclear weapons were directed to report to him and soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze in washington march 22-23
in another development, soviet defense minister dmitri t. yazov announced the soviet union would begin to withdraw its shorter-range ss-12 missiles from east germany and czechoslovakia late this month as a ``display of goodwill.''
elimination of the missiles is required under the intermediate-range nuclear weapons treaty president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev signed in december. the treaty has not yet been ratified in the soviet union or united states
last week the east german news agency adn reported that troops had begun dismantling ss-12s, based in waren, east germany
shultz also told a news conference the soviets indicated they would be more flexible in handling emigration applications, except for those from people who have had access to state secrets
shevardnadze confirmed ``categorically'' that only those with information the government considers important to national security would be barred from emigrating, according to shultz
earlier today, as he opened talks with shultz, gorbachev pledged to achieve peace in afghanistan and to try to reach a new nuclear arms agreement by spring
shultz and the sov ... munist party general secretary smiled broadly as they shook hands and sat down with their aides in opulent catherine's hall in the kremlin
at a picture-taking session, gorbachev said the soviets would ``do our best to achieve peace in afghanistan and to have a non-aligned, neutral afghanistan whici would have good relations with its neighors, with the united states and with the soviet union.''
at the news conference, shultz said he did not have the ``slightest doubt'' that the soviet union would leave afghanistan. but shultz, who came here saying he would seek a specific timetable, gave no evidence he had received one
an estimated 115,000 soviet troops have been in afghanistan since december 1979, backing a pro-moscow government at war with u.s.-armed moslem guerrillas
gorbachev has promised to begin a withdrawal on may 15 if the kabul government and pakistan can agree on terms of a settlement by march 15
shultz, who arrived in moscow on sunday, met until 1:30 a.m. today with shevardnadze, then held talks with premier nikolai i. ryzhkov before meeting gorbachev
after the talks, shultz did not say whether the soviets agreed to support the seven-month u.s. effort in the united nations to impose a worldwide arms embargo against iran for refusing to comply with a u.n.-ordered cease-fire in the iran-iraq war
shultz also vehemently denied that he sought soviet backing for his middle east peace initiative
i didn't come here with my hat in hand looking for support,'' he said
he said the parties in the region, arabs and israelis, would determine whether his trip to the middle east later this week will succeed
the secretary of state has questioned whether the soviet union can play a bigger role in that region because of its human rights record and its lack of relations with israel
on nuclear arms, gorbachev said ``there is still a chance'' of an agreement to reduce by half u.s. and soviet long-range nuclear weapons by the spring. the idea would be to have the pact ready for him and reagan to sign at a moscow summit
gorbachev and reagan signed an agreement in washington dec. 8 to eliminate their intermediate-range missiles, which have a range of about 300 to 3,000 miles. the current negotiations in geneva concern those with a range above 3,000 miles
the geneva talks have been held up because of disagreements over the future of reagan's ``star wars'' anti-missile program and how to verify any new arms treaty
shultz said the negotiators would have until his meeting in washington with shevardnadze to put together three draft documents dealing with verification procedures, ways to eliminate or convert the weapons and methods to help inspectors observe treaty compliance
on sunday, shultz quizzed andrei d. sakharov about human rights, arms control and soviet reforms and met with a group of jewish refuseniks to underscore u.s. concern for human rights in the soviet union
sakharov, who won the 1975 nobel peace prize for his efforts to protect human rights, met with reporters after seeing shultz
sakharov said the soviet union has not yet made enough progress to merit holding an international human rights conference. ``as a precondition for such a conference, i see the liberation of all prisoners of conscience, and the complete end of the war in afghanistan,'' he said
sakharov, a physicist, helped develop the soviet hydrogen bomb in the 1950s. he was exiled to the closed city of gorky in january 1980 for speaking out against the soviet military intervention in afghanistan
korean airlines announced monday it will ban smoking on all domestic flights beginning next month
airline officials said the ban was in line with the worldwide trend of banning smoking on flights of less than two hours. all of kal's domestic flights last less than one hour
the action will not affect kal's international flights, the officials said
until now, kal has banned smoking in half of its seats on domestic flights
the military said monday a south african pilot was missing after his plane was shot down in southeast angola during a raid on angolan and cuban forces
angola's marxist government reported ``violent combat'' in the area and said two of south africa's french-built mirage fighters were downed during low-altitude bombing runs saturday near the garrison town of cuito cuanavale
the announcement by south africa marked the second time during its five-month intervention in angola that it acknowledged losing one of its warplanes inside the country. it has been fighting in support of the unita rebel movement
military headquarters said a plane piloted by maj. edward every, 31, was downed by ground fire during a raid staged because angolan-cuban forces ``posed a potential threat'' to south african troops
angola also identified every by name but did not say whether he was dead or captured. it gave no details about the pilot of the other plane it claimed to have downed
south africa said it launched two other air attacks earlier saturday in southwest angola against guerrilla bases of the south-west african people's organization, known as swapo, in retaliation for the bombing friday of a bank in south-west africa. the death toll in the bombing rose by two to 20 monday, south-west african police said
south africa said it followed up the retaliatory air raids with mortar bombardments saturday and sunday on swapo positions. a military statement said the mortar attacks were ``successful,'' but gave no details
swapo has denied responsibility for the bank bombing. it said monday that south africa's retaliatory raids ``hit innocent civilians'' but not swapo bases
south africa occupies south-west africa, also known as namibia, in violation of a united nations resolution. its forces regularly enter angola to raid bases of swapo, which has been fighting since 1966 for namibia's independence
south africa announced nov. 11 that its troops had intervened in angola's civil war. it is widely believed that south african troops entered angola weeks earlier
unita _ the national union for the total independence of angola _ has been fighting a 12-year bush war for a power-sharing agreement with angola's government, which is backed by soviet advisers and 40,000 cuban troops
angola's president, eduardo dos santos, said sunday that 9,000 south african soldiers are deployed in angola. he said six south african planes have been shot down and 140 south african soldiers killed this year
south africa has refused to disclose the extent of its involvement in angola. it has reported the deaths of more than 30 soldiers since november, and says all its combat fatalities are announced
the military said in november that one of its warplanes crashed in angola while engaged in an attack on swapo forces. it said another plane was hit but returned to a base in namibia before crash-landing
angola's news agency, angop, quoted defense officials monday as saying south african forces renewed their attack on cuito cuanavale on saturday, two days after angola announced its forces had repelled a drive to take the strategic town. now reportedly deserted, cuito cuanavale had been the forwardmost staging point for government attacks on unita strongholds in angola's southeast corner
anolga's defense ministry said ``countless deaths'' had resulted from south african air raids on the southwestern towns of n'giva and lubango. those were the raids which south africa said were aimed at swapo bases
angop reported heavy fighting in central angola along the east-west benguela railway, and said 200 unita guerrillas were killed. seat</head>
attorney general joseph i. lieberman today officially announced his challenge of maverick republican sen. lowell p. weicker jr. in this year's senate race
weicker, 56, who announced his candidacy for a fourth term earlier this month, has made a name for himself as a liberal republican, frequently at odds with his party and president. he has championed constitutional issues and civil rights and worked against school prayer and balanced budget amendments
he squeaked into office for a third term in 1982, but says he expects this to be the biggest win of his career. early polls give him the lead but show lieberman in a good position for a challenger
lieberman, 45, a democratic former state senator who ran unsuccessfully for congress in 1980, said he'll focus on a single theme between now and november: what has weicker done for connecticut?
the populist attorney general attacked weicker for using the senate as ``a debating society'' for his own agenda, issues that don't do much for the average person
as attorney general, lieberman has seized on non-partisan consumer and environmental issues, such as grocery store coupon rip-offs, increased electric rates and dumping sewage into the connecticut river
the candidates will be determined at state party conventions this summer. so far, weicker is unopposed and lieberman has only token opposition from gary johnson, who describes himself as a veterans' rights advocate
the koala, australia's national symbol, could become extinct unless long-term plans are devised to protect its habitat, an expert on the cuddly marsupials warned monday
i am positive that if we don't take immediate action the koala, our famous `animal ambassador,' will slowly but surely slide down the inevitable path toward extinction,'' said don burnett, president of the koala preservation society
he told a three-day koala symposium at melbourne university extinction was only a matter of time as urban development erodes the creature's natural habitat
koalas are found only on the eastern coast of australia. they survive on a species of gum leaf and in recent years a venereal infection has devastated koala colonies
it is generally acknowleged that koalas were more prevalent prior to european settlement of australia in 1788, but no figures are available on their number today. ^eds: rewrites throughout to update with 90 panes broken.</head>
wind gusting to more than 50 mph hurled debris into windows at the sears tower early today, damaging 90 panes and forcing police to close streets around the world's tallest building, authorities said
but police said there were no reports of injuries from falling glass
initially, building officials reported that 19 windows were broken and six others were cracked on the east and southeast sides of the 110-story building, said ernie arms, a spokesman for sears, roebuck and co., whose corporate headquarters are in the building
a survey later in the morning by building engineers found that 90 windows were broken or cracked as the wind gusted to 56 mph, he said
they're not blown out,'' arms said. ``what happened is something flying through the air _ like a pebble from the roof of another building _ hit and broke one window and then others were damaged as that one window came down.''
the broken and cracked windows were located between the 50th and 88th floors and are among 16,000 windows in the 1,454-foot tall building
arms said authorities closed one entrance to the building, leaving two others open. and police patrolman frank daio said authorities were forced to block traffic during the morning rush hour on the four streets surrounding the building. case</head>
the supreme court today agreed to consider broadening protection for criminal defendants who claim they were denied adequate help by lawyers in filing appeals
the court said it will review a ruling that threw out an appeal by an ohio man convicted of rape, robbery and assault
the defendant, steven anthony penson, was convicted of charges stemming from a breaking and entry by three men into a montgomery county, ohio, home on aug. 4, 1984
the three intruders sexually assaulted a man and two women, and also robbed the home
after penson was convicted and sentenced to 18 to 28 years in prison, his attorney refused to file an appeal on grounds there was ``no meritorious issue'' for an appeals court to consider. lawyers for penson's two convicted co-defendants did appeal their convictions
penson's lawyer then withdrew from representing him and penson filed his own appeal
an ohio appeals court said it was troubled by the conduct of penson's lawyer. but the appeals court said, ``we find (penson) has suffered no prejudice in his counsel's failure to give a more conscientious examination of the record.''
the appeals court upheld penson's conviction
the ohio public defender's office that was later assigned to the case said in its appeal to the supreme court that penson's rights were violated
the public defender said the burden of proving penson received ineffective legal assistance in pursuing his appeal improperly was placed on the defendant. the public defender argued that penson should not be required to show specific omissions or errors to establish a presumption he received inadequate representation
penson's original lawyer, in refusing to file the appeal, failed the requirement that he state in writing the grounds that arguably could support an appeal, the public defender said
the public defender urged the supreme court to elaborate on a 1967 ruling that set some standards to judge the effectiveness of lawyers handling appeals
the case is penson vs. ohio, 87-6116
a judge today ordered that the start of gov. evan mecham's trial on criminal charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan be delayed until march 22
judge michael ryan of maricopa county superior court ordered the delay from the original march 9 trial date to allow both sides time for handling pretrial motions and answers
mecham is charged with six counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents in connection with the $350,000 campaign loan made in october 1986 by tempe developer and attorney barry wolfson. willard mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar counts
mecham also faces a feb. 29 impeachment trial by the state senate and a may 17 recall election
assistant attorney general michael cudahy said he needed more time to reply to defense motions in the criminal case. cudahy also complained that attorneys for the mechams had not yet made required pretrial disclosures, including lists of witnesses and exhibits
the governor's lawyers were given until march 7 to file a motion seeking return of the charges to the grand jury for a new finding that enough evidence existed to support the charges
ryan today also scheduled a march 2 hearing on several motions that were filed last week by willard mecham's lawyer, michael scott, and joined today by defense attorney murray miller on behalf of the governor
those motions would remand the charges, dismiss some of the counts and require grand jurors and the prosecutor to submit to questioning. states</head>
leaders in both political parties, trying to assay the hard-to-measure strength of pat robertson, say they expect he'll win some southern republican presidential primaries on super tuesday, come in second in others and pick up a substantial share of the 700 delegates up for grabs that day
interviews by associated press reporters in the 16 states holding republican primaries or caucuses on march 8 underscore that the former television evangelist is a wild card, his strength unfathomable but clearly formidable
we've got seven phone lines and they're jammed with calls these days,'' says north carolina gop chairman jack hawke. ``people are asking questions you just don't hear a lot _ how is a precinct organized, how is a person registered. it leads me to believe they (robertson supporters) are active across the state.''
says hawke's democratic counterpart, jim van hecke: ``i think he's scared the established republican party to death.''
because many evangelical christians, the core of robertson's support, have not participated in the nominating process in the past, his strength in competition with george bush, bob dole and jack kemp is hard to gauge
a new question mark is whether the weekend confession of moral waywardness of another television evangelist, jimmy swaggart, could have any fallout on robertson, who made his fame preaching before the tv cameras
i think bush's biggest competition in the south will come from robertson,'' says political scientist merle black at the university of north carolina. ``it's not inconceivable that he could beat bush in some of these states.''
political observers report that robertson appears weak in the three non-southern republican primaries _ massachusetts, rhode island and missouri. but jennifer dunn, republican chairman in washington state, which holds caucuses march 8, says bush, dole and robertson are so closely clumped that a prediction is impossible
i wouldn't be a bit surprised to see a 30 percent robertson turnout in the delegate selection, with the other candidates splitting the rest,'' mrs. dunn says. says robertson state chairman bruce hawkins: ``we're not just going to take it, we're going to sweep it.''
south carolina, which holds its primary on march 5, three days before super tuesday, could be an early indicator of robertson's strength. observers say a strong robertson showing there could give him a big boost throughout the south. robertson claims he is ready to pull a stunner in south carolina
republican primaries or caucuses will be held on super tuesday in 12 southern states _ alabama, arkansas, florida, georgia, kentucky, louisiana, maryland, mississippi, north carolina, oklahoma, tennessee and texas. nearly a third of the gop's 2,277 convention delegates will be selected on super tuesday
i think robertson in tennessee is going to do pretty well,'' said tommy harper, tennessee campaign manager for bush. a worker at bush headquarters, speaking on condition she not be quoted by name, goes further: ``robertson is the one we are really worried about.''
arkansas state democratic executive director kip blakely, trying to assess robertson's support, says: ``remember the right to life march a couple of weekends ago? it was raining and it was a saturday morning and it was freezing. there were over 3,000 people who turned out. that's pat robertson.''
blakely predicts robertson will win the arkansas primary: ``i think its his.''
robertson will probably come in second in georgia _ if he doesn't come in first,'' says georgia gop chairman emeritus bob bell. ``you don't know how many people are out there in the invisible army and how many will come out to vote. but they're committed with a burning zeal.''
in precinct meetings 16 days ago, robertson won a plurality of delegates to the county conventions which will be held in the 10 largest counties in georgia. only counties with populations over 80,000 held the meetings. robertson chairman brant frost said robertson's support ranged from a low of 35 percent in fulton county (atlanta) to a high of 96 percent in bibb county
next door in alabama, steve french, political director of the state gop, sees no prospect of a robertson win
texas is shaping up to be a bush vs. robertson race,'' bush's son, george walker bush, said last week in texas
robertson is seen as a factor behind republican registration jumps in many states
in louisiana, robertson state director billy e. mccormack, citing a 6 percent jump in republican registration since october, says, ``we feel like we were responsible for 90 to 95 percent of them.''
you take hopkins county, a very conservative, bible-belt area which had a 16 percent increase in (republican) registration from may to october,'' observes stan b. smith, political director for the kentucky gop. ``you got to feel, if you put two and two together, that a lot of that is robertson.''
but bush's state chairman in kentucky, harold rogers, says of the robertson strength: ``essentially it's still limited to the religious conservatives. i don't see him breaking out beyond that very narrow base, except in spotty cases, here and there.''
with am-robertson's prospects
some comments from political observers about pat robertson in the super tuesday states:
north carolina: merle black, political scientist at the university of north carolina at chapel hill: ``i think bush's biggest competition in the south will come from robertson. he's a big unknown. we don't know how strong he is, but he's likely much strongerw hampshire.''
alabama: steve french, political director of the state gop: ``i have no empirical proof, but you get the impression that robertson followers, who have had phone banks working for several months, are identifying here than in ne those needing to register.''
missouri: gop chairman hillard selck: ``it does not appear to be in the cards for pat robertson to make a strong showing in missouri. he's probably going to pick up a few delegates. but you can't go around the nation and pick up a few delegates here and a few there and expect to win the nomination.''
arkansas: dorothy english, executive director of the arkansas republican party, on robertson's supporters: ``many of them are brand new. they're not used to being in the political mainstream of the republican party. in iowa, we saw that a lot of them belong to more liberal chruches like the methodists. many of them are strong, staunch traditional value people.''
vs. tarkanian, 87-1061. picks up 9th graf, `to finance...'</note>
the new managers of united press international plan no hirings, firings or changes in service for at least two months while they study the company's future, the wire service's new president said today
everything is frozen'' during the study period, paul steinle said in a news conference. the new management team has not decided on what course to follow with the financially ailing company
while steinle would not deal in specifics, he said he believes that america's news executives ``want two wire services'' but he said he still needs to talk with people in the news industry because he and others want upi to become ``a market-driven company.''
the management and a team of 15 experts will interview the staff and media executives, assess the company's financial situation and look at options for the next four to six weeks. at that time they hope to have a business plan detailing the company's future
steinle works for wnw group inc., a media investment group whose chairman is dr. earl w. brian. brian recently formed wnw, a holding company, to take control of upi from mexican publisher mario vazquez rana
brian said wnw purchased control of vazquez rana's stock for 10 years in upi for a ``substantial cash payment,'' but he would not say how much. the announcement was made late friday
brian, 45, is chairman of infotechnology corp., a new york firm with at least partial interest in 22 companies, including financial news network, a cable tv service. the companies are mostly in the area of information or venture capital
brian served as secretary of california's health and welfare agency when ronald reagan was governor and went to the 1976 republican national convention as a delegate in reagan's unsuccessful bid to defeat gerald ford. in 1974, he unsuccessfully sought the republican nomination for senate
he told the los angeles times on sunday that revitalizing upi under american ownership was an important personal goal. he added, however, that his conservative views would not influence news coverage
this thing to me is just a little deeper than an issue of turning another company around,'' brian said. ``as a conservative republican, as far as i'm concerned, upi is an extremely important asset to american people.''
giving the wire service new emphasis in such areas as financial news and sports scores, using new technologies for delivery, are being considered, he said. referring to his business interests in those areas, brian said, ``we believe that a lot of this stuff can be done directly by upi itself.''
to finance continuing losses at upi, brian said he will ask private investors to put up money
vazquez rana, who paid $41 million to acquire upi from chapter 11 proceedings in u.s. bankruptcy court in june 1986, reportedly lost a million dollars a month on upi
brian and steinle said they hoped to improve upi's marketing capabilities, and that brian's presence would help
the new managers will be ``doing it all in english,'' brian said, a reference to vazquez rana's inability to speak english
meantime, al rossiter, upi's executive editor, said that ``morale is soaring'' at upi since the new managers took over
one of the reasons brian could not purchase upi outright was an agreement that vazquez rana signed with the wire service guild giving the union the right of first refusal to buy upi
the new upi managers plan to meet later today with the wire service guild
earlier, guild negotiator and spokesman dan carmichael said the union ``wants to see upi remain an integrated, quality, competitive general international news service.''
a proxy represents a transfer of voting power represented by the ownership shares, but not the shares themselves. 02-22 0146</first>
fifty book-lovers spent their third straight day holed up inside a london public library monday to protest the library's planned closure. they passed the time reading and talking
libraries are vital to civilized life,'' said protest organizer roy charterton, 62, a marketing consultant
supporters in the street below the st. pancras reference library used a rope to hoist food supplies up to the protesters
we are sleeping on the floor and bringing food up through a window ... as we have been told if we leave we cannot get back in,'' charterton said
the sit-in began saturday and is scheduled to continue until tuesday, when camden borough councilors are due to meet
the borough blames government-demanded budget cuts for the library's closure. fight</head>
the reagan administration's long and sometimes bumpy road to filling a vacant seat on the supreme court came to an anti-climactic end on monday, justice anthony m. kennedy's first day on the bench
the four hours of subdued technical arguments in the hushed, crimson-draped courtroom were a sharp contrast to the noisy and partisan battles that preceded kennedy's feb. 3 confirmation by the senate
kennedy looked solemn as he entered the chamber, strode past the american flag, stood before the pale marble columns and took his seat at the end of the row of nine justices. that seat, on the far right as spectators face the court, is the traditional place for the high court's newest member
a slight smile crossed kennedy's face during a brief exchange with justice sandra day o'connor, seated next to him, just before chief justice william rehnquist opened the session
the former appellate judge from sacramento, calif., a man with a reputation for being deliberative and well prepared, didn't say a word until nearly an hour had elapsed. and then he asked only one question
the first argument of the four on monday's schedule concerned the state of mississippi's attempt to undertake its own cost review of the grand gulf nuclear plant near vicksburg
kennedy listened intently and took notes during the hour of technical discussion
o'connor and justice antonin scalia, the two most recent additions to the court before kennedy, were among the most aggressive questioners in the first argument
kennedy waited until its closing minutes to ask his first question from the bench of the high court
is it fair to say,'' he asked attorney john maxey, representing the state of mississippi, ``that all of the arguments that mississippi wants to present now ... could have been made before ferc, even though ferc is being asked to draw a different conclusion?''
maxey said no, but kennedy's question was answered in the affirmative by rex lee, the former solicitor general, today representing mississippi power &amp; light. ``these matters can and must be raised before ferc if they are to be raised at all,'' lee said
the next three cases involved railroad worker lawsuits against employers, a technicality concerning sex discrimination in state pension benefits and a surgeon suing fellow doctors over antitrust violations
kennedy's presence brought the court to full strength for the first time since justice lewis f. powell resigned in june. and it marked a return to business as usual following months of conflict between the administration and the senate
the senate intensely scrutinized and ultimately rejected judge robert h. bork, the administration's first nominee. its second nominee, judge douglas h. ginsberg, withdrew after revelations that he had used marijuana
although a conservative for 12 years on the federal bench, kennedy is considered more moderate than either bork or ginsburg. but little is known about his views on abortion regulation, affirmative action, church-state relations or the other politically sensitive issues on which the court is closely divided
women students on both sides of the abortion issue are uneasily sharing the yale women's center this semester after the university overrode the center's decision to exclude opponents of abortion
we've been meeting there once a week,'' said senior kelly askew, president of yale students for life. ``it's not entirely welcoming, but it's getting much better. ... there was lots of anger, bitter feelings.''
askew's group, which has about 10 members, asked the student coordinating committee of the women's center for permission to meet there last semester. the committee said no, largely because of differences over abortion
the women's center, in the basement of a campus building, provides meeting space for several organizations including the staff of the student feminist magazine aurora, the women's action coalition and a lesbian group
the pro-life stand made people uncomfortable,'' said cory margenau, a yale senior and a coordinating committee member. ``it was a very unique situation with the women's center. we've never had any groups who were supportive of pro-life opinions try to come in.''
when the coordinating committee rejected askew's group, she said she viewed it as discrimination
we asked if they were violating the yale freedom of expression policy,'' askew said. ``the center is called the yale women's center and there's no denying the fact that we were all yale women. i would have no argument if they called themselves the yale pro-abortion center.''
she added, ``there is a whole pressure here to be `pc,' to be politically correct. ... part of being pc is being pro-abortion.''
the anti-abortion group took the matter to yale's administration, and both sides met with patricia pierce, associate dean of yale college
sidney altman, the dean of yale college, made the final decision, askew and margenau said
an assistant to altman referred questions to pierce, who said the dispute ``had to do with freedom of expression and not with one's personal political views.''
pierce said that as a result of the dispute, the dean's office decided to spell out who was eligible to use the women's center: groups primarily composed of undergraduate women and concerned with women's issues
margenau said she now agrees with altman's decision that the center is yale property and should therefore be neutral, but the womens' center coordinating committee saw another issue take shape with his decision
we, the five coordinators, learned how little power we really have when it comes to a man's decision. ... the main problem was realizing who really had the power, and it was dean altman, and it was kind of a blow,'' margenau said
countered pierce: ``all the associate deans are women, and we were all in on the decision, and we thought it an excellent one.''
the reagan administration said monday a videotape by marine lt. col. william higgins in which he repeated the demands of his captors in lebanon has no validity because it was made under duress
all statements made by hostages are made under duress,'' said state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley, echoing a similar comment by white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
mrs. oakley noted that the demands, including an israeli withdrawal from its border security zone in south lebanon, are the same as those announced last friday by the organization of the opporessed on earth, one of two groups which claim to have kidnaped higgins
she also disputed a statement by peggy say, sister of the longest-held american hostage in lebanon, that the administration is displaying a double standard by working hardest to free captives seized most recently
we all can understand and sympathize with her anguish and her frustration and her sorrow over her brother's continuing captivity,'' mrs. oakley said
we're making our efforts on behalf of all the hostages. our goal is not the release of this one or that one but rather the safe return of all the hostages.''
mrs. say's brother, terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, was kidnapped on march 16, 1985
mrs. say contended that the u.s. government has been less vigorous in seeking out her brother than higgins, a onetime top aide to former defense secretary caspar weinberger
at the white house, fitzwater said the higgins videotape had been viewed by members of the national security council and white house staff but he did not believe president reagan had seen it
we continue to call for the immediate and safe release of colonel higgins as well as other hostages in lebanon,'' fitzwater said. ``we are not going to give in to the demands of terrorists. we will continue to pursue all avenues for his release.''
asked if reagan had any reaction, the spokesman said, ``you know the president's deep convictions about colonel higgins and all the hostages, but we want to avoid saying anything that could exacerbate the situation.''
palestinian moderates have sought permission from the plo to meet with u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz when he arrives this week to launch a new american peace initiative, arab leaders said monday
but hanna siniora, who reportedly solicited plo chief yasser arafat's approval for a meeting, said the prospects were dim because the palestine liberation organization doesn't want a palestinian delegation to meet with shultz in israel
