rothschild said it had agreed to merge its remaining operations with stern brothers &amp; co., an investment bank in kansas city, mo. stern is a wholly owned subsidary of franklin financial services inc., which in turn is owned by franklin savings of ottawa, kan
the merger ... will form a unique investment banking combination,'' said ernest fleischer, chairman of franklin savings. ``it brings together the advantages of a new york trading desk and regional distribution.''
our stern brothers clients will receive expanded underwriting and distribution capabilities. for l.f. rothschild's clients, we will provide risk management and solid financial backing,'' he added
the announcement said franklin financial would provide a 2{-year, $30 million loan to l.f. rothschild &amp; co., the broker-dealer subsidiary of l.f. rothschild holdings
in a separate announcement, rothschild holdings reported severe losses for both the fourth quarter and all of 1987
rothschild lost $128.8 million on revenues of $32.5 million in the quarter, compared with a net loss of $15.4 million on revenues of $92.4 million in the same period of 1986
for the full year, it lost $129.1 million on $461.4 million in revenues, compared with an after-tax profit of $498,000, or 3 cents per share, on $401.1 million in revenues in 1986
it said approximately $56 million of the losses resulted from arbitrage and over-the-counter trading positions held during the stock market's collapse in late october
rothschild said its planned merger with stern brothers would be subject to the approval of its stockholders and regulatory approval
it said rothschild stockholders would receive a combination of cash and preferred stock in franklin financial, based on the company's book value on march 31
morton thiokol inc. will conduct the fourth in a series of six firing tests for the space shuttle's redesigned booster rocket's nozzle-to-case joint wednesday, company officials say
the objective of the test is to evaluate performance of the joint between sections of the solid fuel booster with deliberately flawed insulation adhesive and a damaged o-ring gasket, said morton thiokol spokesman rocky raab
the test will allow engineers to evaluate the fail-safe performance of the redesigned joint,'' he said
the test, to be held at the aerospace company's wasatch operations plant 25 miles west of brigham city, is one of hundreds undertaken by morton thiokol as part of its booster redesign efforts in the wake of the jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle challenger and deaths of its seven crew members
a presidential commission blamed a leaking booster rocket seal for igniting the shuttle's huge external tank for its liquid fuel main engines
the new case-to-nozzle joint includes 100 added bolts, adhesively bonded insulation surfaces and the added o-ring
dr. john allegro, renowned for his work in deciphering the dead sea scrolls but ridiculed for his theories that western religions were based on the worship of mushrooms, has died. he was 65
allegro died at his home on feb. 17, his birthday, according to death notices and obituaries published monday. no cause of death was given. he is to be cremated tuesday
allegro was a brilliant student of semitic languages at manchester university and went on to study hebrew dialects at oxford university
in 1953, he was named to an international team formed to decipher the dead sea scrolls, which were discovered in caves at qumran on the shores of the dead sea six years earlier
the scrolls, which spanned from about 100 b.c. to 70 a.d., included the oldest known manuscripts of books from the old testament. allegro's gift for deciphering minute texts was crucial. his book, ``the dead sea scrolls,'' was published in 1956 and became a bestseller
allegro's subsequent notoriety caused derision in the scientific community but developed a cult following in the early 1970s. allegro, in his 1970 book ``the sacred mushroom and the cross,'' contended that judaism and christianity were in fact products of an ancient sex-and-mushroom cult
he theorized that jesus's last words on the cross were not a lament to god but ``a paean of praise to the god of the mushroom.''
although trained for the methodist ministry, he became a fervent anti-christian devoted to debunking the story of jesus
allegro also published a 1966 book, ``search in the desert,'' about an unsuccessful search for lost scrolls in the judean desert
he is survived by a son and a daughter. possible</note>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that drastically limits the power of communities to regulate cable television and raises doubts about the constitutionality of a key federal law governing cable operations
the court, citing a lack of jurisdiction, turned away an appeal by two california cities barred from enforcing public access and other rules challenged by a cable operator
the court's action, which appears to have been based on narrow procedural grounds, leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal
the dispute was between officials of palo alto and atherton, calif., and century federal inc., the cable operator
u.s. district judge eugene f. lynch ruled last september that cable regulations adopted by the cities unconstitutionally violated century federal's free-speech rights
he threw out regulations that required century federal:
_to provide public access channels for those not connected with the cable company
_to wire the entire community to make service available to all residents
_to use a ``state-of-the-art'' system to keep pace with the latest technological advances
the judge, who previously had ordered city officials to award an operating license to century federal, called for further hearings to study franchise fee requirements adopted by the cities
palo alto and atherton officials said the ruling appears to declare unconstitutional a 1984 federal law regulating cable tv, even though the judge did not say in so many words he was invalidating the law
although lynch ``purported not to decide the constitutionality of any provision of the act, (his) decision in fact holds that numerous sections of that statute are unconstitutional,'' lawyers for the cities said
the reagan administration, in a ``friend-of-the-court'' legal brief filed by justice department lawyers, urged the court to deny the cities' appeal
the supreme court, in a 1986 ruling that has some bearing on the case acted on today, raised the possibility that communities may be barred from granting exclusive cable tv franchises
the court said cable franchise activities ``plainly implicate first amendment interests.'' but the justices stopped short of a definitive ruling on the constitutional rights of cable operators
the ruling was in contrast to earlier decisions denying a constitutional right to operate over-the-air television or radio stations
many cities award exclusive cable franchises city-wide or for various regions within the city. they also impose rules similar to those adopted by palo alto and atherton
the case is palo alto vs. century federal, 87-946
some parents of students at a school where three faculty members were shot want students to wear identification badges and be subject to random searches with hand-held metal detectors
we're feeling as though some of (the school's) rules and regulations need to be looked at,'' said ivy villafana, whose daughter attends pinellas park high school. ``if we cannot have these metal detectors, then we can have doors that lock from the outside.''
about 50 parents met sunday night to discuss ways to prevent further violence at the school
they plan to submit their ideas to the pinellas county school board during its regular meeting wednesday
school officials were not invited to sunday's meeting, but representatives from the school's parent-teacher-student association were on hand
on feb. 11 two administrators and one student teacher were wounded in an altercation with two students. assistant principal richard w. allen died of his injuries wednesday
at the meeting, one woman favored providing the school resource officer _ a pinellas park police officer assigned to the school _ with a hand-held metal detector. the officer should make random searches, she said
doesn't have to be a reason. just stop them and run them up and down,'' she said
principal marilyn heminger declined to comment specifically on any of the group's suggestions
she said she was glad to hear the meeting was positive, ``and i hope that from (the meeting) come some good things that we can work with.''
one of the two students accused in the shootings had recently been suspended for cursing a teacher
linda leotti, organizer of sunday night's meeting, told parents that other school systems she surveyed around the country send students to counselors before suspending them. she will suggest wednesday that pinellas county institute a similar policy
we want suspensions, but we want counseling,'' ms. villafana said. ``and we don't mean guidance counselors, we mean psychologists.''
if a student uses profanity when expressing frustration to a teacher, he shouldn't be suspended, she said
among the other suggestions: providing counseling for teachers and students; having a substitute resource officer when the regular officer is out; providing new carpeting to replace one with bloodstains; having a crisis-intervention team; and having a parent volunteer force patrolling hallways
angie debo, who came to oklahoma by covered wagon and became known as ``the first lady of oklahoma history,'' has died at age 98
ms. debo, of marshall, died sunday at an enid hospital, said steve lindholm, owner of abernathy funeral home in crescent
the nationally esteemed historian wrote 13 books and hundreds of articles about indian and oklahoma history. last month, gov. henry bellmon presented her with the 1987 award for scholarly distinction from the american historical association
in a new forward she wrote at age 91 for her 1949 book ``oklahoma, foot-loose and fancy-free,'' ms. debo called her home ``more than just another state.''
it is a lens in which the long rays of time are focused into the brightest of light,'' she wrote. ``in its magnifying clarity, dim facets of the american character stand more clearly revealed. for in oklahoma all the experiences that went into the making of the nation have been speeded up. here all the american traits have been intensified. the one who can interpret oklahoma can grasp the meaning of america in the modern world.''
her books include ``the rise and fall of the choctaw republic,'' ``and still the waters run,'' ``geronimo: the man, his time, his place'' and ``prairie city.''
in 1985, her portrait was hung permanently in the rotunda of the state capitol, near portraits will rogers, jim thorpe, and sequoyah
she earned the john h. dunning prize of the american historical society and the alfred a. knopf fellowship in history
a one-hour documentary on her life and work is scheduled to be broadcast next fall as part of public broadcasting's ``the american experience'' series
a funeral was scheduled for wednesday, lindholm said, adding that she had no surviving relatives
the california secretary of state's office is threatening to sue the university of southern california to get back 1,600 cartons of memorabilia left behind by former gov. edmund g. ``jerry'' brown jr., an official said monday
brown, who served two terms ending in 1982, gave the letters, memos, videotapes, pamphlets and personal correspondence to usc 5{ years ago. the collection includes about 4 million items
but secretary of state march fong eu contends his action violates a 1975 amendment to the california public records act
the amendment declares gubernatorial and legislative papers ``public records,'' although usc's chief sacramento lobbyist, former state controller houston flournoy, claims that brown's papers fall under an exception for ``personal correspondence'' and memos from the governor's legal affairs secretary
on jan. 20, mrs. eu's office sent a letter to usc threatening to sue. usc received the letter in early february, and a suit will be filed within 30 days after that unless the matter is resolved, ms. warren said
brown has indicated he chose usc as repository for the documents after the university of california at berkeley turned them down because of lack of space and the state archives balked at the former governor's insistence that the agency hire former brown aide lana beckett to oversee the collection
usc hired beckett but insists that she won the job in an open competition
mrs. eu, who as secretary of state also heads the state archives, argues that the all documents should be in the archives
brown's father, edmund g. ``pat'' brown sr., left records from his eight years as governor to uc berkeley. former gov. ronald reagan left his papers to the private hoover institution at stanford. but both those administrations preceded the 1975 law
assembly gop leader pat nolan has introduced a measure that would invalidate the 1975 law. the bill passed the assembly last year and is now in committee in the senate
the university of massachusetts chancellor on monday rejected calls to excuse students from classes or work so they could take part in a moratorium to consider racial tensions at the 25,000-student university
the university administration joins the undergraduate student senate, which represents the wide majority of students on the campus, in standing against the moratorium on classes planned by members of the graduate student senate this week,'' joseph duffey said in a statement
duffey said the school considered gaining social awareness part of education, but, ``we expect students to attend class and to gain social awareness through class.''
participating in the boycott will not excuse students from responsibility for meeting their academic obligations,'' duffey said
the moratorium, scheduled for tuesday and wednesday, was urged by students last week following settlement of a six-day occupation of a university building by minority students seeking harsher treatment of people involved in racist behavior on campus
about 300 students marched to duffey's office on friday to urge him to sanction the moratorium
the graduate student senate and the minority graduate student association called for all faculty and graduate instructors to cancel their classes, ``but still hold students responsible for the material that would have been taught.'' that book came from head of zane grey society, not grey's son.</note>
a cancer patient who has been reading zane grey books since his childhood had a dream fulfilled when columnist bob greene delivered a rare book that completes an 89-book collection of the western author
i've got something for you,'' said greene, of the chicago tribune, when he handed a small green book to 73-year-old mack landers
the book greene delivered sunday in this fort worth suburb, ``don, the story of a lion dog,'' was published 60 years ago and only about 100 copies exist in this country. it was the last of 89 books landers needed to complete his collection
landers was diagnosed with colon cancer in 1982 and has been told by doctors he has less than three months to live
greene wrote of landers' search for the book in his nationally syndicated column, and said five or six people from across the nation called offering copies. greene accepted one from dr. james h. vickers, president of the national zane grey's west society and director of the pathobiology and primatology laboratory at the national institutes of health in bethesda, md
another copy was offered by zane grey's son, loren
a pre-dawn fire monday destroyed a bulgarian ski-resort hotel that caters to foreign tourists, killing six people and injuring 36, bulgaria's official news agency bta reported
a western diplomat said a dutch woman was killed when she jumped from a window to escape the flames
bta said those injured in the fire at borovets, 22 miles southeast of sofia, were from britain, the soviet union, west germany, the netherlands, greece and denmark
it said two of the dead were dutch, one was bulgarian and three had not been identified
bulgaria has made great efforts recently to attract western tourists to its modern mountain resorts for relatively inexpensive ski vacations. borovets is bidding for the 1989 alpine skiing world championships
throughout the day, most information on the blaze at the moussala hotel came from western diplomats in sofia, the capital, and two british tour companies. bta did not issue its first full report until nearly 15 hours after the fire started
measures were taken to put out the blaze but the building was quickly engulfed in flames,'' the bta report said. ``in the panic that followed, six people died.''
the causes of the fire are still not known,'' it said, and a ``special commission has been appointed to investigate.'' bta added: ``the necessary medical aid has been provided to the injured and the rest of the tourists have been accommodated in other hotels.''
a man who answered the telephone at the state tourist office in borovets, and would not give his name, said the 193-bed alpine-style hotel was completely destroyed
reports said most victims were being treated in local clinics, but a dutch diplomat said two injured citizens of the netherlands were taken to sofia because there was no more room at the clinics
the global ski tour organization in london had 32 customers booked at the hotel, and said a representative in bulgaria acted as interpreter to help police interview the injured and others
several western embassies said they sent diplomats to borovets seeking more information about the fire and the victims
carol thatcher, daughter of prime minister margaret thatcher of britain, was a recent visitor to borovets. the picturesque village in the rila mountains is near mount moussala, at 9,652 feet the highest peak in bulgaria
the state department said monday it was ``extremely unfortunate'' that nicaraguan government cease-fire negotiators did not respond quickly enough to a new truce proposal to prevent the talks from breaking down
spokeswoman phyllis oakley also welcomed what she said was the unconditional acceptance of the proposal by the u.s.-backed contra rebels. the plan had been outlined by the chief mediator, cardinal miguel obando y bravo, during talks last week in guatemala city
the positive attitude of the contras ``further indication of the resistance's willingness to negotiate in good faith and of their desire to achieve a cease-fire,'' mrs. oakley said
she added that the sandinista government's delay in responding to the proposal apparantly led to obando y bravo's decision to break off the talks a day early
the cleric's proposal called for the sandinistas to free all political prisoners, allow complete freedom of expression and resume a dialogue with opposition parties, among other measures
nicaragua's leftist government has said the cease-fire discussions should be limited to the technical aspects of achieving a truce and that political questions should be dealt with separately
obando y bravo's decision to suspend the talks caught the sandinista negotiators by surprise. they said they had been ready to accept his plan in principle and to continue the discussions
a u.s. warship, arriving in the persian gulf on monday as the newest addition to the navy's escort squadron, fired machine-gun warning shots to chase away two fishing boats that ventured too close
although the craft proved to be harmless, a u.s. official said, the boats at first appeared to be boston whaler-type vessels, often used by iran's revolutionary guards to attack commercial shipping
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the trenton fired after the boats approached within 3,300 yards of a u.s. convoy, 30 miles off the coast of dubai, at about 3 p.m
he said, ``trenton ... issued two verbal warnings which were not heeded, and when the boats came within 3,000 meters, it fired a flare and bursts of .50-caliber machine-gun fire, at which time the craft stopped and then moved off to the northeast.''
a helicopter sent up by the missile frigate john a. moore, accompanying the trenton, ``confirmed through observation that both were fishing boats, and neither was hit or damaged,'' he added
while no u.s. warship has been directly attacked by iran, several have fired warning shots when unidentified small boats approached too close or ignored verbal cautions
in one such incident last year, an indian fisherman was killed by gunfire from a navy frigate
american ships also have fired warning shots or come close to firing missiles at iraqi warplanes flying too close during attack sorties against iranian coastal oil shipping
a delegation of u.s. officials is visiting baghdad to discuss the problem with iraqi military leaders
the 17,000-ton trenton sailed through the strait of hormuz hours earlier to join the middle east force, the navy's flotilla in the gulf. it carried a 400-man u.s. marine combat unit and a contingent of marine attack helicopters
u.s. officials said the group was not considered one of the navy's gulf ``transits'' as it did not include any of the kuwaiti tankers reflagged by washington last year for protection from iranian attack
the trenton, one of the ships involved in a current realignment of navy units in the region, is a replacement
when the reshuffling is completed, probably within a week, it will leave the gulf-based force at 16 ships, including six mine sweepers, down one from its maximum strength of 17
next saturday, rear adm. anthony a. less will take over command of the gulf force from rear adm. harold j. bernsen
u.s. officials said the marines aboard the trenton would provide security for naval operations in the gulf, where the 7{-year-old iraq-iran war has seriously affected commercial shipping
iran's official news agency said a prototype of the ``first iranian-made airplane'' made a successful test flight monday and would soon go into mass production
it said the ``multiple-purpose'' aircraft can be adapted for military use, and all parts were made in iran by experts affiliated with the revolutionary guards corps. each plane will ``save $500,000 in foreign exchange,'' said the islamic republic news agency
iran also announced that at the orders of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, 1,139 prisoners have been released as part of an amnesty to mark the ninth anniversary of the islamic revolution
irna said the detainees released in various cities in iran were ``repentant'' and had been pardoned
it did not say what they were jailed for or on what day they were released
iran has already reported freeing more than 1,000 other prisoners following the anniversary of the islamic seizure of power on feb. 11, 1979. counsel law</head>
the supreme court said monday it will judge the validity of a federal law that lets independent counsels investigate alleged crimes by high-ranking executive branch officials
the court also rejected the latest appeal of one target of such an investigation _ marine lt. col. oliver l. north
the court's decision, expected by july, will resolve a major constitutional dispute and will affect the criminal conviction of former white house aide michael k. deaver and the rejuvenated investigation of ex-justice department official theodore b. olson
the decision also could affect other investigations by special prosecutors appointed under the law
the justices allowed special prosecutor alexia morrison to resume her investigation of olson, raising the possibility that grand jury indictments could be handed down before the high court's ruling
a federal appeals court ruled that the watergate-era law creating independent counsels impermissibly gives presidential appointment powers to the federal courts. the appeals court had derailed morrison's investigation
a three-judge panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington ruled, by a 2-1 vote last month, that the independent counsel provisions of the ethics in government act of 1978 were an unconstitutional encroachment of the exclusive power of the president to enforce criminal laws
under the law, a special court appoints independent counsels, or special prosecutors, at the request of the attorney general to investigate alleged criminal wrongdoing
morrison is investigating allegations that olson, a former assistant attorney general, lied to congress in 1983 during a dispute over the environmental protection agency's cleanup program for toxic waste
the appeals court ruling followed a challenge by olson and others to morrison's authority to subpoena their testimony before a federal grand jury
the jan. 22 ruling could jeopardize last month's perjury conviction of former presidential aide michael k. deaver for lying to a grand jury and to a house subcommittee that investigated his lobbying activities
but the appeals court ruling in olson's case is not expected to interfere with the work of lawrence e. walsh, the independent counsel investigating the iran-contra arms and money affair
the supreme court last month refused to consider north's challenge to the parallel appointment walsh accepted last year from the justice department
north was fired as a white house aide after his role in the diversion of money from secret iranian arms sales to the nicaraguan contra rebels was revealed
a different three-judge panel of the appeals court in washington upheld the constitutionality of the backup appointments last year
independent counsel james c. mckay, who is prosecuting former presidential aide lyn c. nofziger on illegal lobbying charges, also accepted a backup appointment
but morrison and whitney north seymour, the independent counsel who prosecuted deaver, did not accept backup appointments
the north appeal acted on monday was from a ruling that barred him from halting walsh's investigation by challenging its legality in a civil lawsuit
the appeals court ruling that dismissed north's lawsuit said, ``potential criminal defendants cannot, by bringing ancillary equitable proceedings, circumvent federal criminal procedure.''
democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis derided president reagan's anti-terrorism policies on monday as worthless in light of the iran-contra affair, prompting reagan's spokesman to retort that candidates shouldn't make a hostage situation a political issue
the massachusetts governor, using the white house as a backdrop after a meeting of the national governors' association with reagan, issued a stinging critique of the administration's iran-contra involvement and the problems it might pose for the next president
asked how he would respond to the latest hostage-taking, dukakis said, ``you never, ever make concessions to terrorism. if you ever do it, then your policy is worthless. and that's what we did.''
referring to the sale of arms to iran during secret negotiations to free american hostages, dukakis said, ``we'll be living with the consequences of what happened for a long time.''
his remarks came as the administration struggled to deal with the kidnapping of another american in lebanon, lt. col. william r. higgins, a marine detailed to a u.n. truce-monitoring force
queried by reporters, dukakis said he would have ``a much tougher, and much more consistent anti-terrorist policy'' than reagan
what happened in 1985 was devastating ... to our ability to be credible when it came to putting together a very tough, no-compromise policy on terrorism,'' he said
this is international crime, pure and simple, and you fight it the way you fight crime _ with tough police work, with effective undercover operations, with military operations against terrorist base camps if necessary,'' the governor added
dukakis' remarks brought a quick rebuke from presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater
i think it's very dangerous to make terrorism a political issue, especially when you're talking about specific episodes,'' fitzwater said
the spokesman asserted that past experience has shown that ``there are any number of aspects to individual hostage-takings that can be exacerbated by political talk or media talk or political statements.''
i would simply urge caution on everyone's part, including political candidates,'' he said
besides hitting reagan's performance on terrorism, the massachusetts governor took advantage of the attention of the white house press corps to question reagan's approach to welfare reform and child care
on a strictly political topic, he also said he was heading into tuesday's south dakota and minnesota contests aiming to prove he has wider appeal than shown by his new hampshire primary victory
if i can do well out there, that will be proof positive this is a national campaign, and a national candidacy,'' he said, adding that he hoped victories there would be a boost for the multiple showdowns march 8 on super tuesday
dukakis joked that he'd used the governors' visit to look the white house over as a possible residence. ``no commuting, don't even have to take the street car, just walk to work _ it's terrific,'' he said with a broad smile
as dozens of camera and microphone-toting technicians and correspondents crowded around him on the white house lawn, dukakis even offered to ``meet with the press two or three times a week'' if he were elected
and to reporters' delight, he dangled the option of hawaiian winter vacations before the oft-traveling pack
it would be tough to top santa barbara,'' one correspondent taunted when the subject came up, noting the lush california resort town near reagan's vacation ranch
how about cape cod _ what do you think?'' asked the massachusetts governor with a grin
mild murmurs of approval were made. then, a query about his winter vacation plans
the berkshires,'' dukakis replied firmly, only to be met by silence
sensing a need to offer a new slant on the subject, the candidate quickly shifted gears
on the other hand, my wife expressed a preference for maui the other day,'' he offered
cheers erupted from the crowd
gov. evan mecham's criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan was delayed by a judge monday until march 22
the delay from the original march 9 trial date gives both sides time to handle pretrial motions and answers, said judge michael ryan of maricopa county superior court
mecham also faces a may 17 recall election and a feb. 29 impeachment trial by the state senate
he is charged with six counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents in connection with a $350,000 campaign loan made in october 1986 by tempe develper and attorney barry wolfson. willard mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar counts
the governor and brother did not answer reporters' questions when they entered and left the courtroom
assistant attorney general michael cudahy told ryan he needed more time to reply to defense motions. cudahy also complained that attorneys for the mechams had not yet made required pretrial disclosures, including lists of witnesses and exhibits
cudahy said the mechams' lawyers made ``more or less a grandstand play'' by saying in court monday that they were ready to go to trial when they had not made the disclosures
the governor's lawyer, murray miller, said those disclosures would be made this week
ryan said he would schedule a hearing later on several defense motions to remand the charges to the state grand jury, dismiss some of the counts and require grand jurors and the prosecutor to submit to questioning
willard mecham's lawyer, michael scott, has claimed in court papers that attorney general bob corbin's office manipulated the grand jury process by having most testimony presented to a state grand jury that met last fall, but holding the matter over for a new grand jury which indicted the mechams on jan. 5
corbin's office has contended, however, that the matter was given to a new grand jury to avoid possible bias because three members of the previous grand jury had signed petitions to recall mecham
miller told ryan that he was prepared to have both the criminal and impeachment trials simultaneously although he indicated he may ask a court to delay the senate's impeachment trial. however, he did not say when or where he would file such a motion
deborah raffin had hoped for an anonymous vacation in the people's republic of china, but on her first day there, throngs of chinese ran up to her shouting, ``nightmare, nightmare.''
it's funny now, but it wasn't funny then,'' the actress said recently. ``at first i thought it was because of my blonde hair and obvious western looks. then i started to think that maybe i was somebody's idea of a nightmare.''
what actually caused the commotion was the chinese people recognizing her from the 1976 film, ``nightmare in badham county,'' in which she played a hitchhiker hounded by a lecherous sheriff. it was a major box office hit in china
that visit six years ago began a love affair between miss raffin and china, and she continued to return, recently to film the $20 million miniseries, ``noble house,'' airing this week on nbc. she plays a tough corporate officer who falls for the head of a trading house, played by pierce brosnan
i had been to hong kong about a dozen times before the filming and took the role as an excuse to go back,'' miss raffin said. ``i feel very comfortable there. it's like the manhattan of asia, so colorful and romantic with a tremendous energy level. it's a world few of us in the united states know anything about.''
a deadly mix of rock and mud threatened hillside homes during a fourth day of violent rains monday which have killed at least 75 people in the rio area
the new danger slowed efforts to reach a buried roomful of children and prompted the mayor to order hundreds of residents to ``get out while there's still time.''
mud-caked survivors flashed thumbs-up signs as they were carted away on stretchers, while rescuers moved gingerly about the unstable hillsides in the city
scores have died there since the heavy rains began triggering sporadic floods and mudslides on friday
civil defense officials warned that huge boulders and rain-loosened earth on many hillsides presented an extreme risk of new avalanches, particularly in the crowded shantytown slums that line the hills
mayor roberto saturnino braga went on television to order hundreds of slum dwellers to evacuate their high-risk homes
get out while there's still time. you may lose your possessions, and we regret that. but we're talking about your lives,'' braga said
in the working-class north rio district of abolicao, rescue workers used sledgehammers and spikes to break up concrete slabs of a three-story apartment building that collapsed under a mudslide sunday night, killing at least nine residents
fourteen people were taken alive from the rubble. television crews broadcasting live from the site showed survivors covered with yellow-brown mud flashing thumbs-up signs as they were borne away on stretchers
civil defense spokeswoman sonia hadid said workers expected to find as many as 11 bodies under the rubble
there was a children's party going on in one of the apartments when it collapsed, so we don't know how many were in there,'' ms. hadid said by telephone
in the santa teresa district near downtown rio, 80 firemen searched for bodies under the debris of a hillside clinic for the elderly that was hit by a mud avalanche late friday. a three-story pavillion of the clinic collapsed and at least 11 patients died
rescue efforts were slowed by rain and by a warning from engineers that a new mudslide could occur at any moment in santa teresa
they have to work carefully, using blowtorches and sledges, removing the metal, concrete and wood. when it starts to rain, they stop. otherwise the whole hillside could come down,'' ms. hadid said
the spokeswoman said the death toll of 75 included only bodies that had reached the morgue and ``the final total certainly will be higher.''
the number of dead varied almost daily as civil defense authorities struggled to get a clear picture of the tragedy's human toll
nearly 9,500 were without homes, a drop from previous days because some flood victims began moving back to their dwellings
state health officials began a massive vaccination campaign against tetanus and leptospirosis, a sometimes fatal infection caused by water contaminated with rat urine and droppings. earlier reports indicated erroneously that leprosy was feared
public service messages on radio and television urged people not to walk barefoot through flood water and to boil their drinking water or treat it with chlorine
braga declared a state of public calamity in rio and estimated the damage at $150 million
the weather bureau said the unusually heavy rain was caused by an antarctic cold front. the forecast was for more rain and gradual clearing by wednesday
earlier this month, 207 people died in flooding and mudslides around the state and 13,000 were left homeless
sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., on monday endorsed bob dole for president, saying the senate republican leader ``is a common sense conservative and is the most electable of all the candidates.''
thurmond, the most senior gop senator, endorsed dole at a capitol hill news conference. in so doing, he broke with other south carolina republicans, including gov. carroll campbell, who have endorsed vice president george bush. lee atwater, bush's campaign director, is from south carolina and has helped him get support there
the south carolina republican primary is on march 5
thurmond, who ran for president himself in 1948, declined to say why he considered bush less electable than dole. he would not criticize any of the candidates, he said
dole was campaigning monday in minnesota and did attend the announcement
