professional politicians do a better job of selecting qualified presidential nominees than the current year-long system of primary elections, former sen. john tower says
tower added that televised presidential debates are no better than ``east texas hog-calling contests.''
the current system is a ``very, very imperfect way to select a national candidate,'' tower said in comments sunday at a convention of the national utility contractors association
in the past, he said, ``the smoke-filled room screened out the candidates who were least competent.''
tower, a republican, said today's system can result in a nominee who has the best commercials and who articulates his ideas best, but who may not be the best president
he also criticized the news media, saying, ``i don't think the mass media are capable. you don't get a balanced assessment from sensational press stories. the mass media have become too strong. on the whole, the media are consumed with an arrogance of power.''
the president of moral majority said monday that television evangelist jimmy swaggart's problems will likely have a negative impact on the republican presidential campaign of former television preacher pat robertson
jerry c. nims, president of the conservative lobbying group, said swaggart's tearful confession and his stepping down from his own tv ministry sunday will not affect robertson's core of supporters
however, the swaggart controversy might change the minds of supporters who had been leaning toward the republican hopeful
he (robertson) has a large base of support'' that wouldn't be affected by the fall of a televangelist, nims told a news conference called by a group of conservative organizations on another subject. ``but it might have an impact outside,'' he said
the moral majority president said robertson's core of followers remains strong, but he may ``well lose some of the fringe'' supporters
nims noted that the minsters who have fallen in the past year, including jim bakker _ are members of the charismatic group, which differs from moral majority and robertson followers
for much of our constituency, it does not have an impact,'' he said
rep. mario biaggi's violation of house ethics constituted ``criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational responsibilities'' and warranted expulsion, the house committee on standards of official conduct said in a report released monday
the committee, which recommended thursday that biaggi, d-n.y., be expelled from the seat he has held for 20 years, explained why it had elected to exercise its most serious punishment
the facts and circumstances giving rise to the violations, being of the most serious nature, warrant the imposition of the most stringent sanction available to the house of representatives,'' the 148-page report said
accordingly, the committee submits that expulsion is the only sanction appropriate to the violations committed by representative biaggi.''
biaggi was not in his office monday, but he said thursday that he intended to vigorously fight the expulsion recommendation
biaggi, 70, was convicted in september of illegally accepting a paid florida vacation from meade esposito, the former brooklyn, n.y., democratic leader. esposito was seeking government help for coastal dry dock and repair co., a financially troubled brooklyn shipyard that owed $280,000 in premiums to esposito's insurance brokerage firm
biaggi was also convicted of illegally crossing state lines to accept the gratuity and obstructing justice by trying to influence how esposito answered the fbi's questions. he was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and a $500,000 fine, and is free pending appeal
the ethics committee concluded that biaggi violated rules against discrediting the house; accepting impermissible gifts from a person or organization with a direct or indirect interest in legislation; failing to report a gift worth $250 or more on his financial disclosure form; and accepting a favor or benefit that might be construed as influencing the performance of government duties
after reviewing evidence from biaggi's trial, the committee ``found that the offenses for which representative biaggi was convicted involved criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational responsibilities.''
the committee's resolution to expel biaggi must be approved by two-thirds of the 435-member house to take effect. the matter may be taken up on the floor at any time, now that the committee report has been released
if the resolution passes, biaggi would be the second congressman expelled from the house since the civil war. rep. michael ``ozzie'' myers, d-pa., was ousted in 1980 after his conviction in the abscam bribery scheme
the committee report also includes a transcript of its closed dec. 17, 1987, meeting, at which biaggi pleaded for leniency and declared, ``i am incorruptible.''
biaggi argued that the vacation he took, at a florida health spa, was ``hospitality'' from esposito, a friend of 40 years, not a gratuity
placing the value of the vacation at about $3,000, biaggi asked rhetorically, ``mario biaggi is going to compromise himself for $3,000? i wouldn't compromise myself for $100,000.''
biaggi also said he did not know that esposito had business with coastal until a bugged telephone conversation on june 2, 1986, more than a year after the florida vacation
at full strength with the addition of justice anthony m. kennedy, the supreme court said monday it wants to hear a second round of arguments in two cases already under study
the unusual move _ having lawyers twice argue a case before the justices during one court term _ could mean that kennedy's tie-breaking vote is needed to resolve the two cases
at issue in one is whether defense contractors may be forced to pay damages for on-duty accidents involving members of the military
the court is deciding whether to reinstate a $725,000 award to the family of a marine helicopter co-pilot who died in a 1980 crash in the atlantic ocean near virginia beach, va
a jury awarded the damages to the family of david boyle, who drowned on april 27, 1983, in the crash of the ch-53 helicopter. but the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals threw out the award against the helicopter manufacturer, sikorsky aircraft, and its parent company, united technologies corp
the appeals court said sikorsky, as a military contractor, was shielded from being sued because the navy approved of the helicopter's allegedly negligent design. the justices heard arguments in the case jan. 12
the second case, which the court first heard jan. 19 and will be reargued sometime in april, involves the convicted killer of an oklahoma policeman
prosecutors say bobby lynn ross shot elk city, okla., police sgt. steve mahan three times after the officer arrived at a motel being robbed by ross on jan. 5, 1983
at issue is whether ross' trial was tainted when the presiding judge refused to disqualify ``for cause'' a potential juror who said he would vote to impose the death penalty _ and would not even consider a life sentence _ if ross were convicted
the potential juror was excluded when ross' lawyer used one of nine ``peremptory challenges.'' ross contends his defense team should not have been forced to expend one such challenge for that juror
both cases are to be decided by july
the court monday refused to reconsider its 4-4 decision last december striking down an illinois law that could have made abortions more difficult to obtain for some teen-agers
the justices rejected a request by illinois attorney general neil f. hartigan that they restudy the law ``after the appointment of a ninth justice.''
kennedy joined the court last thursday, filling an eight-month vacancy, but he did not participate in monday's order denying reconsideration in the illinois case
he did join in the orders requiring reargument in the two other cases
in seeking reconsideration, hartigan emphasized the importance of ``a decision by a full court'' in the case
the illinois law required girls under 18 and still financially dependent on their parents notify both parents 24 hours before having an abortion
the law allowed a girl to avoid notifying her parents if she could prove to a state judge that she was mature enough and well-informed enough to make the decision on her own and that notifying her parents would not be in her best interest
doctors who failed to comply with the law's requirement faced criminal prosecution
a moderate earthquake jarred some central california residents awake, but law enforcement officers said monday no damage was reported
the quake at 11:43 p.m. sunday measured 3.9 on the richter scale of ground motion and was centered about 40 miles west-northwest of bakersfield, said robert finn, of the california institute of technology's seismology laboratory in pasadena
people felt it in the taft and bakersfield areas more than 100 miles north of los angeles and in san luis obispo county
we didn't get any reports of damage,'' san luis obispo sheriff's sgt. greg slane said. ``it was mostly just inquiries from people if there really was an earthquake
we assured them there was.''
a southern pacific freight train crew in santa margarita, 10 miles north of san luis obispo, reported heavy tools shook during the quake. trains were slowed while workers inspected the tracks for damage. none was found, officials in san francisco said
a soviet citizen was convicted of nazi war crimes monday and sentenced to 15 years in jail, the official news agency reported
tass said dmitri maslo was found guilty of high treason and other charges after a trial in the mining town of selidovo in the ukrainian republic
during world war ii, maslo joined the police force in the ukrainian city of krasnoarmeisk and ``voluntarily went over to the side of nazi invaders,'' tass said. it said he arrested and tortured ukrainians and jews and ``on many occasions he took part in the shooting of peaceful civilians.''
maslo, who went on trial feb. 9, also was accused of helping kill prisoners in the krasnoarmeisk jail in 1943 as soviet forces began liberating the area
he fled when the nazis withdrew and settled in khristinovka, near the ukrainian capital of kiev, tass said
five people were killed and five others were injured in a flurry of weekend gang-related shootings despite a police sweep aimed at curbing street violence
sixty officers swept through gang-infested south-central los angeles during a special 16-hour campaign against gang members and drug dealers saturday and sunday. they arrested more than 50 people for crimes ranging from narcotics sales to concealed weapons to grand theft auto, said lt. mark leap
despite the show of force, the violence was unrelenting
in one of the weekend killings, a man was shot by three teen-agers on bicycles, said sheriff's deputy gabriel ramirez
in one especially flagrant gang shooting, four men in a car shouted gang slogans and opened fire on about 50 people gathered in front of a taco bell restaurant sunday, police said. four teen-agers were wounded
the escalating street gang problem in los angeles became evident last month when it stretched out of crime-ridden south-central los angeles and reached into upscale westwood village, where a 27-year-old woman died when she got caught in gang crossfire
the strong police response to that shooting sparked an outcry in less-affluent communities such as the south-central area, where more than 100 people were killed in gang violence last year
mayor tom bradley last week signed an ordinance giving the city 150 more officers, many of which will be used to battle gangs. the city council also approved an anti-gang project that will result in up to 100 gang members in jail on drug charges each month, said deputy police chief glenn levant, 45, the department's newly-appointed ``gang czar.''
a teen-age boy whose father hired a hit man through soldier of fortune magazine to kill his mother fought back tears monday as he testified he feared a similar fate
gary wayne black, 18, took the stand in the second week of a federal court trial of a lawsuit filed by him and his maternal grandmother, marjorie einmann
they are seeking $22.5 million from the boulder, colo.-based magazine, accusing the self-proclaimed ``journal for professional adventurers'' of negligence for running an ad that led to the slaying of sandra black
the ad, placed by john wayne hearn, brought him into contact with robert black
black is on texas' death row for paying hearn $10,000 to carry out the killing of his wife. hearn is serving three life terms in florida for that and two other slayings
gary black, a high school senior who found his mother shot to death in their bryan home three years ago sunday, described her as understanding and kind
she just was the worst person i could lose,'' he said
mrs. einmann, who also testified monday as plaintiffs completed their case against the magazine, said her grandson was so devastated by the killing he not sleep alone or enter his house alone for a year and a half afterward
he constantly twitched, and suffered from severe headaches, she said
during treatment by state mental health counselors, the boy told how much he feared his father, she said
they said his mind was so damaged. ... he feared if someone could get into his own home to kill his own mother, someone could get into my house to kill him.''
if he could hire someone out of soldier of fortune magazine to kill my mother, he could hire someone out of soldier of fortune magazine to kill me, too,'' gary black said of his father
hearn's ad appeared in four issues of the magazine in late 1984, offering services of former marine and vietnam veterans and weapons specialists with jungle warfare expertise for ``high-risk assignments'' in the united states or overseas
a criminologist, park dietz, testified last week the reference to ``high-risk'' meant the person placing the ad was willing to commit a crime
attorneys for the magazine do not deny the ad brought hearn and black together, but insist publisher robert brown had no way of knowing the ad was for illegal activity
brown has testified he would have halted the classified ads for personal services if he had known they were linked to crimes
defense attorneys planned to call several witnesses to testify for the magazine's value as a defense journal
among them would be col. charles beckwith, who led the army's delta force in the unsuccessful attempt in 1980 to rescue the american hostages in iran. comment.</note>
navy secretary james h. webb resigned today, saying he is ``unable to support'' defense secretary frank carlucci's decision to abandon the goal of a 600-ship fleet and criticizing carlucci's leadership in the pentagon
this building needs to be led,'' webb told reporters. ``it needs leadership. it needs some vision. i'm saying that if i had a piece of advice to give to secretary carlucci, it would be to spend a lot more time with the top leaders in this building
he's been spending a lot of time with the state department and a lot of time on the hill. i think they (pentagon leaders) need to feel his vision and to understand what he believes in.''
webb, 42, has held the job less than a year. a highly-decorated marine veteran of vietnam combat, he was the author of ``fields of fire,'' a best-selling novel about the war in vietnam
in his letter of resignation to president reagan, webb said he decided to leave because he could not support the fiscal 1989 pentagon budget proposal crafted by carlucci
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``secretary carlucci is having to make some very difficult adjustments in the pentagon to accommodate budgetary reductions. secretary webb indicates he is unable to operate under these constraints, but i know the president feels he has given very valuable service to the country, and will work with secretary carlucci to find a replacement as soon as possible.''
referring to the internal budget debate that led to last week's submission of the fiscal 1989 budget, webb wrote to reagan:
on three separate occasions, the uniformed and civilian leadership of the navy department provided the secretary of defense with proposed cuts totaling the amount required to meet the budget reduction, but which also would preserve the cherished goal of your administration to rebuild our navy to a minimum of 600 ships.''
because those recommendations ``were rejected by your secretary of defense, i am unable to support him personally or to defend this amended budget during budget deliberations (on capitol hill),'' webb concluded
consequently, i find it necessary to resign from my position as secretary of the navy.''
this (budget cutting) is not being done according to a strategy,'' webb told reporters in his pentagon office
webb, who assumed the post as the navy's top civilian leader just april 10, said his concerns focused on a decision by carlucci to propose the early retirement and mothballing of 16 navy frigates
the navy had to cut $12 billion from its original fiscal 1989 budget plan, but still could have kept those ships by assigning them to the naval reserve instead of consigning them to mothballs, webb continued
without those frigates, webb said there was no way the navy could build to 600 warships in fiscal 1989, as originally planned. indeed, despite the optimistic predictions of other pentagon officials, the decision means the navy will never reach the 600-ship mark, he added
and one of the sad things about this, this was one of the few goals of the reagan administration that was really obtainable, at pretty low cost,'' webb added
webb, one of the youngest men to ever become navy secretary, is a naval academy graduate
he came to the pentagon in 1984 when caspar w. weinberger was the defense secretary, assuming the post of assistant defense secretary for reserve affairs. webb had resigned that position and was preparing to leave government service in early 1987 when the president asked him to replace john f. lehman, the first navy secretary of the reagan administration
in his meeting with reporters, webb declined to speculate on why carlucci had insisted that ships be retired when that step _ in webb's view _ wasn't required
pentagon leaders should always be concerned about ``hollow forces'' that aren't properly manned, but the navy could have reached the 600-ship mark without giving up readiness, webb insisted
the navy secretary said he had wrestled with his concerns for some time but didn't make a final decision to resign until sunday
webb said he had not spoken to carlucci today, but had sent him a copy of his letter to reagan
carlucci, in a written personal statement, said today he had learned of webb's decision ``with regret.''
i wish him well in his future endeavors,'' carlucci said. ``he has earned our respect and gratitude for his service to our nation both in uniform and as a civilian leader within the defense department.''
the pentagon, in a companion statement, said the recent budget debate ``has been one of the most painful in history.''
the compromises have not been easy for anyone, and we regret the fact that the secretary of the navy appears to have found himself unable to defend the department's decisions. under the circumstances, he has done the honorable thing.''
the 70-year-old reputed underboss of the gambino crime family was sentenced monday to 15 years in prison and fined $820,000 for a racketeering conviction
joseph armone, of brooklyn, was convicted dec. 22 of racketeering conspiracy involving extortion, bribery and illegal interstate travel to commit bribery
u.s. district judge jack b. weinstein said he sentenced armone to prison despite his advanced age because he was convinced armone was a high-ranking member of the crime family
weinstein also cited armone's lengthy criminal record, which he said began when the defendant was 15 years old
armone had faced a maximum sentence of 20 years for the most serious charge, racketeering
according to the prosecution, armone was elevated from capo to underboss after he was indicted in 1986. it was also alleged that armone was observed meeting with reputed gambino boss john gotti during the trial
armone was jailed at the time of his conviction after he refused to renounce any organized crime ties as a condition for his release from detention. on monday, armone made a brief statement to weinstein in which he said he had not meant any disrespect to the court in refusing the offer but that he turned it down because he was worried about ``his rights''
prior to sentencing, defense attorney mark krasnow said armone had ``paid his dues to society'' for his previous convictions and charged that his client had been entrapped by the government
prosecutor douglas grover, a special attorney with the justice department's organized crime strike force, said armone had been convicted of ``serious and compelling'' crimes and of being a leader in the gambino family. his life,'' grover said
one of the bribery charges accused armone and one of his co-defendants, joseph n. gallo, of unsuccessfully plotting to give a $20,000 bribe so that gallo's son would be transferred from a state prison, where he was then being held, to a federal prison, where presumably he would receive better treatment
following is the text of an appeal made by kidnapped the u.s. marine officer, lt. col. william r. higgins, and released by his captors monday:
i, william higgins, in order to get me released, these demands have to be met:
one, the withdrawal of israeli forces from all occupied territories in lebanon
two, the release of all detained mujahedeen (holy warriors), lebanese and palestinians, from khiam prison and from all other prisons inside the zionist regime in occupied palestine
three, stopping u.s. intervention in lebanon and stop sending delegations to the middle east area, in order to surround the gains of the islamic revolution in occupied palestine
reagan has to take responsibility for the crimes he has committed against the oppressed people in the region
winds gusting up to 56 mph blasted gravel and other debris into the world's tallest building monday, and 90 of the sears tower's windows cracked or shattered, officials said
there were no reports of injuries from falling glass, said police and officials of sears, roebuck and co., which has its corporate headquarters in the building
police cordononed off the streets surrounding the 110-story building during the working rush hour, and planned to keep one closed as a precaution throughout the day
there are people in the process of boarding up windows and removing cracked windows,'' said gordon jones, a sears spokesman
the windows, 5 feet wide and 8 feet tall, began shattering and cracking at about 3:30 a.m. when gusts of up to 56 mph were recorded in the area, said ernest arms, another spokesman for sears
jones and arms said it appeared that one or more windows was broken by debris, perhaps pebbles from nearby roofs, and the others were broken as pieces came down
however, jones said, ``we don't really know _ it happened in the dark.''
jones said company officials did not have a damage estimate. all the cracked or broken windows were located between the 50th and 88th floors of the 1,454-foot building, said arms
five windows were broken during high winds in april 1984, he said
the former parish priest of an irish nationalist who was shot dead from a british army observation tower said monday the victim was harassed by police and soldiers for at least five years
the rev. brendan mchugh said aidan mcanespie, 23, had to cross into the irish republic every day to his job and was harassed constantly at the army checkpoint
we complained time out of number to the police and military, but no action was ever taken. life for the poor man had just become unbearable,'' mchugh told reporters
the army said it ``deeply regrets'' the shooting sunday. a spokesman said mcanespie was hit by a bullet fired from an observation post about half a mile from the frontier in county tyrone
police said the soldier involved was in military custody and an investigation was being conducted. the soldier was not identified and police would not comment on the priest's allegations
relatives said mcanespie was walking to a regular weekly gaelic football game in aughnacloy, the county tyrone village where he lives
francis molloy, a local councilman, said mcanespie was an election worker for sinn fein, legal political arm of the outlawed irish republican army. the ira denied he was among its members and mchugh, the priest, said he was not involved in paramilitary activity
he was never abused physically, just verbally, and his car was often taken apart,'' he said. ``i don't know why he was singled out for such treatment
the campaign against him must have been going on for at least five years. other young lads were also stopped, but aidan appeared to be getting special treatment.''
shootings of civilians by security forces have become rare compared with the early 1970s, when protestant-catholic strife in the british province was at its height
mcanespie's death came at a time of severe strain in anglo-irish relations over other incidents involving police and the province's roman catholic minority. the government in dublin demanded a speedy report
britain provoked irish outrage last month by saying it would not prosecute policemen accused of perverting justice in the aftermath of the killings of six unarmed catholics in three incidents in late 1982
the strain was compounded by a british appeals court's refusal to overturn the conviction of six irishmen for two bombings that killed 21 people in 1974. irish officials believe the six are victims of a miscarriage of justice
a federal judge monday dismissed drug-related charges against a woman whose boyfriend fell to his death from a plane in 1985 with 77 pounds of cocaine and a defective parachute strapped to his body
u.s. district judge james h. jarvis dropped the counts at the request of assistant u.s. attorney james r. dedrick, who last week lost a bid to use statements mad by rebecca sharp to undercover agents as evidence against her
ms. sharp, 32, a paralegal in lexington, ky., had been set to go on trial march 1 on charges of conspiring with her boyfriend, former lexington narcotics officer andrew thornton ii, to import cocaine and of distributing the drug
under the terms of the dismissal, dedrick can seek another indictment against ms. sharp. meanwhile, her attorney said ms. sharp was pleased at the movie and hopeful the case was over
thornton's body was found on a knoxville driveway sept. 11, 1985. bags of cocaine were tied to his waist, and federal authorities have linked him to about 200 pounds of the drug found in duffel bags scattered across northern georgia for apparent later retrieval. the empty plane was found crashed
a few days later, drug enforcement agency special agent kieran kobell, posing as an associate or representative of ``the colombians'' who supposedly provided thornton the cocaine, went to lexington with a government informant, bertram gordon
kobel said the two met with ms. sharp and she revealed an intimate knowledge of the cocaine smuggling operation
dedrick's motion did not specify why he wanted the charges dismissed, but it seems likely the suppression of ms. sharp's statements was a direct cause
u.s. magistrate robert p. murrian ruled feb. 12 that those statements were made in fear
kobell ``was playing the part of a colombian or representative of a colombian or colombians who had lost $12,000,000 worth of cocaine,'' he wrote in upholding the motion to keep ms. sharp's statements out of evidence
i believe that under the circumstances of this case, the defendant (ms. sharp) had to have been in great personal fear for her safety when she made the statements. ...,'' murrian wrote. ``it would have been smart from her point of view to promise that the deal would go through, that the colombians would not be `ripped off' and that she would kill if necessary to see that happen.''
murrian also said kobell threatened both ms. sharp and fred partin, her attorney in kentucky, according to partin's testimony at the suppression hearing. partin is a former assistant u.s. attorney
kobell has denied threatening ms. sharp
nine organizations, including the american academy of pediatrics and the national education association, announced formation monday of a coalition to lobby on behalf of children with aids
we need money from both government and private sources,'' said edward connor, a member of the academy of pediatrics
conner noted that about 80 percent of the known 839 cases of children with aids in the united states were born to mothers who are drug abusers themselves or sexual partners of drug abusers
if we could reach these prospective parents today, we could stop this expanding problem in nine months,'' he said at a press conference
but he acknowledged that drug abusers are the hardest group to educate about the threat of aids and said more money will be needed to pay for the kind of face-to-face contact that is required to reach them
rather than focus on a particular goal, representatives of the nine organizations said they would engage in a ``generic'' effort to make sure children are not forgotten as programs to combat aids are formulated and implemented
other members of the coalition: children's defense fund, american psychological association, national association of community health centers, child welfare league of america, american nurses association, national association of children's hospitals and related institutions and the western association of children's hospitals
sen. paul simon, who once said he'd drop out of the race for the democratic presidential nomination if he didn't come out of minnesota or south dakota with a victory, said monday he doesn't expect to carry either state but plans to fight on anyway
i'm continuing to campaign all the way to atlanta, period,'' the illinois senator told reporters during an appearance at the university of minnesota
simon also predicted that when the democratic national convention convenes in atlanta in july it would be ``not likely we will have any one person with a majority.''
on the eve of the minnesota precinct caucuses and the south dakota primary, simon was offering a new scenario for survival of his financially troubled campaign
i have to say candidly it is unlikely i am going to win in minnesota or south dakota,'' he said. ``i think we're going to do respectably. i think we're going to do respectably on super tuesday and then the whole thing, in a sense, starts over because i think we're going to have a very scattered result after that.''
he noted that the next big event after march 8, the day dubbed super tuesday because 20 states will hold primaries or caucuses, will be the primary in illinois, his home state
i think we're going to have a new ballgame,'' he said
after his third-place finish in the new hampshire primary last week, simon said he would drop out of the race if he didn't come up with a victory in minnesota or south dakota
what changed my mind,'' he said, ``was an avalanche of support from around the nation which said we want to have someone who represents the party's progressive wing.''
asked on what he based his contention that he would do ``respectably'' in the south on super tuesday, simon cited polls he said showed him ``doing pretty well'' on a state-by-state basis
i haven't led in any of them, but i've been doing pretty well so far,'' he said
during an earlier appearance at gustavus adolphus college in st. peter, simon proposed that anyone signing up for welfare be required to take a literacy test. if they can't read or write, they would be required to take an adult literacy program, he said
we need to move massively on this,'' he said
democrat albert gore jr. won the support monday of sen. howell heflin, a southern conservative who said he wanted to ``educate'' the presidential candidate to more conservative or moderate views
he's not too far to the left, but i've got to try to bring him to the middle a little bit,'' said heflin, of alabama. ``i'm going to work on him.''
heflin appeared with his senate colleague from neighboring tennessee at a news conference scheduled by the gore campaign to trumpet what they regarded as an endorsement by an influential and respected southern conservative lawmaker
gore also used the news conference to renew attacks on democratic rivals richard gephardt, a missouri congressman, for inconsistency and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis for foreign policy inexperience
heflin's remarks, however, highlighted the difference between the alabama senator's conservative voting record in congress and that of gore. gore has positioned himself to the right of his rivals on defense and foreign policy issues, but has a voting record that critics say is more liberal than his rhetoric suggests
heflin said gore has common sense and a ``down-home centralist philosophy.''
but he acknowledged gore was to the left of himself when he was asked about how they have differed on such issues as military aid to the nicaraguan contras and money for president reagan's nuclear defense shield program
i have a hope that i can educate him a little bit, and bring him over a little bit more,'' heflin said
gore opposes military aid to the contras, while saying he would support some humanitarian aid, and has opposed money for star wars, although he has said he would support some research consistent with existing treaties
gore had a rating of 70 in 1986 from the liberal americans for democratic action, meaning his votes on selected issues agreed with that group's position 70 percent of the time. he had a rating of 9 from the conservative american conservative union. heflin, by contrast, had ratings of 25 from the ada and 65 from the acu
heflin said he regarded gore as the most electable of the democratic candidates and ``strong on national defense.''
al gore is the only democratic candidate in this race who can carry the south in november,'' he said
his roots run deep in southern soil, and he has never forgotten rural america from whence he came,'' heflin said
gore renewed the criticism of his rivals, accusing dukakis of suggesting it was ``fine with him if the soviet union established a client state in central america, so long as they did not put soviet offensive weapons in that client state.'' dukakis has sharply denied making such a statement
it is another example of his total lack of experience in foreign policy,'' gore said
gore repeated criticism of gephardt for changing positions on issues such as abortion, the minimum wage and taxes. but gore acknowledged he had voted in 1984 for legislation that had mandatory production control provisions similar to the farm proposals gephardt now backs and gore denounces as disastrous for the economy
there is a difference between changing your mind on one or two issues over a 12-year period, and having a wholesale change in dozens and dozens of key positions,'' he said, referring to gephardt
he also said gephardt's ``whole approach to the electorate is in contrast to the approach during his career in the congress.''
gore also campaigned in maryland, one of the 20 states holding democratic primaries or caucuses march 8, where he said stopping the flow of illegal drugs into the country would be a top priority for his administration. he stopped at the coast guard's curtis bay shipyard, which the reagan administration has scheduled to close and which he pledged to keep open
president reagan asked the senate on monday to ratify a treaty with canada that he said should help the two countries prosecute terrorists, drug traffickers and other criminals
the treaty on mutual legal assistance in criminal matters was signed by reagan and canadian prime minister brian mulroney at their meeting in quebec city, canada, on march 18, 1985. the white house said submission was delayed while annexes to the pact were worked out by the two nations
it is one of a series of such legal assistance treaties being negotiated by the united states
similar pacts have gone into force with italy, the netherlands, switzerland and turkey
others have been signed but not yet gone into force with colombia, morocco, mexico, thailand, belgium, the bahamas and the united kingdom on behalf of the cayman islands
reagan sent the treaty with mexico to the senate for consideration just before his meeting with mexican president miguel de la madrid in mazatlan, mexico, on feb. 13
in his message to the senate, he said the treaty with canada ``should be an effective tool to prosecute a wide variety of modern criminals including members of drug cartels, `white-collar criminals' and terrorists.''
the treaty provides for the two countries to assist each other in taking testimony or statements of witnesses; providing documents, records and evidence; executing requests for searches and seizures and serving documents
it also provides for assistance in proceedings relating to forfeiture of the proceeds of crime, restitution for victims and collection of fines. capital</head>
this seaside town is girding for another successful spring break, while former mecca fort lauderdale faces defections to exotic resorts and uncertainty at home over whether it should keep encouraging college students
the 1960 film ``where the boys are'' established fort lauderdale as the nation's spring break center, but daytona beach has taken the lead in florida recently
daytona beach will play host this year to about 500,000 young vacationers between feb. 28 and april 1, while fort lauderdale may be lucky to attract the 200,000 that came last year, officials say
not all of the defectors are going to daytona beach
in recent years, the bahamas, florida's panhandle, texas' south padre island and the mexican resorts in cancun and acapulco have cultivated the free-spending students
i doubt if i have 100 reservations to fort lauderdale, but probably 8,000 for cancun,'' rob brown, president of travel turf tours in bethlehem, pa. told the wall street journal last week
there's some talk about how mexico's coming into prominence,'' florida tourism division spokesman raul marcucci said monday. ``it started happening last year.''
but with 16,000 hotel rooms along 23 miles of beach, daytona beach is expecting a strong turnout
we know that, on an average, each student visiting daytona beach spends between $325 and $400 here,'' said evelyn fine, executive director of the mid-florida research and business center of daytona beach community college. ``assuming each dollar is spent seven times in the local economy, my guess is we're looking at about $130 million this year.''
mtv and national college television networks will broadcast live from daytona beach over the peak march 20 weekend
two breweries are sponsoring free concerts, a soft drink maker is sending a portable dance club to motel parking lots, and countless other national distributors will promote everything from suntan lotion to peppermint schnapps, including tennis shoes and do-it-yourself pregnancy tests
tour promoters say daytona beach has become the spring break mecca partly because fort lauderdale officials, weary of the trouble that came with the collegians, have been cracking down
in the past five years, i've seen a gradual increase to daytona, just because of the strictness of the enforcement in lauderdale,'' said ron good, president of campus marketing inc. in glen ellyn, ill. ``you can really kind of let loose in daytona; it's a little bit wilder.''
daytona beach police jailed 270 people when an all-night, rock-throwing melee broke out on the strip in 1975. but fort lauderdale ran into even more trouble. a crackdown two years ago resulted in 2,500 arrests
across florida, state officials this year are urging bar owners to obey the law on the drinking age of 21
the division of alcoholic beverages and tobacco is presenting workshops in traditional spring break cities to educate bar owners and employees about florida's drinking laws
meanwhile, ``for sale'' signs have been sprouting in fort lauderdale
last year was a devastating year for a lot of the small hotels, and some of these mom-and-pop hotels already are being listed for sale,'' said real estate broker max sebastiani
while city officials emphasize family vacations, some merchants are still rooting for the college students
there's only a small group that doesn't want the college students,'' said ``crazy gregg'' newell, former bar owner and director of the fort lauderdale '88 committee promoting spring break. ``and they don't seem to be directly involved with beach business.''
