scandals surrounding two of the most prominent ministers of the assemblies of god may have created a false impression that the church is riddled with discipline problems, an official said monday
the evangelical church, which counts more than 16 million adherents worldwide and operates four colleges in springfield, is investigating the misconduct of louisiana evangelist jimmy swaggart. officials say swaggart has revealed an undisclosed transgression. on sunday, he tearfully stepped down from his television pulpit
another prominent television evangelist, the ptl's jimmy bakker, lost his assemblies of god credentials last year amid charges of sexual misconduct. swaggart was said to have been active in uncovering that scandal and bakker accused him of plotting to take over ptl
`those are the only two in our whole denomination that have that kind of recognition,'' said church spokeswoman juleen turnage. ``so people may feel that this is indicative of the assemblies of god denomination, and that is not true
we have over 30,000 credentialed ministers in the assemblies of god in the united states. at any given time, any given year, fewer than one-half of 1 percent are ever called into discipline... .''
mrs. turnage said 12 areas of misconduct, ranging from doctrinal aberrations to moral failure, call for disciplinary action
mrs. turnage said that, according to by-laws, the church's louisiana district has six months to complete its investigation of swaggart, though it is not expected to take that long
now that he has confessed to the sin, it will be a matter of the district meeting and forwarding a report and its reccommendation to the executive presbytery here in springfield,'' mrs. turnage said
swaggart could be suspended or dismissed as an assemblies minister. in either case, he would have the option of entering a rehabilitation program that would take at least two years, turnage said
swaggart appeared before his congregation in baton rouge, la., sunday to ask forgiveness from his family and church for an act he did not describe publicly. he said he would not return to his pulpit until the church investigation was completed. measures</head>
soldiers, guerrillas and a communist leader were killed monday despite emergency measures to curb one of the bloodiest spates of violence the country has seen in three decades
ten peasants were singled out at a cockfight sunday and shot by men wearing black hoods, official reports said. in all, 27 people have been killed in ambushes and assassinations over two days
president virgilio barco last month ordered a state of emergency in an attempt to halt a wave of violence that has taken the lives of more than 1,700 people in the last year. more than 120 people have been killed this year
most of those deaths came after barco ordered army troops to reinforce the police and increased jail terms for many violent crimes, especially those committed by drug traffickers, leftist guerrillas and paid assassins
leftist guerrillas on monday released seven mayors and two reporters kidnapped earlier this month, the radio stations rcn and caracol said
last week the rebels freed four mayors and a reporter they had abducted. the guerrillas warned the mayors to budget more money to help the poor and said they planned to blow up the country's main oil pipeline again to keep oil from being exported
all 11 mayors and three reporters kidnapped were from towns in northeast colombia and all had been held for about a week
the kidnappings were by the national liberation army, known as the eln, which follows the political ideology of cuba's fidel castro. the rebel group has blown up the country's main oil pipeline 13 times since jan. 12
the latest victim of an apparent right wing death squad was carlos gonima, a communist leader and assistant city attorney in the northwest city of medellin
a man riding on a motorcycle monday shot and killed gonima and wounded his driver as gonima headed for work at city hall, the national police said in a news release
gonima was a member of the leftist patriotic union party, which has seen more than 500 of its members killed since it was organized by former guerrillas in 1985
leftist guerrillas ambushed an army patrol monday, killing four soldiers, the press office for the government of the state of antioquia said in a news release
in southwest colombia guerrillas attacked the towns of trujillo and caloto on sunday and killed seven policemen, the army's 8th brigade said in a communique
near vistahermosa, in a jungled area in the southeast state of meta, 20 men wearing black hoods and carrying submachine guns surrounded dozens of men attending a cockfight on sunday, the police said
ten peasants were separated from the group and and shot as they pleaded for their lives, the policer said. the police report did not say who was suspected in the massacre. drug traffickers have long dominated large areas of the vast jungles in eastern colombia
the traffickers kill people they suspect of being informers or for refusing to let traffickers use their land for growing coca trees, the source for cocaine
a broadcast reporter and a mother and her 15-month-old girl were killed sunday when gunmen opened fire on the reporter's car as the three traveled along a highway near the western city of cali, the national police there said in a news release
the reporter, belisario zambrano, of the cali station rcn, was the 30th reporter to be slain in colombia in 11 years. zambrano reported frequently on the government's efforts against narcotics
an indian running for mayor in a small town in northwest colombia was assassinated sunday
the victim, jose gilberto motato, was the leading candidate for mayor in the town of riosucio, the mayor there, alberto diaz, said in a broadcast report over the radio chain caracol
motato was the leader of an indian movement for land reform and other programs to help poor people in the area in the state of caldas
a city councilman, rafael ballesteros, was also killed sunday in chicogorodo in the northwest state of antioquia, the bogota daily el tiempo quoted national police there as saying
the councilman was a member of the ruling liberal party. about 100 members of colombia's two dominate parties, the liberal and the conservative, have been killed in the last year, with the army and police blaming guerrillas for most of the killings
exporters have sold china an additional 405,000 metric tons of u.s. wheat at subsidized prices for delivery in the 1987-88 marketing year, the agriculture department said monday
the sales, equal to almost 14.9 million bushels, were handled by five companies: cargill inc., 135,000 tons; nichimen america inc., 35,000; bunge corp., 35,000; continental grain co., 100,000; and artfer inc., 100,000
william l. davis, acting general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said the sales were part of an authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced feb. 5 under the export enhancement program, or eep
although no selling prices or other details were announced, recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $2.76 per bushel, indicating a u.s. farm value of about $41 million
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat
china bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous eep arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies
davis said the bonuses due the five companies averaged $40.38 per ton, or about $1.10 per bushel of wheat. the bonuses will be paid in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp
china has 495,000 tons remaining for use under the eep initiative announced on feb. 5, he said
four small bombs exploded in the parking lot of a u.s. military compound early monday, damaging several cars but causing no injuries, police reported
they said at least one person climbed the fence around the cook barracks before dawn and set six homemade devices on the ground beside parked cars, but only four of the bombs went off
police estimated the damage at $2,900. they said no individual or group claimed responsibility for the attack. u.s. officials did not comment on the incident
cook barracks is located on the outskirts of goeppingen in the southern state of baden-wuerttemberg
a 24-year-old mental patient who was not considered dangerous walked away from a psychiatric center and assaulted two relatives with a hatchet monday, critically injuring one of them, police said
the patient, donald rattray, was arrested at his home in the city's bronx section after he allegedly assaulted his brother-in-law and an uncle at 5 a.m., said sgt. maurice howard, a police spokesman
rattray was not considered dangerous by officials at bronx psychiatric center, to which he had been voluntarily admitted, said steven osborne, a spokesman for the state office of mental health
the brother-in-law, james selvin, 30, was struck twice in the head by the hatchet. he underwent surgery for his wounds and was listed in critical condition at jacobi hospital, spokesman susan mueller said
the uncle, onis rattray, 46, was in stable condition at the hospital with cuts to the left hand. both men lived with rattray
rattray was being held on charges of first-degree assault and criminal possession of a deadly instrument, the hatchet
rattray escaped from the psychiatric center saturday evening, osborne said
he got into an unlocked janitor's closet on the second floor, broke the window and escaped by tying a bunch of sheets together and climbing from the second floor window,'' osborne said
rattray was voluntarily admitted to the hospital feb. 16., osborne said
rattray had left the center without consent feb. 8, the spokesman said. police were called to the family home feb. 13 because rattray was behaving irrationally, howard said. he then voluntarily readmitted himself
patients who are voluntarily admitted to the hospital may petition to leave at any time, but the approval process takes up to three days, osborne said
a contingency plan to help prevent an uncontrolled meltdown of the financial markets won the endorsement monday of the chairman of the house energy and commerce committee and three other representatives
our markets remain vibrant, but they are at the same time delicate,'' rep. john dingell, d-mich., wrote in a letter to the heads of three regulatory agencies. ``to permit them to function without such a contingency plan courts unnecessary risk.''
the letter was also signed by reps. edward markey, d-mass., chairman of the house telecommunications and finance subcommittee; norman lent, r-n.y., ranking minority member on the energy and commerce committee, and matthew rinaldo, r-n.j., ranking minority member of the finance subcommittee
the letter to the securities and exchange commission, commodity futures trading commission and federal reserve board was prompted by the oct. 19 stock crash
the market decline ... was a wrenching and sobering experience for the marketplace, market participants, regulators and those of us in congress with oversight responsibilities for our securities markets,'' the letter said
it noted a recommendation by the general accounting office, congress' research arm, that regulators prepare a plan for dealing with any similar emergency in the future
we believe that his recommendation ... should be implemented as a concrete first step toward increased coordination among the markets and restoration of investor confidence,'' the letter said
the congressmen asked the regulators to report to congress by march 25 on their efforts to craft a plan for coordinating decisions by regulators and communicating them to the markets
they also asked the agencies to determine ``how much authority the marketplaces should have to act independently of the regulators in crisis circumstances.''
the letter urged the agencies to agree on circumstances that would allow relaxed interpretation of rules ``to facilitate market liquidity, such as the interpretation of rules associated with corporate stock repurchase plans,'' and on the provision of funds to the economy by the federal reserve during times of market turmoil
congress, meanwhile, has been considering long-term measures to ensure greater market coordination, ranging from a partial merger of the sec and cftc to the creation of a new oversight body. bgng: ``blandon, a ...'' to update with meeting lasting 2{ hours.</note>
a former top aide to panamana's strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega met under heavy guard monday at the u.s. courthouse with prosecutors investigating the iran-contra affair
jose i. blandon presumably was questioned by the staff of independent counsel lawrence e. walsh about noriega's agreement to train nicaraguan rebels at the request of lt. col. oliver north, a former national security council official who is a target of walsh's investigation
blandon, a former panamanian intelligence official, was escorted by heavily armed u.s. marshals as he arrived at the courthouse for his 2{-hour meeting with members of walsh's staff
a former top intelligence official in the panamanian government, blandon was a key informant for federal prosecutors in florida who earlier this month obtained indictments charging noriega with taking at least $4.6 million in bribes to protect a major colombian drug ring
he is now in the protective custody of u.s. marshals
blandon recently told the senate foreign relations committee that noriega agreed to provide training for nicaraguan anti-sandinista rebels after recieving a request from north in 1985
north sought the training on panamanian soil because congress had banned direct u.s. military aide to the rebels, blandon said
blandon, who was fired last month as panama's consul general in new york, told congressional hearings earlier this month that north met with noriega on a yacht in june 1985 near the panamanian city of balboa. the two met again four months later in noriega's office, blandon said
during one of the meetings, noriega offered to send panamanian soldiers to nicaragua on ``terrorist sabotage'' missions but north said he had no authority to accept such an offer, blandon said. north said, however, he would relay noriega's offer to his superiors at the national security council, blandon testified
blandon said noriega also met in december 1985 with rear adm. john m. poindexter, who had just been appointed national security adviser
poindexter, who is also a target of walsh's investigation, resigned nov. 24, 1986 following revelations that proceeds of u.s. arms sales to iran had been diverted to help buy arms for the contras
north was fired the same day that poindexter submitted his resignation to president reagan
in his testimony to the senate foreign relations committee, blandon said noriega headed a ``criminal empire'' that sold drugs with the knowledge of u.s. officials
blandon also said one of noriega's pilots flew a cargo of cocaine to a ranch in costa rica owned by an american supporter of the contras
noriega was indicted by federal grand juries in miami and tampa earlier this month on charges that he accepted at least $4.6 million in payoffs from colombia's medellin drug cartel, said to supply 80 percent of the cocaine shipped to this country
the indictments charge that noriega accepted the payoffs in return for laundering drug money, providing protection for cocaine shipments and a haven for drug dealers. noriega has strongly denied any wrongdoing
state and local government workers received annual pay raises last year averaging 4.9 percent under collective bargaining contracts with public employee unions, the labor department said monday
the pay increases were below the average 5.7 percent raises received by state and local government employees in 1986. but the workers still fared better last year than federal employees who got a 3 percent pay increase and private sector workers whose wages rose an average 3.3 percent
however, the bureau of labor statistics noted that union contracts in the public and private sectors differ significantly
state and local governments, for example, tend to have a higher proportion of professional and white-collar workers. union contracts in the private sector, on the other hand, often include lump-sum bonuses and cost-of-living adjustments excluded from the wage calculations and usually absent in the public sector
the figures showed that local government workers with wage increases averaging 5.3 percent outpaced state employees workers with an average 4.3 percent raise
among occupation groups, primary and secondary school teachers got the biggest raises at 6.3 percent, followed by transit and other transportation workers at 4.8 percent. reaction; picks up old graf 17, ``illinois gov. ...''; adds one graf with captain kangaroo.</note>
president reagan cautioned the nation's governors monday against pressing for costly federal solutions to the problems of welfare and child care
his remarks to the national governors' association were labeled a disappointment by massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, a democratic presidential hopeful, who said reagan should be backing the governors' bipartisan welfare reform bill in the senate
reagan instead said he still strongly supports a less costly republican alternative that the house rejected two months ago
he also cautioned the governors to go slow on the issue of child care, where both democrats and republicans in congress are proposing to expand federal support and subsidies for working parents
maybe it's my conservative bent, but i can't help but feel uneasy sometimes,'' he told the governors gathered in the east room of the white house
welfare programs have become ``a crippling poverty trap . ... they keep the poor poor,'' reagan said. ``now, much of the push for child care is designed to rectify the ills of earlier programs, and many of these efforts are timely and good. but in this area, more than any other, government should tread carefully.''
reagan said the alternative bill sponsored by house minority leader robert michel, r-ill., would also give states freedom to ``develop your own ideas on child care.''
afterwards, dukakis told reporters that he was very disappointed
just one word from the president, i think, would get this bill passed and done before the election, and get it off the table as a partisan issue and get going,'' said dukakis
he keeps telling us stories about california, and we're trying to explain to him that the vast majority of people on welfare these days are single mothers with young children, and it's a combination of real training for real jobs, combined with day care, that makes a difference,'' said dukakis
howard baker, reagan's chief of staff, said reagan would veto the house-passed welfare reform bill, but might approve a less expensive measure still being shaped by the senate finance committee
the governors are pushing sen. daniel patrick moynihan's bill, which would toughen enforcement of child support, help states pay for job training and make participation mandatory for most unemployed adults. it would also provide some transitional medicaid and welfare benefits for families exiting the relief rolls for work
moynihan, a new york democrat, has 56 co-sponsors for his bill, which would cost $2.3 billion over five years, compared to the $4.3 billion house bill, which would raise benefits and prohibit states from denying welfare to families with both parents in the home
baker said the moynihan bill is not yet satisfactory, but he held out the hope that moynihan and sen. john heinz, r-pa., might be able to fashion a compromise satisfactory to reagan
heinz, like moynihan a member of the senate finance committee, has not introduced an alternative bill
moynihan said in a telephone interview he heard two messages from reagan: ``one says that we're going to veto the house bill. the other says we can try to work something out. i choose to respond to the second message. there's too much at stake here. if the president is interested in the subject, i'll be happy to work with sen. heinz on anything.''
rep. tom downey, d-n.y., who spearheaded passage of the house bill, said in an interview, ``the time to do something about welfare is now and the only person who seems opposed to it or looking at the past is the president. we're not going to end child poverty by leaving it to the states to do it. they don't have the money.''
illinois gov. james thompson, a republican, told reporters, ``i think there's just a fundamental disagreement about how far to go on welfare reform, especially with regard to cost. the governors changed their mind, not the president.'' but despite that sticking point, thompson said, ``i still hold out hope that between the administration and the senate we'll get a bill.''
arkansas gov. bill clinton, a democrat who is leading the governors' push for welfare reform, emerged from the meeting and said he felt reagan was open to compromise
i am encouraged because basically their negotiating strategy with everybody always is to take the hardest possible line and then come off of it at the end,'' clinton said
in the private meeting that followed reagan's speech, clinton said, ``i told him we thought his bill was not a good bill and that we were willing to make some changes in what came out of the house, but we weren't going to get anywhere if his emissary kept saying, `well, we're going to veto whatever passes that we don't like.''
clinton said reagan replied that ``he heard us ... and was willing to work with us, so i think that's good.''
alabama gov. guy hunt, a republican, said he shared reagan's misgivings about the house-passed welfare bill. he said it ``might really compound the problem'' by increasing federal funding without giving states more control over welfare rules
what the states need is flexibility to allow them to ``gradually remove (people) from welfare'' instead of terminating their benefits as soon as they get a job, hunt said
later, the governors' committee on human resources heard television's captain kangaroo, bob keeshan, plead for corporations to start providing quality day care. ``i'm almost ashamed at times to be an american,'' the children's performer and advocate said. ``we are half a century behind in addressing day care. we are going to pay an enormous price a quarter-century down the line.''
president reagan on monday designated edward j. philbin, a former san diego lawyer and law professor, as acting chairman of the federal maritime commission
edward v. hickey jr., chairman of the commission, died in january
philbin, 55, has been a member of the commission since 1984. before that, he served three years as deputy assistant secretary of defense for reserve affairs
philbin joined the university of san diego law faculty in 1970 and became assistant dean in 1973. he was also a partner in a san diego law firm specializing in civil litigation
he is a member of the naval air reserve and served several tours of active duty. vote</head>
sen. sam nunn said monday the new u.s.-soviet nuclear arms control treaty won't be ratified until after his armed services committee the panel finishes its line-by-line examination of the pact
that laborious process began monday after the state department sent the senate 31 volumes of documents involved in the long negotiations which led to the intermediate-range nuclear forces (inf) pact
it is very regrettable that we have to go through this,'' said the georgia democrat, who emerged victorious in a fight with the reagan administration over the legal meaning of treaties
nunn, chairman of the armed services panel, said he didn't know how long it would take the committee to finish its work
the panel is one of three senate committees considering the treaty, which was signed in december by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. ratification by the full senate, which requires a two-thirds vote, is expected later
the inf fight was based on a previous dispute between the democratic-controlled congress and the reagan administration over the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty and reagan's star wars anti-missile program
a number of star wars tests would be banned unless the united states moved from the current ``narrow'' interpretation of the abm treaty to a ``broad'' view
the reagan administration had asserted it wasn't bound by what previous administrations told congress about the meaning of the abm pact, a view the white house at one point tried to push in the senate debate over the inf treaty
nunn threatened to block the treaty until secretary of state george p. shultz promised last month that administration comments on the treaty were ``authoritative,'' meaning that future administrations couldn't try to change how the treaty is viewed
since shultz's promise was delivered, ``we can now proceed, confident that the treaty the committee is being asked to approve is the same treaty'' the administration believes it negotiated, nunn told maynard glitman, one of the chief negotiators for the u.s. team which worked out the treaty, during a committee meeting monday
the committee has sent the state department a list of 135 questions about possible ambiguities in the treaty, nunn said. most are technical questions but some involve queries about possible interpretation of the pact, which bans missiles with ranges from 300 miles to 3,400 miles
sen. john glenn, d-ohio, told glitman, ``i'm sorry there was a reinterpretation of the abm treaty that made this necessary.''
it's sad we have to go through the exercise we're going through here,'' said sen. james exon, d-neb
while the armed services panel was going through a detailed scrutiny of the pact, the senate foreign relations committee continued taking testimony from public witnesses
dr. edward teller, the physicist who is considered the father of both the hydrogen bomb and reagan's star wars program, told the foreign relations panel he thought the fights over the meanings of treaties were ``senseless debates.''
teller said he supports the treaty, although he is deeply distrustful of the soviet union
speaking of the treaty, he said, ``my personal approach is careful, doubtful, yet positive,'' he said
six european relief workers abducted by rebels in ethiopia's northern tigre province were released monday and are in good condition, spokesmen for a belgian medical organization reported
they said the doctors and nurses were seized thursday in tigre where separatists have been fighting the marxist government for years
reginald moreels, president of the belgian branch of medecins sans frontieres (doctors without borders), told a news conference the victims were belgian doctors germaine hanquet and michel moreau, dutch nurse roland raaijmaekers an irish doctor and two irish nurses
moreels said they were released in adigrat, 12 miles north of idaga hamous where the aid organization has been operating a hospital for three years
news of their release was reported to brussels by dr. pierre harze, who had been sent to ethiopia to try to gain their freedom
morrels said harze had not yet met with the six
jean-pierre luxen, director of the belgian organization, said the two belgian doctors would go to northern city of asmara and return to belgium later this week. he said other doctors would replace them at the hospital in idaga hamous, 340 miles north of the capital of addis ababa
luxen said the medical team was abducted without violence by members of the popular front for the liberation of the tigre who also seized the group's vehicle and medical supplies
seyoum musse, an official with the popular front's office in london, had announced earlier monday that the six had been released
in a telephone interview in london, he said: ``the whole aim of taking them with us was to show there are millions of people who are beyond the reach of ... isolated symbolic (government) food distribution centers like the one they were stationed at
the aim is to dispel the government's misinformation that millions are being reached with aid,'' he added
he said the government will not allow foreign relief volunteers ``to go outside the place they work. for this reason we have taken them a few hours away. they are the guests of millions of starved people.''
medicins san frontieres is an international non-governmental organization that has medical aid projects in 15 countries in central america, africa, the middle east and asia
two more universities on monday announced plans to help boost the number and expertise of peace corps volunteers with programs giving them graduate-level training or course credits for their service
starting with about 10 students in the 1988-89 school year, the university of alabama at birmingham will offer candidates for master's degrees in public health a chance to ``get their training before they do their (peace corps) service,'' said dr. juan m. navia, chairman of the school's public health department
some of our finest (public health graduate) students are the ones who have served in other countries as peace corps volunteers. and many of them have the frustration: `if only i had know this then,''' navia said at a news conference at the carter presidential center. ``we're going to reverse the order.''
peace corps director loret miller ruppe also signed an agreement monday with the university of south carolina in columbia, which will offer internship credit to special education graduate students who do a tour of duty in the peace corps
mrs. ruppe said the two programs are similar to one announced earlier for public health master's degree candidates at boston university, also starting next fall. and all three are modeled after a program for master's degree students in public policy at rutgers university, which will send its first group of volunteers to the peace corps this spring
these programs will help us ensure a steady flow of volunteers with the skills we need in developing countries,'' mrs. ruppe said
she said the corps hopes to double the number of volunteers by 1992 and to increase dramatically the number of minority volunteers, who now number about 110 out of 5,200
the peace corps is starting a number of innovative programs to help meet that goal
harvard university school of dentistry has agreed to send some of its fifth-year dental students to the peace corps for six-month stints, in an experiment with shorter tours of duty than the usual two years, she said
under another new program, teachers in virginia can take sabbaticals to spend a year in peace corps-sponsored teacher training centers around the world, she said
in northfield, vt., some military cadets at norwich university are participating in a peace corps alternative to campus rotc and eventual military service. a bill pending in congress would authorize $5 million a year for five years to enable the peace corps to test the rotc-alternative program elsewhere
both the alabama and south carolina programs will target minorities
also monday, helene robertson of birmingham, ala., a 77-year-old former peace corps volunteer to botswana, received the lillian carter award for enduring voluntary commitment
the award is named after former president jimmy carter's mother, who was in her 60s when she served in the peace corps in india
receiving ``leader for peace'' awards were lillian lewis, wife of rep. john lewis, d-ga., an original peace corps volunteer in 1961 and associate director of the institute for international affairs and development at atlanta university; atlanta mayor andrew young for a recruiting public service announcement he did for the peace corps; and the coca-cola co. for its financing of a peace corps program to re-establish contact with former volunteers
a funeral will be held wednesday for roger j. williams, a leading authority on nutrition who died at age 94
a professor emeritus at the university of texas, williams died saturday of pneumonia in an austin nursing home. he had been in ill health for several months, but still kept in touch with ut scientists, many of whom he persuaded to come to austin
williams' work in nutrition at the ut clayton foundation biochemical institute, which he founded, led to the discovery of more vitamins and their variants than at any other research facility in the world
he was particularly interested in the role nutrition played in physical and mental well-being. until he retired in 1985, williams worked regularly in his laboratory on the ut campus
williams was a proponent of ``biochemical individuality,'' a concept that no two people are exactly alike physiologically and therefore everyone has different nutritional requirements
one of williams' most significant accomplishments was the discovery and isolation of pantothenic acid, one of the ``universal vitamins'' required by all living cells and essential to life. later he discovered and named folic acid, a substance used by every cell in the body
survivors include his wife, phyllis, three sons, a daughter, nine grandchildren and 10 great-grandchildren
dr. david otis fuller, a fundamentalist preacher who helped found a children's radio ministry and the grand rapids baptist college and seminary, has died at age 84
fuller died sunday at blodgett memorial medical center, hours after complaining of faintess during a prayer meeting at wealthy park baptist church, where he was pastor until his 1974 retirement
born in brooklyn, n.y., fuller founded the children's bible hour, a grand rapids-based christian radio program now broadcast by 660 radio stations worldwide
he was one of the leading fundamentalist preachers in the country,'' said the rev. robert gage, minister of wealthy park baptist church. ``it is going to leave a big void for us.''
funeral services are scheduled for wednesday at wealthy park
fuller is survived by his wife, virginia; a daughter, mrs. beverly berman of west hartford, conn.; sons alan of golden, colo., and david of tuckahoe, n.y.; a sister, muriel fuller of new york city; 10 grandchildren and one great-grandson. with reagan congratulatory message and planned response. pickup 7th graf pvs ``denktash proposed...''</note>
cyprus' greek and turkish leaders sparred monday only a day after elections, with the turkish head proposing talks in neutral territory and the greek president-elect insisting they be held on his own turf
the dispute over a matter of protocol disappointed some who had for a new start in talks to reunify cyprus in a federation
the sparring began when turkish cypriot leader rauf denktash invited greek cypriot president-elect george vassiliou to informal talks on the future of the island, to be held in a neutral area. vassiliou countered with an invitation to denktash ``to come and see me at the presidential palace.''
i am the elected president of the cyprus republic and in that capacity i would be most happy to welcome mr. denktash as the leader of the turkish cypriot community,'' vassiliou said in a radio interview
denktash is president of the breakaway turkish republic of northern cyprus, which was proclaimed in 1983 and is internationally recognized only by turkey. he does not recognize vassiliou, who will be sworn in next sunday, as president of all cyprus
vassiliou, a millionaire businessman backed by the communist party, defeated veteran right-wing politician glafcos clerides in general elections sunday. only greek cypriots voted
an official announcement said president reagan sent vassiliou a message of congratulations, expressing the wish to continue relations with cyprus
i look forward, through you, to continuing the friendly relations between our two countries, a relationship which has been characterized by a special warmth and a constant effort to build mutual respect and understanding,'' reagan's message said
i know that you have the determination to make the effort to bring about the lasting peace which has so long escaped the people of cyprus,'' the message said
vassiliou said he will thank reagan in a message expressing hope the united states will more actively to persuade turkey to withdraw its troops
denktash proposed in his invitation to vassiliou that the talks be held at the ledra palace hotel, a u.n. headquarters on the green line dividing turkish and greek cypriots. he said the meeting ``would be between the leaders of the two politically equal parties or between the presidents of two equal political entities.''
vassiliou had said during his campaign that he was willing to meet with the turkish cypriots without preconditions
but his counter-offer to meet denktash at the presidential palace in the greek cypriot-controlled zone, citing his own role as president of cyprus and denktash only as leader of the turkish cypriot community, was certain to be rebuffed
in the interview with the british broadcasting corp., vassiliou indicated no new flexibility in the conflict between greek and turkish cypriots
he accused turkey of building up its military presence in the turkish cypriot zone in northern cyprus since the 1974 invasion which partitioned the island. the invasion followed a coup by greek cypriot extremists aimed at uniting the entire island with greece
the realities of cyprus are that in these years, turkey, instead of recucing its military presence here, has been building it up in every way,'' he said
he also accused turkey of bringing in 40,000 to 50,000 turkish settlers to beef up the turkish cypriot minority, which numbered 120,000 at the time of the invasion. the greek cypriot population is more than 500,000
after election results were announced early monday, vassiliou said he would work for the withdrawal of turkish troops and settlers, but woud try to achieve a spirit of rapprochement with the turkish cypriots
greek-turkish negotiations have been stalled since president spyros kyprianou, who lost a bid for a third term in the first round of elections feb. 14, rejected proposals for a two-zone federation proposed by the united nations in 1986
the proposals had been accepted by denktash, who now insists upon them as the basis for restarting talks
kyprianou had insisted that before any talks began on a federation, all turkish troops must withdraw and the turks must allow greek cypriot refugees, who fled after the 1974 invasion, to return to their homes in the north
the u.n. proposals suggested that talks on troop withdrawal and the ``right of return'' would be discussed by committees simultaneously with talks on the nature of the federation
secretary of state george p. shultz tasted the fruits of mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms first-hand monday as he hosted a candlelit dinner at a cooperative restaurant that was once a money-losing bar
the red-brick skazka (``fairy tale'') restaurant off southeastern moscow's taganka square would have been illegal before last year's decision by soviet authorities to loosen laws governing individual labor and cooperative ownership
as soon as we heard they were authorizing cooperatives, we decided to start one,'' said sergei v. kutuzov, the head of the nine-member collective that runs the skazka
the restaurant, which can seat 34 customers in its upstairs dining room, opened april 1 last year. its hearty russian fare swiftly made it so popular with muscovites and foreign residents that profits soared to as much as $23,300 a month, kutuzov said
skazka's friendly waitresses and prompt service are in stark contrast to the situation that prevails at most of moscow's state-owned restaurants, where customers sometimes wait for hours before being served
cooperatives are also more expensive than state-run restaurants, which has led some soviets to oppose them as socially unjust
the dinner menu offered shultz cost between $25 and $33 per person, kutuzov said, compared to an average of $3 to $8 for an evening meal in a government-owned restaurant
a table piled with sturgeon in aspic, pickled vegetables inside a pumpkin, bottles of mineral water and grapes was set out for shultz, who had finished two days of talks in moscow with top soviet officials, including gorbachev, the communist party leader
skazka's chefs also prepared homemade noodle soup with mushrooms, a cabbage soup called ``shchi,'' stuffed pork cutlets, dumplings with mushroom and chicken and small russian pancakes
shultz, who was accompanied by his wife helena and u.s. ambassador jack matlock, met in the dining room with some of the soviet union's top cultural figures and intellectuals, including cinematographer elem klimov, playwright mikhail shatrov, economist nikolai shmelov and writer vladimir soloukhin
reporters briefly allowed into the wood-paneled room before shultz arrived spotted one apparent concession to the vip guests _ bottles of georgian and french wines set out on a table
as a cooperative, the skazka normally does not have the right to serve alcohol
gorbachev said in mid-january that 13,000 co-ops had been established in the soviet union. he said more than 300,000 people were working for themselves within guidelines set by the government to encourage better services and goods than those provided by the state-run sector
the venture has been a clear success for the nine people who put up a total of $5,000 to launch the skazka. last month kutuzov, chairman of the skazka cooperative, took home $1,050, more than three times the average soviet wage of $330
the building that now contains the restaurant was once a bar favored by ``lyubers,'' body-building enthusiasts from a moscow suburb that some press reports have said prey on long-haired soviet youths who like western rock music
either because of its tough clientele, or because the health-conscious lyubers did not drink enough alcohol, the bar lost money, kutuzov said
now its clientele has radically changed, with foreigners making up as much as 90 percent of the dinner customers on a given evening, kutuzov said
the guided-missile frigate uss antrim has been selected to steam through the nation's mid-section this year for the navy's annual great lakes cruise, the service said monday
the cruise, part of the navy's campaign to recruit sailors, will send the antrim to 21 ports over three months
this annual navy event ... offers a unique opportunity for residents of the great lakes region to see first-hand a ship from today's modern navy,'' the service said
the antrim will begin its cruise with a june 16 stopover at port jefferson, n.y., the navy said. among the larger cities to be visited are montreal; windsor, ontario; milwaukee; chicago; duluth, minn.; erie, pa.; oswego, n.y., and toronto
the antrim will end the 1988 cruise in september with stops in baltimore and savannah, ga., on the way to its homeport in mayport, fla
vice president george bush stumped in south carolina monday, saying sen. strom thurmond's endorsement of rival bob dole raises the stakes in the state's march 5 republican presidential primary
i have great respect for sen. thurmond,'' said bush. ``it's going to make this an even more dramatic ground of confrontation.''
the south carolina gop primary comes just three days before the super tuesday round of contests in 20 other, mostly southern states. the four republican candidates have said their showing in south carolina will be crucial leading into super tuesday
during a three-hour visit to myrtle beach, bush spoke briefly at a civic club luncheon, addressed about 1,200 students and visitors at myrtle beach high school and then held a series of meetings with reporters
gov. carroll campbell, the chairman of bush's southern campaign accompanied the vice president and said the dole campaign has ``created a do-or-die situation'' by pushing for the south carolina senator's endorsement
everybody loves strom thurmond, i love strom thurmond. i think they've raised the stakes. they've said, `now we've got him; now we're going to win,''' campbell said
bush called south carolina ``a key state'' and campaign aides said he will likely spend at least four more days campaigning in the state prior to march 5
bush, with reporters in tow, stopped briefly at a luncheon meeting of the myrtle beach rotary club at a local seafood restaurant
i think i'm going to win in south carolina,'' bush said. ``if i win in south carolina, i will be the next president of the united states.''
bush flew to the state from texas, before heading on for additional stops in tennessee and missouri
the visit came on the eve of caucuses in minnesota and a primary in south dakota, but bush said, ``you've got limited resources and we've allocated to super tuesday and south carolina.''
sen. jesse helms has asked the cia to investigate allegations by a panamanian dissident that the agency passed personal information to panama's strong man, gen. manuel antonio noriega, about helms and sen. edward m. kennedy, it was disclosed monday
the request was made in a letter helms sent last week to cia director william webster following congressional testimony two weeks ago by jose i. blandon, a former noriega associate who is now a leading critic of panama's defense chief
in the letter, a copy of which was made available to the associated press, the north carolina republican said it is ``improper and illegal'' for the cia to maintain files on members of congress
at the time of blandon's testimony, the cia said it ``categorically denies'' his allegations
a cia spokeswoman, sharon foster, had no comment monday on helms' letter except to say that communications from members of congress are confidential but are taken seriously and are answered
in a separate letter to fbi director william sessions, helms asked whether the agency had ever passed on information about members of congress or their staffs to the cia and whether it ever it had engaged in wiretaps or surveillance on him or members of his staff
blandon, testifying before a senate subcommittee on feb. 9, said the cia passed to noriega data about helms, kennedy, d-mass., and two of their aides. the two senators have been among noriega's strongest critics on capitol hill, citing allegations of noriega's involvement in drug trafficking
helms said blandon's credibility ``appeared to be high.'' he added that he received information from other countries indicating the cia had delivered similar information to them on other senators
he asked webster whether the cia had ever maintained information on members of congress or their staffs and whether such information was ever passed on to any official of a foreign government, specifically the panamanian defense forces
helms indicated he was skeptical about the cia's denial, contending that it made an inquiry afterward to cia field offices and to the heads of u.s. agencies involved in national security issues as to whether the denial was accurate
ms. foster of the cia said she was unable to comment on that allegation
blandon, meanwhile, met under heavy guard monday at the u.s. courthouse with prosecutors investigating the iran-contra arms and money affair. he presumably was questioned by the staff of independent counsel lawrence e. walsh about noriega's agreement to train nicaraguan rebels at the request of lt. col. oliver north, a former national security council official who is a target of walsh's investigation
blandon was a key informant for federal prosecutors in florida who earlier this month obtained indictments charging noriega with taking at least $4.6 million in bribes to protect a major colombian drug ring
a principal witness in the drug conspiracy case against panamanian gen. manuel antonio noriega faces up to 20 years in prison when sentenced this week for his part in the ring which smuggled 500,000 pounds of marijuana and 1{ tons of cocaine into the united states
but steven michael kalish, 35, expects leniency for his testimony against noriega, which included kalish's report that he made made $900,000 in payoffs to the panamanian strongman
obviously, he's hoping he won't have to spend too much time in jail,'' said dick deguerin, kalish's friend and defense attorney in houston
kalish pleaded guilty a year ago during the trial of his partner, leigh bruce ritch, and has since emerged as a principal witness against noriega in the tampa conspiracy case. noriega also faces separate racketeering and drug charges in miami
ritch, 34, is serving a sentence of 30 years in prison
in the tampa case, kalish testified he gave noriega cash and jewelry in exchange for panamanian banking services and military protection
kalish told a u.s. senate panel last month that he became attracted to panama in 1983 because of its international banking facilities. he flew there with $2.4 million in cash and met with cesar rodriguez contreras at the bank of boston building in panama city, kalish said
rodriguez, who was slain in colombia in 1986, ``offered me an entire package of corporate banking and investment services and even armored car delivery from the airport,'' kalish testified
rodriguez introduced kalish to noriega at the general's home, kalish told the committee. at their first meeting, kalish delivered a suitcase with $300,000 cash, he said, and discussed his investment plans in panama. for the next 10 months, kalish told the panel, he used panama as his base, living in a three-story spanish-style house around the corner from noriega's
in november 1983, kalish bought the panamanian defense forces a boeing 727 jet to deliver shipments of drug profits from the united states to panama. in exchange for a bell 212 helicopter kalish bought for the defense forces, according to the charges, noriega arranged for an irrevocable $2 million line of credit for kalish from a panamanian bank
noriega also provided kalish with a diplomatic passport and agreed to let ritch and kalish use panamanian banks to launder more than $100 million in anticipated profits from a million-pound marijuana smuggling venture that kalish was organizing in colombia in early 1984, according to the federal charges
kalish began his career in drug trafficking at an early age, his friends say
the son of a mid-level gulf oil corp. executive who died in 1980, kalish was born in texas and grew up in bellaire, a comfortable suburb of houston. deguerin said kalish was already selling marijuana when he dropped out of the 11th grade
i don't believe he ever had a straight job,'' said deguerin
by age 27, kalish had been indicted twice in houston for trying to import 140,000 pounds of marijuana in two loads nine days apart in december 1979. the second seizure _ 100,000 pounds _ was then the largest ever in texas. kalish eventually fled, assumed a new identity and in 1983 settled in tampa, where he worked with ritch, says assistant u.s. attorney robert kennedy in tampa
kalish and ritch set up a smuggling organization and a sophisticated nationwide distribution network that made more than $200 million in four years
the kalish-ritch organization began to fall apart when the fbi arrested kalish on july 26, 1984, as he was boarding a chartered lear jet under an assumed name at tampa international airport
lyn nofziger's defense attorneys filed motions monday to set aside the former presidential aide's illegal lobbying convictions on the grounds that prosecutors failed to prove he violated the law
the defense also filed a motion for a new trial, contending that u.s. district judge thomas a. flannery erroneously instructed jurors about determining whether the issues nofziger lobbied about were of ``direct and substantial'' interest to the white house
nofziger, 63, was convicted feb. 11 of three counts of illegally lobbying former white house colleagues on behalf of wedtech corp., a maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of the air force a-10 anti-tank plane
the former white house political director faces a potential two-year prison term and a $10,000 fine for each of the three convictions. he is scheduled to be sentenced march 25
in its motions in u.s. district court, the defense repeated contentions made throughout the four-week trial that the prosecution team headed by independent counsel james c. mckay failed to prove that the issues nofziger raised with former colleagues were ``particular matters'' of ``direct and substantial interest'' to the white house
the gross insufficiency of the evidence mandates that the guilty verdict ... against mr. nofziger b set aside and that a judgment of acquittal be entered,'' defense lawyer robert plotkin and e. lawrence barcella said in their pleadings
in asking for a new trial, the defense said the definition of ``direct and substantial interest'' that flannery gave the jury during final instructions ``clearly encompassed interest well beyond the scope of the statute.''
this instruction allowed jurors to confuse the ``personal interest of certain representatives of the white house'' with ``direct and substantial'' interest, the defense said
for instance, references in testimony to pier f. talenti, a volunteer on nofziger's white house staff who visited wedtech corp.'s plant, might be the only basis for the jury to conclude the white house had an interest in wedtech's bid for a military engine contract, the defense said
although he was not called as a witness, talenti was described by a former wedtech executive as expressing interest in the company's bid for a contract to build small engines for the army in 1981
an army procurement official also testified that talenti urged consideration of wedtech's bid that year
the defense said flannery's ``internally inconsistent and confusing'' instruction ``failed adequately to explain the comparative and relative importance of a matter to the white house, and it did not instruct the jury to place that interest in its proper context.''
nofziger, who left the white house in early 1982, was convicted, among other things, for sending an april 8, 1982, memo to then-presidential counselor edwin meese iii urging support for wedtech's efforts to persuade reluctant army officials to award the $32 million contract
the very purpose of the communication to mr. meese was to create and stimulate interest, a contact that is not prohibited'' by the law, the defense said
meese, now attorney general, testified at the trial that he couldn't recall receiving nofziger's note, which suggested he enlist the support of reagan and other top administration officials. bgng `former tv ...; inserts new 24th graf bgng ``former colorado...'' with hart figures</note>
former tv evangelist pat robertson took out $5.5 million in loans last month as the presidential contenders headed to the cash-draining super tuesday primaries, and george bush remained by far the richest candidate with more than $9 million in the bank
among democratic hopefuls, money leader michael dukakis had a $4 million bankroll, his financial statement shows
robertson reported $5.5 million in loans and contributions of $1.3 million during january, in addition to the $6.5 million he got in federal matching funds. robertson had earlier said he might not use the matching funds because he was philosophically opposed to the public financing system
he ended the month with $5.5 million in cash on hand, second only to bush's warchest, but robertson had an outstanding debt of $6 million
robertson's campaign did not immediately return calls monday evening to answer questions about where he got the loan or what it was for
in an interesting twist, bush, while raising the most money, has actually spent less against the overall primary season spending limit than any of the other republican contenders, including the struggling campaign of rep. jack kemp of new york
the bush forces have been carefully husbanding their resources to ensure they don't reach the $27 million limit too early in the nominating campaign, thereby shorting themselves for the contests that come after the super tuesday races on march 8
the latest campaign figures are contained in reports filed over the weekend with the federal election commission. the reports cover totals for the month of january
as of jan. 31, the vice president had spent $10.7 million against the $27 million cap, compared to kemp's $12.8 million. sen. bob dole, r-kan., had spent $13.5 million and ended january with $4.2 million in the bank
robertson reported spending a whopping $17.5 million against the cap, and his report showed heavy expenditures across the super tuesday states, topped by more than $1 million spent in texas. by contrast, bush spent $335,743 in texas, dole spent $81,645 there, and kemp spent $11,312
on the democratic side, none of the candidates were approaching that level, with dukakis spending the most against the ceiling, at $7.8 million
kemp continued to squeak by financially, taking out $750,000 worth of loans in january and ending the month with a debt of $1.3 million. kemp hoped to pay that off with the help of nearly $600,000 in government matching funds he expects to receive by the end of this month, said campaign political director charlie black
kemp aides are relying on a heavy mail solicitation which has brought in a steady flow of money in recent weeks, including most of the $1 million kemp raised in january, he said. kemp is netting about $400,000 a week in fund-raising, black said
black insisted the campaign is not in serious financial trouble, though he conceded, ``sure, i'd like to have another couple million to spend on super tuesday.'' he said he has budgeted about $1.5 million for the campaign through super tuesday, and is spending between $250,000 and $300,000 on television for south carolina's march 5 primary
black said that kemp's spending against the overall limit is not a problem because he will buy tv time in only seven super tuesday states
among the democrats, sen. paul simon of illinois and rep. richard gephardt of missouri both ended january in debt, and had to take out loans to keep their campaigns afloat in february's iowa caucuses and new hampshire primary
simon took out a $523,674 loan in january, and ended the month with a $691,069 debt and only $401,176 in the bank
gephardt did not report any january loans but, according to aides, did borrow money this month. he entered february with $820,260 in debts and $172,477 in cash on hand
democrats michael dukakis, the massachusetts governor, and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, on the other hand, were in good shape _ dukakis with $4 million in the bank and $511,789 in bills to pay off, and gore with $2 million on hand and $84,248 in obligations
gore ignored the iowa race to concentrate on the super tuesday states, but he raised very little money during the time the other candidates were campaigning hard in iowa and new hampshire. he collected only $180,746 in contributions during january, in addition to the $1.8 million in matching funds he got, his report showed
dukakis raised $804,839 in contributions and got $3.5 million matching funds
most candidates got very large matching fund payments in january, the first month the government funds were released, and the sums were based on the candidates' fund-raising for all preceding months. candidates can receive matching funds from the federal treasury for every contribution of $250 or less. the fund is supported by the $1 checkoff on individual tax returns
democratic contender jesse jackson reported raising $610,036 in donations, plus $598,021 in matching funds during january, ending the month with $509,978 in cash on hand and $354,881 in obligations
former colorado sen. gary hart ended the month with $615,547 in cash on hand after collecting $70,303 in contributions and $937,325 in matching funds
simon's finance director, bob edgar, announced that the senator has raised more than $1 million in donations so far this year, and in the two weeks following the feb. 8 iowa contest set a record for his campaign
his report shows that in january he raised $534,259 in contributions, $1.9 million in matching funds, and $523,674 in loans
gephardt collected $212,702 in contributions and $1.9 million in matching funds. gephardt's campaign manager, bill carrick, has said that the congressman will not buy tv advertising in all 20 super tuesday states, but will concentrate on texas, arkansas, louisiana, oklahoma and florida
as of the jan. 31 report, however, gephardt had spent very little in those states _ for example, a total of $69,809 in texas, compared to dukakis' $301,829, and $23,454 in florida, compared to dukakis' $206,861 there
in arkansas, louisiana and oklahoma, gephardt had spent less than $5,000 each as of the beginning of this month
dukakis has also far outspent gore in the south, a region in which the tennessee senator has pinned his presidential hopes
all firefighters scheduled to work monday night's shift joined scores of other colleagues in calling in sick, leaving providence's fire protection to 87 firefighters who have been on duty around the clock since friday
meanwhile, a superior court judge delayed ruling on the city's request for contempt citations against 110 firefighters who called in sick over the weekend in defiance of a back-to-work order
judge americo campanella gave union president leo j. miller until 10 a.m. tuesday to inform all 450 members of the union that they must to return to work under the temporary restraining order issued saturday by another judge
miller was also ordered to furnish a list of all firefighters who had called in sick over the weekend and outline the nature of their illness or the illness of family members they said they were staying home to care for
city officials went from home to home monday leaving notices for firefighters of the contempt hearing. campanella indicated his decision to put off ruling on the matter hinged on the relatively low number of firefighters contacted either by the city or miller
the union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of 479. campanella indicated his decision to put off ruling on the matter hinged on the relatively low number of firefighters contacted either by the city or miller
miller, a fire captain, denies the union orchestrated any sickout
if found to be a job action as moise and city officials assert, the sickout would be illegal under rhode island law
the dispute apparently concerns language in a contract ratified by firefighters in december that the city has yet to sign
miller said the city is trying to renege on a provision that calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit. union members also complain that promises to replacement worn-out or damaged equipment like boots, helmets and firecoats have not been fulfilled
all but one of the 51 firefighters scheduled to report for work at 8 a.m. saturday called in sick friday, said fire chief michael f. moise
an additional 60 called in sick for the shift that was supposed to begin at 6 a.m. sunday, moise said
assistant fire chief gilbert h. mclaughlin jr. told campanella that all of the firefighters scheduled to report at 6 p.m. monday had called in sick
i have nobody coming in,'' mclaughlin testified
the union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of 479. the firefighters, divided into four platoons, work two 10-hour days and two 12-hour days, then are off four days
moise said the 87 firefighters in the platoon that has been kept on duty since friday evening will stay on the job until the issue is resolved
the chief testified the average absentee level is seven to eight firefighters for any particular shift
miller agreed the number of sick firefighters was ``unusually high.''
most of the people he contacted after the restraining order was issued said either they or someone in their family had a 24-hour virus, miller said
miller said he called in sick because his mother, who has heart trouble, also had the flu
ragosta tried to show the sickout presented a danger to the public health and safety. moise said he was becoming concerned that fatigue among firefighters on the job since friday might affect their ability to operate sophisticated equipment and their response time in a crisis
he said the sickout was costing $20,000 a day in overtime and related expenses
high winds blew across much of the nation monday, felling trees and power lines and prompting weather forecasters to post gale warnings in coastal and lake areas
an intense low pressure system over ontario produced the gusty south to southwesterly wind from the southern plains across the tennessee and ohio valleys and into the lower great lakes region and vermont
blasts of up to 120 mph were recorded at mines peak, colo., in the early-morning hours. power outages due to wind knocking down utility poles were reported at fort smith, ark., where several carport awnings were blown loose in gusts up to 52 mph
a gust of 61 mph whipped erie, pa., shortly after noon, while wind of 50 mph and up was clocked at burlington, vt.; buffalo, n.y.; cleveland; st. louis; indianapolis; cheyenne, wyo.; and rapid city, s.d
high-wind warnings and wind advisories were posted for parts of western minnesota, western texas, lakes erie and huron and the northern new england coast
meanwhile, strong northerly winds of 25-40 mph brought colder weather to the northern and central plains
temperatures dropped from the mid-40s to the mid-20s in one hour at nunn and briggsdale, colo., early monday morning as a cold front plowed through the area
arctic air accompanied the strong winds across minnesota and north dakota. the temperature at warroad, minn., dropped from 30 degrees to 8 degrees in two hours as the cold air pushed through
snow was scattered across parts of montana, wyoming, northeastern colorado and northern maine. two to 5 inches of snow was reported in the casper, wyo., area
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 11 at international falls, minn., to 81 at mcallen, texas. the early-morning low for the nation was 14 below zero at gunnison, colo
for tuesday, snow was forecast from northern new england across parts of new york state; scattered snow showers or flurries in northern sections of the ohio valley and the upper great lakes; widely scattered snow showers in the mountains of montana and colorado; rain from central and southern new england across the middle atlantic coast states into the tennessee valley; and rain showers from the central gulf coast through northern florida, georgia and the western carolinas
temperatures will remain below freezing across the northern half of the plains, the upper half of the mississippi valley and the great lakes region, with readings only in the single digits over portions of north dakota and northern minnesota. temperatures will reach the 60s and 70s from california across the desert southwest, and from southern and central new mexico across much of texas, the central gulf coast states and the southern atlantic coast states, with readings in the low 80s in parts of the desert southwest, extreme southern texas and southern florida. elsewhere, temperatures will range from the upper 30s to the 50s
ron sexton's reward for winning a school contest was nothing to snort at. then again, it probably didn't make him squeal with delight
sexton, a history teacher and wrestling coach at wilmington high school, came in first in a school project to raise money for children's hospital in columbus. his payoff _ he had to kiss a pig
he put his mouth where the smart money was, planting a kiss on the snout of a pig during a pep rally friday while the students and faculty watched
sexton won a contest in which students and teachers put money in gallon milk jugs as their way of choosing a sow smoocher. there were 45 teachers up for votes, which cost 25 cents to cast, said home economics teacher bonnie hansen
the contest, dubbed ``squeal of fortune,'' raised nearly $250
auburn residents better not plan to serve pie this weekend _ not with a horde of curly, larry and moe fans headed their way
three stooges aficionados from throughout the nation are expected to converge on this central maine city to share recollections of the zany antics that entertained generations of moviegoers and television viewers
the two-day convention, which begins saturday, will feature about 30 dealers in stooges memorabilia, imitators of the threesome and, of course, a pie fight
they kind of created the pie fight,'' said ron eugley, the convention organizer. ``in about a quarter of their shorts, there's somebody getting a pie in the face.''
eugley, a 36-year-old salesman from auburn, said the convention has been promoted in the national magazine published by the three stooges fan club and is expected to draw more than 700 fans
the convention will be addressed by telephone by emil sitka, a supporting actor for the stooges who is writing a book about the late comics
stooges movies will be shown throughout the convention, eugley said, including some never seen by the general public
curly was married four times _ he had quite the thing for women _ and we'll have some films of his weddings,'' eugley said. he said convention-goers will also see films of moe howard entertaining at a backyard barbecue
proceeds from the convention will go to the american cancer society, in part because howard died of the disease. two weeks</head>
an oil rig helicopter and a phantom jet fighter came within a half-mile of colliding over the north sea on monday, according to the helicopter firm. it was the third reported near-miss in two weeks in britain's crowded skies
the earlier incidents involved jetliners carrying hundreds of passengers and prompted calls for an inquiry into growing air congestion before the summer travel season begins. the government on monday accused air traffic controllers of fomenting ``public hysteria'' and said there was no cause for alarm
bristow helicopters said its puma craft carrying 11 passengers and two crew members from an oil rig 165 miles northeast of aberdeen climbed sharply as it neared the scottish city after air traffic controllers warned that it was on a collision course with a royal air force jet
bristow said its helicopter moved up from an altitude of 2,000 feet and the phantom passed below. both aircraft landed safely and no one was reported injured
a bristow spokesman said the helicopter pilot filed an ``air miss'' report with the civil aviation authority, or caa
earlier monday, transport secretary paul channon promised an investigation into an incident sunday involving a british caledonian ba 1-11 and a pan american boeing 727
channon told the house of commons the jetliners came within 2,000 yards while flying over southern england but he said they were not in danger of colliding
he said the number of near-misses had declined sharply in the last 10 years. ``we musn't be complacent, neither must we overreact,'' he said
in the previous incident this month, a british airways lockheed l1011 and a balkan bulgarian tu 54 with a total of 543 people aboard narrowly avoided colliding. the caa called that an ``exceptionally serious'' case and channon said the authority took the unusual step of asking the department of transport to make an independent investigation
according to the caa, the number of near-misses per 100,000 flying hours in british air space decreased from 6.2 in 1980 to 2.8 in 1986
it said there were 12 incidents involving serious risk last year, unchanged from 1986
chris stock, president of britain's largest air traffic controllers' union, said the control system is nearly overloaded
the system is working at full blast,'' said stock, head of the 1,500-member guild of air traffic controllers. ``if a mistake is made then there is very little room to maneuver.''
he said safety should improve when a new computer system is inaugurated in 1990 and a new control center in 1995. the guild has demanded increased manpower in the meantime, saying five job vacancies at the main control center in west drayton have not been filled since september
the caa on monday claimed the controllers were promoting public alarm to gain leverage in negotiations over working conditions, including the number of controllers on duty at peak times
the controllers are putting pressure on the caa by harping on the subject of safety,'' said the authority spokesman who was not identified in line with government policy. ``anonymous controllers are constantly feeding information engendering alarm and concern.'' in washington, with 3 grafs to update with robertson figures; picks up 19th graf pvs, on the democratic; new 4th-to-last graf, at lander, with robertson calling for school prayer</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis said monday he might authorize military operations against terrorist base camps if he wins the white house. gop hopeful bob dole taunted vice president bush for ceasing efforts in south dakota and minnesota, battlegrounds for this week's campaign contests
i don't know where george bush is,'' dole said in duluth. ``later today we're going to send him a map of minnesota so at least he gets a little idea where it is.''
bush was in south carolina and tennessee, virtually conceding the south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses to his gop rivals. but he predicted he wouldn't be hurt by that
i think i'm going to be the next president of the united states,'' the vice president said in myrtle beach, s.c
dole is heavily favored to win the south dakota contest. but he sounded less confident of his chances for victory in minnesota, where former television evangelist pat robertson and rep. jack kemp have waged energetic campaigns
on the democratic side, dukakis has invested heavily in minnesota in hopes of bagging a win outside his new england backyard. he, rep. richard gephardt, sen. paul simon, sen. albert gore jr. and jesse jackson have campaigned heavily in south dakota as well
gephardt campaigned in south dakota and wyoming, while his spokesman accused gore of hypocrisy and released a list of what he said were switches in position the tennessee senator has made on issues ranging from abortion to farm policy to spending for the mx missiles
that was an attempt to turn the tables on gore, who has vigorously attacked gephardt for switching his position on key issues
dukakis made a brief visit to washington, where he took part in a national governors' association meeting with president reagan
he emerged from the session to blast the president's anti-terrorism policy and say the united states would be living with the consequences of secret arms sales to iran for a long time
you never, ever make concessions to terrorism,'' dukakis said. ``if you ever do it, then your policy is worthless.''
he added: ``this is international crime, pure and simple and you fight it the way you fight crime _ with tough police work, with effective undercover operations, with military operations against terrorist base camps if necessary.''
dukakis did not elaborate on what conditions might prompt him to authorize military operations
but white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said such talk could conceivably make life more difficult for a hostage. ``i would simply urge caution on everyone's part, including political candidates,'' he said
simon was in minnesota during the day, invoking the name of the state's late sen. hubert h. humphrey as he bid to score well in the caucuses
the illinois senator was cheered enthusiastically by a crowd at gustavus adolphus college in st. peter, minn., where he said he would propose a mutual nuclear test ban treaty with the soviet union if elected
simon once said he needed to win in either minnesota or south dakota this week to keep his campaign alive, but has since pulled back from that standard. ``i am going to do respectably,'' he said, adding he believes the democratic race will stay muddled beyond the march 8 round of contests _ mostly in southern and border states _ known as super tuesday
in washington, financial reports filed with the federal election commission showed bush's campaign with the biggest bankroll _ $9 million _ going into the super tuesday primaries. among democratic hopefuls, dukakis led with $4 million on hand
robertson reported $5.5 million in loans and contributions of $1.3 million during january, in addition to the $6.5 million he got in federal matching funds. robertson had earlier said he might not use the matching funds because he was philosophically opposed to the public financing system
he ended the month with $5.5 million in cash on hand, second only to bush's warchest, but robertson had an outstanding debt of $6 million. robertson's campaign did not immediately return calls monday evening to answer questions about where he got the loan or what it was for
with most of the campaign still to go, bush had spent $10.7 million against the $27 million campaign limit, compared with kemp's $12.8 million and dole's $13.5 million. robertson reported spending a whopping $17.5 million against the cap, and his report showed heavy expenditures across the super tuesday states
on the democratic side, dukakis had spent the most against the ceiling, at $7.8 million
also on monday, democrat gore won the endorsement of alabama sen. howell heflin as he continued lining up support of as many southern politicians as possible in advance of super tuesday
but in an unusual news conference, heflin said he wanted to ``educate'' gore on some of the issues. ``he's not too far to the left, but i've got to try to bring him to the middle a little bit,'' heflin said. ``i'm going to work on him.''
in the republican race, kemp appeared before an economics class at the university of minnesota and called bush's advocacy of a four-year budget freeze ``embarrassing.''
said kemp, ``can you think of anything more yawning in a peresidential campaign that having the republican candidate running for president say, `if i become president i'm going to freeze the budget for four years?'''
robertson was in south carolina, where he has declared he needs a win in the march 5 primary. he announced his support for legislation to limit textile imports and challenged bush to do the same
at lander college in greenwood, robertson won applause when he called for school prayer. it used to be, he said, that ``little children could pray in the public schools of america and we've got to see that once again.''
dole won the endorsement of south carolina sen. strom thurmond
the kansas senator's campaign manager, former sen. bill brock, took several sharp jabs at bush and his campaign. he accused the vice president's campaign of taking two ``cheap shots'' before the iowa caucuses and the new hampshire primary
he said the first attempt failed. the second one ``worked short term. we'll see whether they worked in the long term,'' he said. with ball's likely nomination and webb's resignation to be accepted at white house tuesday.</note>
navy secretary james h. webb abruptly resigned monday, accusing defense secretary frank c. carlucci of abandoning the reagan administration's goal of a 600-ship navy and of demonstrating a lack of leadership and vision
this building needs to be led,'' webb said in telling reporters of his decision. ``it needs leadership. it needs some vision. i'm saying that if i had a piece of advice to give to secretary carlucci, it would be to spend a lot more time with the top leaders in this building
he's been spending a lot of time with the state department and a lot of time on the hill. i think they (pentagon leaders) need to feel his vision and to understand what he believes in.''
webb, 42, a highly decorated marine veteran of vietnam combat and the author of the best-selling vietnam war novel, ``fields of fire,'' left after only 10 months in his pentagon position
he told president reagan in his resignation letter that the president could have realized his cherished goal of building a 600-ship fleet, were it not for carlucci
an administration official who asked not to be identified said carlucci wants to recommend that william l. ball iii, assistant to the president for legislative affairs, be nominated to replace webb. the source said the white house probably would announce ball's nomination on tuesday, at the same time it announces formal acceptance of webb's resignation
talking to reporters, webb accused carlucci of ordering him to keep quiet about internal budget fighting, saying the defense chief had written him a note saying he should deny news stories reporting it was the defense department _ and not the navy _ proposing to mothball ships
now, i'm not going to deny the truth,'' webb said
carlucci declined to respond to the criticism, issuing a written statement saying only that he had learned of webb's resignation decision ``with regret.''
the pentagon added in a separate statement, however, that if webb had decided he could not ``defend the department's decisions'' on the budget, then ``under the circumstances, he has done the honorable thing.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said: ``secretary carlucci is having to make some very difficult adjustments in the pentagon to accommodate budgetary reductions. secretary webb indicates he is unable to operate under these constraints, but i know the president feels he has given very valuable service to the country ...''
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the senate armed services subcommittee that oversees the navy budget, said in a statement: ``i'm sorry to see jim webb go. in his brief stint, he impressed the armed services committee as an able secretary.''
although i am not endorsing his views, his resignation has obviously launched an important new stage of the debate about pentagon priorities and the size and type of navy we need.''
three times, webb said, the navy developed a plan for cutting its fiscal 1989 budget in such a way that the goal of expanding the fleet to 600 ships could still be reached. and each time, he said, the navy's advice was ``ignored'' by carlucci
i can only conclude that the decision to reduce the level of our fleet to a point that it may never reach the 600-ship goal was motivated by other than military and strategic reasoning,'' webb wrote reagan
webb and others have argued that 600 ships were the minimum needed for the navy to meet its worldwide commitments
since his recommendations ``were rejected by your secretary of defense, i am unable to support him personally or to defend this amended budget during budget deliberations (in congress),'' webb said
consequently, i find it necessary to resign from my position as ecretary of the navy.''
webb's decision to step down surprised navy and pentagon officials alike
he assumed the post only last april, seven months before carlucci succeeded caspar w. weinberger
the navy, like all the services, was ordered in early december to slash its fiscal 1989 budget proposal to comply with a new deficit-reduction plan. ultimately, webb said, the navy ended up being told to cut $12.3 billion from its original spending plan
as finally approved by carlucci, the navy has told congress it wants $96.4 billion in budget authority and intends to mothball 16 navy frigates, webb said
the pentagon said the mothballing would leave the navy with 580 ships by the end of fiscal 1989 and that it can still build to 600 by fiscal 1992
webb asserted, however, the mothballing is unnecessary and the navy would never reach 600 ships
one of the sad things about this is that this is one of the few goals of the reagan administration that was really obtainable, at pretty low cost,'' webb said
the navy could have transferred those 16 frigates to the naval reserve ``for well under $100 million'' rather than place them in mothballs, preserving them as ``deployable'' warships ready for an emergency, he declared
webb declined to speculate on why carlucci might have rejected such options
but in another broadside at the new defense secretary, webb complained that once carlucci arrived, ``the number of people who are participating in the decisions (became) smaller.''
webb, one of the youngest men to ever become navy secretary, is a naval academy graduate
he came to the pentagon in 1984 under weinberger, assuming the post of assistant defense secretary for reserve affairs. he had resigned and was preparing to leave government service in early 1987 when the president asked him to replace john f. lehman, the first navy secretary of the reagan administration
webb said monday he intended to return to his work as a novelist and possibly, journalism as well. bgng: australian foreign... adds 4 grafs on criticism</note>
angry, defiant palestinians marked ``martyrs' day'' in the occupied territories monday with graveside speeches and stone-throwing demonstrations as they remembered the 61 arabs killed in clashes since december
attorney general yosef harish meanwhile released a letter to defense minister yitzhak rabin, criticizing rabin's policy of allowing soldiers to beat protesters
you cannot use force as a means of punishment, abuse or humiliation,'' harish said
one palestinian was shot and wounded monday in this west bank town 10 miles north of jerusalem and another was shot during a demonstration at jabaliya refugee camp in the gaza strip, according to hospital sources. the army said it was checking the reports
australian foreign minister bill hayden, attending a dinner in jerusalem with foreign minister shimon peres, criticized israel's ``sometimes arbitrary and violent way'' of dealing with the disturbances
the jersualem post reported the international committee of the red cross in geneva has strongly protested the israeli actions
about 1,500 additional police officers, brought in from throughout israel, flooded jerusalem in advance of the visit of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, set to begin thursday. the reinforcements will back up the holy city's normal contingent of 1,000 officers
authorities fear shultz's presence will lead to an upsurge in violence by arabs pressing their case for an end to 20 years of israeli occupation of the west bank and gaza, seized during the 1967 middle east war
the latest spate of unrest started dec. 8 and has resulted in scores of deaths, hundreds of injuries and arrests
in kfar naami, a village of 2,000 inhabitants six miles west of here, about 1,500 arabs marched through the streets chanting anti-israeli and anti-american slogans
in a fiery speech at the graveside of one of the two village residents who have died from army bullets, a speaker rejected the shultz trip
from this grave we condemn the shultz visit and the united states. these masses,'' he said gesturing to the crowd, ``are led by the plo. we will continue to achieve our goals and not satisfy american policy in the region.''
grafitti in kfar naami read: ``no for the visit of shultz; yes, to the palestinian government. yes to the plo.''
despite the rhetoric, palestinian moderates are trying to persuade plo leader yasser arafat to lift his ban against local palestinians talking to shultz. if washington's peace plan is to succeed, shultz needs to bring palestinians into the talks
in an interview monday in tunisia, arafat said the palestine liberation organization was ready to meet with the united states
we have declared that we are ready to meet with all of the permanent members of the security council, including the american administration,'' arafat said, speaking on cbs-tv's ``this morning.''
without a meeting with palestinians, the shultz initiative is bound to fail,'' said sari nusseibeh, a university professor and one of six arabs originally slated to meet shultz
conservative prime minister yitzhak shamir has expressed strong reservations about the american initiative. while saying he is willing to listen and consider any ideas from washington, he clearly does not like the american initiative which revolves around swapping land for peace. he also is worried about moving too quickly
in a speech to european jewish leaders sunday night, shamir said a long period of practical experience and coexistence is needed before the question of sovereignty can be broached
any attempt to force the pace and to shorten the period would be a detriment to the very essence of the (camp david) agreement,'' he said
army radio said shamir told the parliament's foreign affairs and security committee israel will not withdraw from the territories, even under pressure
shamir's labor party rival, foreign minister peres, has largely accepted the american initiative
in the upcoming days we will have a political discussion in the cabinet,'' shamir told the radio monday. ``then we shall see whether we (he and peres) can talk to mr. shultz as partners or not.''
the radio quoted the prime minister as saying he and peres could be forced to call early elections because of their disagreements
justice ministry spokeswoman etty eshed said the attorney general's letter was prompted by the many complaints received from palestinians in the territories
i checked them and found the number of the complaints ... raised suspicion that defining these cases as `aberrations' does not reflect reality,'' harish wrote
hayden, nearing the end of a middle east tour, told peres, ``australians are deeply concerned by what's happening today in the unrest in the occupied territories ... the sometimes arbitrary and violent way in which it has been met.''
in his response, peres said israel ``did not want to dominate'' the palestinians and added: ``i know my country has been painfully criticized by countries of the world. we take it seriously, with chagrin.''
the jerusalem post quoted maurice aubert, vice chairman of the international committee of the red cross, as saying a letter recently was delivered to israel's icrc representative in geneva calling on shamir ``to bring to an immediate end these serious acts perpetrated against civilians.''
it said the letter declared that ``thousands of people have been the victims of brutality and grave ill-treatment at the hands of israeli soldiers.'' graf. pick up 2d graf pvs bgng: lt. col. eduardo...</note>
