police increased patrols monday at a fundamentalist christian television station that has been hit by sporadic sniper fire twice in a week
no one was injured in the latest incident, on sunday morning, said wmpv-tv owner ed bowlds
we just think it's some kind of weirdo,'' bowlds said. ``he's not trying to hit anybody. that's obvious. it may be somebody wanting publicity.''
glenda mcleod, a producer at the station, said one employee was inside the building sunday, but the shots were fired into the eaves. she also said glass was broken in the front door, but not by gunfire. she said she thought someone had attempted to break into the building
police placed the building under surveillance after bullets hit it wednesday. there have been no arrests in either incident
police capt. tommy hart said two additional patrol cars were assigned to the area. he said the sniper could have been encouraged by the station's on-the-air comment that officers seemed to take a long time to arrive after the first shooting incident
