in 1925, president calvin coolidge's inauguration was broadcast live on 21 radio stations coast-to-coast
in 1933, in his inaugural address, president franklin d. roosevelt pledged effective leadership to pull the country out of the great depression, saying, ``the only thing we have to fear is fear itself.''
in 1933, the start of the roosevelt administration brought with it the first woman to serve on a president's cabinet: labor secretary frances perkins
in 1952, actor ronald reagan and actress nancy davis were married in san fernando valley, calif
in 1971, canadian prime minister pierre elliott trudeau married margaret sinclair in north vancouver, british columbia. they later divorced
in 1977, more than 1,500 people were killed when an earthquake registering 7.5 on the richter scale shook southern and eastern europe
ten years ago: the chicago daily news, founded in 1875, published its last issue with a huge headline reading, ``so long, chicago.''
five years ago: during his central american tour, pope john paul ii visited nicaragua, where he celebrated a mass that was interrupted by shouted revolutionary slogans from militiamen
one year ago: president reagan addressed the nation on the iran-contra affair, acknowledging that his once-secret overtures to iran had ``deteriorated'' into an arms-for-hostages deal
today's birthdays: actress paula prentiss is 49. rock musician chris squire is 40. actress kay lenz is 35
thought for today: ``history is not life. but since only life makes history, the union of the two is obvious.'' _ louis d. brandeis, u.s. supreme court justice (1856-1941)
today is saturday, march 5, the 65th day of 1988. there are 301 days left in the year
today's highlight in history:
on march 5, 1770, the ``boston massacre'' took place as british soldiers who had been taunted by a crowd of colonists opened fire, killing several people
on this date:
in 1766, a spanish official, don antonio de ulloa, arrived in new orleans to take possession of the louisiana territory from the french
in 1867, an abortive fenian uprising against english rule took place in ireland
in 1868, the senate was organized into a court of impeachment to decide charges against president andrew johnson
in 1933, in germany, the nazi party won a majority of seats in parliamentary elections
in 1946, former british prime minister winston churchill, during an address at westminster college in fulton, mo., spoke of an ``iron curtain'' stretching from the baltic to the adriatic
in 1953, soviet dictator josef stalin died at the age of 73 after 29 years in power
in 1970, a nuclear non-proliferation treaty went into effect after 43 nations ratified it
in 1976, the british pound fell below $2 for the first time
in 1977, president jimmy carter took questions from 42 callers in 26 states on a network radio call-in program moderated by cbs-tv newsman walter cronkite
in 1982, comedian john belushi was found dead of a drug overdose in a rented bungalow in hollywood. he was 33
in 1984, the u.s. supreme court ruled, 5-4, that a city could use public money to set up a nativity scene without violating the constitutional separation of church and state
ten years ago: striking miners voted overwhelmingly against a proposed contract that would have ended a 90-day walkout. president jimmy carter began considering measures to try to force the miners back to work
five years ago: bob hawke and his opposition labor party defeated australian prime minister malcolm fraser's conservative coalition
one year ago: president reagan called on congress to approve the final installment of a $100 million aid package for nicaraguan contra rebels, one day after a speech in which he'd called his iran initiative a mistake
today's birthdays: actor rex harrison is 80. actor dean stockwell is 52. football player-turned-actor fred williamson is 50. violinist eugene fodor is 38. singer andy gibb is 30
thought for today: ``having only friends would be dull anyway _ like eating eggs without salt.'' _ hedda hopper, american gossip columnist (1890-1966)
you can't look at david j. colmans' book, but you can read it
the book _ on using computers in public relations and related fields _ was written on computer by people contacted via computer, edited on computer and published on computer
and since it exists only in the memory of a computer in columbus, ohio, the book can only be read by using a computer
the essence of the book is to share information on the `this is how i do it' use of technology in the communications arts,'' said colmans, vice president of an atlanta public relations firm
colmans is one of about six ``system operators'' of a computer network called the public relations special interest group. along with co-editor ron solberg of chicago, he has compiled the book over about four years
in it are chapters written by the public information officer for kansas city, mo., who tells how he has set up a computer network to tell citizens what is happening in the city; discussions of ``voice mail,'' a sophisticated, computer-operated telephone answering and message system; and numerous other aspects of how to use technology in the field
the computer book, which would be about an inch thick if printed, is better than one on paper, colmans said, because ``once you buy a hardcopy book and put it on the shelf, that's it for eternity _ whatever's in the book is the information.''
with an on-line book, not only are you not stuck with having to have all the information sitting on your shelf, ... but the minute something becomes obsolete, bang, it's gone. and the minute something comes in that's interesting and new, in a matter of a couple minutes it's on line and available for everybody to see,'' he said
the book _ with the official title of ``the functional use of computers in public relations, marketing and advertising'' _ is a true creature of electronics
virtually the entire book was brought together through electronic mail messages and sharing of text as opposed to voice communication,'' colmans said
there were very few phone calls. ... the book itself was created in an electronic communications environment. i have met, face to face, about six of the 40 to 50 people that i communicate with electronically. most of them are just type on a screen to me,'' he said
colmans is not your average computer hacker, sitting in front of a terminal, wrapped up in the nuts and bolts, or bits and bytes, of technology
about five years ago, i started getting interested in computers to help me do my work, not just to play with, because i'm one of those people that can't write a program,'' he said
i don't know how a computer works any more than i know how a television set works. but i do know how to turn on a tv and i do know how to turn on a computer.''
in compiling the book, colmans said, ``the big issue that we discovered was, and still is today, that there are so many kinds of computers out on the market and there's a real lack of understanding among computer users that ... you can actually get those computers to talk to each other.''
because the book has not been published in the traditional sense, colmans earns nothing from the people who use it
we have not done this project to make money; we've done this project to share information,'' he said, although there has been some discussion about publishing a ``hardcopy of the book'' in the future
allan hendrickse, a mixed-race politician and member of president p. w. botha's cabinet, defied apartheid laws more than a year ago and went swimming at a whites-only beach. then at botha's demand, he apologized
doubts immediately arose that the highly regarded hendrickse would ever regain credibility among his non-white constituents
but he has made a remarkable comeback
hendrickse now is recognized as perhaps the only elected official in south africa with both the will and the power to defy the president
as leader of parliament's mixed-race chamber, he is in a position to force botha's national party to the polls next year, three years earlier than it would like
botha he needs consent from all three chambers of parliament to delay the election from 1989 to 1992. hendrickse, whose labor party holds 76 of 85 seats in the house of representatives, says he won't acquiesce unless botha abandons the government's policy of segregated neighborhoods
this demand is unlikely to be met and has resulted in hendrickse's forced resignation from the cabinet. but the confrontation appears to have boosted his popularity among the country's 3 million ``coloreds,'' as mixed-race south africans are called
suddenly a lot of people who were disinterested or antagonistic are now realizing that you can find yourself in a position of altering the course of history in this country,'' hendrickse, 60, said at a recent news briefing. ``it does give you and the people you represent a feeling of importance.''
hendrickse's political fortunes have seesawed since he helped found the labor party in 1969
he was detained for two months in 1976 for his anti-apartheid stance, but came under fire from activists in 1984 when the labor party agreed to participate in a new tricameral parliament setup. chambers for asians and coloreds were created to join the dominant white chamber, although the nation's black majority remained excluded
the asian and mixed-race chambers are allowed to handle their ``own affairs'' _ deciding to how to allocate public funding for their own communities, for example. but the 1984 constitution gives the majority party in the white chamber almost total power to set national policy and to override even combined opposition from the other chambers
hendrickse said he would cooperate with the new system for five years in an effort to dismantle apartheid from within. activists nonetheless denounced him as a sellout for joining botha's cabinet as minister without portfolio
our participation within the system must not be construed as an acceptance of the system,'' said hendrickse. ``we walk the difficult road of being in and yet being out.''
in january 1987, the portly politician made a seemingly bold challenge of the government by wading into the surf at a whites-only beach in port elizabeth
botha, in a televised speech, furiously ordered hendrickse to apologize or quit the cabinet. hendrickse apologized
it was a demolition job with such humiliation for rev. hendrickse that he is unlikely to recover from it,'' peter gastrow, chairman of the white opposition progressive federal party, said at the time
now, white liberals applaud hendrickse's tougher tactics and are considering possible alliances with his labor party
hendrickse still has many detractors, including activists who totally reject the tricameral parliament. at the university of the western cape, a leftist, predominantly mixed-race school, rector jakes gerwel said hendrickse's resurgence had been ``a non-event.''
the pro-government media also has been critical, for different reasons. the citizen, a johannesburg newspaper, maintained that the labor party had become ``fractious and militant'' after being set on a ``dangerous collision course'' by hendricske
hendrickse says he holds no personal animosity toward botha but is clearly pleased at having found an effective means of challenging him
it's not a question of personal power or strength, but rather a recognition of the correctness of the decision to participate (in parliament),'' he said. ``in spite of the constitutional inadequacies, we were able to find a gap, a weakness, and thus find ourselves in a powerful position.''
in addition to his leverage over the election schedule, hendrickse has blocked a government proposal to begin joint debates among the three parliamentary chambers. without joint voting and other reforms, the change is meaningless, hendrickse maintains
regardless of whether the white election is delayed, hendrickse wants mixed-race elections to proceed as scheduled next year. only 30 percent of colored voters went to the polls in 1984, when activists urged a boycott, and hendrickse says the turnout next year could rise to 50 percent
he said pro-government forces are seeking to weaken him by dividing his party. allegations have surfaced that national party officials tried to bribe labor party members into deserting him
there is speculation that botha may retire soon, and hendrickse has raised an intriguing scenario regarding the choice of a successor by the electoral college
the college consists of 50 national party members, 25 labor party members, and 13 members from the asian chamber's majority party. hendrickse says the asian and mixed-race electors could thwart the selection of a hardliner if they could persuade seven or more relatively liberal nationalists to join them in electing a moderate, such as foreign minister roelof ``pik'' botha, no relation to the president
hendrickse was raised in uitenhage, near port elizabeth, the fifth child of a congregational minister. he grew up in an integrated neighborhood and became a minister himself
in 1971, the mixed-race community was forced to move to a colored township under terms of the group areas act, which mandates segregated neighborhoods. hendrickse has described his father's anguish as he watched their home and church being destroyed
now, he wants the national party to abolish the group areas act and says he has done enough compromising
fourteen candidates of various political hues are in the race for venezuela's presidency, but polls give two centrists the leading edge so far in the campaign for december's balloting
a former anti-government guerrilla hopes to become a serious third option, but the other 11 candidates are given little chance
one of the centrists is eduardo fernandez, who is known as ``the tiger.'' the other is carlos andres perez, a former president who has been matching practically every every campaign promise fernandez has made
the former guerrilla is teodoro petkoff, a socialist
fernandez and perez represent the two political parties that have dominated venezuelan politics since dictator marcos perez jimenez was overthrown in 1958 after six years in power
accion democratica (ad), the social democratic party now in power, is fielding perez, a 69-year-old charismatic leader with considerable political experience
perez's government in 1973-77 is popularly associated with the oil-prices boom in 1974
he is considered to have a slight edge now for the dec. 4 election, although the 47-year-old fernandez, the copei or christian democratic party candidate, has made inroads by raising the issue of electoral reform
after a shaky start, fernandez took the initiative with calls for direct elections of state governors, rather than by presidential appointment, and voting for individual congressional candidates, rather than by party lists
i don't think there is an electoral system in the entire world as primitive as ours,'' fernandez told reporters recently
according to a recent gaither poll done for perez's ad, the promise of reform enabled fernandez to narrow the distance between him and perez to 11 percent by late january, from around 30 percent in november
following fernandez's electoral-reforms proposal, perez came up with one of his own
i propose to the nation a pact for reform, to deepen and open our democratic system,'' perez announced at a public celebration jan. 23 marking the 30th anniversary of the perez jimenez's overthrow
the 10-point pact for reform contains proposals almost identical to the fernandez's
the only thing (perez) has to do now is support my candidacy,'' fernandez complained at a recent rally
the two major parties have staked out electoral bases so broad that voters are sometimes hard pressed to see a difference
fernandez and perez preach political reforms of the democratic system, but they agree it should stay democratic
they argue about the degree of state intervention in the economy, but they agree the state should intervene
copei, a member of the christian democratic organization of america, is considered somewhat more conservative, while ad, which belongs to the socialist international, is more labor-oriented
but they are both centrist. their members run from conservative to liberal, but most are somewhere in between
venezuela's presidency has flipped back and forth between the ad and copei five times in the six elections from 1958 to 1983. an ad candidate succeeded an ad president only once
their success in dominating venezuelan politics has relegated all the other parties to marginal political roles
the ex-guerrilla petkoff is carrying the banner of the movimiento al socialismo
in the 1960s, when an indigenous guerrilla movement was active, petkoff preached a socialism bordering on communism
but he gave up his fight, accepting amnesty offered by the government. he moderated his views and is now a member of congress. his party dropped its affiliation with moscow following the soviet-led invasion of czechoslavakia in 1968
but even though petkoff started his campaign by trimming his bushy moustache and longish hair in an effort to dispel any conceptions of radicalism, he isn't expected to win much more than 5 percent of the vote
that was as much as his party got into 1978, its best year
the remaining candidates are even worse off. they are formally in the race but are not making much of a difference
venezuela's first woman presidential candidate, ismenia villalba, is running on the slogan, ``ismenia, take her into your heart.''
this is one of a series of periodic reports by associated press correspondents on the way of life in other countries
india is taking the bullock-cart into the 21st century
at least 500 researchers in about a dozen government-aided institutes are at work modernizing the ancient, creaking, plodding carts, and even the world bank has donated funds. carts of various shapes and designs, made of plastic and aluminum, are being tested or have been developed
there is nothing funny about our project,'' said mittar pal dhir, director of the road research institute in new delhi. ``for us, animal-drawn carts are of great importance.''
india has an estimated 13 million bullock carts drawn by about 26 million of the neutered bulls, along with 2 million carts pulled by water buffaloes, camels, horses, mules and donkeys
the carts are seen most often in villages, where about 640 million of the india's 800 million people live
but they also are seen on major highways and an estimated 3 million plod along city streets, often slowing engine-powered traffic and infuriating motorists
bullock carts have even been used to pull mig fighter jets to parades and earth satellites to launching pads
dhir said it would be 50 years before india could eliminate animal-drawn carts, given their crucial role in indian life
capital investment in animal-drawn carts is put at $7.6 billion
more than 20 million indians earn their living by driving, renting, and repairing the carts
the figure is striking given the fact that indian railways, the fourth largest in the world, employ only 16.3 million people,'' said rupinder gupta, a mechanical engineer for the road research institute. gupta has designed six types of bullock cart for field trials
each year, animal-drawn carts move 14.4 million ton-miles of freight
dhir estimates that india's animal-drawn carts provide about 40 million horse-power, equal to about 320,000 medium-duty trucks used in the united states as city delivery vehicles
without bullock carts, india also would have had to import an additional 6 million tons of fuel each year. it now imports 17 million tons of crude oil annually
one of the innovations is the replacement of the carts' wooden-spoke wheels with pneumatic tires
engineer gupta said carts with pneumatic tires can pull 2.5 tons of weight against the maximum capacity of 1.5 tons for conventional carts
researchers in the southern state of karnataka also have come up with plastic bullock carts, and in neighboring andhra pradesh state a tire company has produced carts of lightweight aluminum
another idea behind non-wooden carts is to reduce demand for lumber. an estimated 165,000 medium-sized trees are felled each year to make conventional carts
so you see, there is a solid logic behind metal carts,'' said gupta
he listed other reasons for updating the carts
we want to increase tillage and output, reduce damage to roads and injury to animals so that the poor animals can have a longer lifespan,'' he said
to protect the animals, curved and padded yokes are being introduced. studies have shown that some draft animals' lives are cut short by cancerous infections on the neck from unpadded and uncurved yokes
reflectors are being added as another safety feature
other new fittings are bush bearings, cast-iron springs, shock absorbers, draw bars that adjust for animals of different height, and mud scrappers
a fodder box can be put on carts that go long distances
as for road damage, director dhir said the biggest culprit is wooden wheels
in monetary terms the annual damage is to the tune of 7,000 million rupees ($538 million) to the roads,'' he said
farmers seem to like the idea of improving bullock carts
it is an excellent idea,'' said jhandu singh, 64, of jharsa, a village 30 miles south of new delhi
but this should have had been done 25 years ago. we have suffered for long, and so did the animals.''
officials, too, say the new carts are catching on, but this itself is creating problems
we do not have enough new types of carts for all,'' said kalle khan, project economist of the district rural development agency in jharsa, whose office received only 16 new carts
there are more than 200 claimants. even some gypsies saw the carts and were attracted. they wanted at least one. i told them no. these are for farmers.''
another reason for high demand is that the government is subsidizing the price by about 35 percent
it is estimated that the largest of the old wooden carts costs the equivalent of about $300. newer wooden carts, without the government subsidy, cost $270 to $460. the plastic and aluminum carts are 25 percent more expensive. photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>

editor's note _ the former mayor of syracuse, n.y., will be sentenced this week on charges that he extorted hundreds of thousands of dollars from people wanting to do business with the city. lee alexander, a democrat, pleaded guilty to the charges, saying he accepted sole responsibility for what happened
in his day, lee alexander was one of the most visible mayors in america, a politician who seemed destined for bigger things
now he appears destined for prison
as mayor of new york's fifth-largest city, alexander had a penchant for beautiful women, chauffeur-driven limos and bodyguards. he was a snappy dresser with a deep tan, his hair always in place
during his 16 years as mayor, alexander, a democrat, was often the spokesman for the nation's mayors. he served as president of the u.s. conference of mayors and six times was elected president of the national conference of democratic mayors
there was talk of a big job in washington, speculation that he might some day run for governor. party leaders made him their candidate for the u.s. senate in 1974, but he lost the primary to former u.s. attorney general ramsey clark
now it turns out the man who looked so urbane and polished was actually an extortionist, using his power to coerce money from people wanting to do business with the city of syracuse
alexander's scheme preyed on architects, lawyers, engineers, and insurance agents. they paid him up to 25 percent of the cost of the project and payments were made in bonds, gold coins and cash
for example, an architect paid alexander $125,000 for the opportunity to work on a project at the city's hancock international airport and another paid $25,500 for a hospital parking garage expansion. an insurance agent paid an alexander bagman $26,200 for a fire policy and a lawyer paid a bagman $2,878 to handle the legal work on a downtown building project
a lot of people turned down the deals and nothing happened,'' said u.s. attorney frederick j. scullin. ``alexander was astute enough to know where he could put the pressure. if someone caved in, well, he kept the pressure on. if someone rebuffed him right away, he'd back right up.''
by the time alexander left city hall in 1986, he was a millionaire
now he has to pay it all back
alexander pleaded guilty to charges that he violated federal racketeering laws by using his power as mayor to extort money, that he conspired to obstruct the investigation and that he evaded income taxes on his illegal profits
sentencing is scheduled for march 10
the federal prosecutor is recommending that alexander be sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined $100,000. scullin said he believes that a 10-year sentence would be longer than any handed to a public corruption figure in the nation
alexander could have faced 690 years in prison if convicted on all 40 counts of the original indictment
the former mayor has also agreed to return $1.2 million of his illegal profits. alexander has said the settlement will leave him in worse financial shape than he was in 1970 when he began his mayoral career
some of alexander's bounty was turned over to prosecutors by attorneys delivering shopping bags filled with valuable bonds and coupons. some of the money was banked overseas in such places as the bahamas and panama, according to scullin
nine other people who have pleaded guilty to charges stemming from the investigation will be sentenced along with alexander
alexander's undoing started with scullin's appointment as u.s. attorney for northern new york in 1982. scullin, who grew up in syracuse and earned his law degree from syracuse university, said he had heard talk that alexander was crooked
this thing really began when i first became u.s. attorney,'' scullin says. ``there were rumors on the street then about alexander being a wheeler and a dealer. if not kickbacks, then there was talk about a lot of conflicts. the rumors were pretty rampant. i decided we should look into it and put them to rest one way or another.''
at first, it was slow going. but the investigation persisted
you keep working and working, nibbling away at it, developing whatever information you can,'' scullin says. ``there was a pattern of no-bid contracts and professional fees
we got a couple of breaks. we got lucky.''
the internal revenue service and the fbi joined scullin's attorneys in the investigation. a witness came forward offering information in exchange for immunity. ``that was the crack in the dam,'' scullin says
at its peak, alexander was the focus of attention of a team of prosecutors, 20 fbi agents and another 20 irs agents
what they came up with was enough evidence to persuade a grand jury to indict the mayor
alexander always seemed on the verge of becoming a political heavyweight
in 1976, he passed up an opportunity to be an early supporter of jimmy carter's presidential campaign to serve as upstate campaign coordinator for the ill-fated campaign of henry jackson
his extortion scheme was designed to increase his influence with national politicians, according to scullin
he wanted to be considered a viable influence on the democratic party and make things happen,'' scullin said. ``he could get the money where other people could not.''
many of the kickbacks alexander arranged were made in the form of political contributions to big-time democrats, scullin said. new york city mayor ed koch, gov. mario cuomo and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis were among the recipients
toward the end he sort of lost track of the political contributions,'' scullins said. ``as he could see his star dwindling the last three or four years, i think he was more concerned about lining his own pockets. he got greedier and greedier as time went on.''
opponents were critical of alexander's frequent trips away from syracuse, saying he was more interested in traveling than tending to local problems. alexander defended his travels, saying he came back with federal money for his city
alexander found an opportunity to get some publicity one day when a gunman killed a man, then took a pregnant woman and her baby hostage in a predominantly black neighborhood, holding police off for most of the day
after being held back by police for many hours, news photographers were suddenly allowed to approach the house. the door opened and alexander ran out of the house clutching the baby to his chest. photographs of the mayor carrying the baby to safety were displayed by newspapers across the country the next day. black leaders complained that it was the only time alexander had ever visited the neighborhood
on the local level, alexander was a skillful and effective politician. until alexander came along, the republicans dominated syracuse and onondaga county politics. alexander's campaign not only ended a 16-year republican rule of the mayor's office, but led the democrats to control of the common council
not everyone liked alexander. when shots were fired at his house, police were prompted to build a guardhouse outside the home
city auditor roy bernardi was probably alexander's most vocal critic. bernardi's complaints were aimed mainly at the way the mayor did business
the auditor said he knew then that the city was paying too much money for projects and was always doing business with the same people
i noticed a pattern that if not illegal, and i had no proof of that, it was not in the best interest of the city,'' said bernardi, who is still the city auditor
ironically, while alexander was in power, his republican opponents who controlled surrounding onondaga county were the target of a special prosecutor investigating political corruption. despite the talk on the street, the special prosecutor didn't pay much attention to the democrats
the special prosecutor was appointed by then-gov. hugh carey, a democrat, to investigate allegations that republicans illegally coerced political contributions from public workers. the investigation netted convictions against several key republicans who claimed they were unfairly singled out for activities common in politics and also practiced by city hall democrats
but the crimes of the republicans pale when compared with what was going on in alexander's city hall office
the republicans were convicted of violations of a state law prohibiting political fund-raising in public buildings and misdemeanors. juries returned acquittals on the more serious charges. no republicans went to prison and no democrats were ever indicted in that special investigation
alexander is not talking publicly about his troubles, his lawyer said. after making his guilty plea, alexander issued a statement saying the city never paid for any services it did not receive
i accept sole responsibility for what happened,'' alexander said in his statement. ``while pursuing the highest standards of integrity with respect to the conduct of members of my administration, i did not apply those same standards to myself.''
tom young, a democrat, is the mayor now, and he runs things differently. instead of personally selecting who does business with the city, young has contractors submit competitive bids. young has a panel study the proposals before a contract is awarded
there are many who still believe alexander was good for syracuse
i never saw any sign of any wrongdoing,'' says robert visser, the city clerk who has worked in city hall since 1974
he did an awful lot of good for the city and eventually the good will outweigh the bad. if it had not been for the former mayor, the city of syracuse would not be in the great shape it is in today.'' photos. colorfoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</note>

editor's note _ she was accustomed to the privileged life of an european princess, the daughter of king ferdinand and queen marie of romania and great-granddaughter of england's queen victoria and czar alexander ii of russia. today princess ileana leads the disciplined life of a cloistered nun as the rev. mother alexandra
her family jewels are gone and her castle is property of the communist state, but romania's princess ileana has found peace at a monastery in rural western pennsylvania
the 79-year-old princess is now known as the rev. mother alexandra, one of 12 nuns who share food, work and prayer at the romanian orthodox monastery
the nun of 27 years was the founder of the orthodox monastery of the transfiguration, the first english-speaking orthodox monastery in the united states
but vestiges of her royal past remain, even at the monastery
portraits of her parents, romania's king ferdinand and queen marie, hang in the living room of the a-frame house she shares with another nun
gold and silver icons dating as far back as the 15th century fill a corner of her bedroom, including one handed down in the family from czar nicholas i of russia and said to contain a splinter of christ's cross. antique icons also decorate the monastery's small, candle-lit chapel, as do crosses and triptychs, some of which she brought from europe
a small, gold container on a bed stand holds her most precious possession, a handful of romanian soil snatched during her escape from soviet communism in the wake of world war ii. she wants it buried with her
there's a big gap between then and now,'' she says. ``so much has happened in between.''
uncomfortable sitting with idle hands, the tall, stately nun worked on a knotted prayer rope as she reflected on her multifaceted life
it's been different so many times over,'' she says. ``but, you see, one lives day by day, doesn't one?''
she refuses to compare her royal and religious ways of life
there is no point,'' she said. ``i did my duty as a princess. and now i'm doing my duty as a nun.''
her superiors, nonetheless, are impressed by her example
as a person, as an individual, i have admiration because even not having a position, she could have had a social life, which would be much more in keeping with other people of her background,'' said bishop nathaniel popp, 47, head of the romanian orthodox episcopate of america
instead of saying she was a princess who became a nun, i think it was more she was a nun coming through the life of a princess.''
although just a child during the german invasion of world war i, princess ileana accompanied her mother, the queen, from hospital to hospital, administering to romania's wounded and hungry. by the time world war ii erupted, both her parents were dead, her older brother, carol, had ascended the throne, one sister had become queen of yugoslavia and another queen of greece
princess ileana was living in a castle outside vienna, wife of an archduke of austria and the mother of six
afraid of the nazi regime, princess ileana and her family moved in 1944 to romania. there she set up hospitals and did what she could for her suffering compatriots
in december 1947, the king of romania was forced by the communists to abdicate and the following week, princess ileana and the rest of the royal family were exiled
princess ileana immigrated with her family to switzerland and then argentina before settling in 1950 in the united states, a move that ultimately led to divorce. to support her children, she sold her cherished diamond and sapphire tiara, lectured about life behind the iron curtain, and wrote an autobiography titled, ``i live again.''
it wasn't until 1961, after her children were grown, that the 52-year-old princess became a postulant. she ended a second marriage to do so
in my heart,'' she says, ``i always wanted to become a nun. but there was so much to be done in romania when i was young.''
princess ileana took the monastic vows of stability, obedience, poverty and chastity in 1967 and, with that profession, became mother alexandra. later that year, she put up a trailer on 100 acres of farmland outside ellwood city and began building an english-speaking monastery for orthodox women of all ethnic backgrounds. photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>

editor's note _ the society of automotive engineers was founded shortly after the turn of the century as a clearinghouse for a free exchange of ideas at a time when inventors were making contraptions that suited their own tastes. just as it set the standards for the production of automobiles, sae now is proposing interchangeable parts for spaceships
an organization of engineers, best known by its initials on motor oil cans, hopes to do for spaceships what it did for automobiles and airplanes
the society of automotive engineers (sae), founded in 1905, is a global engineering network for the exchange of ideas. members have included henry ford, orville wright, harvey firestone, thomas edison and charles lindbergh
sae writes standards on such things as what grade of motor oil works best in cold temperatures, how much reflection comes from a taillight lens, the process that makes a brake stop a car
more than 900 standards cover every passenger car
these standards make sure a product performs in a generally expected way. they are guideposts by which government and industry have measured performance for 83 years in self-propelled vehicles
we serve the public by getting the technology out so that others can build upon it and use it as a steppingstone without having to reinvent the wheel,'' says max e. rumbaugh jr., executive vice president of sae
sae now has its eyes on the stars
it created a space standardization advisory committee, which met for the first time in december, for possible standards on spaceships. sae hopes to work with the national aeronautics and space administration on guidelines that would reduce confusion, eliminate duplication and cut costs
the space program has been so unique, we've been experimenting with technology that is one of a kind,'' says arshad hafeez, sae's aerospace engineer
six of the 25 members on sae's exploratory committee are from nasa, which wants to have a space station in orbit in the next decade so it can assemble ships in space, among other things
it's getting to the point where some standardization will help everybody,'' says dick weinstein, manager of engineering standards and practices for nasa
there's enough on the horizon that if we don't do something soon, we could be in big trouble. everybody will be going in a different direction.''
rumbaugh adds: ``as they start putting things up there like a space station, you've got to have interchangeability of parts for repair and maintenance
you can't be coming back down here when a light bulb goes out and build a new one to take back up. standards allow you to reduce the cost of manufacturing. making one of a kind costs you a fortune.''
sae has its world headquarters in a three-story, red brick building about 30 miles north of pittsburgh near the pennsylvania turnpike and interstate 79
with 52,000 members in 82 countries, it has 25,000 technical papers on file, holds 20 meetings a year, publishes two magazines and has an engineering library
none of the volumes will make a best-seller list, but they titillate engineers
esoteric titles include: the internal combustion engine in theory and practice, volumes one and two; fuel alternatives for spark ignition and diesel engines; reinforced thermosetting plastics for ground vehicle applications; the toyota production method; and human tolerance to impact conditions as related to motor vehicle design
some car manuals are available in spanish, french and german
anyone who pours a can of motor oil can notice the letters sae along with numbers corresponding to the viscosity of the oil. sae standards cover 11 grades of oil, with lower numbers performing better in lower temperatures
oil companies voluntarily produce and label their products by sae standards
other sae deeds are less visible
a lot of the work is sort of boring,'' rumbaugh says. ``we don't have a lot of hoopla. sae just attempts to get the job done. oftentimes, a job can get done a heck of a lot better before it gets a lot of media exposure. we prefer to do things before getting the hype.''
sae was fringhouse for a free exchange of ideas at a time when inventors were making contraptions that suited their own tastes
each car still has unique style features. but sae standards cover such things as ounded as a cleahow much light is emitted by headlamps, the shade of red in a taillight, the area of the windshield that should be cleared by a wiper and the size of the lug nuts that hold a rim onto a wheel
sae also helped develop the closed-in auto body, the self-starter that replaced the hand crank, the hydraulic brake, the synchronized transmissions that eliminated gear noises and led to the automatic transmission, shatterproof glass, power steering and power brakes
the american automobile industry has thrived on the principle that the exchange of technical information improves society,'' rumbaugh says. `` they are less secretive than almost any other industry in the world.''
william sherman, writing in 1980 on the journalists also met with a member of what bleibtreu said was the contra human rights commission
salt lake city _ mayor palmer depaulis has invited a reporter to take a second look at the city the newsman described in print as a ``perry como kind of place'' where the mormon church dominates daily life
depaulis says he doesn't want to appear defensive but sent a letter to the los angeles times inviting david lamb to return for a second look
in his letter feb. 17, depaulis said lamb's story overlooked the city's rich cultural climate and ethnic diversity, as well as its beautiful mountain scenery
i wish he could see the 10th st. patrick's day parade, whose grand marshal this year is consul general of ireland, or the italian-american columbus day celebration, ongoing since 1934, or our annual greek festival and hispanic fiesta,'' depaulis wrote
the mayor said he might try to find a sponsor for lamb if the invitation is accepted
lawrenceville, ga. _ the gwinnett daily news will convert to morning publication in early may, the newspaper announced in its feb. 21 editions
it currently publishes in the afternoon five days a week and in the morning on saturday and sunday
executive editor jim osteen said, ``moving to morning publication will allow us to produce a more expansive, complete newspaper for our readers. it will also allow our coverage of sports and the stock market report to be more timely.''
the gwinnett daily news, purchased in june by the new york times, becomes the second suburban atlanta newspaper to switch from afternoon to morning publication. the marietta daily journal announced similar plans earlier this year
in the last 10 years more than 100 afternoon newspapers across the country have switched to morning publication. photo.)</note>

editor's note _ a boston television reporter took to the streets a few years ago and asked dozens of passersby to describe the current sky without looking up. only one in 10 could do so. that inspired him to design a sky-watching program for schoolchildren called ``for spacious skies'' that is getting rave reviews from many educators
it was a blustery new england morning, with a cutting wind blowing off boston harbor. people were staying inside if they could, but pat keohane and her first-graders were up on the school roof again, looking at the pale winter sky
what's moving the clouds?'' she asks, pointing at a bank of cumuli
the wind,'' reply the kids in an enthusiastic chorus
there's light blue, and dark blue and baby blue over there,'' says a little girl, her scarf flapping as she stared intently at the heavens
the boy next to her interrupted: ``there's a swordfish with a long nose.'' his comments were suddenly lost in a babble of other kids' voices
look, those clouds look like a sweat suit,'' said one
i see an upside-down dragon,'' another giggled
back at their desks later, the children took turns spelling sky-related words in a variation of the classic hangman game, doing well on big ones like ``lightning,'' and ``showers.''
a diminutive boy spelled ``rain,'' and ms. keohane asked: ``what would happen if we didn't have rain for 100 days?''
there would be no flowers and no wildlife,'' one of the pupils piped up
that wouldn't matter,'' said another. ``we'd still have water in the sinks.''
in ms. keohane's inner-city classroom at the josiah quincy school and at about 1,400 others across the country, teachers say that a program called ``for spacious skies'' is helping pupils academically and emotionally
some of those involved with the program go even further, suggesting that sky watching can turn tough inner-city kids away from drugs and desperation and on to aesthetic beauty instead
jack borden, originator of the program, says, ``wherever you are you have the sky, whether you are living in the high mountains or the worst of slums. as a matter of fact, the person living in the worst slums often has access to the most sky.''
a study conducted by researchers at harvard university's graduate school of education appears to support some of the positive claims made by teachers enthused about sky watching
using two classrooms at an elementary school in needham, a community about 15 miles west of boston, the study compared pupils who participated in ``for spacious skies'' in the fall of 1985 and again at the end of the school year, with those who were not encouraged to look at the sky
the researchers found that the emphasis on looking up, followed by drawing pictures and writing about the sky, ``significantly increased the level of aesthetic sensitivity in visual art and literature.''
the benefits gained from a program such as this would have a great value in any school curriculum,'' the study said
the program encourages children to keep journals on their observations and some of them write poetry and draw pictures, said researcher liz rosenblatt. ``the fact that kids are exposed to the arts in this way helps create an awareness that probably helps the increase in their skills.''
for spacious skies'' is named after the familiar first line of the katherine lee bates poem, set to music by samuel a. ward as ``america the beautiful.''
borden, a quixotic former television reporter, believes that we cannot spend life looking at our feet. his vision came to him about 10 years ago, while working at boston's wbz-tv
taking to the street, he asked dozens of passersby to describe the current sky without looking up. only one in 10 could do so
i myself was a non-aware person,'' borden says. ``then i began to see that it's a good thing to turn people on to the sky.''
since that summer day in 1977, borden, 59 , has formed a non-profit company to distribute ``for spacious skies'' teaching kits, which offer suggestions on how to use the heavens to teach just about anything
`for spacious skies' is designed to help teach mathematics, english, creative writing, music, art and science,'' according to the preface of a booklet meant for schools in the new england area. ``this program, just like the new england sky, is limitless. with the sky as a catalyst, your student's imagination can be challenged to its limits.''
the kits, which are mailed to schools for about $7.50, include guides for teachers on presenting the material. they contain tables of wind-chill factors, relative humidity and barometric pressure, songs about the sky, and sample observation sheets for students to note weather conditions
donna cataldo, a support specialist at josiah quincy, outlined the different uses of the program at her 830-pupil school:
some of the upper classes are keeping charts about the length of the day and how that relates to the harvest and growing cycles, and that brings out social studies...what are some of the origins of feast days and festivals that are based on the length of the days and the growing season
at lower grades, kids can do bar graphs of how many sunny days there were in january and how many snowy days there were...measuring and counting and a number of interdisciplinary skills. it allows children to write. they might also do a science project around wind speed.''
gov. michael dukakis proclaimed last march 18 ``for spacious skies day'' in massachusetts
the american meteorological society honored the program for its work in public education a year ago and scheduled presentations on ``for spacious skies'' at its annual meeting this year at anaheim, calif
weather forecasters are borden's key allies in getting the word to teachers about sky watching. many have mentioned the program during their broadcasts, and some have gone even further, incorporating aspects of ``for spacious skies'' in weather lectures and seminars for children and teachers
meteorologist bruce schwoegler of boston's wbc-tv said he was amazed at the interest in ``for spacious skies'' booklets offered on the air to teachers
i ran a three-part series in our news last march in which we offered 3,500 teachers' guides...and we had a very enthusiastic response,'' he said. ``they were all gone within a month.''
in pittsburgh, weatherman brian sussman of kdka-tv said his station's booklet giveaway had similar success
discussing the program's value in tougher inner-city schools, sussman drew parallels between sports and sky watching
just like athletics has been a vehicle to get kids out of the ghetto, i'm looking at `for spacious skies' as a vehicle for sparking interest in a particular field like geography,'' he said. ``what i'm seeing is kids who are interested in something else than mtv. they, for the first time, are observing the beauty of nature.''
violet witherspoon, a disciple of sky watching who teaches the third-grade at the john marshall elementary school in boston's dorchester section, expressed similar sentiments
i told the children, `you don't need drugs, let the sky be your drug,''' she said
they can look at the sky and daydream. they don't have to have fine clothes, they don't have to have fine cars, beauty is all around them, and it's free.'' photo.)</note>

editor's note _ born in a virginia hill town, seka got interested in the porn business through her boyfriend who owned adult bookstores. today she's a legend in the adult-film industry, as a performer and as an astute businesswoman
a porn queen who found her way to the other side of the camera is ascending toward the top in a $1 billion-a-year business where many women work but precious few call the shots
she's a platinum blonde whose stage name is seka. at 33, she has appeared in more than three dozen hard-core adult films over the past decade
she is still legendary,'' said paul fishbein, publisher of adult video news magazine. ``when today's generation delves into the adult-film market for the first time, she is still the one they want to see.''
but the big reason for seka's financial success is that she sued her manager under federal corruption laws and gained control of her name, her films and a business that turns annual profits in six figures
dressed demurely in a sweater and slacks and tucked into the corner of a dark restaurant, seka looks every bit the businesswoman she is as chief executive officer of the chicago-based pearl productions ltd., which sells everything from lighters with her logo to panties
nobody has ever taken care of me,'' seka says matter-of-factly, running a bright pink fingernail through her close-cropped, platinum hair. ``and as long as i look after business, nobody ever will.''
seka (she will not disclose her given name) was born in the virginia hill town of radford, where the main industry was an arsenal that manufactures dynamite
she married a factory worker before she finished high school, but the marriage didn't last long
all i knew was i wanted to be on my own. i wanted to be independent,'' she recalled. ``i didn't want to wake up and have someone next to me saying, `fix me coffee and breakfast.'''
her introduction to the porn industry came during the mid-1970s through a boyfriend who owned adult bookstores. the more she became involved in the trade, the more she became convinced, ``i could do it better.''
she worked her way back from the distributors she knew through the bookstore business to the moviemakers themselves, went to california one bright day in 1977, answered an ad for a nude model, and started working that afternoon
seka was paid $200 for her first movie, a 15-minute, 8mm film
many of her early films _ she made more than two dozen between 1977 and 1979 _ were only slightly more memorable, although the pay scale improved considerably
she was, however, just another 23-year-old ingenue making adult films, indistinguishable from dozens of other young women in the de rigeur black nylons and garter belts of the times. then she met a makeup man with big plans. it was 1980 and the home-video market was just beginning to heat up
he made her over, bulked her up with weights and vitamins, changed the way she dressed, and managed her business in the bargain. her new look debuted in 1981 in club magazine and the result was booming sales
yet, after what should have been a very profitable rise to the top of her profession, seka had to hire an attorney simply to look at her own books. one glimpse and she sued her manager for diverting income
she worked sparingly over the next two years, ultimately finding herself in 1984 with a handsome settlement and control of a potentially lucrative business now that the home-video market was changing the rules of the adult-film game
no longer dependent on recovering most of the costs from theaters, adult film-making became an almost risk-free venture
a handful of pornographers had recognized the home-video market's untapped potential ahead of the major movie studios and already were doing land-office business
a movie that could be made for as little as $150,000 if shot on film _ or $20,000 if shot directly onto videotape _ becomes a profit-maker after only moderate sales and rentals
that meant an adult film had only to sell about 20,000 videocassettes _ an average wholesale cost of $25 per cassette _ to qualify as a megahit. by comparison, a major movie studio needs to sell 50,000 units to approach the same status
and seka needed only one look to realize that under the new economic reality, age and overexposure were threatening her main asset _ her body
so in 1984 she added a copyright attorney to gain control of her old material, then a contract attorney to make certain she got top dollar for whatever new material she released
she has made just two feature films since then _ only one has been released _ studied diction and elocution and devoted most of her time to mastering business skills: computers, flow charts, marketing and the like
her return to the adult-film industry as an actress came in a big way with the 1986 film, ``careful, he may be watching.'' the movie, which cost about $230,000 to make, stars seka in a dual role as twins, one evil, one not
she also conceived the story line, developed the script and served as producer. former porn star actor richard pacheco directed, making the film something of a trailblazing effort from start to finish
careful'' won the adult video news awards for best picture and best director, capped off by seka's induction into the hall of fame. but she says ``careful'' won't begin making money until it's been on the market for about 2{ years
i can wait,'' she said. ``i've got some projects, an exclusive magazine deal, things i can't talk about in the wings. i've even been offered the opportunity to be in a major motion picture, but there were casting couches behind the screen
at least what i do,'' seka concluded, ``is on the screen.'' photo.)</note>

editor's note _ janwillem van de wetering wrote his first book at age 40 after years of hopping around the globe and pursuing an interest in zen buddhism. the dutch-born author, who now lives in maine, was interviewed in new york where he was visiting his publisher
fans of offbeat mysteries set in exotic locales dote on dutch author janwillem van de wetering, a former amsterdam cop who spent two years in a zen buddhist monastery in japan
but even though his novels often have a zen flavor, van de wetering says the three heroes of what his publisher calls ``the amsterdam cop series'' are not followers of the oriental philosophy
they've never heard of buddhism or zen,'' says van de wetering, who now makes his home in maine, drawn there first by a zen teacher. ``i mention it sometimes, in a joking manner, because it's popular with the dutch intelligentsia. the police couldn't care less. they think it's all long-haired nonsense.''
yet, their supercool investigations read like they're following the zen practice of attaining enlightenment by intuitive insight, beyond intellectual reasoning
a lot of people do that,'' van de wetering says. ``if you can't figure it out, then don't try to figure it out but stay with it.''
van de wetering, now 56, wrote his first book when he was 40. it was ``the empty mirror,'' about his experiences in the zen monastery
he has written three childrens books, two novels, two books about zen, a biography of dutch diplomat-author robert van gulik and is best known for 12 mysteries, most set in amsterdam
the first mystery van de wetering wrote, ``outsider in amsterdam,'' introduced the wonderfully detached commissaris, a dutch municipal police officer, and his underlings in the murder brigade, adjutant grijpstra and sgt. de gier
originally i wanted to write a realistic book about the police,'' van de wetering said during a visit to new york to visit his publisher. ``i had been a policeman myself and thought i could do it. it never came off, even at first. none of the characters wanted to do that
grijpstra was going to be the nasty guy. he immediately became sympathetic. he is my dutchman, my everyman, my superego. he is not into fantasy. i intended him to be pretty dumb but he isn't
de gier turned out to have tremendous energy that everybody has as a child and then it gets repressed and organized by society. with de gier it never got organized. he is not in the police for any good purpose; he's an adventurer. he's tremendously curious; he wants to see what goes on. he doesn't necessarily sympathize with goodness and frown on evilness
the only one who's got it all together is the commissaris. he looks like a gray mouse, with his limp, but he really is a combination of them and goes beyond both of them. he is what i think a zen master ought to be like. the commissaris is convinced it doesn't matter what you do but he will always do the nice thing.''
two of van de wetering's mysteries have been made into movies in holland. contracts for an american movie have been signed for ``hard rain,'' published in 1986 by pantheon. ballantine has published all the mysteries and the two books about zen in paperback
the author, whose name is pronounced yan-villum van de vet-tevin, started visiting a zen teacher on the coast of maine in the 1960s. in 1975, he and his colombian wife, juanita, settled nearby. he became disillusioned with the zen teacher but stayed in maine because he likes the country. his wife took up gardening. their daughter is married
we live on 60 acres, which is quite normal there,'' he says. ``i see my neighbors when i go look for them. but too many artists hang out in that part of the world. we meet each other in endless encounters that consume too much time. i really have to discipline myself when i go to the post office not to lose all day
the weather is so interesting. we all have boats. there's a big colony of seals and we talk about what they do and what bird is coming for the summer or leaving for the winter
i have very little discipline. if i don't want to work, i peer at the window and hope the dog will come in. when i want to work, i'll work through the night and the next day won't go to the post office.''
van de wetering's hobby is making junk sculpture, which he displays around his property
i was always frantic about finding certain parts. an old man said, `just let it come to you.' i do that all the time now. when i turned 50, i was worried about dying. i wanted a vehicle to guide me across _ a horse. the afternoon i thought of it, i went to the beach and found legs and ribs, a sheet of plywood that was a wonderful fit and rope for the tail.''
van de wetering learned about the amsterdam police work during seven years in the reserve police, working mostly nights and weekends
i had to do it because i got accused of dodging the draft. i left holland when i was 19 and never remembered to come back. it was kind of a punishment. i liked it. after four years i could have quit.''
at 19, van de wetering went to south africa to work, then to england to study philosophy for a year
dissatisfied with western philosophy, he spent two years in a zen monastery in kyoto, japan. after that he worked for a chemical company in colombia, in real estate in australia, returned to amsterdam to take over his uncle's wholesale textile business. he got bored with that, sold it after seven years and moved to maine
he started to write during the seven years in amsterdam
i always wanted to write,'' he says. ``i couldn't. i did bits and pieces and articles. i read that henry miller started when he was 40. i kept the desire alive. i started writing when i was 40.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>
mario van peebles, making his first real venture into television, is amazed that producers and network executives are listening to his suggestions and putting them on the screen
van peebles stars in the nbc comedy-adventure series ``sonny spoon'' as an unorthodox detective who is part con man, part actor, and regularly slips into other characterizations to get the job done
last year, he appeared in about six episodes of nbc's ``l.a. law'' and won the naacp image award as best supporting actor for his role in ``heartbreak ridge.''
brandon tartikoff, president of nbc entertainment, called him in for a meeting and asked him to do a series. producer stephen j. cannell saw a short film he did and wanted to work with him. so tartikoff, cannell and van peebles went to work on the idea of ``sonny spoon.''
van peebles suggested some scenes for the show. ``one is that i hide out in a baptist church dressed up as a big lady in the choir,'' he says. ``then the choral director points to me and i have to sing a solo. they used my suggestion
in another show, a friend of mine steals some jewels from a mobster, not knowing he's a mobster. when he finds out, i dress up like a priest and return the jewels
sonny's like a chameleon. he can plug into any character. in the episode we're doing now i go undercover as a white yuppie. i have blue eyes and blond hair
it's exciting for me as an actor. you get to play so many different roles. i can cross age lines, sex lines, race lines.''
during his lunch break in his trailer, which is parked in the veterans cemetery in westwood near the campus of ucla, he eats a quick lunch brought to him by his mother. later, the company moves to wilshire boulevard
on arrival at the new location, van peebles points to a banged-up yellow porche carbriolet. ``they wanted to give me a new porche,'' he says. ``i said no, sonny would drive a car with dents in it.''
until about two years ago, van peebles was working mostly in the theater as an actor, writer and director. he grew up in show business as the son of director-actor melvin van peebles
a short film he wrote, directed and played in, ``juliet,'' attracted some attention. ``it's about a girl who goes through a bunch of guys,'' he says. ``i played all the guys. cannell saw that and wrote some of those characterizations into `sonny spoon
van peebles says that both tartikoff and cannell encouraged his suggestions about the show
to tell the truth, i wasn't sure anything would come out of it,'' he says. ``that's why i was so bold in speaking up. for instance, i said i didn't want my character to carry a gun. i called him a `finagling humanitarian.' it's like when bugs bunny comes up against the tasmanian devil. he has to get out of that situation on his wits alone
that makes it a little tougher to write. it's easy to write that a character gets out of a car and pulls a gun. it's much harder to have him suddenly become a hispanic taxi driver.''
van peebles got a degree in economics at columbia university and went to work as a budget analyst for the city of new york
i figured if i could do mayor (edward) koch's budget i could do a movie budget,'' he says. ``i thought it was time to get back into acting and thought dad would help out. i took him to his favorite chinese restaurant. i said, `i've got my degree, are you going to help me out?'
he said, `no.' he said the restaurant was full of people who were waiting for a break. it was up to me to go out and make my own breaks. but mom and dad were very supportive. they came to see me in every little play i did. now i meet some kids of famous people who can't do anything on their own.''
van peebles likens his interest in acting, writing, directing and producing to working on a farm
on a farm you don't just do one thing,'' he says. ``you plow a field, fix the tractor, feed the chickens, patch up the barn roof. in other words, you do everything. that's the way i grew up in the business.'' photo.)</note>
alan ayckbourn may be known as britain's most prolific comic playwright, but the man often billed as an english neil simon says his plays are getting darker
in his 32nd play, ``woman in mind,'' now at off-broadway's manhattan theater club, the author presents a heroine on the brink of madness. audiences may laugh at first, ayckbourn says, but he hopes the chuckles ultimately catch in the throat
it's an attempt to be a popular play saying something serious,'' the 48-year-old ayckbourn said the other day in an office at london's national theater where he has been in residence as a director and a playwright since the fall of 1986
i stopped calling my plays comedies years and years ago,'' says the london-born writer who began his career as an actor and stage manager
people write and say, `woman in mind' is rather sad at the end, isn't it?' and i say, `well, yeah. i only said it was a play, not a comedy.'''
a rotund, engaging man with a low laugh that sometimes swallows up his words, ayckbourn has made his reputation over two decades by chronicling the humors and the horrors of the british lower middle class
while such colleagues as harold pinter and tom stoppard spin elegantly phrased dramas out of the mores of the well-heeled, ayckbourn's terrain is the same middle class that makes up his audience. they are the people he courts and, sometimes, critiques
i take the audience by the hand and take them down a path they would not normally have gone,'' ayckbourn says
that audience has remained loyal over two decades, since his 1963 play ``mr. whatnot,'' about a mute piano tuner, brought him acclaim and an agent, the influential margaret ramsey
according to a 1985-86 british arts council report, ayckbourn's plays were second that year only to shakespeare's in numbers of performances given throughout england's regional theaters
his work is performed in more than 35 countries as far afield as uruguay, australia, and kenya. although several have been seen on broadway _ most recently ``bedroom farce'' in 1978 _ he has not yet enjoyed a broadway smash
broadway is the toughest nut to crack, of course, in the whole world,'' ayckbourn said, conceding he was preoccupied with the new york reception of ``woman in mind.''
i don't know how they'll take it,'' he said of the play, which casts stockard channing _ 1985's tony-winning star of ``joe egg'' _ as a middle-class englishwoman named susan who seeks refuge from her dreary domestic routine in a fantasy world rife with its own dangers
i wanted to get inside somebody else's head, really inside it, and see if i could bring the audience with me,'' ayckbourn says. ``i also wanted to say, `this is what it must be like to have your powers of mental perception slipping away from you.'''
in susan's case,'' he continues, ``you suddenly realize she's unreliable _not deliberately, but that her perceptions of what is real and what is not are completely false. she begins to get reality and dream muddled.''
woman in mind,'' which had a successful west end production starring julia mckenzie, is just one recent ayckbourn play that looks at the moral and psychological underside of people and their society
in ``a small family business,'' currently at the national theater, ayckbourn weaves a tale of ethical decay in which the upstanding hero, jack mccracken, gets sucked into corruption both at home and at work
henceforward,'' which played houston's alley theater last fall with george segal and which opens on the west end with ian mckellen in november, dramatizes a futuristic british society dominated by thugs, hoodlums, and people who have become robots
it's a far cry from the ayckbourn of ``absurd person singular'' and ``the norman conquests,'' two hits from the mid-1970s which showed london and broadway the playwright's clockwork precision with a laugh
does the author sometimes feel that his earlier works were written by a different person?
it's like looking at an old snapshot and saying, `i don't remember looking like that,''' he said. ``i no longer really remember why i wrote them. i've just moved on.''
he said he's no longer as concerned with craft per se as he once was
when i started, it was like a kid discovering he's got 10 fingers. it's great to use them all, and i use them quite a lot,'' said ayckbourn, whose works often feature multiple endings _ some decided by coin tosses _ and chinese box-like plays-within-plays
once you've done a few of those bravado tricks and shown yourself you can do it, the technique i hope sinks a little bit.''
more recently, ayckbourn has had great success as a director. his production of arthur miller's ``a view from the bridge,'' starring michael gambon as eddie carbone, ended its acclaimed yearlong run on feb. 20
he also directed john ford's 1630 verse drama, ``'tis pity she's a whore,'' at the national's olivier auditorium. rupert graves, who appeared as the gamekeeper scudder in the film ``maurice,'' stars as the incestuous giovanni
now it's back up north to the yorkshire city of scarborough, a resort and conference town where ayckbourn is the artistic director of the stephen joseph theater-in-the-round. there, he will open his 35th play, ``love of my life.''
and what's that like?
he chuckles: ``it's a bit lighter.''
then came a series of jolts, starting with a summit meeting in october 1986 between gorbachev and reagan in which the leaders came close to agreeing on the elimination of all ballistic nuclear missiles. this stunned west europeans, who felt the americans had not adequately consulted them on such a proposal, which they strongly opposed
from that point, it was increasingly clear that major reductions in nuclear arms were likely. the first step was taken this past dec. 8 when reagan and gorbachev signed the treaty eliminating land-based intermediate-range nuclear missiles, representing about 4 percent of their arsenals
with the inf treaty, as it is called, expected to win u.s. senate approval within a few months, and the superpowers already agreed in principle to 50 percent cuts in their long-range, or strategic, nuclear arms, nato finds itself facing tough choices about adjusting its military posture
one of the most difficult and immediate choices is whether and how to modernize the u.s.-controlled nuclear weapons that will remain in europe after the american cruise and pershing 2 rockets are withdrawn
the gist of the debate is that most nato governments, including the united states, say this upgrading is vitally important, while most factions in west germany's coalition government strongly oppose it
lord carrington of britain, the nato secretary general, says the alliance must ignore soviet warnings that an upgrading of the nuclear arms would inflame the arms race and violate the spirit of east-west disarmament efforts
if you don't modernize, eventually you don't have any nuclear weapons, which they (the soviets) would like,'' carrington said in an interview
the west germans have clear reasons for disliking the more than 2,000 nato nuclear weapons that are candidates for modernization: most of them, including artillery, bombs and land-based missiles, are in west germany; if fired the likelihood is that many would strike only in east or west germany. while their nation is divided, germans still regard themselves historically as one people
the west german government in bonn wants nato to open negotiations with the soviets on reducing short-range nuclear arms _ those with ranges of less than 500 kilometers (310 miles) and not covered by the u.s.-soviet treaty. the united states, france, britain and other alliance members fear this would play into the hands of gorbachev, who has said repeatedly that his aim is to rid europe of all nuclear weapons
some european analysts worry that it eventually could be the undoing of nato itself
the reopening of the nuclear issue in germany has the potential ultimately to break up the alliance,'' pierre lellouche, deputy director of the institut francais des relations internationales, wrote in a recent newspaper column
from the u.s. viewpoint, improvement of nuclear weapons remaining in europe is directly linked to the question of whether some of the american troops in europe, mostly in west germany, may be pulled out
the reagan administration has said repeatedly that it opposes any troop withdrawals. yet u.s. secretary of defense frank carlucci said recently that if europe lost its short-range nuclear arms _ either through negotiation or obsolesence _ a troop pullout might be considered
america's allies have gotten the message
under whatever administration comes next in the united states, there will be more pressure for reducing the american commitment in europe,'' said de hoop scheffer, the dutch ambassador to nato
said another nato ambassador, speaking privately: ``there is a feeling here that despite the best intentions of the current administration, it's only a matter of time before the u.s. troop levels are reduced.''
manfred woerner, the west german defense minister who is due to succeed carrington as nato's top political officer this summer, was quoted as saying in a recent newspaper interview that he saw ``a certain evolution'' in u.s. thinking that raises some questions about how long the west europeans can count on the united states to keep its troops on the continent
that's why our european role (in nato) must reflect our own interests,'' he said
these are some of the top names in nato:
pierre harmel _ a belgian law professor, premier and cabinet minister, his 1967 report on the alliance's long-term goals remains the basis of nato strategy. it was the harmel report that identified the twin themes of seeking to establish an east-west detente while maintaining strong defenses
gen. dwight d. eisenhower _ the first supreme allied commander europe, serving from december 1950 to may 1952, at rocquencourt, france
lord ismay of britain _ the first secretary general of nato, serving in 1952-57
joseph m. luns of the netherlands _ nato's secretary general for a record 13 years. he was succeeded in 1984 by britain's lord carrington, the current secretary general
gen. bernard w. rogers _ an american, he was the longest-serving nato supreme commander. he retired last summer after holding the job for eight years
manfred woerner _ currently west germany's defense minister, he is scheduled to replace carrington as secretary general this summer. he will be the first west german to hold nato's highest political office
a few months ago, olga osipov had a good income from a prestigious job teaching chinese. now she and her family run a chinese restaurant and they are $25,000 in debt
but they saw it as an opportunity opened up to them by general-secretary mikhail s. gorbachev's economic reforms
perestroika,'' the name given gorbachev's modernization program, has changed the lives of people like mrs. osipov and her family and promises to touch millions more as the drive for a more efficient soviet economy gathers steam
the small chinese restaurant run by mrs. osipov and her family is their own, with each member owning a share and getting a share of the profits. it is officially recognized as a cooperative
the meikhua also is a model of what soviet authorities had in mind when they loosened laws last year to permit cooperatives and individual labor, such as moonlighting, giving soviet citizens an official touch of private enterprise
opened nov. 17, the meikhua cafe is the only known family-run chinese restaurant in the whole of the soviet union, which shares a 3,000-mile border with china
operating a cooperative gets around a major theoretical hurdle, because anyone who does not work for himself or for the state is thought to be exploited by an employer
but the meikhua cafe and other cooperatives face difficulties in offering alternatives to the state-run economy
meals in the cooperatives are more expensive than in the multitude of state-run restaurants. ingredients are hard to come by and consumer resistance is high because cooperatives' prices fluctuate with the market and availability
among the co-ops that have sprung up under the new law are establishments that produce plastic beach shoes and children's jackets sewn from scraps in armenia. others harvest fish, pick wild berries and repair apartments in the siberian city of kurgan
moscow has a cooperative extermination service and a cooperative that refers callers to other cooperatives. about 70 co-op restaurants have opened in moscow, which has a population of nearly 9 million
gorbachev told writers and editors in mid-january that 13,000 co-ops had been established and more than 300,000 people were working for themselves within the narrow confines of new regulations intended to encourage better supply, goods and services that in the state-run economy are notoriously slow and of poor quality
this is not particularly many for a country like ours, but nevertheless a step forward has been made,'' he said
each new venture must be approved, granted a location and outfitted by local authorities and the state-run enterprises against whom the cooperative competes. those who want to start a cooperative or work for themselves often report discouraging bureaucracy and heavy licensing fees
but mrs. osipov, taking a break one recent morning from chopping vegetables and meat in the meikhua's kitchen, said the bureaucrats moved quickly in her case because moscow had no cooperative serving chinese food
that is one indication officials are more interested in providing a little variety than in fostering competition
mrs. osipov's son, volodya, 27, a teacher of english and chinese, was washing floors and cleaning tables on his day off from teaching
i come at 9 o'clock in the morning and don't leave until 11 o'clock at night,'' mrs. osipov said. ``and my son, he's teaching at school from 8 a.m. until 2 p.m. then when he's done at school, he comes here by 3 o'clock.''
we work a lot,'' she said. ``honestly, it's hard.''
main dishes at the meikhua can cost from 2.90 rubles (about $4.75) for a pork and cabbage dish to 8 rubles ($13.25) for braised sea slugs, a specialty. the sea slugs must be marinated for several days and take several hours to prepare, mrs. osipov said
a five-ounce serving of rice costs 30 kopeks (50 cents). a few more kopeks brings a pot of jasmine tea
service at the restaurant's nine tables was quick and friendly, and everything on the menu was available. at state-run restaurants, it often is easier to ask the waiter which of the dishes on the menu actually are available, and service is notoriously slow
mrs. osipov was born in northeast china of a russian mother and chinese father. she and her husband cook home-style food from her native region
volodya, and another son, a daughter and son-in-law do everthing else. all but the 49-year-old mrs. osipov kept their old jobs or remained at their studies
the family would like to hire an extra cook and keep the cafe open longer than five hours a day, six days a week. but their intent to keep it essentially a family-run business fits well within the limited scope of the law
asked if he would prefer to teach or run the cafe, volodya said: ``i would like, if it was possible, to be more creative as a teacher, to work there. but it has been very interesting here so far. to create something is always interesting. here it's possible to govern yourself fully.''
the family needed 15,000 rubles ($25,000) to get started, and friends advanced some of the money to help them turn a former two-family apartment building into a restaurant. a bank lent more money at 3 percent interest, and government organization provided the kitchen equipment and furniture
the cafe's income is about 500 rubles (about $825) a night, roughly half of which goes for food, heat and electricity. family members are paid about 250 rubles ($413) each a month, some 50 rubles ($82.50) more than the typical soviet factory worker
because prices in cooperative restaurants are higher than in state-run restaurants, some soviets grumble that the cooperatives are too expensive for the average citizen
in a recent article, the communist party newspaper pravda printed several letters from readers complaining about prices at cooperatives
one letter writer, i. cherkashin of moscow, said cooperatives had not forced prices down by providing more competition but had driven them up
who is it that makes the laws on prices _ the market, cooperatives, or the government?'' he asked
cooperatives get the bulk of their food from farmers markets, where prices are unregulated and run substantially higher than state markets and stores. supply, while still uncertain, is usually better in the farmers markets, particularly for fresh fruits and vegetables rarely found in moscow during the long winter
we'd like to have a constant supply ... so we don't have to depend on the market,'' volodya said. ``if they are selling meat one day for seven rubles a kilogram and the next day for 12 rubles, our prices jump.''
to get the spices she needs for chinese cuisine, mrs. osipov travels occasionally to kirghizia, a republic of soviet central asia bordering china. but some spices, she said, cost a ruble ($1.65) a spoonful, adding more to the prices on her menu
if an award is given for silliest movie of the year, ``a tiger's tale'' is likely to have few serious competitors. it's not offensive, not insulting _ just plain silly
and it's too bad because a lot of the ingredients in this romantic comedy had potential for something better. ingredient no. 1 is ann-margret, an actress with so much skill and innate dignity that she almost saves the film. but not quite
she is cast as rose butts, the divorced mother of a wild teen-age daughter in a nondescript texas town. rose works as a nurse by day but spends her nights nursing lonely drunks
into her bored, sad life comes her daughter's castoff teen-age boyfriend, bubber, who becomes smitten with the mother and won't take no for an answer
thus begins an unlikely may-december romance between the naive 19-year-old boy and the middle-aged mom. but once the two begin to cuddle, no one seems to know what to do next, least of all scriptwriter peter douglas, who also directs
he diverts our attention to a few subplots. there's bubber's dilemma over whether to give up his pet tiger, valentino (the most enchanting performer in this flick). and there's bubber's widowed father's dilemma over whether to marry again. the father, a retired veterinarian who keeps snakes around the house, is portrayed by charles durning, another gifted actor whose efforts are wasted here
finally, a crisis is created to bring rose and bubber back in focus. it turns out that her daughter, shirley, enraged by mom's unconventional affair, has had her revenge. when she left to live with her father, she poked a hole in rose's birth control device. can you guess the result?
the rest of the plot is so preposterous you have to laugh
it should be mentioned that a major flaw from the outset is the lack of even the smallest spark of chemistry between ann-margret and her teen-aged lover, c. thomas howell, a gangly, wholesome kid with a texas accent who would seem more likely to fall in love with a horse
a tiger's tale'' is rated r for sexual subject matter
motion picture association of america rating definitions:
g _ general audiences. all ages admitted
pg _ parental guidance suggested. some material may not be suitable for children
pg-13 _ special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. some material may be inappropriate for young children
r _ restricted. under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian
x _ no one under 17 admitted. some states may have higher age restrictions
hollywood has never been able to get a fix on tony bill, and that seems to be just the way he likes it
he graduates from the university of notre dame in 1963 and steps into a star-making role as frank sinatra's brother in ``come blow your horn.'' just as his acting career is rolling, he turns filmmaker and co-produces ``the sting,'' which won an academy award as best picture of 1973
next he becomes a director, specializing in such unpretentious films as ``my bodyguard.'' he even established his own little studio, not in the mainstream but in the ragtag beachfront subur   bill has directed a new film, ``five corners,'' an off-beat comedy-drama about life in the bronx in the 1960b of venice. s. the only recognizable name in the cast is jody foster. it is the first screenplay written by john patrick shanley, who has received an oscar nomination for the script of ``moonstruck.''
i'm a nut for originality,'' bill said in an interview. ``i like original screenplays _ ones that are not from books or plays or short stories. i like scripts that are not like another movie i've seen. they are special, unique, personal, human. they're not about cars or robots f in ``five corners''?
i always said i'd never cast myself in one of my own pictures. i have fun now and then acting in other people's productions. i can always think of somebody better than myself when it comes to casting something.''
as an independent filmmaker, bill has experienced many rough periods _ ``lots of them, and there will be many more. lots of debts. lots of risks. lots of bets that i've lost, as well as bets i've won
it's the life of a professional gambler; that's what filmmakers are,'' he said. ``you put your money where your mouth is. you try to play the hand as well as it can be played. you think you've made a good movie, and it's a disaster. you think you've bet on a longshot, and it's a winner. it's the life of a poker player.''
concert pianist eugene istomin has loaded his steinway on a van and is driving from town to town for his 1988 tour _ an unusual way for classical musicians to hit the road
it hasn't been done this way for 50 years at least,'' istomin says. ``paderewski (the polish pianist and composer who died in 1941) had a private railroad car
there are a lot of places on my tour where so-called `big name' artists don't go. the seating capacity of halls is small and people can't afford to pay very high fees.'' istomin is accepting what he terms ``reasonable'' fees
i'm playing in a lot of communities which would otherwise not hear me, on a magnificently prepared, superb piano, playing a good program. it's giving me a lot of gratification.''
from january through may, his solo piano recitals are east of chicago. the western tour will start in september in texas
istomin, whose wife, marta, is artistic director of the kennedy center for performing arts in washington, is always on the move. last fall, he played a recital in brussels, ate a sandwich in his hotelroom at midnight, arose at 5 a.m. to fly to paris where he boarded the concorde to new york. he was met at kennedy airport, handed a tuxedo, taken to rehearsals for the grammy lifetime achievement award show and played that night on the televised show to honor isaac stern
you can not perform to your maximum ability, doing it this way, and i didn't,'' he said. ``it's the wrong way to do things.''
his intention now is to perform by making short hops from town to town for a few years or more
this tour is the right way to do things,'' he said. ``when you play, it doesn't have to be only for the fancy swells and sophisticates. the same kind of people, who read the same kind of books and listen to the same kind of music, live in smaller towns.''
the tour began at a college in winter park, fla., with the second concert at a senior citizens center outside miami
istomin has two programs. program a includes bach, schubert, beethoven, debussy and chopin. he has recorded program b for ada, a french company that releases compact discs. he calls it ``a bit more esoteric. schumann's `first sonata' isn't often played. it was written to murder the hands of pianists. it's terribly difficult and beautifully inspired, not the kind of piece you normally take on a barnstorming tour.''
he also will play debussy and some infrequently heard rachmaninoff on program b. ``that's what my pianos really serve for,'' istomin said. ``these pieces require a sophisticated brand of piano playing i can offer with these instruments.''
istomin has been thinking about a tour such as the one he's doing for years. ``i started playing at 17. i played 200 concerts in my first two seasons. i was soloist with the busch chamber orchestra, paid $250 a week by columbia artists management.''
his first of more than 40 recordings was bach's ``d minor piano concerto'' with the busch players in 1945
i played concerts with umbrellas stuck under the sounding board and keys that wouldn't go down,'' he said. ``i would complain. people would say, `he's a nasty young man.' the good part of it was that some very high-level music-making was done. i was part of it. i know we had a lot of success and people enjoyed the concerts.''
he'll probably give 100 concerts this year, too. ``i had the stamina half a century ago. i hope i have it now,'' the artist said. ``i'm 62. i feel like i'm 26 and hysterical. i think i never grew up
the concerts are strenuous but the traveling is easier these days.'' cities are not more than 300 miles apart; istomin and the piano technician drive by car, and luggage oes in the van with the piano
i like playing in unpretentious circumstances,'' he said. ``pretention is not the same as excellence. i think the public, wherever the town, is people who react to and feel what is happening. to me, that's the whole meaning of this trip
i'm not warming up for a program in some big hall. i've already played these pieces in new york and london. i want to play in winter park, fla., the way i play in carnegie hall
sometimes people ask me to sign a program they've saved 35 years. those people touch me. i want to do something really nice for those people, for whom music really matters.''
istomin played at a general motors cancer research award dinner in washington in 1981
they sent me a check for $7,000, my regular fee. i sent it back, donating it to sloan kettering institute for cancer research. they were touched by that and said to let them know if there was ever anything they could do for me. when i started thinking about this tour, i thought maybe they would help me.''
gm designed a van, with a hydraulic lift and temperature control, to carry istomin's piano and is lending it to him free. the tour itself doesn't have corporate sponsorship. transmitted jan. 11 under a washington dateline as part of the special edition on ``taxes and your money,'' are asked to used the following:</head>
the associated press, as part of the ``taxes and your money'' special edition, misstated the formula for determining what portion of social security benefits is taxable. the starting point for the calculation is total income subject to tax plus half the social security benefits
