the national association of realtors said that sales of existing single-family homes and condominiums totaled 3.885 million units last year, down a slight 0.3 percent from the 1986 level of 3.897 million units. sales in both years were the fastest pace of this decade
meanwhile, the average price of an existing home rose to a nationwide median of $84,900, an increase of 5.1 percent in 1987, slightly ahead of the rise in consumer prices, the association said
when the tip of a screwdriver needs squaring, clamp it in a vise. file so that the tool does not rock, otherwise you will not get a straight blade tip. always file away from yourself
if it becomes necessary to loosen a window that won't budge, don't use a screwdriver blade between the window and the frame. instead, hold a putty knife as flat as you can get it and tap the handle gently with a light hammer. the screwdriver may work all right, but it will leave gouges in the wood
lacquer thinner is the solvent for lacquer, denatured alcohol for shellac, and turpentine or mineral spirits for oil-based finishes. despite this general rule, read the instructions on the label to determine what the solvent is for the particular product
when you use a wrench or pliers on a kitchen fixture, put adhesive tape or something similar on the nut to keep it from getting chewed up
always buy a hand tool by picking it up and going through the motions of using it. the ``feel'' of the tool is important. if it doesn't seem right, it will be even more uncomfortable when put into actual use
a cheap tool remains a cheap tool through its lifetime. buying the least expensive tool you can find is usually poor economy. not only won't it last as long as the good one, it will never give you a fine performance, even at the start
accidents occur on extension ladders because people insist on overreaching, mostly so they don't have to move the ladder so much. don't be a casualty of that sort of thinking. get down and move the ladder as often as necessary to keep you from stretching
never strike anything with the side or cheek of a hammer
tinner's snips are used for cutting light sheet metal. larger snips for cutting heavier metal are referred to as shears. when snips are used for cutting hardened metal _ rather than soft _ the cutting edges will be damaged
early american indians quarried natural sharpening stones for use on the tips of spears and arrows
a pushbroom is excellent for spreading blacktop sealer on a driveway
in a poll conducted at the 1988 national association of home builders convention in dallas, performance and durability were ranked as the most important qualities to seek in the purchase of power tools
ease of use ranked third, followed by warranties, price and available accessories. when builders were asked to name the first three types of power tools do-it-yourselfers should buy, they chose the circular saw, power drills and miter saw. after that, in order, came the radial arm saw, belt sander, pad sander, router and planer
the poll was conducted by ryobi american corp., bensenville, ill
talks between pan am corp. and the 4,500-member union representing reservation clerks broke off. the teamsters union vowed to disrupt operations through ``guerrilla warfare'' but put off any strike
pan am officials said sunday that airline service would continue without interruption even if there eventually is a walkout, and threatened to discipline any workers disrupting service
but the federal mediator involved in the negotiations said he was optimistic the two sides would return to the bargaining table
a wall street speculator has been charged with weapons possession and witness intimidation after authorities alleged he plotted an attack on convicted financier ivan f. boesky
the arrest of john a. mulheren, once a close associated of boesky, marked the first public indication of potential violence in the insider trading scandal
mulheren, a general partner in the firm jamie securities co., was arrested in possession of an israeli-made semi-automatic rifle. he was ordered held in lieu of $17,500 after a hearing friday
polaroid corp. said it has asked a federal court for $5.7 billion in damages from the eastman kodak co., which was found in 1985 to have infringed on polaroid patents in the instant photography market
the request made friday marks the latest development in a 12-year-old case that forced kodak out of its $200 million-a-year instant photography business. a hearing is set for march 18 but a trial date has not yet been set
wall street sent texaco inc.'s stock smartly higher following word that t. boone pickens was seeking permission to buy at least 15 percent of the beleaguered oil giant, a stake similar to that already held by fellow corporate raider carl c. icahn
texaco, which has been reorganizing itself as it prepares to emerge from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, has been fighting efforts by icahn _ its largest shareholder _ to strip the company of its anti-takeover defenses
company officials have feared that icahn or another raider would try to take the company over and sell its assets to boost the value of their stock. texaco stock closed friday at $42.62{ per share, up $1.87{
gillette co. said it would resist coniston partners' attempt to place four representatives on its board of directors, setting the stage for a battle that analysts say could end gillette's lengthy fight to remain independent
coniston, which controls a roughly 6 percent stake in the consumer products maker, stated in a securities and exchange commission filing friday that it intended to nominate four candidates for the board seats up for election at gillette's annual meeting in april.   
the national broadcasting co. said it had tentatively agreed to sell five radio stations to emmis broadcasting corp., a privately-held concern based in indianapolis, for $121.5 million
nbc had previously disclosed it was looking for buyers for its seven radio stations, and reaffirmed friday that it hoped to sell the remaining stations
the stations which would be sold to emmis broadcasting are wnbc-am and wyny-fm in new york, wjib-fm in boston, wkqx-fm in chicago and kyuu-fm in san francisco
president reagan defended his tax and budget policies in an election-year economic report to congress, saying his administration had turned economic despair into hope
reagan's seventh annual economic report issued friday headed off accusations by democratic presidential candidates that a $2.4 trillion national debt and record trade imbalances during the reagan years had hobbled the country and eventually would reduce americans' standard of living
a federal appeals court has stayed a lower court decision that would have cleared the way for a merger creating the nation's largest glass container company
the u.s. court of appeals said friday the stay, which keeps the proposed merger between owens-illinois inc. and brockway inc. on hold, remains in effect until further notice
the merger would make the combined company the largest manufacturer of glass containers in the industry
california regulators are seeking superior court approval to liquidate troubled tmic insurance co., which has been operating under state conservatorship for two years
the problems of tmic, formerly known as ticor mortgage insurance co., stem from the $1.4 billion default of equity programs investment corp., or epic, a virginia-based land syndicator that had acquired 20,000 properties for tax-shelters partnerships
a spokeswoman for california's insurance commissioner said friday the state still hopes an alternative to liquidation can be worked out before an april 6 court hearing
the balance of power in the banking industry has shifted dramatically since the october stock market crash, leaving many of the nation's largest institutions vulnerable to takeovers, a study said
the report released friday by mac group, a cambridge-based financial research firm, rated 19 of the 50 largest u.s. banking institutions as susceptible to takeovers as of the end of last year, compared with just four by sept. 30
ford motor co. workers learned their stake of the automaker's $4.6 billion 1987 profits will average more than $3,700 each when profit-sharing checks are handed out next month
ford officials announced friday that a record $635 million in profit-sharing will be distributed to hourly and salaried workers march 8
in 1987, ford outearned industry-leader general motors corp. for the second consecutive year. while ford workers reap the benefits, gm workers will receive no share of profits for the second straight year
the stock market jumped ahead friday on a late outburst of buying
the dow jones average of 30 industrials climbed 28.18 points to 2,014.59, its highest close since it stood at 2,051.89 on jan. 7. for the past week the average showed a net gain of 31.33
bond prices barely budged. the dollar turned in a mixed performance in foreign exchange, and gold prices rose
in other markets, coffee futures for near-term delivery surged above $1.40 a pound friday for the first time since december 1986. cattle futures advanced sharply, while grains and soybeans, precious metals, energy futures and stock-index futures all moved higher
about 6,000 employees began a strike monday over a pay dispute at land-rover, the first walkout against the state-owned automaker in about six years
it was also the second job action against the british automaking industry this month. production was resuming monday at ford motor co. following a two-week stoppage
about 1,000 workers set up picket lines at the gates of the state-owned land-rover plant at solihull, just outside birmingham in the british midlands
huge traffic jams, some more then a mile long, nearly blocked roads leading to the plant as the pickets stopped supervisors and office workers in their cars and urged them not to cross the picket line
the strike over a pay dispute was the first at the company since november 1981, said a land-rover spokeswoman, speaking anonymously in keeping with british custom
she said the strike would mean the loss of 200 land-rover and range rover vehicles a day, with a retail value of about 3 million pounds, or about $5.25 million
land-rover is a division of rover group, the vehicle manufacturer which the government plans to sell to the private sector. it is separate from the rover group's carmaking division, austin rover
south africa's inflation rate, as measured by consumer prices, slipped to 14.2 percent in january from 14.7 percent in the previous month, the central statistical services said monday
the government attriubted the improvement to a substantial decline in food prices
hyundai motor co. said monday it would continue to sell its cars in canada despite a canadian ruling that the south korean automaker was ``dumping'' its product
hyundai officials also said the automaker will complete an assembly plant, now under construction in bremont, quebec, by early next year as scheduled
they said the plant is to assemble 50,000 cars initially and have a maximum output of 100,000 cars
the department of national revenue of canada last week upheld its earlier ruling that hyundai cars were being ``dumped,'' or sold for less in canada than in south korea
the canadian authorities acted on complaints by the candian subsidiaries of general motors corp.and ford motor co
hyundai officials said they were optimistic that the canada import tribunal would rule in favor of hyundai in reviewing the anti-dumping case by march 20
hyundai officials said hyundai has stopped shipping stellar and pony models to canada and now ships only excel
hyundai marketed 32,985 cars in canada, including 21,118 excels
japanese automakers produced fewer cars, trucks and buses in january over the same period a year ago, the japan automobile manufacturers' association said monday
the group said output totaled 918,348 vehicles, down 2 percent from 1987
last month's decline followed 1.9 percent growth in december, and breaks a string of five consecutive year-on-year rises
a spokesman for the organization said the effects of declining car exports outweighed continued growth in domestic sales
prime minister noboru takeshita said monday that japan won't comply with foreign demands calling for liberalization of rice imports
it was the first time takeshita publicly declared his opposition to lifting a ban on importing foreign rice since becoming prime minister last november
it is natural for us to uphold the objectives of'' a diet resolution calling for improvements in self-sufficiency in food, including rice, takeshita said during a session of the lower house budget committee
both houses of japan's diet unanimously adopted a resolution against the lifting of a rice import ban in 1980 and 1984
the japanese government purchases almost all rice produced by farmers at several times higher than an international price and then sells it to consumers, through retail shops, for somewhat lower prices
the nation's ban on rice imports has become an issue between japan and the united states, which says japan has an obligation to place its rice program on the negotiating table
japan had a trade surplus of $59.8 billion last year with the united states
japanese farmers, agricultural organizations and some government officials argue that opening up the country's rice market would not only harm farmers but endanger japan's food security
korean air said monday that smoking will be banned on all domestic flights beginning next month
airline officials said the ban is in line with a worldwide anti-smoking trend on short-range flights of less than two hours. all of the carrier's domestic flights last less than one hour
the action would not affect korean air's international flights
