on friday the dow jones industrial average jumped 28.18 points to a six-week high of 2,014.59
advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 on the nyse, with 999 up, 479 down and 469 unchanged. big board volume totaled 180.30 million shares, against 151.43 million in the previous session. a version moving on general news wires.</note>
senate agriculture committee chairman patrick j. leahy is set to raise the curtain on hearings into the problem of hunger plaguing the nation's homeless and families living in poverty
i know that the budget pressures will remain with us all this year and for the foreseeable future,'' the vermont democrat says. ``but america's future depends on its children. the wealthiest, most powerful nation in the world must once again resolve to eliminate hunger in america.''
the hearings, set to begin march 1, will come as the government prepares to suspend distribution of milk, cheese, rice and honey to low-income households under the temporary emergency food assistance program, or tefap, because stocks are depleted
leahy says a report will be released this week dealing specifically with the rural poor and that he intends to follow up with hearings on the overall extent of hunger in america
tefap is best known as the program under which poor people were able to go to community action centers and other designated places in their neighborhoods to receive free allotments of powered milk and cheese
it came into being in 1981 as the reagan administration wrestled with enormous surpluses of agricultural commodities and the massive storage costs they entailed. those huge surpluses have now been diminished considerably by price changes under the 1985 farm law that have discouraged excess production
the agriculture department announced feb. 12 that dwindling stocks will prevent tefap distributions of milk and cheese in may. rice and honey stocks will be depleted by march distributions, usda said. it said flour, cornmeal and butter distributions will continue as before
cheese, nonfat dry milk, rice and honey distributions will be suspended when we have given it all away,'' said john w. bode, assistant secretary of agriculture for food and consumer services. ``when we get more, we will distribute it.''
the department said that one in every seven americans receives federal food assistance at some point each year at a taxpayer cost of more than $56 million a day. it said surplus foods amounting to 5 billion pounds worth more than $5 billion have been distributed under tefap since 1981
according to figures compiled by the senate agriculture committee, more than 15 million people have supplemented benefits they already receive from the food stamp program with tefab commodities
but the panel says the 18 million people who were taking part in the food stamp program as of september represented no more than 60 percent of those living in poverty
leahy said he went to new york last week ``to survey for myself the extent of hunger in our nation's richest city.''
as a senator, i have seen poverty in the third world that was worse than any i have seen in the united states,'' leahy said in a floor speech reporting on his trip. ``but the sense of hopelessness that i encountered in the south bronx was as deep as any that i have encountered in south america.''
he said many families told him they ``cannot buy enough food _ even with food stamps _ to feed their children.'' he quoted christina walker, operator of a food stamp hotline, as saying her organization receives thousands of calls from households that run out of food stamps
that they run out is not surprising,'' he said. ``the average food stamp benefit is around 50 cents, per person, per meal _ the maximum benefit is 81 cents per meal
think about what 81 cents worth of groceries would look like _ not much. what would happen if you spilled a carton of milk _ or dropped a carton of eggs?''
some individuals living in poverty are unable to obtain food stamps because they have no address, he said
he also recounted the experience of a south bronx mother of six whom he identified as gladys who was having difficulty in storing perishables because her refrigerator was broken. he said she tried to keep milk and eggs cold by placing them next to the window but lived in fear that rats would get at them
