first republicbank corp. ran full-page advertisements in local newspapers today reiterating that it was not involved in merger negotiations and blaming seasonal and anticipated factors for its shrinking deposits
the advertisements seek to reassure depositors of texas' largest bank holding company, which has been plagued by huge losses stemming from its portfolio of troubled loans
during the past few days, there have been several articles and news stories about the current state of our bank,'' the ad stated. ``many of the items reported in these articles have been misleading and some just plain wrong. consequently, we feel it necessary to respond to these reports.''
since first republicbank reported a $656.8 million loss on jan. 19, there have been questions about its ability to weather anticipated losses from its $3.9 billion portfolio of troubled loans
speculation in the financial markets last week sent first republicbank's common and preferred shares tumbling and helped disrupt its system for raising deposits
on sunday, first republicbank chairman gerald w. fronterhouse issued a statement denying the reports. the company ``is not involved in merger or acquisition discussions with anyone. also, we are not aware that the federal deposit insurance corp. is negotiating with any other parties regarding our company.''
he said the fdic had assured first republicbank ``that its policy is to advise the institution before engaging in such negotiations.''
the advertisement addresses three points: merger rumors, deposit safety and deposit activity
there have been several misleading newspaper stories concerning our bank's recent deposit activity,'' the advertisement stated
through mid-february, the corporation's average total deposits have only declined by approximately 4{ percent this year. more than half of the reduction was an expected decline in foreign deposits, with the balance due primarily to normal seasonal factors.''
the bank represents only one-third of the corporation's total deposits, fronterhouse said
the letter encouraged first republicbank customers to call if they had further questions
the chairman of allegheny international inc. says the company will be stronger after it emerges from bankruptcy reorganization because of the strength of its consumer products business
oliver s. travers said two of allegheny international's subsidiaries, sunbeam corp. and almet-lawnlike inc., are profitable and would not have had to file for reorganization were it not for the parent company's complex financial situation
he said that including almet-lawnlike, sunbeam's net worth, or assets minus liabilities, is about $400 million
sunbeam is very healthy, as evidenced by its excellent results for the first four months of this fiscal year and by its strong backlog of orders,'' said travers, chairman since 1986
the pittsburgh-based holding company and some of its subsidiaries, filed saturday in u.s. bankruptcy court for protection from its creditors while it reorganizes. also included in the filing are sunbeam holdings inc. and chemetron corp
greg drahuschak, analyst for butcher &amp; singer, said the filing announcement was ``no horrendous surprise.''
it's probably the best operating move they had, given their credit situation and the need they had for operating capital,'' he said. ``this gets the banks off their backs for a while. unfortunately, the sacrificial lamb in this process is the common shareholder.''
allegheny international said it has lined up fresh financing of $175 million from two major new york banks, travers said. the credit line provides enough cash to run the companies during the reorganization, he said
chapter 11 provides the means to implement corporate restructuring and continue the company's profitable turnaround,'' travers said
the bankruptcy court petition was a key to getting the additional money, said chief operating officer thomas albani
while negotiations with the two banks occurred before the filing, the financing was made afterward. legally, that puts the lenders in a ``superpriority'' position ahead of other creditors, albani said
the total liabilities of the company and its subsidiaries, which include such items as payroll and accounts payable as well as bank debt, are about $845 million. its tangible assets are about $735 million
total debt alone for the parent company and its subsidiaries amounts to $525 million, of which $175 million is in short-term bank loans and $350 million is in various long-term commitments
allegheny international lost about $200 million from 1985 to 1987, largely due to debt incurred through a spree of acquisitions in prior years as well as heavy losses in real estate, gas and oil and credit operations
under a new management team since robert buckley resigned under pressure in 1986, the company has shed 19 subsidiaries and severely cut its corporate overhead
the efforts bore fruit in the first quarter of fiscal 1988, which ended dec. 31, 1987, when the company posted a profit of $7.25 million _ its first in two years
profits from consumer products amounted to $31.5 million in the quarter, compared with $19.2 million for the same period in 1986
the filing does not affect sunbeam corp.'s consumer products operations in canada, mexico, venezuela and peru, according to the company. it also does not affect industrial and high technology companies that allegheny international is in the process of divesting
allegheny international, prior to 1981, was known as allegheny ludlum industries. the company acquired sunbeam corp. that year for $534 million
consumer products manufactured by sunbeam includes small household appliances, electric blankets and barbeque grills. almet-lawnlite manufactures lawn and patio furniture
grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher today on the chicago board of trade
long-range bullish attitudes prevailed in the grain and soybean pits, and little selling pressure surfaced this morning after last friday's steep sell-off just before the close
everybody that needed to get out got out on friday,'' said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc. ``now they're all gunning again, coming back for more.''
supportive fundamentals included relatively light farmer selling of grains over the weekend and dry weather in the soybean-growing region of southern brazil, lespinasse said
in early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.22{ a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 1} cents higher with march at $2.01 a bushel; oats were } cent lower to \ cent higher with march at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 3{ cents higher with march at $6.34 a bushel
livestock and meat futures mostly were higher in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle were unchanged to .42 cent higher with april at 73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .30 cent higher with march at 83.35 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .43 cent higher with april at 44.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .18 cent to .58 cent higher with february at 53.85 cents a pound
all livestock futures settled higher on friday while frozen pork bellies ended lower
the commodity futures trading commission has notified 22 traders at the chicago board of trade that the cftc staff will recommend civil charges of prearranged and fraudulent trading against them, according to a published report
but some of the traders involved say the trading technique in question is practiced daily on many commodity exchanges and is not prohibited by the exchanges' rules, the wall street journal reported in today's editions
officials at the cftc, the federal agency that regulates futures exchanges, would neither confirm nor deny the report
the only enforcement action the commission will comment on is a publicly filed complaint,'' said kate hathaway, a cftc spokeswoman
the case, reportedly involving trading at the world's biggest market for u.s. treasury bond futures, may be one of the largest single instances of alleged futures trading violations
the journal said the allegations concerned certain trades made in the board of trade's huge treasury bond futures pit in mid-1986. the traders maintained that the type of trading being investigated _ loosely known as a ``ginzie'' trade, where a customer gets two different prices for portions of the same buy or sell order _ is widespread on futures exchanges, the newspaper said
the cftc notifications are part of a procedure designed to give potential defendants a chance to argue to the commission that it should not follow its staff's recommendations
the traders received the notices last wednesday and thrusday and were given two weeks to respond with the written arguments to the cftc, the journal reported
the number of oil and gas rigs working in the united states rose by 10 this week to total 978, baker hughes inc. announced monday
this week's total reflects the number of rigs working as of last friday. a year ago the count was 839, baker hughes stated
the previous week, the rig count had dropped by 18 to total 968. the rig count usually declines during the first few months of the year
houston-based baker hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number of rigs actively exploring for oil, and not rigs producing oil. the rig count is the most widely-watched industry index of drilling activity
hughes tool co., which merged this year with baker international corp. of orange, calif., has kept track of the number of working rigs since 1940
in december 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the count reached a peak with 4,500 active rigs. but in the summer of 1986, the rig count fell to 663 _ the lowest since hughes began compiling figures _ as oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel
among the major oil producing states, texas gained 12 rigs this week, followed by kansas, 10; wyoming, three; north dakota, two; and colorado, one
new mexico posted the largest decrease, losing five. ohio and oklahoma lost two each; louisiana and michigan lost one each
foodmaker inc., the operator and franchiser of jack in the box restaurants, will acquire chi-chi's inc., a 200-unit mexican restaurant chain, in a leveraged buyout for about $230 million, the companies announced monday
under the agreement, which has been approved by the boards of both companies, foodmaker will acquire chi-chi's in a $10.15 a share tender offer. the sale was expected to be completed about april 1
we believe it will be an excellent vehicle, along with the jack in the box chain, for growth acceleration and to build stockholder value,'' said jack w. goodall jr., chairman and president of foodmakers
san diego-based foodmaker will finance the acquisition with short-term loans from a group of banks led by wells fargo bank na, goodall said, but foodmaker was confident chi-chi's cash flow would be sufficient to fund the purchase
he also said chi-chi's headquarters would remain in louisville with its current management
we think this transaction, which is not conditioned upon obtaining financing, is in the best interest of our stockholders, and we are pleased that foodmaker intends to continue the growth of chi-chi's and maintain our headquarters in louisville,'' said hal smith, chairman and chief executive of chi-chi's
chi-chi's operates and franchises full-service mexican restuarants. for the six months ended oct. 31, chi-chi's had net income of $6.7 million on revenue of $144.5 million
foodmaker inc., operates and franchises more than 900 jack in the box fast-food restaurants located mainly in the western and southwestern united states
foodmaker had net earnings of $13.9 million in 1987 on revenue of $598 million
