volume on the big board came to 109.87 million shares with two hours to go
the u.s. dollar fell monday against all major currencies except the canadian dollar in listless european trading
gold prices rose in europe after slipping in hong kong
dealers attributed the dollar's slide mainly to uncertainty over the state of the u.s. economy
while recent reports that the u.s. trade deficit had narrowed had supported the dollar, dealers said there were no new incentives to keep it from falling
in london, the british pound rose to $1.7630 from $1.7505 late friday
in tokyo, the dollar fell to close at 129.95 japanese yen from 130.53 yen on friday. in later trading in london, the dollar slipped to 129.27 yen
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late rates friday, included: 1.6955 west german marks, down from 1.7075; 1.3930 swiss francs, down from 1.3985; 5.7500 french francs, down from 5.7675; 1.9040 dutch guilders, down from 1.9150; 1,252.25 italian lire, down from 1,257.75, and 1.2738 canadian dollars, up from 1.2702
gold prices rose in thin trading in europe in response to the dollar's weakness, bullion dealers said
in london, the metal rose to $446 a troy ounce from $442.90 late friday. in zurich, gold rose to $446.50 from $443 late friday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell to $447.12 an ounce from $447.51 saturday
silver bullion rose in london to $6.41 a troy ounce from $6.37 late friday
for the first time, drexel burnham lambert inc. has acknowledged publicly that the staff of the securities and exchange commission has recommended that drexel and some of its employees face civil charges
the investment firm also confirmed it has been under investigation by a federal grand jury
the information is contained in a preliminary prospectus for new america high income fund inc., a new high-yield ``junk bond'' fund being drexel is underwriting. such information routinely is required in prospectuses to warn would-be investors of potential risk
the document describing the fund was dated feb. 16 and mailed to investors last week
it stated drexel had advised the fund about the sec staff recomendations for civil actions against the firm and against some employees ``relating to transactions, some of which may have involved `high yield' bonds.''
no assurance can be given that the results of any such sec action or grand jury investigation will not have an adverse effect on drexel burnham lambert inc. and-or the market for `high yield' bonds, a market in which drexel burnham lambert inc. is an important participant,'' the prospectus said
despite the caveat, sales of the fund apparently were unaffected on friday, its first trading day, when it closed unchanged at $10 per share
steven s. anreder, drexel's chief spokesman, on monday declined to comment outside of the information contained in the prospectus
in january, drexel and several ranking employees _ including junk-bond chief michael milken _ reportedly were informed that the sec staff had decided to recommend charges of violations of security laws
on jan. 27, the wall street journal said the focus of the sec's investigation of drexel involved possible violations of securities laws in corporate takeover situations, particularly ``stock parking'' _ the hiding of true ownership of stock in someone else's name. the practice can be used to evade sec reporting requirements
drexel and the employees have lodged their opposition to the decision with the sec, but the federal agency had not decided whether to proceed, according to the prospectus
the firm previously has acknowledged that an investigation was under way, but it has maintained that no wrongdoing took place
the prospectus says drexel has furnished documents to a federal grand jury in new york, and some employees have appeared before the panel
drexel reportedly has been the object of government scrutiny since the breaking of the scandal surrounding former arbitrager ivan f. boesky, because of the firm's extensive involvement in financing of corporate takeovers involved in the scandal
grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower monday after a late sell-off on the chicago board of trade
a mixed opening was followed by firmer prices across the board, but the gains did not hold up
the decline near the session's end was led by commission-house selling of soybeans and soybean oil, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
the beans and oil were the two markets that really collapsed, and that collapse pulled everything else down,'' he said
soybean traders closely are watching the large brazilian soybean crop, which is nearly ready to harvest, lespinasse said. weather conditions in brazil will have an increasing impact on u.s. soybean futures as the harvest gets under way
at the close, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.22{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with march at $1.99{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower with march at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with march at $6.27 a bushel
monsanto co., a pioneer in the development of synthetic turf for sports fields, said monday that it had sold its astroturf industries inc. subsidiary to a west german company
terms of the sale to balsam sportstattenbau gmbh &amp; co., k.g., of steinhagen, west germany, were not disclosed. astroturf industries will become a wholly-owned subsidiary of balsam and will remain based in dalton, ga., a company spokesman said
monsanto installed the world's first commercially-produced synthetic turf playing surface in the astrodome in houston in 1966. since then, astroturf surfaces have been installed in hundreds of sports stadiums and athletic fields around the world
balsam has offered jobs to ``essentially all'' of the businesses' 100 employees and will keep its management team intact, monsanto group vice president earl n. brasfield said
balsam is the multinational market leader and manufacturer of sports and recreational surfaces, and has been serving as monsanto's european and asia-pacific distributor for astroturf recreational surfaces. it also has other u.s.-based subsidiaries that market and install indoor and outdoor sports floor systems
the agreement gives balsam the rights to the astroturf trademark, but monsanto will continue using the trademark in its doormat business
monsanto spokesman dan bishop said the buyer asked that the annual sales figure for astroturf not be released
but he said astroturf sales amounted to less than one-half of one percent of monsanto's annual sales. monsanto had sales of $7.64 billion in 1987
bishop said the sale was made because astroturf ``was not part of our new strategy.'' the company's primary business is in fibers, plants, resins and specialty chemicals
stock prices pushed ahead today as traders awaited new signs of the outlook for the economy and interest rates
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 13.92 to 2,028.51 by 3 p.m. on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by more than 3 to 2 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 918 up, 572 down and 474 unchanged
analysts said traders were looking ahead to congressional testimony tuesday by alan greenspan, chairman of the federal reserve board
several statistical reports are also due this week on such subjects as durable goods orders, the consumer price index and personal income and consumption
of special interest to wall streeters is the commerce department's revised figure for the gross national product in the fourth quarter of last year, scheduled to be issued thursday
the department earlier estimated gnp growth, after adjustment for inflation, at a 4.2 percent annual rate in the october-december period. many analysts believe the new figure will be higher
economists at smith barney, harris upham &amp; co., for example, say it is possible that the report will show growth of 5.5 percent or more
polaroid rose 2\ to 29} and eastman kodak dropped 1| to 40|. late friday it was disclosed that polaroid was seeking to recover as much as $5.7 billion from kodak in connection with violations of instant-photography patents
among other actively traded blue chips, international business machines gained 1{ to 114~; exxon \ to 43, and general electric 1[ to 44]
allegheny international dropped { to 2~ for a loss of 14.8 percent. over the weekend the company filed for protection under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained .92 to 147.88. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .97 at 281.13
volume on the big board came to 131.66 million shares with an hour to go
the supreme court on monday upheld a ruling that sharply curtails the power of communities to regulate cable television, while raising doubts about the constitutionality of a key federal law governing cable operations
separately, the justices agreed to hear appeals by the reagan administration and coal mining companies trying to block the possible award of billions of dollars in black lung disease benefits to thousands of miners
in the cable television case, the high court cited a lack of jurisdiction in turning away an appeal by palo alto and atherton, calif., which were barred from enforcing public access and other rules challenged by cable operator century federal inc
but the court's action apparently was based on narrow procedural grounds and leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal
u.s. district judge eugene f. lynch ruled last september that cable regulations adopted by the two california cities unconstitutionally violated century federal's free-speech rights
the lower court had thrown out regulations requiring the company, among other things, to wire the entire community to make service available to all residents and to use a ``state-of-the-art'' system to keep pace with the latest technological advances
lynch, who previously had ordered city officials to award an operating license to century federal, called for further hearings to study franchise fee requirements adopted by the cities
palo alto and atherton officials said the ruling appears to declare unconstitutional a 1984 federal law regulating cable tv, even though the judge did not say in so many words that he was invalidating the law
the reagan administration, in a ``friend-of-the-court'' legal brief filed by justice department lawyers, urged the high court to deny the cities' appeal
in the case involving black lung disease benefits, the high court said it will review a ruling that the government must reopen some previously rejected claims for benefits
the reagan administration maintains the ruling by the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals, if extended nationwide, could force officials to re-examine 94,000 claims at potentially tremendous cost to the overburdened fund that pays benefits to miners afflicted with the disease
the lower court had ruled last march that thousands of miners seeking the benefits had been unfairly denied a hearing. the ruling applied to miners with less than 10 years of work in the mines whose claims were denied in the late 1970s and early 1980s
the appeals court said the u.s. department of labor must take a fresh look at the claims under liberalized standards adopted by congress in 1977. the appeals court applied the ruling to miners who failed to exhaust their administrative remedies or who missed deadlines for filing court appeals
in other business-related action monday, the supreme court:
_agreed to study a key affirmative action issue _ the power of local governments to require minority participation in public works projects. the justices will hear an appeal by richmond, va., officials seeking to revive a so-called set-aside program for construction industry businesses owned by minorities
_agreed to decide whether states may tax any income from oil and natural gas extracted from the outer continental shelf. the court said it will hear an appeal by shell oil co. challenging an iowa tax
_agreed to decide whether a 5 percent tax illinois imposes on all telephone calls charged to in-state numbers interferes with interstate commerce. gte sprint communications corp. is involved in the suit
_let stand a ruling that forces ann arbor, mich., officials to justify in federal court a zoning ordinance limiting where adult bookstores may be opened for business
_rejected an appeal by mill valley, calif., investor john olaques who said he lost $500,000 because of an insider-trading scheme. the court let stand a ruling excluding olaques from receiving any money from a $7.8 million settlement of the case, which stems from a proposed merger between santa fe international corp. and kuwait petroleum co. in 1981
the midamerica commodity exchange and first commodity corp. of boston have agreed to a $3.51 million settlement ending all fraud litigation against first commodity, the exchange announced monday
under the agreement, $3.01 million will be paid directly to defrauded customers, whose losses totaled more than $51 million in 1984, the exchange said in a news release
midam will retain first commodity's $500,000 guarantee deposit and the now-defunct firm waived all claim to those funds, the news release stated
midamerica in 1986 found that first commodity had violated exchange rules through its use of promotional materials, fraudulent and misleading sales practices and its withdrawal of guarantee funds on deposit with the exchange
the exchange expelled the company and fined it $3.51 million. first commodity later went out of business
plaintiffs in the class action applaud the midam's efforts and contributions in helping settle the largest reported class action commodity fraud settlement to date,'' said marvin miller, one of the plaintiffs' chicago attorneys
james brooks, general counsel for first commodity, could not be reached to comment immediately on the settlement. an answering service collected requests for comment from the defunct firm
the midam board of directors felt this settlement met all the objectives of the exchange, the futures industry, and the needs of defrauded investors,'' said midamerica president thomas r. donovan
the agreement stipulates that first commodity will pay $3.01 million to a settlement fund to be administered by the federal district court in boston, where investor cases were consolidated
the fund will be used to compensate those investors for some of their losses
the u.s. district court ``has preliminarily approved a settlement class of potentially defrauded fccb customers eligible for compensation. this settlement raises the amount in the fund to a currently estimated $5.3 million,'' the exchange stated
william murschel, an exchange spokesman, said he did not know how many investors were involved, but the release said ``virtually every fccb customer lost money, most of them losing 50-90 percent of their investments
customer out-of-pocket losses in 1984 totaled in excess of $51 million, nearly $30 million of which went to fccb in the form of commissions,'' the exchange said
pan am corp. and the union representing 4,500 ground employees in 14 cities remained in a stalemate monday following the breakup of their talks, and teamster leaders vowed ``guerrilla war'' against the financially troubled airline
travel agents reported that some customers have shunned pan am flights as a result of the conflict, which was sparked after the teamsters' strike deadline passed at 12:01 a.m. sunday
talks in which management was seeking $35 million in concessions from the union broke down sunday afternoon
no negotiating sessions were held monday. the union, which represents reservation clerks and other ground staff, put off a strike. but teamster leaders threatened to use disruptive tactics against pan am, which operates pan american world airways, a northeast corridor air shuttle and other services
labor unrest also escalated at another major u.s. airline. flight attendants at minneapolis-based northwest airlines have voted overwhelmingly to strike this weekend if a contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved, a union official said
disclosure of the northwest strike vote came as the two sides readied to resume negotiations for the first time since last month
sources close to pan am, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they were pessimistic about the prospects for a negotiated resolution of the conflict with the teamsters
we can strike (pan am) any time we want,'' said william genoese, director of the teamsters' airline division. ``we're going to pick our strategic time.''
in the meantime, genoese said, ``there's guerrilla war at all the airports. ... the passengers are really going to suffer in this situation.'' he said the tactics would include deliberately misdirecting baggage and cargo and canceling passengers' reservations
pan am spokeswoman pamela hanlon said there was no evidence so far of such disruptions
the operation is running smoothly,'' hanlon said. ``there is no evidence of any job action of any sort at any station.'' she said ``nothing very dramatic'' had happened at john f. kennedy international airport in new york city, pan am's major hub
the company has said it would maintain operations with replacement workers in the event of a strike. the transport workers union at pan am voted friday not to support a teamsters' strike, and pilots, flight attendants and flight engineers are not expected to honor picket lines
there haven't been any problems whatsoever,'' said archie lenzi, chairman of the pan am pilots union's master executive council, noting that he piloted a flight sunday from san francisco to new york without incident
not all travelers appear to be reassured, however
it's a very bad situation for everybody,'' said david perlman, president of dms travel in midtown manhattan. ``some people are shying away (from pan am flights).''
perlman said his agency has been using double bookings as an insurance technique for customers booked on pan am flights. for passengers taking pan am from kennedy airport to europe on monday night, for example, he also booked them on flights offered by other airlines to the same destinations
i think we have to go on the assumption that if there is a strike, all (pan am) flights will be shut down,'' perlman said
james cammisa, a travel industry consultant, estimates that a threatened strike against an airline generally reduces bookings for the carrier by about 10 percent to 20 percent
any kind of strike threat erodes bookings,'' cammisa said, noting that the same thing has happened with eastern airlines, a subsidiary of giant texas air corp. with a history of labor troubles
the public is very concerned about the turmoil (pan am is) having with their unions,'' said steven hoffenberg, chairman of towers financial corp. the loss of bookings resulting from the conflict, he said, ``is going to be enough to drain the company and put them into bankruptcy.''
towers, a debt-collection and insurance holding company based in new york, has said it intends to launch a takeover bid for pan am, with the teamsters' backing. towers owns about 100,000 pan am shares, out of a total of around 139 million shares outstanding
pan am had a net loss last year of $265.3 million on revenue of $2.9 billion, following a 1986 loss of $462.8 million on revenue of $2.5 billion. the company recently signed agreements on more than $330 million in concessions with the unions representing pilots, flight engineers and flight attendants. pan am also went through a major management shakeup a month ago: its new chairman, thomas g. plaskett, briefly headed continental airlines and also worked at american airlines
the teamsters represent workers at airports in boston, detroit, chicago, seattle, san francisco, san diego, los angeles, honolulu, houston, washington, new york and the florida cities of tampa, orlando and miami. the vast majority of the workers are employed in new york and miami
the stock market staged a strong advance today, extending its recent rally as traders awaited new signs of the outlook for the economy and interest rates
analysts said investors were looking ahead to congressional testimony tuesday by alan greenspan, chairman of the federal reserve board
several statistical reports are also due this week on such subjects as durable goods orders, the consumer price index and personal income and consumption
of special interest to wall streeters is the commerce department's revised figure for the gross national product in the fourth quarter of last year, scheduled to be issued thursday
the department earlier estimated gnp growth, after adjustment for inflation, at a 4.2 percent annual rate in the october-december period. many analysts believe the new figure will be higher
economists at smith barney, harris upham &amp; co., for example, say it is possible that the report will show growth of 5.5 percent or more
steel production rose to 1.942 million tons in the week ended feb. 20, an increase of 4.0 percent from the previous week's 1.867 million tons, the american iron and steel institute reported monday
the industry's production amounted to 90.4 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 86.9 percent in the previous week
estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 13.796 million net tons, a jump of 39.6 percent from the 9.882 million net tons in the previous year. the steel operations of usx corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987
production so far this year used 88.2 percent of capacity, compared with 63.7 percent a year earlier
net tonnage by district for the week ended feb. 20: northeast coast, 275,000; pittsburgh, 206,000; youngstown, 128,000; lake erie, 148,000; detroit, 157,000; chicago, 535,000; midwest, 178,000; southern, 218,000; and western, 97,000
the dow jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.70 to 2,040.29, hitting a new six-week high for the third straight session
advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 2 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,148 up, 420 down and 429 unchanged
big board volume totaled 178.93 million shares, against 180.30 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index rose 2.00 to 148.96
first republicbank corp. ran full-page advertisements in local newspapers monday blaming shrinking deposits on seasonal factors and foreign withdrawals and repeating denials that it was involved in merger or bailout negotiations
in an open letter to customers, first republicbank stated that recent news reports on the financial condition of the state's largest bank holding company were wrong or misleading
the advertisement was aimed at depositors, whom the company feared might begin withdrawing funds due to the reports because of concerns about deposit safety
during the past few days, there have been several articles and news stories about the current state of our bank,'' the ad says. ``many of the items reported in these articles have been misleading and some just plain wrong. consequently, we feel it necessary to respond to these reports.''
since first republicbank reported a $656.8 million loss jan. 19, rumors have spread about its ability to weather anticipated losses from its $3.9 billion portfolio of troubled loans
speculation spread to financial markets last week, sending first republicbank's common and preferred stocks tumbling and disrupting its system for raising deposits
the bank said in a statement sunday that 88 percent of its funds come from core deposits, gathered through its system of 134 branches and subsidiary banks. at year's end, first republic had $1.93 billion in foreign deposits, representing about 7.5 percent of its funds
total deposits as of dec. 31 were about $24.5 billion, according to spokeswoman martha larsh. assets totaled $33.2 billion, making first republicbank the nation's 14th-largest bank holding company at yearend 1987
first republic stated it lost slightly more than $1.1 billion in deposits since the end of 1987. first republic chairman gerald fronterhouse said about half the withdrawals _ nearly $550 million _ were at the lead dallas bank
through mid-february, the corporation's average total deposits have only declined by approximately 4{ percent this year,'' the company's ad said. ``more than half of the reduction was an expected decline in foreign deposits, with the balance due primarily to normal seasonal factors.''
the wall street journal reported in its monday editions that federal regulators were preparing a possible $4.5 billion rescue
fronterhouse said in the statement issued sunday that the institution was unaware of any efforts by the federal deposit insurance corp. to arrange an assisted merger for the bank holding company, the nation's 13th largest
furthermore, that agency informed us that its policy is to advise the institution before engaging in such negotiations,'' fronterhouse said
an fdic official said the agency ``would be less than responsible'' if it didn't prepare contingency plans for a troubled bank
first republicbank's ad also addressed the economic condition in texas, which leads the nation in bank failures
these are not the best of times for any of us in texas. but we are totally committed to serving your needs and contributing to your success. we are here for the long term,'' read the letter signed by fronterhouse, joseph musolino and charles pistor, vice chairmen
the dollar drifted lower monday against most other currencies in listless trading that analysts said reflected uncertainty about the outlook for the u.s. economy and interest rates
gold prices were narrowly mixed. republic national bank in new york quoted a late bid for gold at $444.25 a troy ounce, down 75 cents from friday's late bid
traders looking for clues about whether the economy was expanding or falling into a recession are focusing on reports due later this week when the government makes its latest revised estimate of fourth-quarter economic growth and issues reports on consumer prices, income and spending in january
marc chandler, currency analyst for dean witter reynolds inc. in chicago, said the currency market was being pulled in opposite directions
he said the market had been heartened by two consecutive monthly declines in the u.s. trade deficit, which could indicate the federal reserve may not have to encourage lower interest rates to assure continued progress in reducing the imbalance
but chandler said dollar traders remain concerned that the trade deficit still was too large for comfort. he said there has been speculation that european central banks sold dollars last week, inhibiting the currency's rise, in an effort to maintain stable foreign exchange rates
in tokyo, the dollar fell to 129.95 japanese yen from 130.53 yen on friday. in later trading in london, the dollar slipped to 129.27 yen. in new york, the dollar fell to 129.35 yen from 130.05 yen friday
in london, the british pound rose to $1.7630 from $1.7505 late friday. the pound finished at $1.75925 in new york, up from $1.7495 last friday
