the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market added 2.86 to 359.98. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 283.01, up 2.85. stock</head>
dissident investor henley group inc. proposed monday that santa fe southern pacific corp. scrap part of its financial restructuring and instead sell $780 million in new stock to henley
the move, which would boost henley's stake in chicago-based santa fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was expected to receive a cool reaction from santa fe, which has been fending off henley's unwanted overtures since mid-1987
santa fe spokesman robert gehrt said the proposal would be taken up at santa fe's regularly scheduled board meeting tuesday. he added there might be a comment after that
henley's proposal calls for santa fe to stop the planned payment of $5 per share in high-yield ``junk bonds'' for each of its 157.3 million shares on march 1. santa fe already has made a $25-per-share cash payout
henley has claimed persistently that the pay-in-kind debentures would leave shareholders with a large tax liability because of the way they are structured
instead, henley proposed that santa fe sell henley $780 million worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. proceeds from that deal would be used to make a onetime $5-per-share cash payout to all current shareholders
the proposed deal would mean 44.6 million new shares for henley and would boost santa fe's total shares outstanding to 201.9 million
henley now owns 24.6 million shares, or 15.7 percent, of santa fe, a railroad, land and natural resources concern
but henley conditioned its proposal on santa fe voiding its current ``poison pill'' takeover defense that would be triggered if any holder's stake exceeds 20 percent
if any hostile suitor exceeds that limit, other santa fe shareholders would be permitted to buy new stock at half price
henley repeatedly has criticized santa fe's adoption of the ``poison pill'' last december, saying it restricted the ability of major holders such as itself and toronto-based real estate concern olympia &amp; york developments ltd. to maneuver
in a setback for henley, santa fe earlier this month gave two seats on its board to officials of olympia &amp; york. in exchange, olympia &amp; york agreed to support santa fe's restructuring plans
however, in mid-february olympia &amp; york launched a surprise tender offer to boost its holdings in santa fe to 19.9 percent from its current 10.5 percent
olympia &amp; york's action has caused speculation that the canadian company still intends to push for break-up of santa fe as a means of increasing the company's value
stock-index futures overcame selling resistance monday to settle at their highest values since the oct. 19 stock market collapse
on other markets, cotton futures collapsed; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals were mixed; and energy futures were lower
the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 stock index gained 3.90 points to settle at 266.85 on the chicago mercantile exchange, topping the previous post-collapse high of 264 points set jan. 5
the march contract had rallied above the psychologicially important 264-point barrier earlier in the session only to fall back. but the second surge inspired broad-based follow-through buying that continued until the close, indicating the market had potential to move even higher, said abbe cocuzza, stock-index strategist for shearson lehman hutton inc. in new york
ms. cocuzza speculated the next point of resistance was 274 points, the level at which the march s&amp;p 500 contract opened on oct. 19 after hitting a low of 280.40 in the previous session
cotton futures prices collapsed on the new york cotton exchange in a sell-off linked to the impending expiration of the march contract
tuesday marks the first notice day for the march cotton contract. traders holding ``long,'' or buy, positions rushed to liquidate those positions to avoid the possibility of being locked into agreements to take physical delivery of cotton on the contract's march 9 expiration date, analysts said
the sharp decline in the march contract's price touched off computerized sell programs that drove prices on the three near-term contracts down the daily limit and sent prices on other contracts to new life-of-contract lows, said ernest simon, cotton specialist for prudential-bache securities inc
the contract for march delivery of cotton settled at 60.40 cents a pound, down the 2-cent limit
grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the chicago board of trade
a mixed opening was followed by firmer prices across the board, but the gains did not hold as commission houses became heavy sellers of soybeans and soybean oil near the close, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
the beans and oil were the two markets that really collapsed, and that collapse pulled everything else down,'' he said
wheat settled } cent lower to 1\ cents higher with march at $3.22\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with march at $1.99\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower with march at $1.90} a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents lower to 3 cents higher with march at $6.27\ a bushel
cattle futures declined while pork futures rose on the chicago mercantile exchange. profit-taking and hedge selling pressured the cattle contracts, and the pork complex rallied on better-than-expected cash prices, analysts said
live cattle were .15 cent to .75 cent lower with april at 72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to 1.03 cents lower with march at 82.52 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent to .33 cent lower with april at 44.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.10 cents lower to .35 cent higher with february at 54.02 cents a pound
gold retreated slightly while silver gained a bit in light trading on new york's commodity exchange
gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents lower with april at $447.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent higher across the board with march at $6.41 a troy ounce
oil prices edged lower after fluctuating in a narrow range. some analysts cited reports of overproduction and other problems within the organization of petroleum exporting countries that could point to bigger oil supplies
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 25 cent lower with march at $16.62 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent to .56 cent lower with march at 45.79 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .25 cent lower with march at 46.32 cents a gallon
wells fargo &amp; co. has reached a formal agreement on its proposed acquisition of barclays bank of california for $125.7 million in cash, the two banking companies said monday
wells fargo said the proposed acquisition, announced more than five weeks ago and subject to approval of federal regulators, is expected to be completed during late spring
the purchase should have ``minimal, if any, dilution on earnings per share in 1988 and will make a positive contribution to earnings per share in 1989,'' the company said in a press release
wells fargo's stock rose $1.62{ a share to $51.62{ monday on the new york stock exchange. barclays stock closed unchanged at $32.62{
barclays bank of california, a subsidiary of barclays bank plc and the 17th largest bank in the state, had year-end assets of approximately $1.3 billion. it operates 50 branch offices, has about 1,100 employees and will continue to maintain corporate offices in both san francisco and los angeles
san francisco-based wells fargo is the parent company of wells fargo bank, third largest bank in california and ninth biggest in the nation. it had year-end assets of $44.2 billion
the deal continues wells fargo's aggressive retail expansion across california. years</head>
atlantic richfield co.'s alaska subsidiary said monday it is prepared to invest more than $7 billion in the oil-rich state over the next 10 years if petroleum prices and tax policies are stable
about $3 billion would go toward development of known reserves, arco alaska inc. president bill wade told the anchorage chamber of commerce. spending of the rest would depend on the discovery of new oil fields, including any reserves under the arctic national wildlife refuge if congress allows exploration there
to accomplish all of this will require reasonable oil prices and a stable tax policy,'' wade said
the plan assumes prices in the $20-per-barrel range for a few years, followed by increases in the mid-1990s, said arco alaska spokeswoman susan andrews
she said arco has not asked for any changes in alaska's tax structure and does not plan to in the near future
arco alaska operates half the giant prudhoe bay oil field, which along with other north slope oil fields supplies 20 percent of the nation's domestic oil
the dollar fell marginally against the japanese yen in early trading tuesday, while stock prices posted a moderate advance
the dollar opened at 129.27 yen, down 0.68 yen from monday's close of 129.95 yen on the tokyo foreign exchange market
currency dealers said there were no specific incentives affecting the exchange dealings, but that the dollar remained under pressure because of japanese concerns about the u.s. economy
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which rose 73.30 points monday, gained another 25.71 points or 0.1 percent in early trading, moving to 24,872.42
the dollar fell to the lowest trading level in two weeks in early tokyo trading tuesday due to further selling by foreign banks
the u.s. currency opened at 129.27 yen, down 0.68 yen from monday's close of 129.95, and was quoted at between 128.85 and 129.35 two hours after the start of trading
on the stock market, share prices rebounded from morning lows and were little changed by mid-day
the nikkei index of 225 selected issues ended the morning session at 24,860.28, up 13.57 points, or 0.05 percent, from monday's close. the index rose about 100 points in the last 30 minutes of the morning session from a trading level of around 24,759
volume by the end of the morning session was estimated at 330 million shares, down from 450 million shares during monday's morning session
finance minister kiichi miyazawa told a news conference tuesday that the higher prices of stocks on the tokyo stock exchange reflected japan's sound economic fundamentals and optimism by investors about the future
the seven-up co. will introduce an amber colored soft drink labeled 7-up gold designed to reach young adults, company officials said monday
the company is characterizing the new product as ``the wild side of 7-up,'' a natural spice flavored soft drink sweetened with aspartame
7-up gold is the missing link in the 7-up family,'' said john r. albers, chief executive officer of the company, a subsidiary of the dallas-based investment group hicks &amp; haas
company officials said they are trying to reach a mostly male 18- to 34-year-old market with the new drink. the company also will introduce a diet 7-up gold
russ klein, senior vice president of marketing, said that while the image of 7-up is clean-cut and conservative, 7-up gold is aimed at mainstream soft drink consumers who generally drink colas
but like all 7-up products, it will be ``light, refreshing, thirst quenching, crisp, natural and translucent,'' klein said
shipments of the new drink will begin in april, in time for the spring and summer seasons, with national distribution expected by the end of may, officials said. the company will spend more than $10 million in advertising for the drink this spring and summer, klein said
the new drink follows the introduction of cherry 7-up and diet cherry 7-up last year. those drinks have captured 1.7 percent of the lucrative soft drink market
albers said 7-up gold now gives the company ``the most complete, competitive line-up'' in the soft drink industry
